      BPSdualpot_ena HBridge B Switch: Enables the use of dual (redundant) 
      position feedback control 
      BPSerr_maxVbat Obsoleted parameter 
      BPSerr_minVbat HBB - minimum battery voltage entry condition for Unable to 
      reach higher/lower BPS faults. 
      BPSerr_neg HBB - Unable to reach lower BPS fault target-actual percentage 
      threshold. Exceeding this threshold for the duration, battery voltage and 
      run mode entry conditions sets the fault. 
      BPSerr_pos HBB - Unable to reach higher BPS fault target-actual percentage 
      threshold. Exceeding this threshold for the duration, battery voltage and 
      run mode entry conditions sets the fault. 
      BPSerr_run_mode HBB - run mode entry condition for Unable to reach 
      higher/lower BPS faults. This parameter should be set to stopped or 
      cranking for systems where an unable-to-reach position error will prevent 
      the engine from reaching an underspeed/running status. 
      BPSerr_wait HBB - minimum duration entry condition for Unable to reach 
      higher/lower BPS faults. 
      BPSraw_LP High-speed anti-aliasing low-pass time constant for the raw PS 
      feedback voltage. 
      BPS_cmd_AD HBB Throttle position command (volts) 
      BPS_cmd_pct HBB Throttle position command (%) 
      BPS_EE_store HBB EEPROM restore enable switch. If enabled, the idle/full 
      offsets will be stored in EEPROM and restored on power-on. 
      BPS_learn_EE_ofst PS learn EEPROM offset. This value specifies a small 
      offset that is applied to the learn value prior to storing a successful 
      learn in EEPROM. Using a non-zero value here prevents the EEPROM value 
      from being the absolute min/max value ever seen during a learn sequence. 
      BPS_learn_full_lim HBB PS learn full limit. Limit voltage calculated from 
      PS1 full default (indicates a theoretical position beyond open stop in the 
      open direction) 
      BPS_learn_full_ofst HBB PS learn full offset. Defines the offset applied 
      to the full default for the learn algorithm. 
      BPS_learn_full_seek HBB PS learn full seek. Defines the actuator %open 
      limit to start the full learn algorithm. 
      BPS_learn_idle_lim Limit voltage calculated from HBB PS1 idle default 
      (indicates a theoretical position beyond closed stop in the closed 
      direction) 
      BPS_learn_idle_ofst HBB - Defines the offset applied to the idle default 
      for the learn algorithm. 
      BPS_learn_idle_seek HBB - Defines the actuator %open limit to start the 
      idle learn algorithm. 
      BPS_pct HBB throttle position (percent) 
      BPS_step_max HBB - Used for 3-phase motor control only used when PS1 is 
      set to a feedback option based on "steps". 
      BP_def Default value of Barometric Pressure (BP) 
      BP_est_ena This flag tells the software whether or not to use MAP/TOP 
      based BP estimation for calculating actual BP. If this flag='MAP/TOP 
      estimate / BP present', the MAP/TOP signal is used in the normal way to 
      estimate BP in psia. If this flag='BP absent / EBP estimate', MAP/TOP 
      based BP estimation is NOT done and the BP_def pressure is used as the 
      actual BP in psia. The 'internal sensor' option is only available on ECM 
      platforms with an on-board barometric pressure sensor. 
      NOTE: If MAP_sensor='Not Present', BP estimation is not done regardless of 
      the BP_disable switch state. If a TOP sensor is not present (i.e. not a 
      supercharged application), the TOP based estimate defaults to a MAP based 
      estimate. 
      BP_internal_comp internal (compensated) barometric pressure reading in 
      psia 
      BP_key_halt If Key-on timer (key_on_tmr) is between BP_key_wait and this 
      parameter, MAP or TOP may be used to generate an initial value of BP 
      BP_key_wait If Key-on timer (key_on_tmr) is between this parameter AND 
      BP_key_halt, MAP or TOP may be used to generate an initial value of BP 
      BP_LPEGR_tau Specifies the time constant for the low-pass filter applied 
      to the barometric pressure input. The output of this filter is used 
      exclusively for low-pressure EGR flow calculations and diagnostics. This 
      low-pass filter is applied to any BP input source configured by the "BP 
      estimate/measurement" parameter on the Altitude worksheet. 

      Small changes (~0.1 psi) to BP can result in sudden significant changes to 
      calculated EGR flow. Applying a low-pass filter with a large time constant 
      to the BP input will result in smoother, more gradual changes to the EGR 
      flow. 
      BP_MAP_H MAP low limit for BP estimation; If MAP/TOP is above this limit, 
      BP estimation may be performed. 
      BP_max BP high pressure fault max BP threshold 
      BP_min BP low pressure fault min BP threshold 
      BP_RPM_H BP rpm high limit; BP estimation may be used below this threshold 

      BP_sample_tau LPF time constant used on MAP Based Estimate of BP 
      BP_TPS_L BP estimator condition requirement on TPS; above this value BP 
      estimation may be performed 
      brake_cfg This input is used for a foot or parking brake:
      Valid = Depressed
      Open = Released 
      brake_chan This input may be attached to an emergency brake for governor 
      interlock validation and secondary foot pedal control. However, it is 
      treated as a foot brake input in J1939 communications, and used as a 
      cruise-control disable. When parameter is set to 'J1939 EBC1', the input 
      is received in SPN 1121 (ECI SPN 561) from the following messages:
      0x18F00100 (ECI PGN 61441)
      0x18F0010B (ECI PGN 42269)
      0x18F00117 (ECI PGN 42365)
      0x18F00121 (ECI PGN 42325)
      0x18F00127 (ECI PGN 42486)
      0x18F001D0 (ECI PGN 42485)
      0x18F001EF (ECI PGN 42484) 
      brake_fault Foot brake input switch fault is active OR primary/secondary 
      brakes disagree 
      brake_open_released Foot brake input value (0=valid/depressed, 
      1=open/released) 
      brake_override_actv Indicates when the brake pedal override feature is 
      inhibiting foot pedal commands. 
      brake_override_mode When set to 'Enabled - Allow Brake TSC1', depressing 
      the brake pedal while the vehicle speed exceeds the "Brake override 
      minimum road speed" will disable all foot pedal commands, except for 
      braking TSC1 requests. A braking TSC1 request is defined as a negative or 
      zero torque or torque- limit request. Positive torque/torque-limit and 
      speed control requests are ignored. When set to 'Enabled - Allow All 
      TSC1', depressing the brake pedal while the vehicle speed exceeds the 
      "Brake override minimum road speed" will disable all foot pedal commands, 
      but allow all P32 TSC1 requests. Temporary powertrain control TSC1 
      requests are needed for AMT downshifting while the brake pedal is being 
      pressed. 
      brake_override_RSmin Minimum vehicle speed where depressing the brake 
      pedal disables foot pedal commands. 
      brake_sec_cfg This input is used for a foot or parking brake:
      Valid = Depressed
      Open = Released 
      brake_sec_chan Enter the secondary brake input channel, or 'Disabled' if 
      only 1 brake input exists. This is a redundant foot brake input used to 
      validate the primary brake input. If the two brake inputs disagree, the 
      "safe" scenario is chosen. For example, cruise control will be disabled if 
      either brake input reads a depressed brake pedal. 
      BRANCH_10090 Reserved parameter 
      BRANCH_10091 Reserved parameter 
      BRANCH_10092 Reserved parameter 
      BRANCH_10093 Reserved parameter 
      BRANCH_10094 Reserved parameter 
      BRANCH_10637 Reserved parameter 
      BRANCH_10638 Reserved parameter 
      BRANCH_10639 Reserved parameter 
      BRANCH_1660 Reserved parameter 
      BRV_comp_ena This feature reduces the EGR diluent command and/or the EGR 
      valve delta-P command during tip-outs to compensate for the opening of the 
      boost recirculation valve (BRV). 
      BRV_comp_ms Once activated, this determines how long the BRV compensation 
      will remain active. 
      BRV_comp_tmr If this value is non-zero, BRV compensation is active. This 
      timer is initialized to BRV_comp_ms when BRV compensation activates and 
      counts down to zero. 
      BRV_dilpct_reduct This parameter specifies the percent reduction in the 
      commanded diluent flow percentage while BRV compensation is active. 
      BRV_EGRvlv_dP This parameter can be used to limit the EGR valve delta-P 
      command while BRV compensation is active. Typically, 0.4-0.5 psi is 
      required for accurate open-loop EGR tracking. However, the delta-P can be 
      reduced via this parameter to help open the IRV, if needed. Set this 
      parameter to a value higher than the steady-state EGR valve dP table to 
      disable this feature. 
      BRV_MAPd_dtmin BRV compensation will activate if the MAPd derivative is 
      decreasing at a rate lower than this limit (tip-out) and TIP-MAPd is 
      increasing faster than the limit below. 
      BRV_TIPMAPd_dtmax BRV compensation will activate if the TIP-MAPd 
      derivative is increasing at a rate higher than this limit (BRV opening) 
      and MAPd is decreasing faster than the limit above (tip-out). 
      BRV_wait_ms Once BRV compensation is activated, this determines how long 
      the BRV compensation must be inactive (with both the MAPd and TIP-MAPd 
      derivatives below the activation thresholds) before it can re-activate. 
      BstPtarget_Hi_abs Target boost pressure entry condition for "Control 
      overboost" diagnostic 
      BstTIP_Hi Overboost Fault Condition: Delta P above the current TIP target 
      will initiate overboost fault validation 
      BstTIP_Hi_abs Overboost Fault Condition: Maximum absolute TIP target 
      required to initiate overboost fault validation 
      BstTIP_Hi_dtdz Overboost Fault Condition: Max dP/dt required to initiate 
      overboost fault validation. 
      This should be a small NEGATIVE psi/sec value such as 1 psi/sec. 
      BstTIP_Lo Underboost Fault condition: Delta P below the current P target 
      that will initiate underboost fault validation 
      BstTIP_Lo2 "Control underboost 2" diagnostic. Delta-P below the current P 
      target that will initiate underboost fault validation. 
      BstTIP_Lo2_abs "Control underboost 2" diagnostic. Minimum absolute P 
      target required to initiate underboost fault validation. 
      BstTIP_Lo2_dtdz "Control underboost 2" diagnostic. Maximum dP/dt required 
      to initiate underboost fault validation. 
      BstTIP_Lo2_ECT "Control underboost 2" diagnostic. Minimum ECT required to 
      initiate underboost fault validation. 
      BstTIP_Lo2_RPM "Control underboost 2" diagnostic. Minimum ECT required to 
      initiate underboost fault validation. 
      BstTIP_Lo2_RPM_max Maximum engine speed threshold fault condition for the 
      "Control underboost 2" diagnostic. 
      BstTIP_Lo_abs Underboost Fault condition: Minimum absolute P target 
      required to initiate underboost fault validation 
      BstTIP_Lo_dtdz Underboost Fault condition: Min dP/dt required to initiate 
      underboost fault
      validation. This should be a small POSITIVE psi/sec value
      such as +1 psi/sec. 
      BstTIP_Lo_ECT Underboost Fault Condition: ECT min required to initiate 
      underboost fault validation 
      BstTIP_Lo_RPM Minimum RPM entry condition for "Control underboost 1" fault 

      BstTIP_Lo_RPM_max Maximum engine speed threshold fault condition for the 
      "Control underboost 1" diagnostic. 
      BstTIP_Lo_speed_exec If set to "Yes", the 'Control underboost 1' and 
      'Control underboost 2' diagnostics will execute when full authority 
      discrete speed governing is active. For this governing mode, the "P 
      target" value used to evaluate the first two fault conditions for each 
      diagnostic is determined based on the "Boost Pressure Control Expected 
      TIP" table lookup (Monitors worksheet) using the current MAP.

      Diagnostic execution for active discrete speed mode governing only applies 
      to turbocharged applications. 
      BstTIP_slow_delta Boost control slow to respond diagnostic. Delta-P below 
      the current P target that will initiate fault validation. 
      BstTIP_slow_dtdz Maximum dP/dt required to initiate Boost control slow to 
      respond fault validation. 
      BstTIP_slow_MAP Minimum MAP absolute pressure required to initiate Boost 
      control slow to respond fault validation. 
      BstTIP_slow_rpm Minimum RPM required to initiate Boost control slow to 
      respond fault validation. 
      bst_appd_enabled Enables the “Boost delta approach” control feature. This 
      feature provides a mechanism to limit overboost and underboost by 
      temporarily adjusting and slewing the desired boost TIP target to slow the 
      approach. This adjusted “boost TIP desired approach” value (bst_TIPdapp) 
      is used when calculating the TIP error for PID control.

      The following options are available:

      - Disabled – the boost approach delta control feature is disabled. This is 
      the default.
      - Enabled – Upper and Lower – boost approach delta control is enabled for 
      both upper approach (underboost control) and lower approach (overboost 
      control).
      - Enabled – Upper only – boost approach delta control is enabled for upper 
      approach (underboost control) only.
      - Enabled – Lower only – boost approach delta control is enabled for lower 
      approach (overboost control) only. 
      bst_appd_lwr_delta Obsoleted parameter 
      bst_appd_lwr_d_pt The calculated lower delta point 
      bst_appd_lwr_mode Parameter sets the method for slewing up the TIP desired 
      approach value (bst_TIPdapp) to the actual TIP desired value (bst_TIPd). 
      When set to 'Slew up at constant rate', the approach value (bst_TIPdapp) 
      is slewed up to the actual value (bst_TIPd). When set to 'Slew to TIP 
      target', the difference between the actual value (bst_TIPd) and the 
      approach value (bst_TIPdapp) is slewed to 0. Changes in the actual value 
      (bst_TIPd) will be reflected in the approach value (bst_TIPdapp) while 
      slewing. 
      bst_appd_lwr_m_pt The calculated lower margin point 
      bst_appd_lwr_offset The boost TIP desired approach value (bst_TIPdapp) can 
      optionally be slewed to an offset from the actual boost TIP desired value 
      (bst_TIPd) for a specified duration of time, "Lower approach offset time". 
      This parameter specifies the offset. Set to 0 psi to disable. 
      bst_appd_lwr_slew Obsoleted parameter 
      bst_appd_lwr_slew_m This setting defines a margin below the lower approach 
      delta point at which slewing up to the actual boost TIP desired value 
      (bst_TIPd) will occur. This lower approach slew margin point allows 
      slewing to begin slightly below the delta point to prevent cases where TIP 
      may take excessively long to cross the delta point. Setting this value to 
      0 will result in slewing starting when TIP achieves or passes the delta 
      point. 
      bst_appd_lwr_time Amount of time to hold the boost TIP desired approach 
      value (bst_TIPdapp) at the lower approach offset point. When time has 
      expired, the TIP desired approach value will finish slewing to the actual 
      boost TIP desired value (bst_TIPd). See "Lower approach offset" for more 
      details. 
      bst_appd_upr_delta When TIP is higher than the desired boost TIP target 
      plus the “Upper approach delta” plus the “Upper approach slew margin” the 
      desired boost TIP target will be temporarily set to the delta point. 
      bst_appd_upr_d_pt The calculated upper delta point 
      bst_appd_upr_m_pt The calculated upper margin point 
      bst_appd_upr_slew This setting defines a margin above the upper approach 
      delta point at which slewing down to the actual boost TIP desired value 
      (bst_TIPd) will occur. This upper approach slew margin point allows 
      slewing to begin slightly above the delta point to prevent cases where TIP 
      may take excessively long to cross the delta point. Setting this value to 
      0 will result in slewing starting when TIP achieves or passes the delta 
      point. 
      bst_appd_upr_slew_m This setting defines a margin above the upper approach 
      delta point at which slewing down to the actual boost TIP desired value 
      (bst_TIPd) will occur. This upper approach slew margin point allows 
      slewing to begin slightly above the delta point to prevent cases where TIP 
      may take excessively long to cross the delta point. Setting this value to 
      0 will result in slewing starting when TIP achieves or passes the delta 
      point. 
      bst_BP_enabled This feature reduces the target TIP and potentially MAP at 
      high-altitudes. The TIP target will not be reduced below BP + 1.0 psia, to 
      avoid setting the TIP target to an unachievable condition. A phi 
      multiplier is applied via the following formula to allow constant power 
      operation:

      Phi_altitude = Phi_base * [1 + (dPhi/dTIP) fraction * 
      TIP_reduction/TIP_nominal]

      This feature is ignored for supercharged applications and during boost EMP 
      mode operation. The spark timing offset is also useful for naturally 
      aspirated applications, and can be used even when boost is disabled.

      If the TIP-only option is selected, once TIP is reduced to the boost MAP 
      target, the TIP reduction is frozen and no further reductions occur (power 
      maintain mode). If the TIP+MAP option is selected, once TIP is reduced to 
      the boost MAP target, the TIP and MAP targets will be simultaneously 
      reduced (overspeed protection mode).

      If the "Load-Limit & EGR MinNom: 2D Table" option is selected, the TIP 
      target and phi multiplier are not used. Instead, the same tables are 
      reused to apply a load-limit and EGR MinNom limit. In this mode, the spark 
      timing offset is ignored.

      The "Load-Limit & EGR MinNom: 2D Table with Load Threshold" option is 
      similar to the "Load-Limit & EGR MinNom: 2D Table" option, with these 
      differences:
      - The "Spark Timing Offset / MAP Load Threshold" table and "MAP load 
      approach delta" specify a MAP load window for slewing to the altitude EGR 
      min/nom fraction, and for calculating a derate percentage due to EGR 
      octane adaptation.
      - A low-pass filter can be applied to the load limit.

      bst_BP_lim Boost limit based on barometric pressure 
      bst_BP_LL_tau Tau for the load limit percentage requested by the altitude 
      compensation system. This parameter is only used when "Boost altitude 
      compensation" is set to "Load-Limit & EGR MinNom: 2D Table with Load 
      Threshold". 
      bst_BP_loadlim Current load limit percentage requested by the altitude 
      compensation system. 
      bst_BP_MAP_load MAP load threshold where the altitude EGR min/nom fraction 
      is fully active. This threshold is also used for calculating the "Derate 
      for EGR octane adaptation". 
      bst_BP_MAP_load_app Approach threshold for slewing to the altitude EGR 
      min/nom fraction. 
      bst_BP_MAP_load_dlt Delta for calculating the "Map load approach 
      threshold". The "MAP load approach threshold" = MAP load interpolated from 
      the "MAP Load Threshold" table, minus the delta. 
      bst_BP_oct_derate Additional derate to account for additional EGR added 
      for octane adaptation. The derate is calculated as the change in MAP 
      caused by the additional diluent as a percentage of the MAP no-load to 
      full-load range. The additional diluent is calculated at the current MAP 
      load threshold. 
      bst_BP_phifrac Boost altitude compensation phi fraction for Phi_alt = 
      Phi_base * (1 + Bst_BP_phifrac) 
      bst_carb_dP_ena If enabled, the boost delta-P target mode will account for 
      the pressure drop across a variable-venturi carburetor when computing the 
      throttle position to achieve the desired MAP and TIP targets. This 
      parameter is ignored while operating in the TIP absolute and EMP modes. 
      bst_dCdA_margin This value is used to provide a fixed CdA margin near 
      fully-closed throttle positions, in order to keep the off-zero response 
      reasonable. For example, if the throttle is almost closed and

      this value = 5% max CdA
      CdA,current = 0.005 (estimated from current position)
      CdA,slewed = 0.010 (estimated from CdA,current + 250 g/sec/sec * 5ms)
      CdA,100% = 4.0 (from the throttle calibration)

      then the actual CdA limit used will be
      max (0.010, 0.05*4.0) = 0.2

      With this value set to 0 in the above example, the throttle could get 
      'stuck' or take a significantly longer time than desired to open since the 
      limited resolution of the throttle model calibration could result in 
      almost identical TPS% values for CdA values of 0.005 and 0.010. 
      bst_discrete_gov By default, the TIP target is generated from the load 
      command (FPP). In discrete speed governing modes, FPP is typically 0% and 
      the target TIP is reduced (i.e. full power is not achieved). If 
      full-authority mode is selected, the load command is set to 100% (max 
      boost) and the throttle is used for governing. This option must be enabled 
      to achieve full-power when using the PTO feature (note it is also required 
      when using the PTO w/the min governor settings). 
      bst_dmdot_inc The throttle opening rate will be automatically limited to 
      ensure the change in flow across the throttle is below this limit. 
      bst_dPd delta-P value for delta P Wastegate control 
      bst_dP_EMP_Ki Obsoleted parameter 
      bst_dP_limit_active NO/YES logical indicating that delta P TPS limiting is 
      active/engaged 
      bst_dP_limit_ena If enabled, the delta-P limit below will be enforced as 
      the minimum TIP-MAP target. For example, the MAP target will be 
      upper-limited by MAPd <= TIP - bst_dP_limit_min. This parameter is ignored 
      while operating in the TIP absolute and EMP modes. 
      bst_dP_limit_min This parameter is ignored while operating in the TIP 
      absolute and EMP modes. 
      bst_dP_surge delta P across throttle that results in compressor surge. As 
      a result, bst_DPd should be less than this value to prevent a surge event 
      from occurring. 
      bst_EMPd_max Maximum exhaust manifold pressure to prevent engine choking 
      bst_EMPd_min minimum exhaust manifold pressure in psia for adequate EGR 
      control 
      bst_EMP_max_active Obsoleted parameter 
      bst_EMP_min_active Obsoleted parameter 
      bst_EMP_Pratio_max Obsoleted parameter 
      bst_Iacc_dP delta P offset from the boost EMP loop 
      bst_Iacc_TIP WGP integrator accumulator value used in TIP CL 
      bst_Iacc_WGP Integrator accumulator wastegate actuator command fraction 
      bst_IATnom Nominal IAT temperature reference for boost temperature 
      compensation. 
      bst_IAT_crct Boost target correction multiplier based on IAT constant 
      power requirements 
      bst_IAT_crct_ena Enables/Disabled Boost IAT correction 
      bst_Kd_TIP TIP feedback loop derivative gain. This loop's output value is 
      a wastegate pressure target. 
      bst_Kd_TIP_atten TIP feedback loop derivative gain attenuation multiplier 
      when the TIP feedback error is 0 psi. Set to 100% to disable attenuation. 
      See "TIP gain attenuation threshold" for details. 
      bst_Kd_WGP WGP feedback loop derivative gain. This loop's output value is 
      a wastegate actuator command. 
      bst_Kiv_dis_time Parameter is the amount of time to slew "TIP feedback 
      Kiv" gain to 0 when the gain is disengaged. Gain is disengaged when the 
      TIP feedback error is less than "TIP feedback Kiv disengage error". 
      bst_Kiv_dis_TIPe The TIP feedback error must be less than this parameter 
      to disengage the "TIP feedback Kiv" gain once gain is engaged. Set to -128 
      psi to never disengage the "TIP feedback Kiv" gain. 
      bst_Kiv_ena_TIPe The TIP feedback error must be greater than this 
      parameter to allow the "TIP feedback Kiv" gain to become engaged. Set 
      parameter to -128 psi to always engage the "TIP feedback Kiv" gain. 
      bst_Kiv_TIP TIP feedback loop integrator velocity gain. This loop's output 
      value is a wastegate pressure target. 
      bst_Kiv_WGP WGP feedback loop integrator-velocity gain. This loop's output 
      value is a wastegate actuator command. 
      bst_Ki_TIP TIP feedback loop integrator gain. This loop's output value is 
      a commanded WGP. 
      bst_Ki_TIP_atten TIP feedback loop integrator gain attenuation multiplier 
      when the TIP feedback error is 0 psi. Set to 100% to disable attenuation. 
      See "TIP gain attenuation threshold" for details. 
      bst_Ki_WGP WGP feedback loop integrator gain. This loop's output value is 
      a wastegate actuator command. 
      bst_Kp_TIP TIP feedback loop proportional gain. This loop's output value 
      is a commanded WGP. 
      bst_Kp_TIP_atten TIP feedback loop proportional gain attenuation 
      multiplier when the TIP feedback error is 0 psi. Set to 100% to disable 
      attenuation. See "TIP gain attenuation threshold" for details. 
      bst_Kp_WGP WGP feedback loop proportional gain. This loop's output value 
      is a wastegate actuator command. 
      bst_Ksc_DP Proportional gain applied to (DPd - DP) when computing desired 
      throttle outlet pressure (TOP), where DP is the delta-P across the 
      supercharger. 
      bst_Ksc_MAP Proportional gain applied to (MAPd - MAP) when computing 
      desired throttle outlet pressure (TOP). 
      bst_loadcmd Engine load command utilized by the Boost Control System 
      bst_MAPd Desired MAP value for delta P Wastegate control 
      bst_MAPd_dt Boost MAPd derivative estimate. 
      bst_MAPd_dttau A low-pass filtered version of the MAPd derivative is used 
      in low-pressure EGR applications. This time constant specifies the 
      low-pass filter to apply to the 2-point backward difference derivative. 
      bst_MAPd_load Boost MAP load desired 
      bst_MAPd_load_max Parameter is a theoretical calculation of "Boost MAP 
      load desired" that assumes "Boost target load command" was at 100%. 
      Parameter is an estimate of the immediately available MAP-load for the 
      current engine conditions (TIP, altitude, EGR, etc.). Estimation does not 
      include load limits or remote torque requests. Parameter is currently only 
      calculated for turbocharged engines where "Boost control mode" set to 
      'delta-P'. Value can be used to calculate SPN 3357 "Actual Maximum 
      Available Engine Torque Percent" in EEC2. See "J1939 max available torque 
      broadcast" for details. 
      bst_MAP_surge MAP estimate for compressor surge. As a result, bst_MAPd 
      should be less than this value to prevent surge 
      bst_MAT_derate Boost target derate multiplier based on MAT derate 
      bst_mode Selected boost control mode. TIP absolute = TIP target only, 
      delta-P = MAP target based with TPS/TIP control. 
      bst_Ptarg_FSO Legacy variable 
      bst_Ptarg_P Active delta P or TIP target value from Lookup table 
      bst_rpm Filtered engine speed used for interpolating boost target pressure 
      and boost throttle command computations. 
      bst_rpm_tau Time constant for engine speed used in boost throttle command 
      calculations. Note that this is a second-order filter of the 
      window-averaged rpm.

      This parameter is ignored while operating in the TIP absolute mode. 
      bst_supercharge Turbocharged selection assumes the throttle is downstream 
      of the turbocharger, and throttle inlet pressure and WGP sensors are 
      available. Supercharged selection implies the throttle is upstream of the 
      turbocharger, and a throttle-outlet sensor is available. 
      bst_surge_dP_active Obsoleted parameter 
      bst_surge_MAP_active Obsoleted parameter 
      bst_Temp_mult Total combined boost temperature/derate multiplier 
      bst_TIP Filtered TIP used for boost throttle command computations. 
      bst_TIPd Desired TIP used for both Delta P and TIP wastegate control 
      bst_TIPdapp The boost TIP desired target potentially modified by the boost 
      approach delta feature 
      bst_TIPMAPd_dt Boost TIP-MAPd derivative estimate. 
      bst_TIPMAPd_dttau A low-pass filtered version of the TIP-MAPd derivative 
      is used in low-pressure EGR applications. This time constant specifies the 
      low-pass filter to apply to the 2-point backward difference derivative. 
      bst_TIP_atten_psi Parameter sets the TIP feedback error threshold for TIP 
      control gain attenuation. When the absolute value of the TIP feedback 
      error is less than this parameter's value, then the associated Kp, Ki, and 
      Kd control gains are attenuated.

      The PID gains are attenuated linearly from 100% to a calibratable 
      percentage of their original value. The following parameters set the TIP 
      control gains when the TIP feedback error is zero:
      "TIP Kp percentage when error zero"
      "TIP Ki percentage when error zero"
      "TIP Kd percentage when error zero"

      Set this parameter to 0 psi to disable all gain attenuation. To disable a 
      specific gain's attenuation, set the respective TIP gain percentage when 
      error is zero to 100%. 
      bst_TIP_Iacc_high TIP integrator high 
      bst_TIP_Iacc_low TIP integrator low 
      bst_TIP_Iacc_mode Configures the method for limiting the TIP control 
      loop's integrator. When set to 'Legacy' mode, the integrator is allowed to 
      wind up/down to the controller's limits, regardless of the proportional 
      and derivative term contributions. The summation of PID terms may be 
      outside the controller's limits. When set to 'Enhanced' mode, the 
      integrator can wind up/down to the controller's limits, but is limited by 
      the proportional and derivative contributions. The summation of PID terms 
      cannot be outside of the controller's limits. 
      bst_TIP_surge TIP estimate for compressor surge. As a result, bst_TIPd 
      should be less than this value to prevent surge 
      bst_TIP_tau Time constant for TIP used in boost throttle command 
      calculations. Note that this is the time constant for a second-order 
      filter; the first-order filter uses the standard slow low-pass time 
      constant.

      This parameter is ignored while operating in the TIP absolute mode. 
      bst_TIP_toggle_ena Boost Manual Mode - Boost TIP toggle enable 
      bst_TIP_toggle_ms Boost Manual Mode - Boost TIP toggle period 
      bst_TIP_toggle_P1 Boost Manual Mode - Boost TIP pressure 1 (toggle between 
      this and P2) 
      bst_TIP_toggle_P2 Boost Manual Mode - Boost TIP pressure 2 (toggle between 
      this and P1) 
      bst_TOPd Desired TOP used for delta-P TOP Wastegate control 
      bst_TPSd Desired TPS position for delta-P wastegate control 
      bst_TPSd_raw Boost delta-P Mode - Boost TPS command (pre-limiting) 
      bst_TPS_dmdot_ena If enabled, the boost TPS command will be slew-rate 
      limited by the change in mass flow across the throttle. 
      bst_TPS_filt This parameter controls low-pass filters for the engine speed 
      and TIP measurement used in the boost throttle command compuations. 
      Filtered engine speed and TIP measurement used for each setting:
      - Disabled: "rpm slow average" (rpm_filt) and "TIP slow value" (TIP_slow)
      - Both rpm and TIP: low-passed rpm_filt using the "Boost TPS command rpm 
      tau", and low-passed TIP_slow using "Boost TPS command TIP tau"
      - rpm only, TIP unfiltered: "rpm slow average" (rpm_filt) and unfiltered 
      TIP. This is the recommended setting.

      This parameter is ignored while operating in the TIP absolute mode. 
      bst_WGAact Wastegate actuator feedback fraction 
      bst_WGAact_tau This time-constant is used to low-pass the WGA command and 
      estimate the WGA position when feedback is not available. 
      bst_WGAchan Parameter sets the wastegate actuator output channel.

      When set to 'CAN-based WGCV', the ECM does not directly control the 
      wastegate actuator or even the pressure control loop. A CAN-based 
      wastegate control valve (WGCV) receives the desired wastegate pressure 
      (bst_WGPd) from the ECM and performs closed loop control with its own 
      pressure sensor and valve. This option requires the "WGP source" to be set 
      to 'CAN-based WGCV' on the Inputs worksheet. The following ECI PGNs are 
      required: 65409, and 42285-42286. The following SPNs are required: 
      64766-64770. 
      bst_WGAcmd Wastegate actuator command fraction 
      bst_WGAcmd_DC Wastegate actuator command PWM duty cycle 
      bst_WGAcmd_FF Feedforward constant used when no WGP feedback is available 
      from the wastegate actuator (Ki=0 and Kd=0). 
      bst_WGAcmd_FF_source Select the source, either a static Single Point value 
      or a dynamically determined value from the 2D WGP Feedforward Command 
      table. This value will be used as the feedforward constant when a WGP 
      sensor is not available in the wastegate actuator. 
      bst_WGAcmd_FF_tbl The dynamically determined value from the WGP 
      Feedforward Command 2D table which is used when the bst_WGAcmd_FF_source 
      is set to 'Table Based'. 
      bst_WGAcmd_tau Time constant for wastegate actuator command output 
      low-pass filter. 
      bst_WGAcmd_V Wastegate actuator command voltage 
      bst_WGAVmax Wastegate actuator max control voltage. This is the voltage at 
      which no further increase in voltage will cause an increase in valve 
      position. 
      bst_WGAVmin Wastegate actuator min control voltage. This is the voltage at 
      which no further reduction in voltage will cause a decrease on valve 
      position. 
      bst_WGPa Actual WGP (used in the Boost Control Loop) 
      bst_WGPd Final desired WGP 
      bst_WGPdi Target Waste-Gate Pressure (WGP feedback target - initial) 
      bst_WGPd_dot WGP desired derivative 
      bst_WGPd_dotena Enables/disables use of an estimated WGP derivative target 
      based on a backward difference from the TIP feedback loop. 
      bst_WGPd_tau Time constant for desired WGP output low-pass. 
      bst_WGPe Wastegate pressure control loop error term = bst_WGPd - bst_WGPa. 

      bst_WGPneut Pressure at which the wastegate actuator is in a neutral 
      position (balanced between full open and full closed positions). 
      bst_WGPnl_ena Enabled/disable the non-linear WGP target pressure mapping 
      table. This function is used to linearize wastegate response. 
      bst_WGPsource Select the wastegate pressure source. 'TIP' indicates that 
      the pressure is sourced from the turbo compressor, and 'Constant Supply' 
      indicates that the pressure is sourced from the vehicle/engine compressed 
      air source. 
      bst_WGPsource_Pc This is the pressure of the constant supply for the 
      wastegate when this configuration is selected. 
      bst_WGPWM_per If the PWM output channel is 3 or 4, then a selectable 
      output pulse period (1/frequency) is available. If this parameter is set 
      to 0, then the output runs at the normal maximum frequency if 2 KHz (0.5 
      ms period), otherwise it may run at periods up to 52.0 ms in increments of 
      0.5 ms. 
      bst_WGPWM_type This switch controls the final output interpretation for 
      the WG
      control PWM output. In 'Electrical PWM' mode, the min/max voltage/% 
      specifications below work as voltage limits with Vbat compensation. In 
      mechanical mode, theses min/max limits are now interpreted as % (0-100) 
      limits on mechanical duty-cycle with no Vbat compensation. Any changes in 
      these values will require gain re-scaling for equivalent gain operation.

      This option is for single-leg PWM outputs only and is ignored if one of 
      the H-bridges is assigned as the current output channel. 
      bst_WGP_test Enable this mode to allow manual entry of the WGP desired 
      pressure. 
      bst_WGP_toggle_ena Boost Manual Mode - Boost WGP toggle enable 
      bst_WGP_toggle_ms Boost Manual Mode - Boost WGP toggle period 
      bst_WGP_toggle_P1 Boost Manual Mode - Boost WGP toggle pressure 1 
      bst_WGP_toggle_P2 Boost Manual Mode - Boost WGP toggle pressure 2 
      BTN_stop_ena If enabled, this allows the auto-crank / pass-thru trigger 
      input to also function as an engine-stop command input. 
      BTN_stop_occurred indicator that a push button engine stop request is what 
      caused the engine to halt 
      BTN_stop_rpm_min The engine speed must be above this limit before the 
      push-button stop feature will work. 
      BTN_stop_wt Additional debounce time to validate an autocrank trigger 
      input push-button stop request before shutting down the engine. Note this 
      is in addition to the normal debounce time used on auxiliary inputs. 
      BUZZout_mirror Buzzer output pin 
      BUZZ_FB_raw buzzer output low-side voltage diagnostic input 
      BUZZ_off_loVf Buzzer open diagnostic - Low-side feedback minimum threshold 
      entry condition 
      BUZZ_on_hiVf Buzzer control short to power diagnostic - Low-side feedback 
      maximum threshold entry condition 
      C2ASpd_ena This switch enables the Cam2 input as an auxiliary speed 
      (frequency) input source. The variable C2ASpd_raw_freq is the computed 
      frequency in Hz. 
      C2ASpd_freq_raw Cam2 Aux Speed pulse input frequency 
      C2ASpd_hist_avg_t The length of time over which the roadspeed will be 
      sampled from pulse versus time data. This should be >= 20ms and <= 150ms. 
      C2ASpd_hist_tout Timeout value during lack of receiving pulses to label as 
      zero speed. This value should be >= 50ms and <= 190ms, and should also be 
      > the speed averaging window time. Typical value is 150ms - no real reason 
      to change. 
      CAC_dP_C Charge Air Cooler Model: CAC flow rate delta P scale 
      CAC_dP_nom Charge Air Cooler Model: CAC nominal delta P 
      CAC_eta Charge Air Cooler efficiency 
      CAC_eta_lo The CAC efficiency threshold entry condition for "CAC 
      efficiency lower than expected" diagnostic. Condition only applies when 
      the diagnostic's temperature source is COT. 
      CAC_eta_lo_COT Temperature threshold entry condition for "CAC efficiency 
      lower than expected" diagnostic. The threshold is compared to either COT, 
      IAT, or TIAT, depending on the diagnostic's temperature source. Measured 
      temperature must be above this value for fault to be evaluated. 
      CAC_eta_lo_kph Roadspeed threshold entry condition for "CAC efficiency 
      lower than expected" diagnostic. Enter a value of 0 if a roadspeed sensor 
      is not present. 
      CAC_eta_lo_mdota Air mass flow threshold entry condition for "CAC 
      efficiency lower than expected" diagnostic. The measured air mass flow 
      must be above this value for fault to be evaluated. 
      CAC_eta_lo_TIP The TIP threshold entry condition for "CAC efficiency lower 
      than expected" diagnostic. Only applies when the diagnostic's temperature 
      source is IAT or TIAT. 
      CAC_eta_lo_Tsrc Temperature source for "CAC efficiency lower than 
      expected" diagnostic.
      When set to 'COT', the COT, AAT, and TIAT inputs must be configured.
      When set to 'IAT', the IAT and TIP inputs must be configured.
      When set to 'TIAT', the TIAT and TIP inputs must be configured.

      See 'Inputs' worksheet to configure temperature and pressure sources. 
      CAC_eta_nom Charge Air Cooler Model: Nominal efficiency 
      CAD_camsync_to_TDCC This parameter above describes the distance between a 
      normal cam pulse (use the pulse closest to TDCC) and TDCC. For 
      shifted-pulse cam configurations, this parameter should be set to the 
      location of the 1st normal pulse following the shifted pulse. 
      CAD_crankcam_extra This is an additional calibration parameter used only 
      by certain crank-cam configurations.
      See the details below for the crank-cam modules that depend on this 
      parameter:1) Generic 6-2 crank, 6+1 cam: This parameter indicates the 
      position of the 'extra' cam pulse in CAD ATDCC. The cam1 sync tooth 
      position/phasing parameter above describes the distance between a normal 
      cam pulse (use the pulse closest to TDCC) and TDCC.2) Generic 6-2 crank, 
      4-pulse variable cam:This parameter describes how far the cam is advanced 
      from its nominal/standard configuration. It is only used for cam-syncing 
      with these patterns. Only positive values are accepted.

      The standard scenario ( for this parameter) looks at the cam state at the 
      crank tooth prior to the sync tooth. As an example, if this parameter is 
      set to 18 CAD, then the cam state from 4 (=18/6+1) crank teeth ago is used 
      for cam sync. Sync_allow must be greater than (this_parameter / 6 + 1).3) 
      For shifted-pulse cam configurations, this parameter should be set to the 
      amount of shift. Use positive values if the shifted pulse is delayed (i.e. 
      the cam tooth delta pattern is: normal delta, large delta, small delta, 
      normal delta) and negative values if the shifted pulse is advanced (i.e. 
      the cam tooth delta pattern is: normal delta, small delta, large delta, 
      normal delta). 
      CAD_sync_to_camtrust Obsoleted parameter 
      CAD_sync_to_TDCC Enter the CAD offset between the "sync" tooth and TDC 
      compression on cylinder #1. For gap-toothed wheels, sync is first achieved 
      on the second tooth after the final gap tooth. For example, if TDC#1 is 54 
      CAD after the last gap tooth (assigning 0 CAD to the final gap tooth and 
      +6 CAD to the first tooth after the gap) on a 60-2 pattern, enter 54 - 2*6 
      = 42 CAD for this value.

      Note this value should be fixed for a given application and adjustment is 
      not normally necessary. However, in the event the spark timing is off and 
      minor adjustment is necessary: increase this value to retard timing, and 
      decrease this value to advance timing. 
      CAD_TDC_cyl_shift 1D Interpolation Table: Input is cylinder firing order, 
      output is shift from even TDC spacing (CAD ATDC nominal) 
      calibration_error flag used for tracking calibration/configuration errors 
      calibration_key unlock key to allow calibration-only modes - placed in 
      persistent memory for post-sleep related cal tools 
      cal_grp_cksums Calibration Group: calculated checksum 
      cal_grp_cksum_ee Calibration Group EEPROM Ram-Mirror: checksum 
      cal_grp_cksum_hst1 Calibration Group EEPROM Ram-Mirror History: checksum 
      cal_grp_cksum_hst2 Calibration Group EEPROM Ram-Mirror History: checksum 
      cal_grp_hrs_ee Calibration Group EEPROM Ram-Mirror History: hours 
      cal_grp_locked Calibration Group: Set Locked/Unlocked 
      cal_grp_lock_ee Calibration Group EEPROM Ram-Mirror: lock 
      cal_grp_lock_hst1 Calibration Group EEPROM Ram-Mirror History: lock 
      cal_grp_lock_hst2 Calibration Group EEPROM Ram-Mirror History: lock 
      cal_grp_revisions Calibration Group: Assigned revision number 
      cal_grp_rev_ee Calibration Group EEPROM Ram-Mirror: revision 
      cal_grp_rev_hst1 Calibration Group EEPROM Ram-Mirror History: revision 
      cal_grp_rev_hst2 Calibration Group EEPROM Ram-Mirror History: revision 
      cal_grp_scalars Calibration Group: Assigned Group to scalars 
      cal_grp_tables Calibration Group: Assigned Group to tables 
      cal_grp_valid Calibration Group Is Valid Flag 
      cal_pwd_ena Enables the Calibration Password verification during EDIS 
      authentication. 
      cal_sync_attempts 4G to SPOCK calibration sync unsuccessful attempts - cal 
      checksum did not match after the sync. Max three attempts allowed before 
      sync is disabled. 
      cal_sync_status 4G to SPOCK calibration sync status 
      cal_sync_timer 4G to SPOCK calibration sync timer - sync starts when timer 
      goes to zero 
      CAM1_ana_raw Cam1 magnetic pickup voltage feedback (raw volts) 
      cam1_input_redirect This switch allows hardware edge events coming into 
      the Cam1 input pin to redirect to the Cam2 software handling routine. For 
      example, if a hardware platform does not have a physical (i.e. hardware) 
      Cam2 input channel but does have an available Cam1 input channel, this 
      switch can be set to Cam2 to make the platform behave as if the Cam1 input 
      pin is connected to the Cam2 input pin. 
      cam1_mag_dec_tau Low pass time constant for sensing the falling edges of 
      the cam1 teeth 
      cam1_mag_inc_tau Low pass time constant for sensing the rising edges of 
      the cam1 teeth 
      cam1_mag_maxpct Limits the PWM trigger level output to this percentage of 
      the adaptive trigger level measurement. Generally, 80% provides reasonably 
      robust performance. 
      cam1_mag_trig_min Amplitude, multiply by 2 for peak-to-peak voltage 
      trigger. 
      cam1_min_pw Enter the minimum pulse width. Pulses smaller than this will 
      be rejected and treated as noise. This value should be < 6.4us. Set this 
      parameter to zero to disable the noise cancellation feature. 
      cam1_rise_trigger Cam1 rising trigger level 
      cam2loss Specifies the number of cycles that must occur without receiving 
      a cam pulse before considering the "Cam2 loss (exhaust)" diagnostic fault 
      check as failed. 
      cam2loss_crkng Number of engine cycles with no Cam2 sensor input signal to 
      wait before Cam1 loss fault is set. 
      cam2loss_crkng_ena Enable Cam2 loss fault during engine cranking. 
      cam2loss_rpm Specifies the minimum RPM fault condition for the "Cam2 loss 
      (exhaust)" diagnostic fault . 
      CAM2_ana_raw Cam2 magnetic pickup voltage feedback (raw volts) 
      cam2_capture Capture edge (rising or falling) used for cam2 sensing 
      cam2_HW_cfg Cam input hardware interface configuration. 
      cam2_input_redirect This switch allows hardware edge events coming into 
      the Cam2 input pin to redirect to the Cam1 software handling routine. For 
      example, if a hardware platform does not have a physical (i.e. hardware) 
      Cam1 input channel but does have an available Cam2 input channel, this 
      switch can be set to Cam1 to make the platform behave as if the Cam2 input 
      pin is connected to the Cam1 input pin. 
      cam2_mag_dec_tau Low pass time constant for sensing the falling edges of 
      the cam2 teeth 
      cam2_mag_inc_tau Low pass time constant for sensing the rising edges of 
      the cam2 teeth 
      cam2_mag_maxpct Limits the PWM trigger level output to this percentage of 
      the adaptive trigger level measurement. Generally, 80% provides reasonably 
      robust performance. 
      cam2_mag_trig_min Amplitude, multiply by 2 for peak-to-peak voltage 
      trigger. 
      cam2_min_pw Enter the minimum pulse width. Pulses smaller than this will 
      be rejected and treated as noise. This value should be < 6.4us. Set this 
      parameter to zero to disable the noise cancellation feature. 
      cam2_rise_trigger Cam2 rising trigger level 
      Camini_slew_tout This is the time over which the maximum cam control 
      actuation authority will be slewed in from zero following engine starting. 
      Set this value to zero to allow instantaneous full-authority control 
      following start. 
      camloss "Cam1 loss (intake)" diagnostic - number of cycles without 
      receiving a cam pulse signal (calibratable fault condition) 
      camloss_crkng Number of engine cycles with no Cam1 sensor input signal to 
      wait before Cam1 loss fault is set. 
      camloss_crkng_ena Enable Cam1 loss fault during engine cranking. 
      camloss_pulse_cnt Legacy pulse counting adds a multiplier of 16 to the 
      number of cycles of crank teeth required with no cam pulse.

      Exact pulse counting does not add a multiplier to the number of cycles of 
      crank teeth required with no cam pulse. 
      camloss_rpm "Cam1 loss (intake)" diagnostic - minimum RPM threshold entry 
      condition 
      camnoise "Cam sync noise" diagnostic - Number of allowed cam re-sync 
      events before initiating diagnostic monitoring. 
      camnoise_cnt number of cam sensor re-sync events - up-counter with 
      diagnostic resetting 
      camnoise_tout Cam sync noise diagnostic - monitoring window 
      Camrat_ena During an impending cam fault auto-unlocking procedure, this 
      switch enables 'phase 2' of the strategy called the 'rattle' procedure. 
      This phase sends multiple short duration low/high current pulses to the 
      cam actuator to attempt to 'unstick' it and return normal operation. If 
      enabled, this phase is initiated at 50% of the fault counter latch time 
      following the phase 1 starting-current pulse and prior to the phase 3 
      high-current 'bump'. The low-pulse time and current are specified 
      constants, and the high-pulse time is constant with a linearly variable 
      current option from 'Camrat_hi_start_I' to 'Camrat_hi_end_I'. 
      Camrat_hi_end_I This is the ending cam actuator current commanded prior to 
      the falling edge of the last high-time pulse of the 'cam-rattle' phase 2 
      cam fault auto-unlocking procedure. The current linearly transitions from 
      the start value to this end value across the total high-time = total 
      pulses * high-time per pulse. 
      Camrat_hi_start_I This is the starting cam actuator current commanded 
      after the rising edge of the first high-time pulse of the 'cam-rattle' 
      phase 2 cam fault auto-unlocking procedure. The current linearly 
      transitions from this start value to the end value across the total 
      high-time = total pulses * high-time per pulse. 
      Camrat_hi_time This is the duration of the high-time during the 
      'cam-rattle' phase 2 cam fault auto-unlocking procedure. 
      Camrat_lo_I This is the cam actuator current during the low-time of the 
      'cam-rattle' phase 2 cam fault auto-unlocking procedure. 
      Camrat_lo_time This is the duration of the low-time during the 
      'cam-rattle' phase 2 cam fault auto-unlocking procedure. 
      Camrat_pulse_cnt This is the total number of 'cam-rattle' pulses to inject 
      during phase 2 of the cam fault auto-unlocking procedure. If this value is 
      set to zero, no pulses are generated. A typical value is 5 pulses which 
      would be 5 low periods and 5 high periods. 
      cam_capture Capture edge (rising or falling) used for cam1 sensing 
      cam_cnt_diag cam input diagnostic rolling tooth counter used by crank/cam 
      diagnostics 
      cam_err_rpm "Intake cam / distributor position" diagnostic minimum RPM 
      entry condition 
      cam_HW_cfg Cam input hardware interface configuration. 
      cam_level_sync This switch signals what the cam state should be at the 
      specified sync tooth. The opposite state implies that the engine is 360 
      CAD (1 rev) from the sync tooth. 
      cam_level_trust This parameter is only used on high-low cam modules that 
      experience cam signal dropout (e.g. axially mounted sensors with excessive 
      drop out).

      To enable this feature, set cam_trust_level to a non-zero value (e.g. 60 
      CAD). For these modules, the 'cam_level_trust' parameter should be set to 
      the minimum required consistent cam-level for syncing. For example, if 
      cam_level_sync =LOW and cam_level_trust = 60*16, then the system normally 
      has a low cam edge at the sync tooth and because of intermittent erroneous 
      high levels (e.g. axial mounted cam sensor that reads low when ferrous 
      material is in front of the sensor), the edge state at crank sync cannot 
      be trusted. For this situation, the cam must be LOW for 60 CAD, and once 
      it is, the sync state is transitioned from -1 to -2. No attempts are made 
      to check the cam sync after the initial transition to a -2 sync state, but 
      an erroneous gap location will completely resync the system. 
      cam_lock_state Cam1 lock state (>0=pre-lock, 0=stopped, -2=locked onto cam 
      signal) 
      Cam_pin_ena This switch enables retention pin unlocking logic.
      This logic is designed to attempt to 'unlock' a variable camshaft 
      retention pin after starting but before a fault is set for inability to 
      control the camshaft.
      This system works in concert with the 'Intake cam position error' and 
      'Exhaust cam position error' faults.
      After the cam engine-starting delays from above, if all conditions are 
      satisfied to set one of these faults, this logic will interject one or 
      more current pulse phases to attempt to restore normal cam control:Phase 
1)
      A single pulse of 'Cam engine-starting current' actuator command for a 
      duration of 'Cam fault phase1 start-current pulse time' when the fault 
      latch timer has exceeded either 25% or 50% of its latch time.
      If no additional phases are selected, this pulse will occur at 50% of the 
      latch time, otherwise at 25% of the latch time.
      In many instances, this single pulse is enough to cause the retention pin 
      to unlock.
      If this is successful, the fault latch time will not expire before the cam 
      becomes controllable - and therefore the fault will never set.Phase 2)
      If 'Cam fault phase2 rattle' is enabled and the cam did not unlock 
      following phase 1, this phase will start when the fault counter exceeds 
      50% of the latch time.Phase 3)
      If 'Cam fault phase3 bump' is enabled and the cam did not unlock following 
      phase 1 or 2, this phase will start when the fault counter exceeds 75% of 
      the latch time.This logic re-arms to allow another pulse interjection 
      chain whenever the fault latch timer has cleared completely and the engine 
      speed is either stopped or falls below the minimum required for the fault. 

      Cam_pin_tout This is the pulse duration for the interjection of "Cam 
      engine-starting current" during phase 1 of an impending cam position fault 
      that is designed to unlock a stuck cam retention pin. See the comments for 
      "Cam fault pin-unlocking logic" from above for more information. If this 
      value is set to zero, this phase (phase 1) of the unsticking logic will be 
      skipped and the logic will move on to phase 2 and phase 3 if those are 
      enabled. 
      cam_pos_CAD This is the estimated position of the cam sensor input 
      relative to the crank sensor. This function is typically used with 
      distributor engines for aligning the distributor. 
      cam_pos_std This is the estimated position of the cam sensor input 
      relative to the crank sensor. This function is typically used with 
      distributor engines for aligning the distributor. 
      cam_pos_tau Low-pass time constant for filtering/averaging the cam 
      position estimation. This function is typically used with distributor 
      engines for aligning the distributor. 
      cam_reqactv Some crank-cam software modules reference this parameter to 
      determine what type (if any) cam activity is required before sync'ing the 
      engine at start. 
      Cam_strt_I This current will be output on any selected cam phaser control 
      PWM channel during starting and until the run timer has exceeded the base 
      + additional timeouts below. 
      Cam_strt_textra ECT based extra delay on start for cam actuator engagement 
      (additive to Cam_strt_tout) 
      Cam_strt_tout The starting current will be output on any selected cam 
      phaser control PWM channel during starting and until the run timer has 
      reached this base value + any additional ECT based timeout from the 
      schedule below. The special value of zero for the combined timeouts causes 
      the cam to immediately begin active controlling on crank. A small value 
      (0.001 sec) will cause the starting current to be used during crank, but 
      will immediately begin active controlling at run speed. 
      cam_tooth_cnt Cam1 tooth counter, value is zero-based. 
      CAN1term_loc 1D Table - Network Termination Status, CAN1: CAN termination 
      location (NA, Rear, Mid, Front) 
      CAN1term_mode 1D Table - Network Termination Status, CAN1: CAN termination 
      mode (Manual, Auto)

      CAN1_15765_2_Rx CAN packet counter 
      CAN1_15765_2_Tx CAN packet counter 
      CAN1_15765_4_Rx CAN packet counter 
      CAN1_15765_4_Tx CAN packet counter 
      CAN1_asw_rx_packs Number of received CAN messages handled by Simulink 
      application software defined CAN Receive messages on CAN channel 1. 
      CAN1_asw_tx_packs Number of CAN messages transmitted by Simulink 
      application software defined CAN Transmit messages on CAN channel 1. 
      CAN1_CCP_chksum Selects the algorithm used by CCP (CAN Calibration 
      Protocol) for 0x0E BUILD_CHECKSUM requests. A2L defined connections (INCA) 
      use the 'Add 08 Sum32' algorithm. NOTE: this selection is not used for CCP 
      ECM reprogramming. 
      CAN1_ISO15031_ena This setting enables ISO 15031 / SAE J1979 Legislated 
      On-Board Diagnostics (OBD) services over the ISO 15765-2 Transport 
      Protocol. Enabling this functionality will allow ISO 15031-compliant 
      diagnostic scan tools to query and control diagnostics services over this 
      CAN channel. This functionality requires the "ISO 15765-2" setting to be 
      enabled. 
      CAN1_ISO15765_2_cid Specifies the CAN identifier formats supported by the 
      ISO 15765-2 Transport Protocol. 
      CAN1_ISO15765_2_ena Enables processing of ISO 15765-2 Transport Protocol 
      CAN frames. This setting must be enable to allow use of the ISO 15031, ISO 
      14230, or ISO 14229 services. 
      CAN1_J1939_DM1_ena Enables or disables broadcasting of the J1939 DM1 
      message on the CAN channel. This setting is typically enabled for 
      J1939-capable CAN channels. 
      CAN1_speed This sets the baud rate for the CAN link during normal 
      operation. 250K baud is the J1939 standard. 
      CAN1_speed_latch Current baud rate for CAN1 link:
      0 = 125k
      1 = 250k
      3 = 500k
      4 = 1000k 
      CAN1_term_ena This switch selects whether or not the CAN1 link is 
      terminated internal to the ECM. This option is only valid on hardware 
      platforms that support software selectable CAN termination. Note that the 
      'Automatic' options are ONLY used on slave ECMs. The master ECM will 
      always default on and never internally toggle its termination. 
      CAN1_UDS_KWP_mode This setting enables additional diagnostic services over 
      the ISO 15765-2 Transport Protocol. The following options are available:

      - Disabled - the additional diagnostic services will not be available
      - Legacy (Mixed) - enables a legacy mode of operation that provides a 
      mixture of a subset of ISO 14229 (UDS) and ISO 14230 (KWP 2) services.
      - ISO 14229 (UDS) - enables ISO 14229 'Unified Diagnostic Services' (UDS) 
      services.
      - ISO 14230 - (KWP) - enables ISO 14230 'Keyword Protocol 2' (KWP) 
      services.

      Enabling these services will allow diagnostic scan tools that are 
      compliant with the enable services to query and control diagnostic 
      services over this CAN channel.

      This functionality requires the 'ISO 15765-2' setting to be enabled.

      Carb_loc Position of the carburetor in the intake track. 'Blow-Through' 
      indicates downstream of the compressor in a boosted application, and 
      'Draw-Through' indicates direct communication with the air cleaner in both 
      boosted and naturally aspirated systems. 
      CAT1_ena CAT1 enable/source selector switch 
      CAT1_Taux_cal CAT1 calibration table selector switch 
      CAT1_vdr CAT1 pullup resistor value 
      CAT2_ena CAT2 enable/source selector switch 
      CAT2_Taux_cal CAT2 calibration table selector switch 
      CAT2_vdr CAT2 pullup resistor value 
      CATdP Reports the calculated deltaP in psi 
      CATdP_ena Calibration variable which allows for the selection of the 
      Sensor Input for measuring Catalyst Delta P 
      CATdP_Paux_cal Catalyst delta-P calibration table selector switch 
      CATdP_P_select Select Catalyst Monitor source sensor 
      CATdP_raw Raw CATdP pressure prior to lowpass 
      CATdP_tau This is the low-pass time constant in ms applied to the Catalyst 
      delta-P sensor. It is used to filter out engine pulsations. 
      CATdP_Vdot_min Catalyst diagnostic minimum exhaust flow - Specifies the 
      minimum exhaust flow for execution of the catalyst exhaust P diagnostic 
      fault threshold checks. This can be used to disable the faults at low flow 
      rates. 
      CATmon_disable If this parameter is set to one of the faulted options, the 
      monitor disable trigger will disable execution of the Catalyst Monitor 
      diagnostics for the current drive cycle when the ECM detects that the 
      catalyst pressure sensor (CATdP or EBP absolute/gage) is unplugged. An 
      unplugged sensor will latch a high or low voltage fault depending on 
      whether the sensor input has an internal pull-down or pull-up resistor. 
      For a sensor input with a pull-down resistor, select 'Sensor low voltage 
      faulted'. Otherwise, select 'Sensor high voltage faulted'.

      The following diagnostics will not execute during the current drive cycle 
      when the monitor disable trigger is active:
      - Gasoline cat monitor
      - LPG cat monitor
      - NG cat monitor
      - Catalyst monitor – exhaust P low
      - Catalyst monitor – exhaust P high 
      CATout_OOR_CBT Minimum catalyst bed temperature (CBT) threshold for the 
      "Catalyst outlet temperature out of range" fault. 
      CATout_OOR_delta Minimum threshold for the "Catalyst outlet temperature 
      out of range fault" defined as the absolute difference between the 
      catalyst bed temperature (CBT) and the catalyst outlet temperature. 
      CATout_OOR_latch_wt Minimum time the CBT, engine speed, and MAP load 
      conditions must persist above their respective thresholds before the 
      "Catalyst outlet temperature out of range" fault latches or unlatches. 
      CATout_OOR_MAPload Minimum MAP load threshold for the "Catalyst outlet 
      temperature out of range" fault. 
      CATout_OOR_rpm Minimum engine speed threshold for the "Catalyst outlet 
      temperature out of range" fault. 
      CATout_OOR_wt Minimum engine run time threshold for the "Catalyst outlet 
      temperature out of range" fault. 
      Cat_bank_mode Catalyst feedback bank control mode (single or dual) 
      CAT_Tin Catalyst inlet temperature 
      CAT_Tout Catalyst outlet temperature

      CBT Catalyst bed temperature 
      CBT_ss Steady State Catalyst Bed Temperature 
      CBT_ss_delta Steady-state catalyst bed temperature 
      CBT_tauactv Catalyst temperature modeling currently active time constant 
      CBT_taustopped Time constant for the catalyst bed temperature to return to 
      ambient air temperature when the engine is stopped. If set to zero, then 
      when the engine stops, the CBT is immediately set to the Steady-State 
      Catalyst Bed Temp from the first row of the Power/Temperature Data table. 
      CCDL_buffer Buffer that stores the crank-cam data logger data 
      CCDL_ena Crank/Cam datalog system enable 
      CCDL_forcetrig Crank/Cam datalog system force trigger 
      CCDL_misfire If enabled, the spark kill selections will not be enabled 
      until halfway through the CCDL sampling, and will be reset upon completion 
      of CCDL sampling. 
      CCDL_reset Crank/Cam datalog system reset 
      CCDL_status Crank/Cam datalog system status 
      CCH_active Logical indicating the crankcase heater is turned on. 
      CCH_CCTflt_cold_OILT Parameter is the temperature threshold for using the 
      "Crankcase heater open-loop long 'on' time max" instead of the standard 
      "Crankcase heater open-loop 'on' time max". 

      When "Crankcase heater open-loop control" is set to 'Enabled - AAT and 
      OILT', then parameter is compared to the oil temperature. If the oil 
      temperature sensor is not available or in a fault condition, then the 
      ambient air temperature is used instead.

      When "Crankcase heater open-loop control" is set to 'Enabled - AAT, IAT 
      key-on', then parameter is compared to the ambient air temperature. If the 
      ambient air temperature is not available or in a fault condition, then the 
      intake air temperature sampled at key-on is used instead. 
      CCH_chan Output channel for controlling a crankcase heater. 
      CCH_CL_control Parameter determines if closed-loop crankcase heater 
      control is enabled. When set to 'Disabled - Open-Loop Only', crankcase 
      heater control is forced to open-loop control. When set to 'Enabled', then 
      closed-loop control is enabled and the crankcase temperature (CCT) is used 
      as feedback for controller. If CCT is faulted, then controller is forced 
      into open-loop control. The following parameters are applicable when 
      closed-loop control is enabled and active:
      "Crankcase heater 'on' temperature"
      "Crankcase heater 'on' debounce time"
      "Crankcase heater 'off' temperature"
      "Crankcase heater 'off' debounce time" 
      CCH_flt_cold_tm Parameter is an alternative maximum time for the crankcase 
      heater to be on when open-loop control is active. See "Crankcase heater 
      open-loop long 'on' temp" for details. 
      CCH_flt_control Parameter determines which sensor inputs are used for 
      open-loop crankcase heater control.

      When set to 'Enabled - AAT and OILT', the ambient air temperature is used 
      to turn on and off the heater. The oil temperature is used to trigger a 
      longer 'on' time. See "Crankcase heater open-loop long 'on' temp" for 
      details.

      When set to 'Enabled - AAT, IAT key-on', the ambient air temperature is 
      used to turn on and off the heater. However, if ambient air temperature 
      sensor is not available or in a fault condition, then the intake air 
      temperature sampled at key-on is used. The ambient air temperature is also 
      used to trigger a longer 'on' time. 
      CCH_flt_off_temp Parameter is the ambient air temperature (AAT) at which 
      the crankcase heater turns off when open-loop control is active.

      When "Crankcase heater open-loop control" is set to 'Enabled - AAT, IAT 
      key-on' and AAT is not available or in a fault condition, then parameter 
      is compared to the intake air temperature sampled at key-on. 
      CCH_flt_off_tm Minimum time for the crankcase heater to be off when 
      open-loop control is active. 
      CCH_flt_on_temp Parameter is the ambient air temperature (AAT) at which 
      the crankcase heater turns on when open-loop control is active.

      When "Crankcase heater open-loop control" is set to 'Enabled - AAT, IAT 
      key-on' and AAT is not available or in a fault condition, then parameter 
      is compared to the intake air temperature sampled at key-on. 
      CCH_flt_on_tm Maximum time for the crankcase heater to be on when 
      open-loop control is active. 
      CCH_off_CCT Crankcase temperature (CCT) at which the crankcase heater 
      should be turned off. Parameter is only applicable when "Crankcase heater 
      closed-loop control" is set to 'Enabled'. 
      CCH_off_dly Minimum time that the crankcase temperature (CCT) must remain 
      above the turn-off temperature before turning off the crankcase heater. 
      Parameter is only applicable when "Crankcase heater closed-loop control" 
      is set to 'Enabled'. 
      CCH_on_CCT Crankcase temperature (CCT) at which the crankcase heater 
      should be turned on. Parameter is only applicable when "Crankcase heater 
      closed-loop control" is set to 'Enabled'. 
      CCH_on_dly Minimum time that the crankcase temperature (CCT) must remain 
      below the turn-on temperature before turning on the crankcase heater. 
      Parameter is only applicable when "Crankcase heater closed-loop control" 
      is set to 'Enabled'. 
      CCH_state Current crankcase heater control state. 
      CCM_type Crank/Cam module selection

      CCP (CAN Calibration Protocol) messages. Set to 'Disabled' to inhibit CCP 
      processing.

      CCP2_DT_counter CCP DT (Tx) packets (CAN2)

      CCP (CAN Calibration Protocol) messages. Set to 'Disabled' to inhibit CCP 
      processing. 
      CCP3_CR_counter CCP CR (Rx) packets (CAN3) 
      CCP3_DT_counter CCP DT (Tx) packets (CAN3) 
      CCP3_session_actv CCP session state (Inactive/Active)(CAN3) 
      CCP_allow This switch should be set to 'Enabled' to allow processing of 
      CCP (CAN Calibration Protocol) messages. Set to 'Disabled' to inhibit CCP 
      processing. 
      CCP_CR_counter CCP CR (Rx) packets (CAN1) 
      CCP_DAQ_ena Selects which CAN channel will be used for CCP DAQ and whether 
      a 5ms or 10ms DAQ list will be available.

      CCP DAQ is only supported on one CAN channel at a time.

      1ms, 50ms, and 100ms DAQ lists are always available. In addition, either a 
      5ms or 10ms DAQ list will be available depending on the selection made in 
      this dropdown. 
      CCP_DT_counter CCP DT (Tx) packets (CAN1) 
      CCP_resource Current CCP access level 
      CCP_session_actv CCP session state (Inactive/Active)(CAN1) 
      CCP_slave_address CCP slave address

      CCT_ena Crankcase temperature sensor input channel 
      CCT_Taux_cal Crankcase temperature calibration table selection 
      CCT_vdr Crankcase temperature input channel pullup resistor resistance 
      value 
      CDdur_act_Tk1_mf_rf Actual spark rise to 15/16 setpoint voltage - tank 1 - 
      misfire/refire spark. 
      CDdur_act_Tk1_ps Actual spark rise to 15/16 setpoint voltage - tank 1 - 
      primary spark. Used by "slow recovery" fault. 
      CDdur_act_Tk2_mf_rf Actual spark rise to 15/16 setpoint voltage - tank 2 - 
      misfire/refire spark. 
      CDdur_act_Tk2_ps Actual spark rise to 15/16 setpoint voltage - tank 2 - 
      primary spark. Used by "slow recovery" fault. 
      CDdur_CAD CAD required to have enough time to fire misfire spark 
      CDdur_nomMF_ticks Estimated spark charge to setpoint voltage - for misfire 
      spark tank voltage setpoint. 
      CDdur_nom_ticks Estimated spark charge to setpoint voltage - for primary 
      or refire spark tank voltage setpoint. Used by "slow recovery" fault. 
      CDmisfire_spkCnt Specifies how many regular spark events for every misfire 
      detection spark event. Set to 0 to disable misfire detection spark events. 

      CD_CoilType Coil type: shielded or unshielded 
      CD_dwell CD spark dwell

      calibration > 0 
      CD_MF_CDdur_LED CD spark misfire detection flag CDdur_CAD_latch valid 
      CD_MF_cntr1 CD spark misfire down counter 
      CD_MF_cntr10 CD spark misfire down counter 
      CD_MF_cntr11 CD spark misfire down counter 
      CD_MF_cntr12 CD spark misfire down counter 
      CD_MF_cntr2 CD spark misfire down counter 
      CD_MF_cntr3 CD spark misfire down counter 
      CD_MF_cntr4 CD spark misfire down counter

      CD_MF_cntr6 CD spark misfire down counter

      cfgout2_chan Specify the output pin for user configurable output (#2) 
      cfgout2_CLloff For CL status comparisons, the options in the drop-down 
      dialog box are assigned sequential values, i.e.
      0 = CL not supported
      1 = Open-loop due to system conditions (warm-up, etc.)
      2 = Open-loop due to driving conditions (transient, etc.)
      3 = Open-loop due to a fault condition
      4 = Closed-loop active
      5 = Closed-loop + adaptive active 
      cfgout2_CLlon For CL status comparisons, the options in the drop-down 
      dialog box are assigned sequential values, i.e.
      0 = CL not supported
      1 = Open-loop due to system conditions (warm-up, etc.)
      2 = Open-loop due to driving conditions (transient, etc.)
      3 = Open-loop due to a fault condition
      4 = Closed-loop active
      5 = Closed-loop + adaptive active 
      cfgout2_CLoff Closed-Loop status for turning configurable output #2 off. 
      For CL status comparisons, the options in the drop-down dialog box are 
      assigned sequential values, i.e.
      0 = CL not supported
      1 = Open-loop due to system conditions (warm-up, etc.)
      2 = Open-loop due to driving conditions (transient, etc.)
      3 = Open-loop due to a fault condition
      4 = Closed-loop active
      5 = Closed-loop + adaptive active
      Selectable operators include <, >, <=, >=, =, <>

      1 = Open-loop due to system conditions (warm-up, etc.)
      2 = Open-loop due to driving conditions (transient, etc.)
      3 = Open-loop due to a fault condition
      4 = Closed-loop active
      5 = Closed-loop + adaptive active
      Selectable relational operators include <, >, <=, >=, =, <>
