      CRI_mchk_persist0 The entry conditions for this mode are constantly being 
      checked, regardless of the current operating mode. The persistence timer 
      that allows entry into this mode is only reset at key-off or when one of 
      the entry conditions is false (i.e. it does not reset on mode 
      transitions). 
      CRI_mchk_persist1 The entry conditions for this mode are constantly being 
      checked, regardless of the current operating mode. The persistence timer 
      that allows entry into this mode is only reset at key-off or when one of 
      the entry conditions is false (i.e. it does not reset on mode 
      transitions). 
      CRI_mchk_persist2 The entry conditions for this mode are constantly being 
      checked, regardless of the current operating mode. The persistence timer 
      that allows entry into this mode is only reset at key-off or when one of 
      the entry conditions is false (i.e. it does not reset on mode 
      transitions). 
      CRI_mchk_persist3 The entry conditions for this mode are constantly being 
      checked, regardless of the current operating mode. The persistence timer 
      that allows entry into this mode is only reset at key-off or when one of 
      the entry conditions is false (i.e. it does not reset on mode 
      transitions). 
      CRI_mchk_persist4 The entry conditions for this mode are constantly being 
      checked, regardless of the current operating mode. The persistence timer 
      that allows entry into this mode is only reset at key-off or when one of 
      the entry conditions is false (i.e. it does not reset on mode 
      transitions). 
      CRI_mchk_persist5 The entry conditions for this mode are constantly being 
      checked, regardless of the current operating mode. The persistence timer 
      that allows entry into this mode is only reset at key-off or when one of 
      the entry conditions is false (i.e. it does not reset on mode

      CRI_mchk_persist6 The entry conditions for this mode are constantly being

      CRI_offtime_min Injector minimum off-time 
      CRI_ontime_CADmax This parameter sets a maximum CAD-based pulse-width for 
      injections. This value is compared to the time-based pulse-width limit and 
      the smallest value is enforced as the current injection pulse-width time 
      limit. 
      CRI_ontime_drymax In an extended cranking dry-rail condition, this 
      parameter sets a maximum time-based pulse-width for injections. This value 
      is compared to the equivalent time for the CAD-based pulse-width limit and 
      the smallest value is enforced as the current injection pulse-width time 
      limit. 
      CRI_ontime_finalmax This is the final maximum pulsewidth time allowed for 
      injections = the smaller of the timebased and CADbased values at the 
      current engine speed. 
      CRI_ontime_max Any individual diesel injection pulse quantity above this 
      limit is forced to this limit. This limit provides hardware thermal 
      protection. 
      CRI_ontime_min Below this pulse width, any individual diesel injection 
      pulse quantity is forced to zero. 
      CRI_PCV_ena CRI fuel pressure sensor input selector switch 
      CRI_Pdry_cycwait Dry-rail mode detection is based on extended cranking 
      beyond this number of engine cycles without achieving normal minimum 
      injection pressure. Once cranking has persisted beyond this number of 
      engine cycles, the alternate dry-rail minimum injection pressures and 
      maximum injection pulse-width limits are utilized. 
      CRI_Pdry_ena Dry-rail mode detection is based on extended cranking beyond 
      a defined number of engine cycles without achieving normal minimum 
      injection pressure. Once this condition is detected, alternate dry-rail 
      minimum injection pressures and maximum injection pulse-width limits are 
      utilized. 
      CRI_Pdry_hyst In an extended cranking dry-rail condition, once the rail 
      pressure is >= CRI_Pdry_min and is considered valid for injection, the 
      pressure must drop below (CRI_Pdry_min-CRI_Pdry_hyst) in order to be 
      considered invalid. 
      CRI_Pdry_min In an extended cranking dry-rail condition, the rail pressure 
      must rise above this limit in order for injections to initiate. 
      CRI_Pdry_runhold After dry-rail mode is detected during cranking and the 
      engine achieves run speed, dry-rail mode minimum injection pressure and 
      maximum injection pulse-width values are held in force for this amount of 
      time. 
      CRI_peakhold_decay This is the time to wait beyond the peak-to-hold 
      transition before recharge is re-enabled during the hold phase if 
      'CRI_hold_recharge' is enabled. 
      CRI_peak_time_max Injector peak maximum time 
      CRI_peak_time_min Injector peak minimum time 
      CRI_pi1main_margin Common Rail Injection: Pilot 1 - Main margin 
      CRI_pi2main_margin Common Rail Injection: Pilot 2 - Main margin 
      CRI_pi2pi1_margin Common Rail Injection: Pilot 2 - Pilot 1 margin 
      CRI_pilot1_priority0 If a conflict exists in the pilot 1/2 specifications, 
      the event selected here will receive priority and the other event will be 
      killed. 
      CRI_pilot1_priority1 Pilot 1/2 conflict priority - Diesel engine operating 
      mode 1. If a conflict exists in the pilot 1/2 specifications, the event 
      selected here will receive priority and the other event will be killed. 
      CRI_pilot1_priority2 Pilot 1/2 conflict priority - Diesel engine operating 
      mode 2. If a conflict exists in the pilot 1/2 specifications, the event 
      selected here will receive priority and the other event will be killed. 
      CRI_pilot1_priority3 Pilot 1/2 conflict priority - Diesel engine operating

      CRI_pilot1_priority4 Pilot 1/2 conflict priority - Diesel engine operating

      selected here will receive priority and the other event will be killed. 
      CRI_pilot1_priority5 Pilot 1/2 conflict priority - Diesel engine operating

      CRI_po1po2_margin Common Rail Injection: Post 2 - Post 1 margin 
      CRI_Prail_actual low-passed version of CRI_Prail_act_raw in bar 
      CRI_Prail_act_ediLP This is the low-pass filter constant used for the 
      actual rail pressure in the rail pressure derivative calculation chain. It 
      is in effect an 'input' filter constant used on the actual pressure. 
      CRI_Prail_act_LP This is the low-pass filter constant used for the actual 
      rail pressure. The low-passed value resulting from the use of this time 
      constant is used throughout the control algorithms and in particular in 
      the 'proportional' and 'integral' signal chains for IMV control. 
      CRI_Prail_act_raw Non lowpass filtered version of the actual measured 
      diesel rail pressure. 
      CRI_Prail_cld common-rail cold pressure target offset in bar 
      CRI_Prail_edot common-rail pressure tracking error derivative in bar/ms = 
      Kbar/sec 
      CRI_Prail_edot_LP rail pressure edot in bar/ms = Kbar/sec 
      CRI_Prail_edot_n Rail pressure edot interpolation (Pressure tracking error 
      derivative calculation linear least-squares window). More points yields a 
      quieter and more accurate derivative, but introduces more time lag. Fewer 
      points has the opposite effect. This value must be <= 20 ms. 
      CRI_Prail_ena CRI fuel rail pressure sensor input selection switch 
      CRI_Prail_hyst Once the rail pressure is >= CRI_Prail_min and is 
      considered valid for injection, the pressure must drop below 
      (CRI_Prail_min-CRI_Prail_hyst) in order to be considered invalid. 
      CRI_Prail_min The rail pressure must rise above this limit in order for 
      injections to initiate. 
      CRI_Prail_min_a This is the final instantaneous minimum rail pressure 
      threshold to allow injection including all hysteresis and normal/dryrail 
      detection influences. 
      CRI_Prail_targdz_LP This is the 2nd-stage time constant for a 2nd-order 
      low-pass filter used for computing the target rail pressure with a 
      'deadzone' smoothing effect. If the instantaneous target and the smoothed 
      target differ by less than the 'CRI_Prail_targ_dz' amount, then this 
      2nd-stage is applied - otherwise the smoothed target is set equal to the 
      2nd stage. 
      CRI_Prail_target CRI fuel rail target pressure 
      CRI_Prail_targ_dz Within this deadzone +/- band, a 2nd-order low-pass 
      filter will be applied to the rail pressure command extracted from the 
      rail pressure target table. Outside of this band, only the first stage of 
      the low-pass will be applied yielding a 1st-order filter. The 
      'CRI_Prail_targdz_LP' time constant is for the 2nd-stage, and the 
      'CRI_Prail_targ_LP' time constant is for the 1st-stage. 
      CRI_Prail_targ_LP This is the low-pass filter constant used for computing 
      the target rail pressure once the 'raw' value has been computed from the 
      calibration tables. 
      CRI_Prail_targ_raw Non lowpass filtered version of the diesel rail 
      pressure target. 
      CRI_pulseoff_force Current forced-off pulse status 
      CRI_pulseoff_hyst To keep from entering a limit-cycle when the forced 
      pulse disabling tables are used (on these tables, the active cell with the 
      most focus is used, instead of interpolation), a hysteresis is applied to 
      the x and y axis lookups. 
      For example, assume the following along the x-axis (the same behavior is 
      true along the y-axis):

      a) Fuel load increases from -14.9 mg/cyl.
      b) Fuel load then oscillates between 14.9-15.1 mg/cyl.
      c) A 2% hysteresis is specified.
      Then, once the active x-cell focus transitions from the 1 mg/cyl to the 2 
      mg/cyl block (which occurs when the load exceeds 15 mg/cyl), it will not 
      return to the 1 mg/cyl block until it has >= 50% + hysteresis, or 52% of 
      the focus.

      In terms of fuel load, after the fuel load exceeds 15 mg/cyl and the 
      active cell changes from the 1 to 2 mg/cyl entry, it must drop to 15 - 
      (2-1)/1*2% = 14.8 mg/cyl before the 1 mg/cyl entry becomes the 'active' 
      cell. 
      CRI_pulseoff_slct0 Forced injection disabling behavior selector - Diesel 
      engine operation mode 0 
      CRI_pulseoff_slct1 Forced injection disabling behavior selector - Diesel 
      engine operation mode 1 
      CRI_pulseoff_slct2 Forced injection disabling behavior selector - Diesel 
      engine operation mode 2 
      CRI_pulseoff_slct3 Forced injection disabling behavior selector - Diesel 
      engine operation mode 3 
      CRI_pulseoff_slct4 Forced injection disabling behavior selector - Diesel 
      engine operation mode 4 
      CRI_pulseoff_slct5 Forced injection disabling behavior selector - Diesel 
      engine operation mode 5 
      CRI_pulseoff_slct6 Forced injection disabling behavior selector - Diesel 
      engine operation mode 6 
      CRI_pulseoff_slct7 Forced injection disabling behavior selector - Diesel 
      engine operation mode 7 
      CRI_pulseoff_slct8 Forced injection disabling behavior selector - Diesel 
      engine operation mode 8 
      CRI_pulseoff_slct9 Forced injection disabling behavior selector - Diesel 
      engine operation mode 9 
      CRI_purge This switch controls a 'General' fuel-rail air purge function 
      which is always actively monitoring fuel rail pressure during cranking and 
      can react with a purge cycle following a specified low-pressure cranking 
      validation wait. This is different than 'Green-engine' rail purge which is 
      initiated at cranking on a one-shot manually (or zero-hour) enabled basis 
      without requiring an extended low-pressure cranking situation before 
      initiation.
      NOTE: These 2 modes (General and Green-engine) are independent and can be 
      enabled separately or at the same time. 
      CRI_purge_accel_limit Reduce the purge level it this filtered crankshaft 
      acceleration limit is satisfied 
      CRI_purge_active logical indicating if rail purge mode is currently active 

      CRI_purge_cranktime Enable the purge function using crank time instead of 
      a fuel sensor 
      CRI_purge_cycwait In general (non green-engine) rail air purge mode, if 
      the rail pressure is below CRI_purge_Plower, then the rail will be 
      validated as requiring purging after the engine cranks for this number of 
      engine cycles. 
      CRI_purge_Plower If any of the rail air purge modes is enabled and the 
      rail pressure is below this (lower) level for CRI_purge_cycwait engine 
      cycles during cranking, then the rail is assumed to require purging. 
      CRI_purge_Pupper If any of the rail air purge modes is enabled, as the 
      pressure rises above this (upper) level after initiation of rail purge, 
      the purge operation is terminated and normal cranking injections are 
      allowed. 
      CRI_purge_rpm_limit Reduce the purge level if this rpm limit is satisfied 
      CRI_purge_spkdis logical indicating that spark is currently disabled 
      during purge operations 
      CRI_purge_spkpct If a time-out is specified for fuel rail purge, this 
      value sets the fraction of that time (starting from the beginning) that 
      spark will be inhibited. 0% allows normal spark throughout the purge 
      pulse, and 100% inhibits spark for the full duration of the purge pulse - 
      or until the pulse is prematurely terminated due to other factors such as 
      pressure-rise, ... 
      CRI_purge_T2 Purge initiated after T2 seconds of cranking 
      CRI_purge_T3 Ramp up to the normal purge settings over T3 
      CRI_purge_T4 Hold the normal purge settings for T4 
      CRI_purge_T5 Ramp up to the advanced purge settings over T5 
      CRI_purge_T6 Hold the advanced purge settings for T6 
      CRI_purge_tmr This is the live ms uptimer that clocks railpurge events. 
      CRI_purge_tout This is the maximum time duration in ms of a rail-purge 
      injector on-time event during cranking.

      at the beginning of injection. It is internally limited to 89.2 volts.

      CrkTT_delt_rpm This is the delta-rpm above idle over which any active 
      'Crank Timing Decay' associated crank ignition timing will be rolled off 
      toward normal ignition timing.

      spark timing adjustments will also be slewed in during the crank-to-run 
      transition.

      CTMA_FSO_CBT If "CTM FSO mode" is set to 'Single-Point', this constant 
      value is used instead of the air mass flow rate table-based steady-state 
      catalyst bed temperature when fuel shutoff is active. 
      CTMA_FSO_cold_AAT Parameter is the cold ambient air temperature for 
      table-based catalyst temperature monitoring during fuel shutoff. Only 
      applicable when "CTM FSO mode" is set to 'Table-Based'. 
      CTMA_FSO_cold_CBT Parameter is the cold ambient steady-state catalyst bed 
      temperature for table-based catalyst temperature monitoring during fuel 
      shutoff. Only applicable when "CTM FSO mode" is set to 'Table-Based'. 
      CTMA_FSO_hot_AAT Parameter is the hot ambient air temperature for 
      table-based catalyst temperature monitoring during fuel shutoff. Only 
      applicable when "CTM FSO mode" is set to 'Table-Based'. 
      CTMA_FSO_hot_CBT Parameter is the hot ambient steady-state catalyst bed 
      temperature for table-based catalyst temperature monitoring during fuel 
      shutoff. Only applicable when "CTM FSO mode" is set to 'Table-Based'. 
      CTMA_FSO_mode Parameter configures the catalyst temperature monitor when 
      fuel shutoff is active. When set to 'Single-Point', the monitor will use 
      the "CTM FSO single-point steady-state CBT" and "CTM FSO single-point CBT 
      tau" parameter values. When set to 'Table-Based', the following parameters 
      are used:
      "CTM FSO CBT Tau Table"
      "CTM FSO table Cold AAT"
      "CTM FSO table Hot AAT"
      "CTM FSO table steady-state CBT - Cold AAT"
      "CTM FSO table steady-state CBT - Hot AAT" 
      CTMA_FSO_tau If "CTM FSO mode" is set to 'Single-Point', this constant 
      value is used for the CBT tau when fuel shutoff is active.

      (newer calibrations).

      CVCSP_ena Parameter switch which assigns the sensor input port for 
      measuring crankcase clean side pressure. 
      CVCSP_Paux_cal Selects the auxiliary pressure calibration table for the 
      crankcase clean side pressure sensor. 
      CVCSP_tau This is the low-pass time constant in ms applied to the 
      crankcase clean side pressure sensor. It is used to filter out engine 
      pulsations. 
      CVCSP_type Selects the sensor type for the crankcase clean side pressure 
      sensor - absolute or differential. 
      CVCS_CVP_delta_lmt The minimum required change in clean-side CVP during a 
      diagnostic period. Only applicable when "CVCS/CVDS diagnostic method" is 
      set to 'Method #2'. 
      CVCS_CVP_diff_max The maximum measured change in clean-side CVP during the 
      previous CVCS/CVDS diagnostic period. 
      CVCS_discon_mdota_max This parameter specifies the maximum air mass flow 
      required to execute the crankcase ventilation clean side disconnected 
      diagnostic. 
      CVCS_discon_mdota_min This parameter specifies the minimum air mass flow 
      required to execute the crankcase ventilation clean side disconnected 
      diagnostic. 
      CVCS_discon_pct This parameter specifies the crankcase pressure percentage 
      threshold for the crankcase ventilation clean side disconnected 
      diagnostic. 
      CVCS_discon_RPM_max This parameter specifies the maximum engine speed 
      allowed to execute the crankcase ventilation clean side disconnected 
      diagnostic. 
      CVCS_discon_tbl This parameter specifies which pressure column in the 
      "Crankcase Expected Pressure" table to reference when applying the 
      crankcase pressure percentage threshold for the crankcase ventilation 
      clean side disconnected diagnostic. 
      CVCS_discon_test This parameter specifies the pressure threshold 
      comparison operator for execution of the crankcase ventilation clean side 
      disconnected diagnostic. 
      CVCS_fault_count Counter for the number of failed CVCS diagnostic periods. 
      Counter increases whenever entry conditions are satisfied and the change 
      in clean-side CVP is below the fault limit at the end of a CVCS diagnostic 
      period. 
      CVdP_dP1_d This parameter stores the current pressure 1 lookup value for 
      the "Crankcase Expected Pressure" table. 
      CVdP_dP1_location Selects the crankcase pressure sensor associated with 
      the "Pressure 1 (psi)" column of the 'Crankcase Expected Pressure" table. 
      CVdP_dP1_pcta This parameter stores the actual pressure delta from the 
      expected pressure 1 table lookup value. 
      CVdP_dP2_d This parameter stores the current pressure 2 lookup value for 
      the "Crankcase Expected Pressure" table. 
      CVdP_dP2_location Selects the crankcase pressure sensor associated with 
      the "Pressure 2 (psi)" column of the 'Crankcase Expected Pressure" table. 
      CVdP_dP2_pcta This parameter stores the actual pressure delta from the 
      expected pressure 2 table lookup value. 
      CVDSP_ena Parameter switch which assigns the sensor input port for

      CVP1 This parameter stores the current CVP1 sensor pressure in psia.

      threshold for the crankcase pressure 1 high diagnostic.

      CVP_abs_def The default crankcase pressure for absolute sensors used as an 
      estimate when actual sensor input is not available. 
      CVP_dP_def The default crankcase pressure for differential sensors used as 
      an estimate when actual sensor input is not available. 
      CV_diag_rst_time The length of a diagnostic period for CVCS/CVDS 
      diagnostic method #2. The ECU records the minimum and maximum values of 
      clean-side CVP, dirty-side CVP, and air mass flow during this time period. 
      When diagnostic period ends, the ECU calculates the maximum change in the 
      values and conducts the diagnostic. Only applicable when "CVCS/CVDS 
      diagnostic method" is set to 'Method #2'. 
      CV_diag_tmr Diagnostic timer for CVCS/CVDS diagnostic method #2. 
      CV_discon_method Parameter determines the diagnostic method for the 
      "Crankcase ventilation clean side disconnected" and "Crankcase ventilation 
      dirty side disconnected" faults. When set to 'Method #2', the CV fault 
      count limit (CV_fault_limit_cnt) is used to latch/unlatch the faults. Set 
      each fault's latch/unlatch times to small values since they are still 
      used, but are not the primary mechanism for latching/unlatching the fault. 
      A latch/unlatch time of 0.050 seconds is recommended. An unlatch time of 0 
      is special and should only be used if the fault should never unlatch. 
      CV_fault_limit_cnt Parameter is the number failed diagnostic periods 
      required to latch the CVCS/CVDS fault. Also, the number of passed 
      diagnostic periods required to unlatch the CVCS/CVDS fault. Set each 
      fault's latch/unlatch times to small values since they are still used, but 
      are not the primary mechanism for latching/unlatching the faults. A 
      latch/unlatch time of 0.050 seconds is recommended. An unlatch time of 0 
      is special and should only be used if the fault should never unlatch. Only 
      applicable when "CVCS/CVDS diagnostic method" is set to 'Method #2'. 
      CV_mdot_a_diff_max The maximum measured change in air mass flow during the 
      previous CVCS/CVDS diagnostic period. 
      CV_mdot_delta_lmt The minimum required change in air mass flow during a 
      diagnostic period. Only applicable when "CVCS/CVDS diagnostic method" is 
      set to 'Method #2'.

      accumulator 
      CWT2_Qload_ss 2-D table based steady-state relative CWT correction

      calibration mode for the cylinder wall heating model constant and tau 
      values when the fuel type is gasoline. Diesel engines will also use this 
      parameter.

      calibration mode for the cylinder wall heating model constant and tau 
      values when the fuel type is LPG. 
      CWT_mode_NG This mode switch selects either single-point or table-based 
      calibration mode for the cylinder wall heating model constant and tau 
      values when the fuel type is NG.

      CylTempSwt_chan Selects the digital input channel used for a cylinder 
      temperature switch. 
      CylTempSwt_chan_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the input, this value 
      determines the active logic state(s). An active state for this input 
      indicates that the differential pressure across the air filter is high. 
      The Default values are:

      Aux DIG1 = Gnd
      Aux DIG2 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG3 = Gnd
      Aux DIG4 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG5 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG6 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG7 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG8 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG9 = Gnd
      Aux DIG10 = Gnd
      Aux DIG11 = Gnd
      Aux DIG12 = Gnd
      Aux DIG13 = Gnd
      Aux DIG14 = Gnd
      Aux DIG15 = Gnd
      Aux DIG16 = Gnd
      Aux DIG17 = Gnd
      Aux DIG18 = Gnd
      Aux DIG19 = Gnd
      Gov1 = Gnd
      Gov2 = Gnd

      DBW2_output This switch can be used to control a secondary throttle on the 
      H-bridge A or B output. The secondary throttle gets its command from the 
      primary throttle, but performs independent diagnostics and closed-loop 
      control. 
      DBW_ctl_cmd Drive-by-wire H-bridge feedback control output fraction (%) 
      DBW_ctl_max Maximum feedback authority 
      DBW_ctl_min Minimum feedback authority 
      DBW_device_status DBW H-bridge device status (No support, Disabled, Fault, 
      or OK) 
      DBW_fault_Ilim DBW drive current high diagnostic: DBW electrical model 
      current threshold entry condition 
      DBW_FB_cmd_LP LPF timer constant used for Smart Actuator output 
      DBW_IAC_mode "DBW / IAC configuration": This switch determines whether the 
      engine is configured for a drive-by-wire throttle (DBW) or a limited 
      authority idle air control (IAC) motor. 
      DBW_iFB_amps DBW (measured) current feedback (amps) 
      DBW_iFB_raw DBW (measured) current feedback (unconverted raw volts) 
      DBW_output_Hz The H-bridge output has a lower-limit of approximately 310 
      Hz in full-bridge mode, and 1 Hz in half-bridge mode. NOTE: Frequencies 
      above 4 KHz must be approved by EControls Engineering to avoid excessive 
      H-bridge driver heating. 
      DBW_output_invert Outputs the following:
      +100% duty-cycle for a -100% position command
      -100% duty-cycle for a +100% position command

      Note that smart-bridge outputs are limited to positive values. 
      DBW_output_type Select the type of drive output. Generally, this should 
      always be set to full-bridge mode. However, if a smart throttle (or 
      similar) actuator is present, smart half-bridge mode will output a 
      commanded position as a 0-100% duty-cycle on the + leg of the H-bridge 
      output, without implementing a closed-loop position control algorithm. The 
      throttle feedback is still available, and faults will still function 
      normally. The (dumb) half-bridge mode can be used to output a 0-100% full 
      closed-loop output on the + leg of the H-bridge output. 
      DBW_pot1_closed_EE DBW PS1 idle/closed 
      DBW_pot1_open_EE DBW PS1 full/open 
      DBW_pot2_closed_EE DBW PS2 idle/closed 
      DBW_pot2_open_EE DBW PS2 full/open 
      DBW_spring_0 DBW Actuator spring load at 0% 
      DBW_spring_100 DBW Actuator spring load at 100% 
      DBW_test_ena DBW test mode enable 
      DBW_toggle_cmd1 H-Bridge Manual Mode - DBW toggle command 1 
      DBW_toggle_cmd2 H-Bridge Manual Mode - DBW toggle command 2 
      DBW_toggle_ena H-Bridge Manual Mode - DBW toggle enable 
      DBW_toggle_ms H-Bridge Manual Mode - DBW toggle period 
      DBW_Vcomp_max This is the maximum voltage for the DBW voltage compensation 
      correction. Voltages >= this voltage will not result in a further 
      reduction in the HB control drive beyond min/max. Set max=min to eliminate 
      voltage compensation. 
      DBW_Vcomp_min This is the standard/minimum voltage for the DBW voltage 
      compensation correction. Voltages <= this voltage will not result in a 
      change in the HB control drive. 
      deltaBP_MAP Barometric pressure configuration: Positive fixed offset 
      between the observed MAP during BP sampling conditions and the actual BP. 
      This is due to the non-zero pressure drop across the throttle body during 
      running engine conditions. 
      DENIED2_cnt Denied activity count (CAN 2) 
      DENIED2_last_PGN Requested PGN is not enabled in calibration 
      DENIED2_last_RA Last DENIED Receiver Address - CAN2 
      DENIED2_last_SA Last DENIED Source Address - CAN2 
      DENIED3_cnt Denied activity count (CAN 3) 
      DENIED3_last_PGN Requested PGN is not enabled in calibration 
      DENIED3_last_RA Last DENIED Receiver Address - CAN3 
      DENIED3_last_SA Last DENIED Source Address - CAN3 
      DENIED_cnt DENIED activity count - CAN1 
      DENIED_last_PGN Requested PGN is not enabled in calibration 
      DENIED_last_RA Last DENIED Receiver Address - CAN1 
      DENIED_last_SA Last DENIED Source Address - CAN1 
      DEPR_compile_date IEPR parameter 
      DEPR_compile_str IEPR parameter 
      DEPR_HistFaultCnts IEPR parameter 
      DEPR_MIL_byte IEPR parameter 
      DEPR_revision IEPR parameter 
      DEPR_strtspk_active Flag indicating DEPR spark inhibit mode is active. 
      Flag is not cleared until certain conditions are met (valid pressure 
      detected, certain number of engine cycles met, etc) 
      DEPR_strtspk_cycles DEPR starting spark inhibit is engaged for delta-P 
      pressures between the low and high trigger levels. Inhibit ceases after 
      the specified number of cycles. 
      DEPR_strtspk_ena Enables/disables start-spark inhibit feature on DEPR 
      applications. This feature is not intended for use on standard EPR/MJ 
      applications and should be disabled. If this feature is set to 'Enabled: 
      Fuel+Start Cmd', the fuel cycle parameters below must be satisfied AND a 
      valid starter command (either using the pass-through/auto-crank trigger or 
      the start PWM detection feature on the 'Starting' page) must be detected 
      before the spark will engage. 
      DEPR_strtspk_hitrig DEPR starting spark inhibit is engaged for delta-P 
      pressures between the low and high trigger levels. Inhibit ceases after 
      the specified number of cycles. 
      DEPR_strtspk_lotrig DEPR starting spark inhibit is engaged for delta-P 
      pressures between the low and high trigger levels. Inhibit ceases after 
      the specified number of cycles. 
      DEPR_strtspk_window Initial pressure monitoring window. If the pressure is 
      100% valid throughout this monitoring window, then spark inhibit is 
      inactive. 
      DEPR_SVN_revision IEPR parameter 
      DEPR_TCalID IEPR parameter 
      DEPR_TID_def IEPR parameter 
      DEPR_TSoftID_def IEPR parameter 
      derate1 Specifies the maximum TPS % when derate 1 is active. This setting 
      is only applicable when operating in drive-by-wire mode and requires the 
      "Power derate 1 DBW limit source" setting to be set to 'Power derate max 
      TPS'. 
      DERATE1_active Logical indicating on-going derate1 activity 
      derate1_dbw_mode Specifies the limit value to use for power derate when 
      operating in drive-by-wire mode.

      When set to 'Power derate max TPS', the engine will be derated by limiting 
      the TPS % to the value specified by the "Power derate 1 max TPS (DBW 
      mode)" setting.

      When set to one of the table options, the engine will be derated by 
      limiting the load %. The load limit % will be obtained from the applicable 
      "Engine Load-Limiting Calibration" "Speed-Based Load Limit" table using 
      the current RPM. The table options do not require the "Load-limiting 
      system" to be enabled. 
      derate1_EGR_minnom -1 : EGR off(-1, 0) : EGR command from interpolation 
      between off and min table
      0 : EGR command from min table(0, 1) : EGR command from interpolation 
      between min and nominal tables
      1 : EGR command from nominal table 
      derate1_FSO_ena FSO enable in derate 1 mode 
      derate1_rev_lim In manual throttle (IAC) mode, a rev limit is used for 
      faults requesting a power derate 1 condition. This rev limit is typically 
      above the power derate 2 rev limit and the fault low rev limit values. 
      derate2 Specifies the maximum TPS % when derate 2 is active. This setting 
      is only applicable when operating in drive-by-wire mode and requires the 
      "Power derate 2 DBW limit source" setting to be set to 'Power derate max 
      TPS'. 
      DERATE2_active Logical indicating on-going derate2 activity 
      derate2_dbw_mode Specifies the limit value to use for power derate when 
      operating in drive-by-wire mode.

      When set to 'Power derate max TPS', the engine will be derated by limiting 
      the TPS % to the value specified by the "Power derate 2 max TPS (DBW 
      mode)" setting.

      When set to one of the table options, the engine will be derated by 
      limiting the load %. The load limit % will be obtained from the applicable 
      "Engine Load-Limiting Calibration" "Speed-Based Load Limit" table using 
      the current RPM. The table options do not require the "Load-limiting 
      system" to be enabled. 
      derate2_EGR_minnom -1 : EGR off(-1, 0) : EGR command from interpolation 
      between off and min table
      0 : EGR command from min table(0, 1) : EGR command from interpolation 
      between min and nominal tables
      1 : EGR command from nominal table 
      derate2_FSO_ena FSO enable in derate 2 mode 
      derate2_latch This switch determines whether or not a fault commanding a 
      low rev limit will stay latched for the remainder of the key-cycle or if 
      it will only be in effect during an active fault condition and while 
      unlatch engine conditions are not yet fulfilled. 
      derate2_rev_lim In manual throttle (IAC) mode, a rev limit is used for 
      faults requesting a power derate 2 condition. This rev limit is typically 
      below the power derate 1 rev limit and above the fault low rev limit. 
      DERATEblk_off A warning may cause a continuous output activation or a 
      blinking/pulsing output. The on/off times specify this behavior. For a 
      continuous-on output in an active state, simply set the off-time to zero 
      and the on-time to any value. 
      DERATEblk_on A warning may cause a continuous output activation or a 
      blinking/pulsing output. The on/off times specify this behavior. For a 
      continuous-on output in an active state, simply set the off-time to zero 
      and the on-time to any value. 
      DERATE_FPPlim Entry value: Current DBW based FPP/TPS command derate limit 
      (with slew control) 
      DERATE_FPPlim_rpm RPM equivalent limit corresponding to DERATE_FPPlim for 
      used in FORCED_IDLE condition used an all all-speed governor 
      DERATE_FPPlim_use Logical flag: Indicates that FORCED_IDLE condition is 
      valid and active 
      DERATE_lamp Output lamp associated with derate faults. 
      DERATE_loadlim The current load limit % based derate limit 
      DERATE_loadlim_slewd Indicates if slewing is active for load limit % 
      calculation 
      DERATE_loadlim_use Indicates if load limit % based derate limit is active 
      DERATE_NOx_active Active indication that NOx control system is requesting 
      a derate. 
      DERATE_TPSlim Entry value: Current DBW based TPS derate limit with slew 
      control 
      DERATE_TPSlim_use Logical used to indicate that the global code that 
      either of DERATE1/2 values are valid and are in force 
      DERATE_TPS_slew_dn This value controls how fast a fault triggered power 
      (TPS) derate, table-based load limit derate, or table-based load limit 
      fault inducement will slew down to its final value when it first becomes 
      engaged (this is a positive value). 
      DERATE_TPS_slew_up This value controls how fast a fault triggered power 
      (TPS) derate, table-based load limit derate, or table-based load limit 
      fault inducement slews away (out) when it disengages. 
      derate_unlatch_FPP If the activity duration for either power derate 2 or a 
      fault low rev limit is set to 'Active Fault and Engine State', then the 
      commanded foot-pedal (or throttle) position must drop below this value 
      once the fault has gone inactive in order to release the derated 
      condition. 
      derate_unlatch_RPM If the activity duration for either power derate 2 or a 
      fault low rev limit is set to 'Active Fault and Engine State', then the 
      engine speed must drop below this value once the fault has gone inactive 
      in order to release the derated condition. 
      DiagTempWUT_calc Parameter configures the expected warm-up time 
      calculation method for the 'Failed to reach diagnostics temperature' fault 
      on the Diagnostics page. When set to 'Single Time Axis (legacy)', only the 
      first time axis in the "Diag Enable Temp Warm-up Time" table is used. When 
      set to 'Dual Time Axis (AAT-based)', both time axes are used. See "Diag 
      Enable Temp Warm-up Time" table for further details. 
      diag_iupr_denom OBD persistent diagnostic IUPR denominator 
      diag_iupr_numer OBD persistent diagnostic IUPR numerator 
      diesel_altd_BP_hi Specifies the high altitude barometric pressure used to 
      calculate the linear mode selection altitude ratio for Diesel engine 
      altitude compensation. 
      diesel_altd_BP_std Specifies the standard altitude barometric pressure 
      used to calculate the linear mode selection altitude ratio for Diesel 
      engine altitude compensation. 
      diesel_altd_ena Enable for naturally-aspirated diesel fueling altitude 
      compensation 
      diesel_altd_LMS_hi Specifies the Diesel engine operating mode associated 
      with high altitude mode behavior table selection for air mass command, EGR 
      diluent command, fuel pressure command, injection quantities, and 
      injection timings. When this mode is active, the calculated altitude ratio 
      is used to interpolate between the tables selected for the standard 
      altitude mode (usually Standard) and the tables selected for this mode 
      (usually Alternate 1/2).

      This parameter is only applicable when "Diesel altitude compensation" is 
      set to 'Linear mode selection' for Diesel engines. 
      diesel_altd_LMS_pct Calculated altitude ratio of current barometric 
      pressure relative to the calibrated BP standard and BP high pressure 
      values. This ratio is used to interpolate between the tables selected for 
      standard altitude Diesel engine operation mode ("Linear mode selection - 
      standard" parameter) and those selected for high altitude operation mode 
      ("Linear mode selection - high altitude" parameter).

      This parameter is only applicable when "Diesel altitude compensation" is 
      set to 'Linear mode selection' for Diesel engines. 
      diesel_altd_LMS_std Specifies the Diesel engine operating mode associated 
      with standard altitude mode behavior table selection for air mass command, 
      EGR diluent command, fuel pressure command, injection quantities, and 
      injection timings. When this mode is active, the calculated altitude ratio 
      is used to interpolate between the tables selected for this mode (usually 
      Standard) and the tables selected for high altitude mode (usually 
      Alternate 1/2).

      This parameter is only applicable when "Diesel altitude compensation" is 
      set to 'Linear mode selection' for Diesel engines. 
      diesel_altd_LMS_torq The calculated max brake torque multiplier for LMS 
      altitude compensation on diesel engines. The max brake torque at the 
      current altitude is calculated by multiplying the max brake torque at 
      standard altitude by this multiplier. This multiplier is calculated as the 
      ratio of the 100% fuel load at current altitude to the 100% fuel load at 
      standard altitude for a given engine speed. This parameter is only 
      applicable when "Diesel altitude compensation" is set to 'Linear mode 
      selection' for Diesel engines. 
      diesel_altd_mult NA diesel altitude compensation load multiplier 
      diesel_lwld_comp_ena Enable for diesel low-load combustion chamber 
      temperature compensation 
      diesel_lwld_ini_wait Wait time to exit initial low-load state of diesel 
      low-load compensation 
      diesel_lwld_ld_thld Lower engine load threshold for diesel low-load 
      combustion chamber temperature compensation 
      diesel_lwld_low_slew Slew rate for compensation factor in low-load mode 
      diesel_lwld_low_wait Wait time before beginning compensation factor 
      slewing when entering low-load mode 
      diesel_lwld_nrm_slew Slew rate for compensation factor in normal mode 
      diesel_lwld_nrm_wait Wait time before beginning compensation factor 
      slewing when returning to normal mode 
      diesel_lwld_slewval Compensation factor for diesel low-load combustion 
      chamber temperature compensation 
      diesel_lwld_spd_thld Lower engine speed threshold for diesel low-load 
      combustion chamber temperature compensation 
      diesel_lwld_state Diesel low-load combustion chamber temperature 
      compensation state 
      diesel_lwld_timer Mode change delay timer for diesel low-load combustion 
      chamber temperature compensation 
      DIL_pct_xslct Obsoleted parameter 
      DIL_pct_xval For faster update of the red color highlighting on xaxis of 
      EGR 2D tables 
      DLOG_base_ptr ECM RAM address of data logger buffer 
      DOCT diesel oxidation catalyst (outlet) temperature in deg R 
      DOCT_ena Designates aux temperature sensor input for measuring Diesel 
      oxidation catalyst (DOCT) 
      DOCT_Taux_cal Auxiliary temperature calibration table selection for DOCT 
      DOCT_vdr diesel oxidation catalyst (outlet) temperature input pullup 
      resistor resistance 
      door_ntrlk Door interlock active logical indication (0=Inactive, 
      1=active=door open) 
      door_ntrlk_ena This switch controls which input a door interlock signal 
      (if any) will be detected on. If the door interlock signal is active, then 
      the engine will be locked at idle and the foot pedal input will be 
      ignored. 
      door_ntrlk_sense This switch controls how a door interlock signal input 
      will be interpreted. All inputs can either be 'Active' = 'Door 
      Interlocked' in either an open or non-open (grounded or +V) state.

      drivebrake_active Logical indicating driveline brake is active 
      drivebrake_chan This output channel on the ECM is actuated according to 
      the driveline brake mode described above. This is typically a low-side 
      output drive. 
      drivebrake_min_ECT Sets the minimum ECT required to activate the Driveline 
      brake.

      NOTES: 'Retarder disabled by minimum ECT' must be set to YES for this 
      minimum ECT to be honored. The Driveline brake minimum ECT requirement may 
      be disabled by the 'Retarder run time override ECT'. 
      drivebrake_mode The driveline braking function can be enabled in one of 
      two modes:
      1) Engine-Brake or Compression-Brake mode:
      This mode turns an output on the ECM to the ON state whenever 
      throttle-open fuel shutoff is commanded.
      2) Transmission Retarder mode:
      This mode turns an output on the ECM to the ON state whenever the foot 
      pedal is detected at the idle position and the engine rpm is above the 
      normal min governor speed plus the fuel shutoff delta rpm.Typically, both 
      driveline braking functions are wired such that a switch at the dashboard 
      is in series with the ECM output so that the driver can selectively 
      disabled this function. 
      drivebrake_off_loVf Brake output open / ground short diagnostic: Low-side 
      feedback max limit (% Vbat) 
      drivebrake_on_hiVf Brake output short to power diagnostic: Low-side 
      feedback min limit (% Vbat) 
      drivebrake_source source address for unit responsible for active driveline 
      braking, used in SPN 1480 
      drivebrake_torq_max Estimated max retard (available) torque percent of 
      reference torque for the driveline brake (compression or transmission) 
      drivebrake_torq_pct Drivebrake torque percent 
      drvtrim_angle Marine drive trim angle in degrees

      dwell_adpt_ena Dwell current control 
      dwell_a_max Dwell adapt maximum delta 
      dwell_a_min Dwell adapt minimum delta 
      dwell_a_prefire_samp This parameter determines when the dwell current is 
      sampled. It is measured in microseconds prior to the falling (firing) edge 
      of the spark dwell. 
      dwell_crk_add Dwell crank add term (when rpm is less than dwell_crk_rpm) 
      dwell_crk_max_accel Enter the maximum engine acceleration during 
      engine-crank conditions. This value is used to calculate a minimum 
      required dwell for low-tooth count wheels. Enter '0' to use the default 
      crnak-cam module dwell. This feature is currently only active on GM 
      distributor-based configurations. 
      dwell_crk_min Minimum crank dwell 
      dwell_crk_rpm Adaptive dwell is disabled while engine speed is less than 
      this threshold. Extra dwell is inserted to improve spark timing accuracy 
      during low-speed high-acceleration conditions. 
      dwell_def Default value of Dwell timing (ms) 
      dwell_d_amp The adapt target current will be adjusted using the Dwell 
      Adapt Target Multiplier RPM / MAP table. This allows the current target to 
      be load and speed dependent. When the engine is running, the resulting 
      adjusted current value is checked to ensure it is not < 4.5 amps and is 
      not > 10 amps. 
      dwell_d_amp_ls Dwell load/speed (adjusted)(amps) 
      dwell_extmod_cnt rolling external spark module diagnostic sample count 
      dwell_extmod_coils 1D Table: Input is firing order or cylinder number, 
      output is coil diagnostic voltage 
      dwell_extmod_diag instantaneous diagnostic spark module off-sample voltage 

      dwell_inc_K Dwell adapt gain 
      dwell_inc_max Dwell adapt maximum step 
      dwell_ls_mult 2D Interpolation Table: Given engine rpm and load (MAP), 
      output is the Dwell Adaptive target multiplier 
      dwell_ls_mult_MAP 2D interpolation table MAP (X-axis) input values 
      dwell_ls_mult_rpm 2D interpolation table rpm (y-axis) input values 
      dwell_max Dwell maximum in ms 
      dwell_min Dwell minimum in ms 
      dwell_min_Vbat Adaptive dwell minimum battery voltage requirement 
      dwell_nom_tbl 1D Interpolation Table: Given the current value of VBat, the 
      output is the nominal dwell in ms 
      dwell_OL Base dwell 
      dwell_open_crkmax Primary Loop Open or Low-Side Short to Ground 
      diagnostic: If dwell current control = 'Monitor Only,' this is the crank 
      dwell maximum threshold 
      dwell_open_i Dwell open current 
      dwell_samp_cnt Dwell adapt samples 
      dwell_sense10_source Firing order 10 for Dwell Current Monitoring/Sampling 
      table 
      dwell_sense11_source Firing order 11 for Dwell Current Monitoring/Sampling 
      table

      dwell_shorted Set the dwell used while the 'Primary Coil Shorted' 
      diagnostic is Active and Latched.

      If this value is set to 0, the faulted spark coil will not be fired. 

      If this value is set to 0 and 'Dwell Current Control' is Adaptive Dwell, 
      the fault will remain active and latched for the remainder of the key 
      cycle. 
      dwell_short_i Coil current measurement taken at or near the start of a 
      coil dwell event 
      dwell_Vbat_tbl 1D interpolation table Vbat input values 
      EBC1_hybrid_mode This setting should only be used in special 
      circumstances, under the advisement of an EControls calibration engineer. 
      When enabled, it provides continued rpm reporting during conditions where 
      EBC1 remote stop is asserted intermittently or the key switch is toggled 
      during an EBC1 remote stop. 
      EBP Exhaust back pressure 
      EBPs Standard Exhaust Back Pressure (EBP) value. 
      EBPs_C_exh Calibration parameter. Multiply this parameter by the square of 
      the exhaust volumetric flow rate generates the (standard) gauge version of 
      EBPs. If the mpsig option is selected, this value must be less than 3.0 
      mpsig/(l/s)^2. 
      EBPs_gauge_def Defines gage pressure at the time testing was conducted. 
      This will stay fixed with any future updates to the EBP estimation model. 
      EBP_acc EBP sensor value after lowpass 
      EBP_C_exh "EBP flow rate constant": Multiply this parameter by the square 
      of the exhaust volumetric flow rate generates the gauge version of EBP. If 
      the mpsig option is selected, this value must be less than 3.0 
      mpsig/(l/s)^2. 
      EBP_def Default exhaust back pressure (EBP) value 
      EBP_ena Parameter switch which assigns sensor input port for measuring 
      Exhaust back pressur (EBP) 
      EBP_est_ena Parameter switch which identifies if EBP is to be estimated 
      (Enabled) and/or set to a default value 
      EBP_gauge Exhaust Back Pressure (gauge version) 
      EBP_gauge_def Default (gage) version of EBP: Measured EBP at maximum 
      airflow condition 
      EBP_mpsi_select In order to use the mpsig setting, the volumetric exhaust 
      flow must be less than 819 L/s (or the exhaust back pressure will be 
      limited to the value at 819 L/s). 
      EBP_Paux_cal Exhaust back pressure (EBP) sensor auxiliary pressure 
      calibration table select 
      EBP_raw Raw EBP pressure prior to lowpass 
      EBP_tau This is the low-pass time constant in ms applied to the EBP 
      sensor. It is used to filter out engine pulsations. 
      EBP_T_select EGT / TOT local temperature selection switch: Parameter 
      switch to determine which temperature is utilized to compute the Exhaust 
      Specific Volume 
      ECam_coil_Id Cam2 (Exhaust) coil desired current 
      ECam_coil_Imax Cam2 (Exhaust) coil integrator max gain 
      ECam_coil_Imin Cam2 (Exhaust) coil integrator minimum gain 
      ECam_coil_Inom ECam nominal current 
      ECam_coil_KTR Cam2 (Exhaust) coil temperature constant (ohms/deg F) 
      ECam_coil_R Cam2 (Exhaust) coil resistance 
      ECam_coil_Rmax Cam2 (Exhaust) coil max resistance 
      ECam_coil_Rmin Cam2 (Exhaust) coil min resistance 
      ECam_coil_Rnom Cam2 (Exhaust) coil nominal resistance 
      ECam_coil_Tnom Cam2 (Exhaust) coil nominal resistance temperature 
      ECam_control Cam2 (Exhaust) control command 
      ECam_control_cal This switch controls the calibration parameter source for 
      Cam2 control. Normally, Cam2 is the exhaust cam and is configured to use 
      the exhaust valve timing table as well as the exhaust PID control 
      parameters. However, if this switch is set to 'Intake / Cam1' then Cam2 
      targets the same timing as Cam1 and uses the same PID control gains. This 
      switch would typically be set to 'Intake / Cam1' for V engines with 
      individual single variable overhead cams per bank. 
      ECam_I_acc Cam2 (Exhaust) integrator value 
      ECam_I_max ECam Integrator max (limit) 
      ECam_I_min ECam Integrator min (limit) 
      ECam_Ki ECam Integrator Gain 
      ECam_Kp ECam Proportional Gain 
      ECam_maxerr Exhaust cam position diagnostic: Cam2 (Exhaust) position error 
      (CAD) threshold entry condition 
      ECam_PWM_DC Cam2 (Exhaust) control PWM duty cycle (DC) 
      ECam_PWM_mode Cam2 (Exhaust) PWM mode (Automatic, Manual Timing, Manual 
      DC) 
      ECam_PWM_taud Cam2 (Exhaust) control PWM low-pass time constant 
      ECam_ref_nom Cam2 (Exhaust) nominal pulse alignment 
      ECam_ref_offset Specifies the absolute CAD offset for the stable edge 
      closest to TDC (reference pulse). 
      ECam_ref_timing Cam2 (Exhaust) nominal valve closing 
      ECam_samp_BTDC Cam2 (Exhaust) edge sample (CAD BTDC) 
      ECam_timing_a Cam2 (Exhaust) close actual (CAD BTDC) 
      ECam_timing_ctrl CAM2/ECam timing control FLAG. Set to Disabled and/or can 
      be set to the D/A port 
      ECam_timing_d Cam2 (Exhaust) close target (CAD BTDC) 
      ECL_chan Selects the digital input channel used for an engine coolant 
      level sensor. 
      ECL_chan_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the input, this value 
      determines the active logic state(s). An active state for this input 
      indicates that the coolant level is normal. An inactive state indicates 
      that the coolant level is low. The Default values are:

      Aux DIG1 = Gnd
      Aux DIG2 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG3 = Gnd
      Aux DIG4 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG5 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG6 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG7 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG8 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG9 = Gnd
      Aux DIG10 = Gnd
      Aux DIG11 = Gnd
      Aux DIG12 = Gnd
      Aux DIG13 = Gnd
      Aux DIG14 = Gnd
      Aux DIG15 = Gnd
      Aux DIG16 = Gnd
      Aux DIG17 = Gnd
      Aux DIG18 = Gnd
      Aux DIG19 = Gnd
      Gov1 = Gnd
      Gov2 = Gnd 
      ECL_inhibit_start Indicates whether engine start is currently inhibited 
      due to a low coolant level. 
      ECL_start_lock_ena If enabled, the engine will not be allowed to start 
      when the engine coolant level sensor indicates a low coolant level. 
      ecm_multi_ECT Select whether the designated input/output is attached to 
      both the master and slave ECM, or only the master ECM. For inputs attached 
      only to the master ECM, the data is shared with the slave ECM via CAN2. 
      For outputs attached only to the master ECM, the pins are still actuated 
      on the slave ECM (they are assumed to be open), however, fault conditions 
      are ignored and the corresponding faults will not set. 
      ecm_multi_MIL Select whether the designated input/output is attached to 
      both the master and slave ECM, or only the master ECM. For inputs attached 
      only to the master ECM, the data is shared with the slave ECM via CAN2. 
      For outputs attached only to the master ECM, the pins are still actuated 
      on the slave ECM (they are assumed to be open), however, fault conditions 
      are ignored and the corresponding faults will not set. 
      ecm_multi_OILP Select whether the designated input/output is attached to 
      both the master and slave ECM, or only the master ECM. For inputs attached 
      only to the master ECM, the data is shared with the slave ECM via CAN2. 
      For outputs attached only to the master ECM, the pins are still actuated 
      on the slave ECM (they are assumed to be open), however, fault conditions 
      are ignored and the corresponding faults will not set. 
      ecm_multi_RELAY Select whether the designated input/output is attached to 
      both the master and slave ECM, or only the master ECM. For inputs attached 
      only to the master ECM, the data is shared with the slave ECM via CAN2. 
      For outputs attached only to the master ECM, the pins are still actuated 
      on the slave ECM (they are assumed to be open), however, fault conditions 
      are ignored and the corresponding faults will not set. 
      ecm_multi_RELAY_wait Select whether verification of active master/slave 
      CAN communication from the slave is required before the master activates 
      its relay. Set this to YES on the master when the master's relay and 
      wiring harness also function as the slave relay. 
      ecm_multi_spkgv If enabled, the slave ECM will perform independent spark 
      governing, based on the target engine speed and spark governing settings 
      from the master ECM. This feature requires multi-engine sync to be 
      disabled. If disabled, spark governing will not be active on the master. 
      ecm_multi_SPK_ena Enable this mode to allow arbitrary spark coil output 
      assignment to firing order based spark events. This feature is most useful 
      with uneven firing events on dual-ECM configurations.

      For example, given the following engine configuration:
      1) 8-cylinder multi-ECM configuration
      2) firing order = 1-5-7-2-6-3-4-8
      3) Master ECM connected to (block) cylinders 1-4
      4) Slave ECM connected to (block) cylinders 5-8

      Then the following coil connections should be made on the master ECM:
      Block #1 = coil 1a
      Block #2 = coil 2a
      Block #3 = coil 1b
      Block #4 = coil 2b

      and the following coil connections should be made on the slave ECM:
      Block #5 = coil 1a
      Block #7 = coil 1b
      Block #6 = coil 2a
      Block #8 = coil 2b

      The calibration would be setup as an 8-cylinder dual ECM/engine 
      configuration with a CAD slave crank offset. The manual coil connections 
      would be setup as

      Master firing order 1 - coil 1a
      Master firing order 2 - X
      Master firing order 3 - X
      Master firing order 4 - coil 2a
      Master firing order 5 - X
      Master firing order 6 - coil 1b
      Master firing order 7 - coil 2b
      Master firing order 8 - X

      Slave firing order 1 - X
      Slave firing order 2 - coil 1a
      Slave firing order 3 - coil 2a
      Slave firing order 4 - X
      Slave firing order 5 - coil 1b
      Slave firing order 6 - X
      Slave firing order 7 - X
      Slave firing order 8 - coil 2b 
      ecm_multi_SPK_mstr1 Multi-ECM spark assignment - master ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 1 
      ecm_multi_SPK_mstr10 Multi-ECM spark assignment - master ECM assignment 
      for cylinder firing order 10 
      ecm_multi_SPK_mstr11 Multi-ECM spark assignment - master ECM assignment 
      for cylinder firing order 11 
      ecm_multi_SPK_mstr12 Multi-ECM spark assignment - master ECM assignment 
      for cylinder firing order 12 
      ecm_multi_SPK_mstr2 Multi-ECM spark assignment - master ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 2 
      ecm_multi_SPK_mstr3 Multi-ECM spark assignment - master ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 3 
      ecm_multi_SPK_mstr4 Multi-ECM spark assignment - master ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 4 
      ecm_multi_SPK_mstr5 Multi-ECM spark assignment - master ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 5 
      ecm_multi_SPK_mstr6 Multi-ECM spark assignment - master ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 6 
      ecm_multi_SPK_mstr7 Multi-ECM spark assignment - master ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 7 
      ecm_multi_SPK_mstr8 Multi-ECM spark assignment - master ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 8 
      ecm_multi_SPK_mstr9 Multi-ECM spark assignment - master ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 9 
      ecm_multi_SPK_slv1 Multi-ECM spark assignment - slave ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 1 
      ecm_multi_SPK_slv10 Multi-ECM spark assignment - slave ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 10 
      ecm_multi_SPK_slv11 Multi-ECM spark assignment - slave ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 11 
      ecm_multi_SPK_slv12 Multi-ECM spark assignment - slave ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 12 
      ecm_multi_SPK_slv2 Multi-ECM spark assignment - slave ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 2 
      ecm_multi_SPK_slv3 Multi-ECM spark assignment - slave ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 3 
      ecm_multi_SPK_slv4 Multi-ECM spark assignment - slave ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 4 
      ecm_multi_SPK_slv5 Multi-ECM spark assignment - slave ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 5 
      ecm_multi_SPK_slv6 Multi-ECM spark assignment - slave ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 6 
      ecm_multi_SPK_slv7 Multi-ECM spark assignment - slave ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 7 
      ecm_multi_SPK_slv8 Multi-ECM spark assignment - slave ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 8 
      ecm_multi_SPK_slv9 Multi-ECM spark assignment - slave ECM assignment for 
      cylinder firing order 9 
      ecm_multi_START Select whether the designated input/output is attached to 
      both the master and slave ECM, or only the master ECM. For inputs attached 
      only to the master ECM, the data is shared with the slave ECM via CAN2. 
      For outputs attached only to the master ECM, the pins are still actuated 
      on the slave ECM (they are assumed to be open), however, fault conditions 
      are ignored and the corresponding faults will not set. 
      ecm_multi_sync Selects between 1 or 2 ECMs per engine. Note this should be 
      configured as 1 ECM per engine unless bank-specific ECMs are being used on 
      a large displacement engine. The 'master' ECM is the ECM with CAN1 source 
      address of 0, and the other ECM is the slave. The master/slave designation 
      can be set by using fixed CAN addresses on both ECMs or by using the 
      master/slave hardware input select option from the 'Marine' page. The 
      following configurations should be made when using 2 ECMs per engine:
      1. DBW throttle control mode w/linear FPP-TPS translation 
      2. Max set point and boost DP modes are disabled 
      3. Multi-engine derates are enabled 
      ecm_multi_Voffset Enter the +/- CAD engine offset for the slave ECM. 
      Typically this is the V-angle of the engine for large-bore engines with 
      shared crank journals. 
      ECP Engine coolant pressure (ECP) value after low-pass filter, in units of 
      psig 
      ECP_def Engine coolant pressure (ECP) default value in units of psig 
      ECP_ena Engine coolant pressure (ECP) sensor input source 
      ECP_hiP "Engine coolant pressure high" fault condition parameter 
      ECP_hiRPM "Engine coolant pressure low" fault entry condition parameter 
      ECP_loECT "Engine coolant pressure low" fault entry condition parameter 
      ECP_loP Obsoleted parameter 
      ECP_loP2 Obsoleted parameter 
      ECP_loRPM "Engine coolant pressure low" fault entry condition parameter 
      ECP_loRPM2 Obsoleted parameter 
      ECP_low_wait "Engine coolant pressure low" fault entry condition parameter 

      ECP_Paux_cal Engine coolant pressure (ECP) auxiliary pressure calibration 
      table selection 
      ECP_raw Engine coolant pressure (ECP) raw value prior to low-pass filter, 
      in units of psig 
      ECP_tau Engine coolant pressure (ECP) time constant for low-pass filter 
      ECrank_cnt_diag crank input diagnostic rolling tooth counter used by 
      crank/cam diagnostic routines (also used by CAM2/Exhaust) 
      Ecrank_cnt_diag_crk Crank input diagnostic rolling tooth counter used by 
      cam2 loss fault when engine is in cranking mode. 
      ECT Engine Coolant Temperature 
      ECTdt ECT change rate 
      ECTgd_ctl_type This switch controls the gauge driver output type 
      configured in hardware on the ECM. 'Duty-cycle PWM' mode indicates that a 
      simple low-side switch is the output, and 'Resistance Simulation' 
      indicates that the output is configured for this special type of control. 
      ECTgd_Id This is the commanded current through the gauge driver circuit. 
      ECTgd_pctref ECT gauge reference percent of scale 
      ECTgd_Ra This is the current actual resistance being generated by the 
      gauge driver circuit as measured by the internal voltage and current 
      feedback systems. 
      ECTgd_Rd This is the current target resistance for the gauge driver 
      circuit. It may include multihelm compensation relative to the tablelookup 
      value. 
      ECTgd_Rdtbl This is the target resistance extracted from the calibration 
      table. 
      ECTgd_Rpu This is the current estimate of the pullup resistance inside the 
      ECT gauge. This value may change with gauge position and/or excitation 
      voltage. 
      ECTgd_Rpu_def This is the default (initial) estimate of the ECT gauge 
      driver's estimate of the pullup resistance inside the gauge itself. This 
      value does not have be accurate - it only affects the initial gauge 
      movement after key-on. 
      ECTgd_Rpu_tau This time-constant determines the effective closed-loop 
      resistance control update rate for the 'Resistance Simulation' mode of 
      operation. It does not apply otherwise. It should generally be set to 
      approximately 100ms, but may be increase or decreased to achieve the 
      desired gauge response time and stability. 
      ECTgd_Vexc_ratio This is the internal resistor divider ratio of the gauge 
      with respect to the supply voltage and ground. If no divider ratio is 
      present internal to the gauge, set this value to 1. 
      ECTgd_Vexc_reg This is the voltage regulator level for the internal gauge 
      excitation voltage. If no regulation exists, just set this value above 
      normal operating voltage (such as 36 volts). 
      ECTgd_V_FB This is the current measured voltage at the gauge driver input 
      pin on the ECM connector. It is used in the computation of the simulated 
      sender resistance. 
      ECTHst_ena Enables the monitoring of ECT to record the histogram, max ECT, 
      and the engine hour meter of the last ECT >= the trigger temperature. 
      ECTHst_hi_HM HM when max ECT was recorded 
      ECTHst_hi_trig Threshold where HM will be recorded 
      ECTHst_max Max ECT while ECT histogram processing is active 
      ECTHst_reset_key ECT histogram reset key - Unique key (1-65535) required 
      to clear the ECT histogram and associated data. 
      ECTHst_reset_usr User entered key to reset ECT histogram data 
      ECTHst_Tbl 1D Interpolation Table: ECT histogram. Input is ECT (degF), 
      output is time (hours) 
      ECTHst_Tbl_ECT 1D Interpolation Table: ECT histogram. ECT input 
      temperature values (deg F) 
      ECTmon_AAT The engine cooling monitor is disabled for the current drive 
      cycle if the ambient air temperature is below this threshold at the start 
      of the drive cycle.

      Refer to "Engine Cooling System Monitor Configuration" description for the 
      list of conditions required to enable the engine cooling monitor for a 
      drive cycle. 
      ECTmon_CL_tmr Coolant temperature warm-up to closed loop activation 
      threshold timer. 
      ECTmon_CL_wait Maximum time allowed for the coolant temperature to reach 
      the closed-loop control activation threshold after engine start. 
      ECTmon_delta The engine cooling monitor is disabled for the current drive 
      cycle if the ECT is within this many degrees of the nominal operating 
      temperature at the start of the drive cycle.

      Refer to "Engine Cooling System Monitor Configuration" description for the 
      list of conditions required to enable the engine cooling monitor for a 
      drive cycle. 
      ECTmon_diag_hyst Hysteresis to apply to the 'ECT dropped below diagnostics 
      temp' ECT fault condition when latching the fault. For the fault condition 
      to be true, the ECT must exceed the fault threshold plus this value. This 
      does not apply to fault unlatching.

      For example, if the diagnostics temperature threshold is set to 150 deg F 
      and the hysteresis is set to 20 deg F, the ECT must exceed 170 deg F to 
      latch the fault provided the other fault conditions are also true. To 
      unlatch the fault, the ECT must be 150 deg F or less. 
      ECTmon_diag_tmr Coolant temperature warm-up to diagnostics enable 
      temperature threshold timer. 
      ECTmon_diag_wait Maximum time allowed for the coolant temperature to reach 
      the diagnostics enable temperature threshold after engine start. 
      ECTmon_oper_tmr Coolant temperature warm-up to operating temperature 
      timer. 
      ECTmon_oper_wait Maximum time allowed for the coolant temperature to reach 
      operating temperature after engine start. 
      ECTmon_state HD OBD Engine Cooling System Monitor status 
      ECTmon_warm_wait Warm engine Engine Cooling System Monitor start delay 
      time. 
      ECTs Standard operating Engine Coolant Temperature (ECT). 
      ECT_adapt Adapt ECT enable - Minimum coolant temperature before allowing 
      entry into adaptive mode. 
      ECT_analog_cfg ECT configuration (pullup resistor assignment) 
      ECT_CL_ena Minimum coolant temperature before allowing entry into 
      closed-loop control. 
      ECT_def Default engine coolant temperature (ECT) value. 
      ECT_diag_min diagnostic monitor enable temperature 
      ECT_gauge_DHena Use this switch to allow the simulated sender driver to 
      drive two (dual-helm) gauges in parallel. Dual-helm mode may either be 
      permanently enabled or it can be indicated using a hardware input channel. 
      A grounded input on any of the pulled-up input selectable choices 
      indicates dual-helm mode. 
      ECT_gauge_DHstat ECT gauge single/dual help status 
      ECT_gauge_dz This value defines a +/- cubic deadzone for multi-engine 
      gauge synchronization. Differences between the average of all multi-engine 
      gauges are reduced by a cubic factor relative to this deadzone, but 
      differences >= this deadzone are displayed at exactly the original value. 
      ECT_gauge_sync This switch will synchronize multiple ECT gauges on a 
      multi-engine configuration within a cubic deadband as defined below. 
      ECT_gauge_value sync'd/unsync'd ECT gauge driver value 
      ECT_HiExp ECT higher than expected 1 diagnostic: ECT threshold entry 
      condition 
      ECT_HiExp2 ECT higher than expected 2 diagnostic: ECT threshold entry 
      condition 
      ECT_HiExp2_MAP ECT higher than expected 2 diagnostic: MAP threshold entry 
      condition 
      ECT_HiExp2_rpm ECT higher than expected 2 diagnostic: RPM threshold entry 
      condition 
      ECT_HiExp2_wait ECT higher than expected 2 diagnostic: run-time threshold 
      entry condition 
      ECT_HiExp_MAP ECT higher than expected 1 diagnostic: MAP threshold entry 
      condition 
      ECT_HiExp_rpm ECT higher than expected 1 diagnostic: RPM threshold entry 
      condition 
      ECT_HiExp_wait ECT higher than expected 1 diagnostic: run-time threshold 
      entry condition 
      ECT_LoExp ECT lower than expected 1 diagnostic: ECT threshold entry 
      condition 
      ECT_LoExp2 ECT lower than expected 2 diagnostic: ECT threshold entry 
      condition 
      ECT_LoExp2_MAP ECT lower than expected 2 diagnostic: MAP threshold entry 
      condition 
      ECT_LoExp2_rpm ECT lower than expected 2 diagnostic: RPM threshold entry 
      condition 
      ECT_LoExp2_wait ECT lower than expected 2 diagnostic: run-time threshold 
      entry condition 
      ECT_LoExp_MAP ECT lower than expected 1 diagnostic: MAP threshold entry 
      condition 
      ECT_LoExp_rpm ECT lower than expected 1 diagnostic: RPM threshold entry 
      condition 
      ECT_LoExp_wait ECT lower than expected 1 diagnostic: run-time threshold 
      entry condition 
      ECT_maxv ECT / CHT high voltage diagnostic: Maximum ECT voltage entry 
      condition 
      ECT_minv ECT / CHT low voltage diagnostic: Minimum ECT voltage entry 
      condition 
      ECT_nom This value represents the nominal thermostat regulating 
      temperature. 
      ECT_nom_min This value defines the minimum ECT that needs to be reached in 
      order to prevent the 'Failed to Reach Operating Temperature' fault from 
      becoming active. Any value bounded by this threshold up to the full 
      nominal operating temperature can be set as the ECT fault condition. 
      ECT_raw ECT raw voltage 
      ECT_restart ECT value for an engine restart condition accumulator 
      ECT_restart_ramp If the engine is stopped and re-started, this ramp rate 
      helps determine what the new 'ECT at start' value will be. After an engine 
      start, an estimated 'ECT at re-start' value will begin ramping up at this 
      rate - but will never be allowed to exceed the actual instantaneous ECT. 
      On engine re-start without the ECM going to sleep, this re-start ECT value 
      will become the new ECT at start value. 
      ECT_sel Input selection for ECT (Default or oil temperature input) 
      ECT_spk_ena ECT > this to enable CD spark related features such as 
      spk_kill and CD diagnostics 
      ECT_start ECT at engine start (latched) 
      ECT_vdr ECT pullup resistor assignment 
      ECWP_AAT_thresh ECWT AAT thresh 
      ECWP_brake_actv_spd ECWP pump speed when exhaust braking or driveline 
      braking is active. 
      ECWP_chan Output channel for controlling a two-speed electromagnetic 
      clutch water pump. A high/100% duty cycle output selects low speed; a 
      low/0% duty cycle output selects the high speed. 

      When "ECWP control method" is set to 'Method #1', high speed is requested 
      for any of these conditions:
      - Idle time above the calibrated maximum seconds
      - Retarder braking active (whether controlled by the ECM, or as indicated 
      by a J1939 ERC1 message where SPN 520, "Actual Retarder - Percent Torque" 
      indicates active application of braking torque)
      - Engine speed below normal operating speed
      - ECT above the calibrated maximum temperature
      - EGRT above the calibrated maximum temperature
      - FT below the calibrated minimum temperature
      - "ECT / CHT high voltage" or "ECT / CHT low voltage" faults are active or 
      latched
      - EGRT input voltage fault is active or latched
      - FT input voltage fault for active fuel type is active or latched
      - active fuel device is CFV, and "EPR / CFV comm lost", "CFV FT high 
      voltage", or "CFV FT low voltage" faults are active or latched 
      ECWP_cntrl_method ECWT control method selection 
      ECWP_ECTdt_thresh ECWT ECT change rate. Every 1s cycle 
      ECWP_ECT_hyst ECWP ECT hysteresis for ECT max temperature 
      ECWP_ECT_max Maximum ECT for the electromagnetic clutch water pump. High 
      speed will be requested when the ECT exceeds this value. 
      ECWP_ECT_thresh ECWT ECT thresh 
      ECWP_EGRT_hyst ECWP EGRT hysteresis 
      ECWP_EGRT_max Maximum EGRT for the electromagnetic clutch water pump. High 
      speed will be requested when the EGRT exceeds this value. 
      ECWP_EGRT_thresh ECWP EGR Temp thresh 
      ECWP_FT_hyst ECWP FT hysteresis 
      ECWP_FT_min Minimum fuel temperature for the electromagnetic clutch water 
      pump. High speed will be requested when the fuel temperature is below this 
      value. 
      ECWP_FT_thresh ECWT Fuel Temp thresh 
      ECWP_idle_MAP_load Maximum MAP load indicating an idle condition for the 
      electromagnetic clutch water pump. 
      ECWP_idle_rpm Maximum engine speed indicating an idle condition for the 
      electromagnetic clutch water pump. 
      ECWP_idle_tmr Time at idle conditions for the electromagnetic clutch water 
      pump. High speed will be requested when the idle time exceeds the 
      calibrated maximum seconds. 
      ECWP_idle_tm_max Maximum time at idle conditions for the electromagnetic 
      clutch water pump. High speed will be requested when the idle time exceeds 
      this value. 
      ECWP_KnkRtd_thresh ECWP Knk Retard thresh 
      ECWP_MaxCoolantTemp ECWT Max coolant temperature 
      ECWP_OILT_hyst ECWP OILT hysteresis 
      ECWP_OilT_thresh ECWP Oil Temp thresh 
      ECWP_PumpSpd_output ECWT Pump speed output 
      ECWP_status ECWT status:
      0 = Disabled
      1 = Full Speed: AAT unavailable
      2 = Full Speed: sensor fault
      3 = Full Speed: high ECT
      4 = Full Speed: high ECTdt
      5 = Full Speed: high OILT
      6 = Full Speed: high EGRT
      7 = Full Speed: high TIAT
      8 = Full Speed: low FT
      9 = Full Speed: brake active
      10 = Full Speed: high knock retard
      11 = Full Speed: low AAT and ECT
      12 = Full Speed: low AAT
      13 = Half Speed: AAT MAP1
      14 = Full Speed: AAT MAP1
      15 = Half Speed: AAT MAP2
      16 = Full Speed: AAT MAP2
      17 = Half Speed: high AAT
      18 = Full Speed: CAN message request
      19 = Half Speed: CAN message request
      20 = Full Speed: CAN message override 
      ECWP_swwait ECWP switching wait time, preferably in multiples of 50 
      ECWP_TempZn_thr1 ECWT Temperature zone thresh 1 
      ECWP_TempZn_thr2 ECWT Temperature zone thresh 2 
      ECWP_TempZn_thr3 ECWT Temperature zone thresh 3 
      ECWP_temp_tmr Timer for electromagnetic clutch water pump temperature 
      conditions. High speed will be requested when the timer is 0; low speed 
      will be requested when the timer is above the temperature validation wait 
      time. 
      ECWP_temp_wait Validation wait time for electromagnetic clutch water pump 
      temperature conditions. High/low speed will be requested when the 
      temperature conditions are valid/invalid for this duration of time. 
      ECWP_TIAT_hyst ECWP TIAT hysteresis 
      ECWP_TIAT_thresh ECWP TIAT thresh 
      ECWP_wait Validation wait time for changing the speed of the 
      electromagnetic clutch water pump.

      EFMA_emix_dP EFMA EGR mixer pressure drop in psi

      EGO1delay EGO response delay time. 
      EGO1fault EGO1 open / lazy diagnostic - EGO cold persistence entry 
      condition 
      EGO1flag System flag - XEGO1 
      EGO1H_DC EGO1 heater duty cycle

      EGO1sw Rich/lean trigger. For UEGO sensors, this voltage is only used for
