      command. 
      EGR_ON_cold_IAT Maximum IAT for using the cold-temperature flow command 
      'on' limit. 
      EGR_OOA_hi_cmd EGR system out-of-authority high diagnostic: minimum 
      commanded EGR entry condition 
      EGR_OOA_hi_err EGR system out-of-authority high diagnostic: EGR commanded 
      - model estimated minimum error entry condition 
      EGR_OOA_lo_err EGR system out-of-authority low diagnostic: EGR commanded - 
      model estimated minimum error entry condition 
      EGR_OOA_lo_mdl EGR system out-of-authority low diagnostic: minimum model 
      estimated EGR entry condition 
      EGR_PRf_actual EGRLP/EGRHP actual computed after pressure pulsation 
      corrections 
      EGR_PRf_observ EGRLP/EGRHP based on an observer instead of the actual 
      pressure pulsation correction, w/o adaptive correction 
      EGR_PRf_pseudo EGRLP/EGRHP based on an observer instead of the actual 
      pressure pulsation correction, w/adaptive correction 
      EGR_PR_mdlerr_max EGR pressure ratio upper limit entry condition: Fault 
      checking for "EGR flow slow to increase/decrease" and "EGR system 
      out-of-authority high/low" faults is only enabled if the EGR valve 
      (fully-corrected) PR used for the model computation is below this limit. 
      EGR_PR_vlv_Dz Obsoleted parameter 
      EGR_PR_vlv_max The pressure ratio computed using EGRLP/EGRHP will be 
      upper-limited to this value when used to calculate valve position. 
      Typically, only one of these sensors is available, or the delta-P is 
      calculated using 2 discrete sensors instead of a true dP sensor. Low 
      values improve stability, larger values improve open-loop tracking 
      accuracy. 
      EGR_PR_vlv_tau This is the low-pass time constant used with the EGR valve 
      pressure ratio estimate. 
      EGR_pstvlv_V This is the total volume of pure EGR in the flow path from 
      the EGR valve metering valve orifice to the air/EGR mixing device. 
      EGR_PWM_period This parameter is used as the PWM frequency for the EGR 
      valve and auxiliary coolant valve outputs, if an H-bridge output is not 
      specified. If an H-bridge output is specified, the H-bridge frequency from 
      the 'DBW' page is used instead and this parameter is ignored. 
      EGR_retard EGR spark timing offset 
      EGR_runtime_wt Obsoleted parameter 
      EGR_sensor_trust Indicates EGR sensor trustworthiness in cold temperatures 

      EGR_senstrst_ECTfrac ECT minimum/nominal request to enable EGR sensor 
      rationalization 
      EGR_senstrst_flt_tm Maximum time to wait for both sensors to become 
      trustworthy. After this time, the "EGRdP higher than expected" fault 
      begins latching if EGRdP is not trustworthy, and the "EGRHP out of range" 
      fault begins latching if EGRHP is not trustworthy. 
      EGR_senstrst_flt_tmr Total time rationalizing EGRdP and/or EGRHP 
      EGR_slowdec_err EGR flow slow to decrease / stuck open diagnostic: EGR 
      model estimated - commanded error lower limit entry condition 
      EGR_slowdec_mdl EGR flow slow to decrease / stuck open diagnostic: minimum 
      model estimated EGR entry condition 
      EGR_slowinc_cmd EGR flow slow to increase / stuck closed diagnostic: 
      minimum commanded EGR entry condition 
      EGR_slowinc_err EGR flow slow to increase / stuck closed diagnostic: EGR 
      commanded - model estimated error lower limit entry condition 
      EGR_spkadv_min Minimum diluent spark timing 
      EGR_spkadv_nom Nominal diluent spark timing 
      EGR_spkextrap_advlmt The minimum EGR spark command table is calibrated at 
      low EGR flows, and should be more retarded than the nominal table. When 
      the actual EGR % exceeds the nominal amount, the spark advance is 
      extrapolated above the nominal table by computing the CAD spark per % 
      diluent from the min nom tables:

      CAD/% = (nom spk - min spk) / (nom % diluent - min % diluent)

      The calculated CAD/% is limited using the min/max advance sensitivity 
      limits, and then multiplied by (commanded diluent % - nom % diluent) to 
      get a proposed CAD advance. 

      The computed advance is upper-limited by this value. 
      EGR_spkextrap_amax The minimum EGR spark command table is calibrated at 
      low EGR flows, and should be more retarded than the nominal table. When 
      the actual EGR % exceeds the nominal amount, the spark advance is 
      extrapolated above the nominal table by computing the CAD spark per % 
      diluent from the min nom tables:

      CAD/% = (nom spk - min spk) / (nom % diluent - min % diluent)

      The calculated CAD/% is limited using the min/max advance sensitivity 
      limits, and then multiplied by (commanded diluent % - nom % diluent) to 
      get a proposed CAD advance. 

      The computed advance is upper-limited by this value. 
      EGR_spkextrap_amin The minimum EGR spark command table is calibrated at 
      low EGR flows, and should be more retarded than the nominal table. When 
      the actual EGR % exceeds the nominal amount, the spark advance is 
      extrapolated above the nominal table by computing the CAD spark per % 
      diluent from the min nom tables:

      CAD/% = (nom spk - min spk) / (nom % diluent - min % diluent)

      The calculated CAD/% is limited using the min/max advance sensitivity 
      limits, and then multiplied by (commanded diluent % - nom % diluent) to 
      get a proposed CAD advance. 

      The computed advance is upper-limited by this value. 
      EGR_spkextrap_ret Extrapolated spark retard 
      EGR_spkextrap_retlmt The minimum EGR spark command table is calibrated at 
      low EGR flows, and should be more retarded than the nominal table. When 
      the actual EGR % exceeds the nominal amount, the spark advance is 
      extrapolated above the nominal table by computing the CAD spark per % 
      diluent from the min nom tables:

      CAD/% = (nom spk - min spk) / (nom % diluent - min % diluent)

      The calculated CAD/% is limited using the min/max advance sensitivity 
      limits, and then multiplied by (commanded diluent % - nom % diluent) to 
      get a proposed CAD advance. 

      The computed advance is upper-limited by this value. 
      EGR_spkextrap_rmax The minimum EGR spark command table is calibrated at 
      low EGR flows, and should be more retarded than the nominal table. When 
      the actual EGR % exceeds the nominal amount, the spark advance is 
      extrapolated above the nominal table by computing the CAD spark per % 
      diluent from the min nom tables:

      CAD/% = (nom spk - min spk) / (nom % diluent - min % diluent)

      The calculated CAD/% is limited using the min/max advance sensitivity 
      limits, and then multiplied by (commanded diluent % - nom % diluent) to 
      get a proposed CAD advance. 

      The computed advance is upper-limited by this value. 
      EGR_spkextrap_rmin The minimum EGR spark command table is calibrated at 
      low EGR flows, and should be more retarded than the nominal table. When 
      the actual EGR % exceeds the nominal amount, the spark advance is 
      extrapolated above the nominal table by computing the CAD spark per % 
      diluent from the min nom tables:

      CAD/% = (nom spk - min spk) / (nom % diluent - min % diluent)

      The calculated CAD/% is limited using the min/max advance sensitivity 
      limits, and then multiplied by (commanded diluent % - nom % diluent) to 
      get a proposed CAD advance. 

      The computed advance is upper-limited by this value. 
      EGR_spkextrap_sens Extrapolated spark actual sensitivity 
      EGR_spkex_pdspanmax Specifies the % diluent difference between the minimum 
      and nominal % diluent commands for using the calculated extrapolated spark 
      sensitivity. When the % diluent difference is above this value, the 
      calculated extrapolated spark sensitivity is used. When the % diluent 
      difference is less than this value, the extrapolated spark sensitivity is 
      interpolated from the average sensitivity up to the calculated 
      sensitivity. 
      EGR_spkex_pdspanmin Specifies the % diluent difference between the minimum 
      and nominal % diluent commands for using the average extrapolated spark 
      sensitivity. When the % diluent difference is below this value, the 
      extrapolated spark sensitivity is the average of the retard/advance 
      minimum and maximum sensitivity. When the % diluent difference is greater 
      than this value, the extrapolated spark sensitivity is interpolated from 
      the average sensitivity up to the calculated sensitivity. 
      EGR_stuckvlv_cnt_max Maximum number of attempts per occurrence to move a 
      stuck valve. 
      EGR_stuckvlv_DChi_tm Maximum time for monitoring an excessive duty cycle 
      before starting a new occurrence of the stuck EGR valve diagnostic. 
      EGR_stuckvlv_dc_lp Low-passed duty cycle, updated during the excessive 
      duty cycle monitoring state of the stuck EGR valve diagnostic. 
      EGR_stuckvlv_dc_max The stuck EGR valve diagnostic will begin excessive 
      duty cycle monitoring when the duty cycle is above this threshold. 
      EGR_stuckvlv_dc_min The stuck EGR valve diagnostic will begin excessive 
      duty cycle monitoring when the duty cycle is below this threshold. 
      EGR_stuckvlv_dc_tau Time constant for updating the low-passed duty cycle 
      during the excessive duty cycle monitoring state of the stuck EGR valve 
      diagnostic. 
      EGR_stuckvlv_movepct Movement distance goal before and after an 
      obstruction for the stuck EGR valve diagnostic to conclude that the valve 
      is not stuck. The calculated movement goal is limited by "EGR minimum 
      position" and "EGR maximum position". 
      EGR_stuckvlv_move_tm Maximum time to attempt to move a stuck EGR valve in 
      one direction. 
      EGR_stuckvlv_nearpct Approach threshold for successful movement of a stuck 
      EGR valve. The current diagnostic step ends when the valve position is 
      within the specified distance of the movement goal. 
      EGR_stuckvlv_rest_tm Duration to set the duty cycle to 0% prior to 
      attempting to move a stuck EGR valve. 
      EGR_stuckvlv_state Stuck EGR valve diagnostic state. 
      EGR_stuckvlv_tmr_max Peak time per ECM boot that the EGR valve diagnostic 
      is monitoring an excessive duty cycle. 
      EGR_stuckvlv_tot_cnt Total occurrence count of the EGR valve diagnostic. 
      EGR_sys_config Determines system-wide EGR handling, based on the EGR 
      pull-off location (post turbine for low-pressure, pre-turbine for 
      high-pressure) and injection point (pre-compressor for low-pressure, 
      post-compressor for high-pressure). 
      EGR_tau_dP_ms EGR venturi flow time constant 
      EGR_tau_MAF_ms EGR measured flow low-pass time constant - MAF 
      EGR_tau_UEGO_ms EGR measured flow low-pass time constant - UEGO 
      EGR_TPSdP_Dz In order to prevent EGR valve delta-P from becoming too 
      small, the throttle delta-P command can be increased to allow for more EGR 
      valve dP. 

      For HPEGR systems, the throttle dP required is equal to 

      EGR_TPS_min_dP = (TIP-EGRHP) + EGR_vlv_min_dP

      because EGRLP=TOP. Before installing the EGR_TPS_min_dP command, the 
      computed right hand side of the above expression is passed through a cubic 
      deadzone and low-pass filter. 
      EGR_TPSdP_Ktrans Enter a non-zero gain to enable additional TPS delta-P 
      requests during transients. This gain is multiplied by the transient EGR 
      command (dmdot/dt) and added into the TPS delta-P request. 
      EGR_TPSdP_limiting For HPEGR systems, the boost throttle delta-P command 
      will be modified to enforce the EGR valve delta-P limit in the 1D table to 
      the right. 

      For LPEGR systems, a separate intake restriction valve (IRV) is used to 
      enforce a minimum EGR valve delta-P. 
      EGR_TPSdP_max Maximum allowed TPS delta-P requested by the EGR system. 
      This value can also be used to prevent a boost recirculation valve from 
      opening due to an excessive EGR TPS delta-P request. 
      EGR_TPSdP_min throttle minimum requested delta-P by the EGR system in psi, 
      required to maintain EGR valve minimum delta-P 
      EGR_TPSdP_tau_dec This is the time constant for the low-pass filter 
      described in the TPSdP deadzone comment above, when the requested dP is 
      decreasing. 
      EGR_TPSdP_tau_inc This is the time constant for the low-pass filter 
      described in the TPSdP deadzone comment above, when the requested dP is 
      increasing. 
      EGR_TPSPR_max Obsoleted parameter 
      EGR_TPSPR_min Obsoleted parameter 
      EGR_transdelay_smr An averaging parameter between 0 (no mixing) and 1 
      (maximum mixing) that accounts for mixing within the volume. 
      EGR_UEGOdP_hi_err EGR UEGO - dP feedback mismatch high diagnostic: EGR 
      (UEGO-dP) feedback minimum error entry condition 
      EGR_UEGOdP_hi_min EGR UEGO - dP feedback mismatch high diagnostic: EGR 
      UEGO feedback lower limit entry condition 
      EGR_UEGOdP_lo_err EGR UEGO - dP feedback mismatch low diagnostic: EGR 
      (UEGO-dP) feedback minimum error entry condition 
      EGR_UEGOdP_lo_min EGR UEGO - dP feedback mismatch low diagnostic: EGR UEGO 
      feedback lower limit entry condition 
      EGR_vent_CdA Enter the effective area for the orifice. This area is used 
      with a compressible flow model to calculate the mass flow rate across the 
      fixed orifice. 
      EGR_vent_CdArmult Obsoleted parameter 
      EGR_vent_dPPin_ph Enter the phase-shift between the dP sensor and venturi 
      pressure inlet sensor data. A phase shift correction is applied to the 
      data before the pressure pulse correction factor is computed. 
      EGR_vent_dPpre_loss EGR delta-P loss across a pre-valve venturi, after 
      recovery is complete 
      EGR_vent_dPpst_loss EGR delta-P loss across a post-valve venturi, after 
      recovery is complete 
      EGR_vent_dPrev_recov Enter the pressure recovery of the EGR venturi used 
      for flow estimation when the flow is in the reverse direction (typical 
      during engine pulsations). 
      EGR_vent_dPvvdt_n Enter the number of 5us samples to use in estimating 
      dP/dt for the volume between the venturi and EGR valve. This volume fill 
      is used as part of the pressure pulsation compensation algorithm. This 
      value must be <= 12, and it is generally best (due to phase-shift 
      compensation) if this is set to an odd value. 
      EGR_vent_dP_config This option specifies the type of delta-P measurement 
      used on the venturi or orifice. The default option assumes the delta-P is 
      setup to measure the inlet pressure - throat pressure. With the default 
      setup, the delta-P sensor will read a positive pressure even under flow 
      reversal. For orifice style configurations where the delta-P sensor will 
      read negative during flow reversal, select the 'orifice' option.If the 
      pressure pulsation correction factor below is set to 0.0 or delta-P 
      measurement is disabled, this setting has no affect. 
      EGR_vent_dP_loss EGR delta-P loss across venturi, after recovery is 
      complete 
      EGR_vent_dP_recov Enter the pressure recovery of the EGR venturi used for 
      flow estimation. This value should be high for an ideal venturi that is 
      appropriately sized, and fairly low for an orifice plate. 
      EGR_vent_location This option specifies the location of the EGR venturi 
      used with an EGR delta-P sensor to measure the EGR flow rate. 
      EGR_vent_MAT_pct The inlet temperature at the EGR venturi is typically 
      somewhere between the EGR cooler outlet temperature (EGRT) and the intake 
      manifold temperature (MAT). Entering 0.0% here assumes the inlet 
      temperature at the EGR valve is EGRT, 100% assumes the inlet temperature 
      at the EGR valve is MAT. 
      EGR_vent_Mx_mult EGR orifice flow correction 
      EGR_vent_Pin EGR venturi inlet pressure in psia 
      EGR_vent_Pout EGR venturi outlet pressure in psia 
      EGR_vent_Ppls_attn EGR orifice/venturi pressure pulsation attenuation 
      factor 
      EGR_vent_Tin EGR venturi inlet temperature 
      EGR_vent_Vvv The volume post-venturi is used for a pressure pulsation 
      compensation algorithm. This should be sized to approximately the 
      post-throat to valve volume for venturis mounted before the EGR valve, and 
      venturi-to-MAP/EGRLP sensor for post-valve venturi applications. 
      EGR_vlv_0pct_dly For spring-return, brushed EGR valves only. Time that EGR 
      valve position command must remain at 0% before PWM duty cycle will be 
      forced to 0%. This is used to prevent wear of the motor due to continued 
      driving of the valve when the EGR command is 0. 
      EGR_vlv_act EGR valve delta P (actual) 
      EGR_vlv_act_dP EGR valve actual delta-P 
      EGR_vlv_cmd EGR valve command 
      EGR_vlv_cmd_dP EGR valve delta-P command. Typically, this is set to the 
      minimum requested EGR valve steady-state delta-P from the 1D lookup table. 
      However, certain transient modifications (e.g. BRV compensation) can 
      momentarily override the steady-state delta-P command. 
      EGR_vlv_ctl_lmt Obsoleted parameter 
      EGR_vlv_DC_hi Duty cycle limit for brushed EGR valves. 
      EGR_vlv_dPos_max For spring-return, brushed EGR valves only. Sets maximum 
      rate of change condition for integral limiting near 0% valve position. If 
      rate of change of the PS1 feedback voltage is less than this value, the 
      zero deadzone limit is met, and the position command is 0%, then the PID 
      integral value will be reset and the PWM duty cycle forced to 0%. 
      EGR_vlv_dP_tau EGR valve actual pressure drop low-pass time constant 
      EGR_vlv_dt_cmd EGR valve diagnostic test command 
      EGR_vlv_dt_state EGR valve diagnostic test state 
      EGR_vlv_HP_mdot Minimum EGR flow command fault condition for the "EGR 
      valve high pressure tube disconnected" diagnostic. 
      EGR_vlv_HP_pcterr Percentage error the absolute difference between the EGR 
      model estimated flow and the actual flow must exceed to latch the "EGR 
      valve high pressure tube disconnected" diagnostic. 
      EGR_vlv_MAT_pct The inlet temperature at the EGR valve is typically 
      somewhere between the EGR cooler outlet temperature (EGRT) and the intake 
      manifold temperature (MAT). Entering 0.0% here assumes the inlet 
      temperature at the EGR valve is EGRT, 100% assumes the inlet temperature 
      at the EGR valve is MAT. 
      EGR_vlv_min_dP EGR valve minimum pressure drop 
      EGR_vlv_poserr_max "EGR valve position slow to respond" fault condition - 
      the maximum allowed EGR valve's position error, value should be a positive 
      number. 
      EGR_vlv_poserr_min "EGR valve position slow to respond" fault condition - 
      the minimum allowed EGR valve's position error, value should be a negative 
      number. 
      EGR_vlv_poserr_Vbat "EGR valve position slow to respond" entry condition - 
      the minimum battery voltage. 
      EGR_vlv_poserr_wait "EGR valve position slow to respond" fault condition - 
      the maximum allowed duration that the EGR valve's position error can be 
      outside of the minimum/maximum limits. 
      EGR_vlv_Ppls_attn EGR valve pressure pulsation attenuation factor, 2048 = 
      use full high-speed correction 
      EGR_vlv_tau The EGR valve position feedback is low-passed using this time 
      constant and the result is used as the actual EGR valve position in the 
      EGR model. Note this parameter has no affect on closed-loop position 
      control of the EGR valve. For systems without actuator position feedback 
      (use H-bridge output channels for EGR valves with actuator position 
      feedback), the EGR valve command is filtered instead, and the result is 
      used as the actual EGR valve position in the EGR model. 
      EGR_vlv_temp_est Estimated temperature of the EGR valve. Only valid for 
      specific types of brushed motor EGR valves. 
      EGR_vlv_temp_max Maximum estimated temperature of the EGR valve allowed 
      before the EGR brushed valve temperature high fault becomes active. 
      EGR_vlv_Tin EGR valve Inlet Temperature (Tin) 
      EGR_vlv_type Only used for brushed-motor EGR valves connected to an 
      H-bridge. Selects whether the valve is a spring-return type or is driven 
      bidirectionally by the motor. 
      EGR_vlv_zero_dz For spring-return, brushed EGR valves only. Sets deadzone 
      for integral limiting near 0% valve position. If the PS1 feedback voltage 
      is within this value of the idle position, the rate of change limit is 
      met, and the position command is 0%, then the PID integral value will be 
      reset and PWM duty cycle forced to 0%. 
      EGR_Vrelay_nominal Enter a non-zero nominal operating voltage to perform 
      voltage compensation on the PWM duty-cycle output. This option is only 
      enabled for PWM ouptuts and is ignored for H-bridge outputs. 
      EGT Exhaust gas temperature 
      EGTs Standard operating Exhaust Gas Temperature (EGT). 
      EGT_def default EGT value 
      EGT_dig_state EGT temperature state (OK, High – Ignored, High) 
      EGT_dig_test Sets the direction of Fault detection for the measured EGT 
      voltage (either great than or less than) 
      EGT_dig_trig Sets Fault level voltage 
      EGT_ena Designates Aux Temperature Sensor input for measuring EGT 
      EGT_Hi_wait Sets delay time before a Fault is set IF the EGT voltage 
      reading is out of bounds (given the engine is running) 
      EGT_maxv Sets threshold for EGT high voltage diagnostic fault. 
      EGT_maxv_MAP Minimum MAP threshold for the "Exhaust gas temperature high 
      voltage" fault. 
      EGT_maxv_rpm Minimum engine speed threshold for the "Exhaust gas 
      temperature high voltage" fault. 
      EGT_maxv_wait Minimum engine run time threshold for the "Exhaust gas 
      temperature high voltage" fault. 
      EGT_minv Sets threshold for EGT low voltage diagnostic fault. 
      EGT_minv_MAP Minimum MAP threshold for the "Exhaust gas temperature low 
      voltage" fault. 
      EGT_minv_rpm Minimum engine speed threshold for the "Exhaust gas 
      temperature low voltage" fault. 
      EGT_minv_wait Minimum engine run time threshold for the "Exhaust gas 
      temperature low voltage" fault. 
      EGT_raw EGT signal - raw volts 
      EGT_Taux_cal EGT sensor auxiliary temperature calibration table selection 
      EGT_vdr EGT input channel pullup resistor resistance value 
      EGT_volt EGT input voltage 
      emcal_CS_16 final 16-bit emissions-calibration checksum 
      emcal_CS_32 final 32-bit emissions-calibration checksum 
      EMP Exhaust manifold pressure 
      EMP_cyl_events Enter the number of cylinder events to use for EMP 
      measurement windowing. Lower values result in faster sensor response, 
      higher values minimize the engine-related EMP pulsations. This value must 
      be >= 1, and the max window is limited to 200ms. Set this value to 0.0 to 
      disable cylinder event based windowing. 
      EMP_ena Parameter switch which assigns sensor input port for measuring 
      EMP. This switch also can be set to allow for estimating EMP_ena. 
      EMP_est This switch selects the type of exhaust manifold pressure estimate 
      to use for volumetric efficiency corrections. Non-turbo engines should use 
      the 'EBP' option, and turbo engines should use the 'TIP' option. EGRHP 
      sensing must be enabled for the third option (EMP = EGRHP + dP cooler) to 
      be valid. 
      EMP_Paux_cal Exhaust manifold pressure auxiliary calibration table 
      selection 
      EMP_slow Slow (LP) filtered Exhaust manifold pressure 
      EMP_slow_tau_ms Slow low-pass filter time constant in ms for the windowed 
      EMP. Set this to 0.0 to disable this filter. This value is set to 0.0 by 
      default, for backwards compatibility. 
      EMP_tau Low-pass filter time constant in ms for the windowed high-speed 
      EMP. 
      EMS3_fuelleak_input Selects the PWM input for a gaseous fuel leakage 
      sender. 
      EMT Exhaust manifold temperature. 
      EMTM_ena Exhaust Manifold Temperature Monitoring Control. 
      EMTM_finish Exhaust Manifold Temperature Monitor Upper Temperature Limit 
      (Gasoline). 
      EMTM_init Exhaust Manifold Temperature Monitor Lower Temperature Limit 
      (Gasoline). 
      EMTM_LoadLim Exhaust Manifold Temperature Monitor Current Load 
      Limit(Gasoline). 
      EMTM_loadlim 1D Interpolation Table: Gasoline Exhaust Manifold Temperature 
      Monitor Based Load Limit (input rpm, output Load Limit percent) 
      EMT_ss Steady-State exhaust manifold temperature. 
      EMT_tauactv Exhaust manifold temperature modeling the currently active 
      time constant. 
      EMT_taustopped Time constant for the exhaust manifold temperature to 
      return to ambient air temperature when the engine is stopped. If set to 
      zero, then when the engine stops, the EMT is immediately set to the 
      Steady-State Exhaust Manifold Temp from the first row of the 
      Power/Temperature Data table. 
      EMWT1 Exhaust manifold water temperature sensor 1 (EMWT1) temperature 
      signal 
      EMWT1_ena Exhaust manifold water temperature sensor 
      enable/channel-selection switch used for marine applications. 
      EMWT1_Taux_cal Exhaust manifold water temperature sensor 1 (EMWT1) 
      auxiliary calibration table selection 
      EMWT2 Exhaust manifold water temperature sensor 2 (EMWT2) temperature 
      signal 
      EMWT2_ena Exhaust manifold water temperature sensor 
      enable/channel-selection switch used for marine applications. 
      EMWT2_Taux_cal Exhaust manifold water temperature sensor 2 (EMWT2) 
      auxiliary calibration table selection 
      EMWT_CWT_C This is a coefficient that can be used to temporarily bias the 
      EMWT estimate based on the current CWT (cylinder wall temperature) VE 
      correction. This is a good short-term load-history indicator, and when the 
      EMWT sensor is located near the exhaust port, it is a good thermal mass 
      influence coefficient. Typical values are on the order of 1 deg F per % VE 
      correction. Note that the units are negative since a negative VE 
      correction indicates a transition from a high load condition (high thermal 
      energy storage) - however the coefficient is entered as a POSITIVE number. 

      EMWT_est EMWT model estimation 
      EMWT_HiExp1_abs Exhaust manifold water temperature (EMWT)1/2 higher than 
      expected level 1 diagnostic: EMWT upper limit threshold 
      EMWT_HiExp1_delt Exhaust manifold water temperature (EMWT)1/2 higher than 
      expected level 1 diagnostic: EMWT - estimated temperature delta threshold 
      entry condition 
      EMWT_HiExp2_abs Exhaust manifold water temperature (EMWT)1/2 higher than 
      expected level 2 diagnostic: EMWT upper limit threshold 
      EMWT_HiExp2_delt Exhaust manifold water temperature (EMWT)1/2 higher than 
      expected level 2 diagnostic: EMWT - estimated temperature delta threshold 
      entry condition 
      EMWT_in EMWT inlet temperature 
      EMWT_in_s This is the standard inlet temperature into the exhaust manifold 
      to be used by the EMWT estimation model. The actual temperature may be 
      read by a sensor, or this value will be used if a sensor is not available. 
      The model will adjust the estimated EMWT based on the sum of inlet 
      temperature and the delta temperature due to the calibration map and load 
      influences. 
      EMWT_maxv EMWT1/2 high voltage diagnostic: EMWT voltage upper limit 
      threshold 
      EMWT_minv EMWT1/2 low voltage diagnostic: EMWT voltage upper limit 
      threshold 
      EMWT_run_wait EMWT fault wait time after start 
      EMWT_sensor_tau This is the average time constant of the EMWT (exhaust 
      manifold water temperature) sensor to be used by the EMWT estimation 
      model. 
      EMWT_ss_rise exhaust manifold water temperature steady-state rise 
      EMWT_vdr EMWT input channel pullup resistor resistance value 
      EMWT_wt_init Enter the time to wait in ms upon a power-up or resume from 
      sleep before the EMWT sensor input has stabilized. If an EMWT sensor is 
      available, the stabilized sensor input is used to initialize the EMWT 
      estimate. 
      engine_number Multi-engine status - Master/Single, Slave 1, Slave 2 or 
      Slave 3 
      engine_select This software switch controls how the engine behaves in a 
      multi-engine configuration. It can be software selected, or it can use a 
      hardware input channel to make the selection. All PUx and PUDx hardware 
      inputs assume a pull-up configuration with open (high) = Master, and 
      ground = Slave 1. All DIGx hardware inputs assume open = Master, ground = 
      Slave 1, and high voltage = Slave 2. 
      engine_SNPN_flash Flash based request: Save SN, PN, VIN and MfgDate to 
      EEPROM after reprogramming 
      engine_SNPN_write Engine ID write command - triggers a write to EEPROM of 
      serial number, part number, VIN, manufacturing date 
      engine_stall_manual In general, this parameter should be set to '0' to use 
      the legacy crank-cam module specific stall speed. If a non-zero value is 
      entered, this entry overrides the crank-cam module specific stall speed. 
      The stall speed is used to shut down fueling and spark during hard 
      decelerations when an instantaneous engine speed (determined between 
      adjacent teeth) exceeds this value. To override the crank-cam module 
      specific non-zero stall speed, enter a '1' in this entry to essentially 
      disable this feature. 
      engine_type Engine type 
      eng_load Fractional current engine load 
      eng_torque_mode Engine torque mode:
      --None
      --FPP
      --Cruise control
      --Power takeoff
      --Roadspeed limit
      --ASR control
      --Transmission 
      --ABS control
      --Torque limit
      --Max governor
      --Electronic brakes
      --Remote FPP
      --Service procedure
      --UNDEFINED
      --Other
      --Not Available 
      enhanced_security EDIS always requires an Interface Password Key derived 
      login password. If this dropdown is enabled, EDIS will require a second 
      OEM-managed license to be present before EDIS will connect to the ECM. 
      enov_slnk_1ms_allwd Indicates the maximum allowed execution time for the 
      1ms runtime loop Simulink user code. 
      enov_slnk_1ms_ena Indicates the presence of compiled Simulink user code 
      intended for execution in the 1ms runtime loop. 
      enov_slnk_1ms_inst Indicates the execution time of the most recent 
      execution of the 1ms runtime loop Simulink user code. 
      enov_slnk_1ms_live Indicates whether the 1ms runtime loop Simulink user 
      code is live or has been shut down due to various violations. 
      enov_slnk_1ms_max Indicates the maximum execution time of the 1ms runtime 
      loop Simulink user code. 
      enov_slnk_1ms_oruns Indicates the number of 1ms runtime loop execution 
      time overruns. 
      enov_slnk_1ms_pct Indicates the maximum execution time for the 1ms runtime 
      loop Simulink user code expressed as a percent of the maximum allowed 
      execution time. 
      enov_slnk_50ms_allwd Indicates the maximum allowed execution time for the 
      50ms runtime loop Simulink user code. 
      enov_slnk_50ms_ena Indicates the presence of compiled Simulink user code 
      intended for execution in the 50ms runtime loop. 
      enov_slnk_50ms_inst Indicates the execution time of the most recent 
      execution of the 50ms runtime loop Simulink user code. 
      enov_slnk_50ms_live Indicates whether the 50ms runtime loop Simulink user 
      code is live or has been shut down due to various violations. 
      enov_slnk_50ms_max Indicates the maximum execution time of the 50ms

      time overruns. 
      enov_slnk_50ms_pct Indicates the maximum execution time for the 50ms 
      runtime loop Simulink user code expressed as a percent of the maximum 
      allowed execution time.

      EOL_oem_action EOL Mode: special action key 
      EOL_oem_key EOL Mode: key to allow EOL functionality 
      EPRPF_active Indicates whether Pulse Flow mode is active 
      EPRPF_brk_lptau The low-pass time constant to use when braking in pulsed 
      fuel flow mode. 
      EPRPF_cbrk_trig When in pulsed mode and the duty-cycle is below this 
      threshold, the commanded duty-cycle is low-passed to reduce valve closing 
      impact. 
      EPRPF_ena Enables MJ/EPR pulsed-fuel flow (PWM) when total suction 
      pressure is below a user-specified threshold. This feature is mostly 
      targeted at starting and low-load conditions on fixed-venturi 
      applications. 
      EPRPF_inst_mult DEPR pulsed fuel flow fuel suction multiplier 
      EPRPF_inst_PW DEPR pulsed fuel flow pulsewidth 
      EPRPF_min_toff The minimum off-time allowed during pulsed-flow mode. 
      EPRPF_min_ton The minimum pulse-width allowed during pulsed-flow mode. 
      EPRPF_obrk_trig When in pulsed mode and the duty-cycle is above this 
      threshold, the commanded duty-cycle is low-passed to reduce valve opening 
      impact. 
      EPRPF_period Specify the period to use in the pulsed-flow mode. 
      EPRPF_Vent_dead Fuel flow is assumed to be stopped when below this 
      threshold. Note this value is only used for closed-loop pulse width 
      correction on the DEPR during pulse-off modes. 
      EPRPF_Vent_hyst Pulsed fuel flow suction hysteresis 
      EPRPF_Vent_min Enter the minimum total fuel-flow driving pressure. If the 
      total fuel-flow driving pressure falls below this limit, pulsed-flow mode 
      is enabled. The duty-cycle is reduced to achieve total suction pressures 
      above this limit. 
      EPR_DC_act EPR duty cycle % feedback. 
      EPR_SenseLP DEPR sensor low-pass time constant 
      ERCV_ACTIV_output Output channel for controlling an Electronic Rotating 
      Crankcase Ventilation (ERCV) motor. 
      ERCV_diag_run_wait Time to wait after ERCV enters the "Run" state before 
      the ERCV reaches a stable closed-loop speed. 
      ERCV_diag_stop_wait Time to wait after engine stop before the ERCV speed 
      input frequency will indicate that the ERCV has stopped. 
      ERCV_speed_freq Current ERCV speed input frequency. 
      ERCV_speed_freq_max Maximum expected speed input frequency after the ERCV 
      has been in the "Run" state for the minimum run wait time. 
      ERCV_speed_freq_min Minimum expected speed input frequency after the ERCV 
      has been in the "Run" state for the minimum run wait time. 
      ERCV_SPEED_input Selects the PWM input for measuring the ERCV speed. 
      ERCV_state Current ERCV control state. 
      ERWT1 ERWT sensor 1 temperature 
      ERWT1_ena Exhaust riser water temperature sensor enable/channel-selection 
      switch used for marine applications. 
      ERWT1_Taux_cal ERWT sensor 1 auxiliary calibration table selection 
      ERWT2 ERWT sensor 2 temperature 
      ERWT2_ena Exhaust riser water temperature sensor enable/channel-selection 
      switch used for marine applications. 
      ERWT2_Taux_cal ERWT sensor 2 auxiliary calibration table selection 
      ERWT_CWT_C This is a coefficient that can be used to temporarily bias the 
      ERWT estimate based on the current CWT (cylinder wall temperature) VE 
      correction. This is a good short-term load-history indicator, and when the 
      ERWT sensor is located near the exhaust port, it is a good thermal mass 
      influence coefficient. Typical values are on the order of 1 deg F per % VE 
      correction. Note that the units are negative since a negative VE 
      correction indicates a transition from a high load condition (high thermal 
      energy storage) - however the coefficient is entered as a POSITIVE number. 

      ERWT_est Exhaust Riser Water Temperature (ERWT) model estimation 
      ERWT_HiExp1_abs ERWT1/2 higher than expected level 1 diagnostic: Exhaust 
      Riser Water Temperature (ERWT) upper limit threshold - fault is triggered 
      above this value. 
      ERWT_HiExp1_delt ERWT1/2 higher than expected level 1 diagnostic: ERWT 
      temp - estimated temp delta entry condition 
      ERWT_HiExp2_abs ERWT1/2 higher than expected level 2 diagnostic: Exhaust 
      Riser Water Temperature (ERWT) upper limit threshold - fault is triggered 
      above this value. 
      ERWT_HiExp2_delt ERWT1/2 higher than expected level 2 diagnostic: ERWT 
      temp - estimated temp delta entry condition 
      ERWT_in Exhaust Riser Water Temperature (ERWT) inlet temperature 
      ERWT_in_s This is the standard inlet temperature into the exhaust riser to 
      be used by the ERWT estimation model. The actual temperature may be read 
      by a sensor, or this value will be used if a sensor is not available. The 
      model will adjust the estimated ERWT based on the sum of inlet temperature 
      and the delta temperature due to the calibration map and load influences. 
      ERWT_maxv ERWT1/2 high voltage diagnostic: Exhaust Riser Water Temperature 
      (ERWT) upper limit threshold - fault is triggered above this value. 
      ERWT_minv ERWT1/2 low voltage diagnostic: Exhaust Riser Water Temperature 
      (ERWT) lower limit threshold - fault is triggered below this value. 
      ERWT_run_wait run time wait for all "ERWT1/2 higher than expected" faults 
      ERWT_sensor_tau This is the average time constant of the ERWT (exhaust 
      riser water temperature) sensor to be used by the ERWT estimation model. 
      ERWT_ss_rise ERWT steady-state temperature rise (delta deg F) 
      ERWT_wt_init Enter the time to wait in ms upon a power-up or resume from 
      sleep before the ERWT sensor input has stabilized. If an ERWT sensor is 
      available, the stabilized sensor input is used to initialize the ERWT 
      estimate. 
      ESD_chan Selects the digital input channel used for the Emergency Shut 
      Down (ESD) switch. 
      ESD_chan_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the input, this value 
      determines the logic state(s) where the engine is allowed to run. An 
      active state for this input indicates that a shutdown is NOT requested. 
      The Default active values are:

      Aux DIG1 = Gnd
      Aux DIG2 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG3 = Gnd
      Aux DIG4 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG5 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG6 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG7 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG8 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG9 = Gnd
      Aux DIG10 = Gnd
      Aux DIG11 = Gnd
      Aux DIG12 = Gnd
      Aux DIG13 = Gnd
      Aux DIG14 = Gnd
      Aux DIG15 = Gnd
      Aux DIG16 = Gnd
      Aux DIG17 = Gnd
      Aux DIG18 = Gnd
      Aux DIG19 = Gnd
      Gov1 = Gnd
      Gov2 = Gnd 
      ESD_LED Indicates the SPOCK ESD switch state. 
      ESD_raw Emergency Shutdown feedback voltage 
      ESD_Sw_state Indicates the SPOCK ESD switch state. 
      ESM_0pwf_dRPM These parameters define the calculation of the current 
      engine power-factor for use by the ESM system. The ESM power factor is the 
      product of the current RPM and FPP based power factors as defined by these 
      parameters. In addition, this particular parameter (0% power RPM) defines 
      the delta-rpm above idle speed at which any ESM min-governor adjustments 
      will be phased out with respect to the standard rpm target min governor. 
      ESM_0pwf_load These parameters define the calculation of the current 
      engine power-factor for use by the ESM system. The ESM power factor is the 
      product of the current RPM and load based power factors as defined by 
      these parameters. 
      ESM_1pwf_load These parameters define the calculation of the current 
      engine power-factor for use by the ESM system. The ESM power factor is the 
      product of the current RPM and load based power factors as defined by 
      these parameters. 
      ESM_1pwf_RPM These parameters define the calculation of the current engine 
      power-factor for use by the ESM system. The ESM power factor is the 
      product of the current RPM and load based power factors as defined by 
      these parameters. 
      ESM_active This indicates the current activity (control) state of the ESM 
      function. 
      ESM_decel_control Enable/disable the idle-return rate limit feature of the 
      ESM system. This feature is currently only implemented for 
      idle-air-control (IAC) systems. It has no effect on drive-by-wire (DBW) 
      systems. 
      ESM_dengage_rate This is the rate at which the ESM slew-limited 
      power-factor will be slewed toward the instantaneous value in a decreasing 
      direction This is a POSITIVE (absolute value) %/sec rate. 
      ESM_dly This is the amount of time after the ESM instantaneous 
      power-factor rises over 0% that the system will wait before increasing the 
      final ESM power-factor. 
      ESM_ena Enables/disables the marine 'Emergency Shift Maneuver' (ESM) 
      management function. 
      ESM_engage_rate This is the rate at which the ESM slew-limited 
      power-factor will be slewed toward the instantaneous value in an 
      increasing direction This is a POSITIVE (absolute value) %/sec rate. 
      ESM_fast_rpmdt This is the idle-return rate-limit that will be associated 
      with a 0% power level. This is the 'fast' rate that should be >= the 100% 
      or 'slow' rate. 
      ESM_gov_auth This min governor authority limit will be used during active 
      idle-return rate-limiting. 
      ESM_idle_dload Emergency Shift Maneuver (ESM) current idle delta-load 
      ESM_idle_dload_max This is the maximum delta-load that will be applied to 
      the idle governor during active ESM. This delta scales with the current 
      power-factor proporational to the max power-factor for idle offsets. 
      ESM_idle_drpm Emergency Shift Maneuver (ESM) current idle delta-rpm 
      ESM_idle_drpm_max This is the maximum delta-rpm that will be applied to 
      the idle speed during active ESM. This delta scales with the current 
      power-factor proporational to the max power-factor for idle offsets. 
      ESM_idle_pwr_max This is the power-factor at which the maximum idle offset 
      delta-rpm and delta-load values will be reached. Below this power-factor, 
      these delta values will be scaled down proportionally. 
      ESM_Ilim_max This integrator max limit will be used by the min governor 
      during active idle-return rate-limiting. 
      ESM_Kd This is the min-governor derivative gain (Kd) that will be used 
      during idle-return control of the engine speed. 
      ESM_Kiv This is the min-governor integral-velocity gain (Kiv) that will be 
      used during idle-return control of the engine speed. 
      ESM_pwr_inst The currently computed instantaneous ESM powerfactor based on 
      the load and RPM box defined above. 
      ESM_pwr_slew The currently computed delayed and slewlimited ESM 
      powerfactor based instantaneous value above. 
      ESM_rpmdtd This is the currently calculated engine speed rate-limit for 
      the idle-return system. It is interpolated between the 0% and 100% 
      power-factor rates and subsequently engage/disengage slewed. 
      ESM_rpmdtdz This is the min-governor rpmdt cubic-deadzone will be used 
      during idle-return control of the engine speed. 
      ESM_SIS_extend This is the time that shift interrupt will be additionally 
      inhibited following reaching 0% power-factor after a > 0% power-factor 
      (and delay wait) event. Set this value to zero to cause shift-interrupt to 
      become active as soon as the power-factor decays back to zero. 
      ESM_SIS_inhibit Emergency Shift Maneuver (ESM) shift interrupt status 
      ESM_slow_rpmdt This is the idle-return rate-limit that will be associated 
      with a 100% power level. This is the 'slow' rate that should be <= the 0% 
      or 'fast' rate. 
      ESM_TPSLP This is the min-governor output (TPS command) low-pass 
      time-constant that will be used during idle-return control of the engine 
      speed. 
      ETC_loss_crank_wt If the transmission in-gear override is ETC2 sourced, a 
      valid ETC2 message indicating an acceptable gear state must be received 
      before the engine is allowed to begin cranking. Using a non-zero value 
      here will increase the ETC2 message timeout and allow the engine to 
      continue cranking if the ETC2 message is lost after cranking begins. Note: 
      This value allows the engine to continue cranking in low-battery 
      situations when the external device (e.g. a hand controller) providing the 
      in-gear indication does not have enough battery supply to remain 
      operational. 
      ETHCth_CHT 1D Interpolation Table: Electronic Thermostat Control (ETHC 
      Schedule). Input is MAP (psia), output is CHT (deg F) 
      ETHCth_MAP 1D Interpolation Table: Electronic Thermostat Control (ETHC 
      Schedule). MAP input values (psia) 
      ETHCth_nomDC 1D Interpolation Table: Electronic Thermostat Control (ETHC 
      Schedule). Input is MAP (psia), output is Nominal DC (%) 
      ETHC_channel Electronic Thermostat Control (ETHC) 
      ETHC_CHT_th Electronic Thermostat Control (ETHC) CHT threshold 
      ETHC_cont_time When the ETHC first turns on, it will remain at 100% duty 
      cycle for this amount of time. After that, it will run at the duty-cycle 
      specified by the proportional gain defined below. 
      ETHC_DC Electronic Thermostat Control (ETHC) threshold duty cycle 
      ETHC_dT Electronic Thermostat Control (ETHC) threshold delta-T 
      ETHC_ena Use this select box to disable or enable an electronic thermostat 
      (ETHC) control output on one of the output channels indicated below. This 
      control mode may be set to 'Manual' to cause the output to turn on at the 
      specified duty cycle. 
      ETHC_Kd Electronic Thermostat Control (ETHC) derivative gain 
      ETHC_Kp Electronic Thermostat Control (ETHC) proportional gain 
      ETHC_period Electronic Thermostat Control (ETHC) pulsing period 
      ETHC_state Electronic Thermostat Control (ETHC) output state (Off, 100% 
      On, Pulse Off) 
      EvsECTCF_ena CHT VE correction enable switch 
      EvsMATCF_ena MAT VE correction enable switch 
      EV_AAT The AAT value received over the CAN network from the environmental 
      sensor. 
      EV_AAT_at_fault_def A boolean indicating that the ambient air temperature 
      value currently being received from the Envirotech is equivalent to the 
      default value the Envirotech would send when the sensor is faulted. 
      EV_AAT_fault_def This setting allows changing the temperature used to 
      determine if the HC08-based Envirotech AAT sensor is faulted. By default, 
      the Envirotech will use a temperature of 76.094 degrees Fahrenheit. 
      Temporarily changing this temperature to the current ambient temperature 
      reported by the Envirotech allows testing of the diagnostic calibration in 
      lieu of actually conditioning the ambient temperature. 
      EV_AAT_mdp_avg Low-passed version of the total mass flow rate to the 
      entire engine at the ports used by the Envirotech ambient air temperature 
      invalid diagnostics when operating with the Envirotech 2 (HC08). 
      EV_AAT_mdp_dAct The current actual delta percent between the mass flow of 
      the engine and the low-passed mass flow of the engine. 
      EV_AAT_mdp_dTrg When executing the Envirotech ambient air temperature 
      diagnostic it waits until a large enough change has occurred in the mass 
      flow of the engine and then looks for an expected change in temperature 
      off of the default value. The change in mass flow is calculated as the 
      absolute value of the difference between the mdot_ports value and the 
      low-passed version of the mdot_ports value dividing by the low-passed 
      mdot_ports value. This results in a percentage value that must match or 
      exceed this calibrated delta value. 
      EV_AAT_mdp_tau Low-pass time constant used to generate the low passed 
      ambient air temperature value used by the Envirotech ambient air 
      temperature invalid diagnostic. 
      EV_AAT_mdp_trig Indicates that the Envirotech ambient air temperature 
      invalid diagnostic has seen a sufficient delta in the mass flow of the 
      engine but not a chance in the ambient air temperature away from the 
      default value. Once this boolean has been set the diagnostic will begin 
      latching the fault. 
      EV_comm_active A boolean indicating if communications with the Envirotech 
      is currently active. This will be set if messages are being received 
      within the expected receive timeout value. 
      EV_config Select the Envirotech measurement configuration. 
      EV_EGRoff_tau If the Envirotech is set to "Intake Air + EGR", it can still 
      be used to measure the intake air humidity in an EGR-off situation. After 
      the EGR has been turned off and the off-wait time has been satisfied, the 
      Envirotech humidity is filtered using this time constant and installed in 
      as the intake specific humidity. When EGR flow resumes, the intake 
      humidity is kept constant until the next EGR-off measurement update. 
      EV_EGRoff_wait If the Envirotech is set to "Intake Air + EGR", it can 
      still be used to measure the intake air humidity in an EGR-off situation. 
      After the EGR has been turned off, this is the wait time that is enforced 
      before the Envirotech reading is assumed valid for intake humidity 
      measurement. When EGR flow resumes, the intake humidity is kept constant 
      until the next EGR-off measurement update. 
      EV_RH_AAT_avg Low-passed version of the ambient air temperature value 
      received from the Envirotech. 
      EV_RH_AAT_dAct The current actual delta between the ambient air 
      temperature and the low-passed ambient air temperature. 
      EV_RH_AAT_dTrg The ambient air temp - the low-passed ambient air temp 
      delta calibration variable for the Envirotech relative humidity invalid 
      diagnostic. 
      EV_RH_AAT_tau Time constant used for the EV_RH_AAT_avg low-passed ambient 
      air temperature value. 
      EV_RH_AAT_trig A boolean indicating if conditions have been met such that 
      the Envirotech relative humidity invalid diagnostic believes the relative 
      humidity sensor to be faulted. 
      EV_RH_at_fault_def Indicates that the specific humidity value being 
      transmitted by the Envirotech is equivalent to the value that would be 
      sent if the relative humidity sensor was faulted. 
      EV_RH_at_unstable Boolean indicating that the current specific humidity 
      being received from the Envirotech qualifies as being near or at the value 
      that would indicate the relative humidity sensor is unstable. 
      EV_RH_faulted_SH The specific humidity value that is expected to be seen 
      if the Envirotech relative humidity sensor is faulted. 
      EV_RH_inv_err_margin To determine if the HC08-based Envirotech relative 
      humidity sensor is faulted the diagnostic must compare the specific 
      humidity value received from the Envirotech (RMT_SH) against the specific 
      humidity value that would be expected if the sensor was faulted. Due to 
      error stacking in calculations a margin of error must be used when 
      performing the comparison of the received value against the expected 
      value. This setting specifies the error margin to use when determining the 
      equivalence. 

      Each allowed value represents an additional bit of error in the value. The 
      smaller the error margin the more likely to miss a faulted sensor, but 
      less likely to trigger a false positive. 
      EV_RH_inv_fault_def This setting allows changing the relative humidity 
      used to determine if the HC08-based Envirotech humidity sensor is faulted. 
      By default, the Envirotech will use a relative humidity of 50%. 
      Temporarily changing this value to the back-calculated relative humidity 
      allows testing of the diagnostic calibration in lieu of actually 
      conditioning the ambient relative humidity. 
      EV_RH_max_SH The maximum allowed specific humidity value expected from the 
      Envirotech. A value higher than this setting will trigger the Envirotech 
      relative humidity invalid fault. 
      EV_RH_near_zero Boolean indicating that the current specific humidity 
      being received from the Envirotech qualifies as being near zero when 
      compared to EV_RH_near_zero_SH. 
      EV_RH_near_zero_SH The specific humidity value that is expected to be seen 
      if the Envirotech relative humidity sensor is reading new 0% RH. 
      EV_RH_rat_mode Enables relative humidity rationalization for the 
      Envirotech 2 (HC08-based). This setting must be enabled if the "Envirotech 
      relative humidity unstable" fault is enabled. Rationalization does not 
      occur if EGR is disabled or when connected to an Envirotech 3.

      When enabled, and the "RH unstable state" is "Unstable" or the unstable 
      state latch indicator is on:
      - specific humidity is set to 0;
      - the "Environmental sensor relative humidity invalid" fault is disabled; 
      and
      - UEGO drift sampling is disabled. 
      EV_RH_unstable Envirotech 2 RH unstable latch status. 
      EV_RH_unstable_SH The specific humidity value that is expected to be seen 
      if the Envirotech relative humidity sensor is reading below 0%. 
      EV_RH_uns_err_margin To determine if the HC08-based Envirotech relative 
      humidity sensor is unstable the diagnostic must compare the specific 
      humidity value received from the Envirotech (RMT_SH) against specific 
      humidity values that would be expected if the sensor was unstable. Due to 
      error stacking in calculations a margin of error must be used when 
      performing the comparison of the received value against the expected 
      value. This setting specifies the error margin to use when determining the 
      equivalence. 

      Each allowed value represents an additional bit of error in the value. The 
      smaller the error margin the more likely to miss a faulted sensor, but 
      less likely to trigger a false positive. 
      EV_RH_uns_latch_pct Latch percentage for the Envirotech 2 RH unstable 
      state. 
      EV_RH_uns_latch_tm Latch time for the Envirotech 2 RH unstable state. 
      EV_RH_uns_state State tracking variable used with the Envirotech relative 
      humidity unstable diagnostic. 
      EV_RH_uns_unlatch_tm Unlatch time for the Envirotech 2 RH unstable state. 
      EV_SH A copy of the RMT_SH value that has been adjusted to match the value 
      expected in the Envirotech. 
      EV_version If an Envirotech is communicating with the ECU, this indicates 
      the version of the Envirotech. 
      exhbrake_active Logical indicating exhaust brake is active 
      exhbrake_chan Select the output channel for the exhaust brake. 
      exhbrake_min_ECT Sets the minimum ECT required to activate the Exhaust 
      brake.

      NOTES: "Retarder disabled by minimum ECT" must be set to 'Yes' for this 
      minimum ECT to be honored. The "Exhaust brake minimum ECT" requirement may 
      be disabled by the "Retarder run time override ECT". 
      exhbrake_mode Select the operating mode for the exhaust brake. In 'foot 
      pedal at idle' mode, the output mirrors the operation of the transmission 
      brake (see the comment in the driveline brake mode above for details). In 
      remotely controlled mode, the output only activates when a negative TSC1 
      torque limit or torque control setpoint is active. The final mode will 
      activate the exhaust brake if commanded by a TSC1 negative torque command 
      OR if the foot pedal is at idle. 
      exhbrake_retard_pct Enter the retard percentage between 0-100% for the 
      exhaust brake. For example, if the retarder torque in the J1939 torque 
      estimation tables at the current engine speed is 500 N-m, and this value 
      is set to 25%, engaging the exhaust brake should provide 125 N-m of 
      braking. The remaining 375 N-m comes from the driveline brake. 
      exhbrake_source Exhaust brake remote source address 
      exhbrake_torq_max Estimated max retard (available) torque percent of 
      reference torque for the exhaust brake 
      exhbrake_torq_pct Exhaust Retarder Torque: Exhaust brake torque percent 
      EXH_preEGR_delay Exhaust pre-EGR transport delay component 
      EXH_preEGR_xa Exhaust pre-EGR transport delay component; air contribution 
      EXH_preEGR_xd Exhaust pre-EGR transport delay component; diluent 
      contribution 
      EXH_preEGR_xf Exhaust pre-EGR transport delay component; fuel contribution 

      EXH_pstEGR_delay Exhaust post-EGR transport delay component 
      EXH_pstEGR_xa Exhaust post-EGR transport delay component; air contribution 

      EXH_pstEGR_xd Exhaust post-EGR transport delay component; diluent 
      contribution 
      EXH_pstEGR_xf Exhaust post-EGR transport delay component; fuel 
      contribution

      ext_cal_sync_CS_32 External calibration sync checksum 
      F201_security Specify the security level required to access this data 
      logging DID 
      F201_version Specify the version number to be returned by the DID or 65535 
      to eliminate the version number from the response data. 
      FAratio Current commanded fuel/air ratio 
      fastidle_act_st This software switch determines what state (Gnd, +V, or 
      open-circuit) is considered 'fast idle active' on the tri-state digital 
      inputs controlling this function. The states not selected are considered 
      'inactive'. 
      fastidle_ena This software switch enables and designates which digital 
      input controls an increased idle (min governor) speed. Note that the 
      Gnd/+V/Open state for these tri-state digital inputs must also be 
      specified. Note also that if a governor switch input is used, the 
      corresponding Gov1/2/3 software switches must be set to 'Disabled' since 
      this system does not actually enable a discrete speed governor - it only 
      raises the min governor target. 
      fastidle_rpm This is the target idle (min governor) speed when the fast 
      idle digital input is valid active. 
      FAstoich_a_G Actual stoichiometric fuel/air mass ratio for the fuel being 
      burned in the engine. 
      FAstoich_a_N Actual stoichiometric fuel/air mass ratio for the fuel being 
      burned in the engine. 
      FAstoich_a_P Actual stoichiometric fuel/air mass ratio for the fuel being 
      burned in the engine. 
      FAstoich_s_G Standard stoichiometric fuel/air mass ratio for the fuel used 
      in the fuel flow calibration. 
      FAstoich_s_N Standard stoichiometric fuel/air mass ratio for the fuel used 
      in the fuel flow calibration. 
      FAstoich_s_P Standard stoichiometric fuel/air mass ratio for the fuel used 
      in the fuel flow calibration. 
      faultact_AL_dis Configures which adaptive learning sub-systems are 
      disabled when a fault that is calibrated with the 'AL Disable' and/or the 
      'AL Disable key-cyc' fault switches selected is active-latched. 
      faultact_persist The fault action persist feature allows enforcement of 
      fault switch selected warnings and derates for an active fault to continue 
      once the fault becomes inactive. To persist actions for a particular 
      fault, select the "Action Persist" fault switch on the Diagnostics 
      worksheet in addition to the desired warnings and derates.

      For 'Cycle' mode, once an active fault becomes inactive, the fault switch 
      actions are persisted through the end of the current engine cycle and 
      subsequent cycles until the inactive cycle count exceeds the "Fault action 
      persist cycle mode count" parameter threshold.

      If 'Fault state mode' is selected, fault switch actions are persisted 
      until a fault is conclusively not faulted in the subsequent engine/warm 
      cycle. At minimum, fault actions are persisted until the end of the 
      current engine cycle if an active fault becomes inactive in the same 
      cycle. 

      Fault actions persisted include:
      - Turn On MIL (if “Fault action persist MIL” is enabled)
      - CL Disable
      - AL Disable
      - Power Derate 1
      - Power Derate 2
      - Low Rev Limit
      - Force Idle
      - Soft Warning
      - Hard Warning

      faultact_persist_cyc When "Fault action persist mode" is set to 'Cycle', 
      this parameter determines how many subsequent engine/warm cycles fault 
      actions are persisted after an active fault with the "Active Persist" 
      fault switch selected has gone inactive. A value of zero will only persist 
      the fault actions to the end of the current cycle.

      If the "Fault system mode" is configured as 'Euro VI' or 'CARB 1971.1', 
      the cycle counter does not start incrementing until the fault transitions 
      from the "Confirmed and active" state to the "Previously active" state, 
      which usually occurs two warm cycles after the active fault went inactive. 
      Thus, fault actions will persist as least one more cycle than configured 
      for this parameter. 

      faultact_persist_MIL If enabled and the "Turn On MIL" fault switch is 
      selected for an active fault, the MIL will continue to illuminate once the 
      fault becomes inactive for the same duration as other fault actions are 
      persisted in both cycle and fault state modes. 

      If the "Fault system mode" is configured as 'Euro VI' or 'CARB 1971.1' 
      this setting is ignored. The MIL behavior will instead be determined by 
      the applicable legislation requirements. 

      For 'Custom' and 'State Standard V (SSV)' fault system modes, the "MIL 
      start cycle minimum persistence" setting is ignored if this parameter is 
      enabled.

      FaultCylBlock_use This setting specifies whether cylinders are referred to 
      in firing order or block order for injector and spark diagnostics. A block 
      order request must be accompanied by valid firing order information for 
      each cylinder before block ordering within the system will actually be 
      used.

      When the "Fuel injection type" is configured for 'Throttle-body' injection 
      firing order will be used for injector diagnostics, regardless of this 
      setting. Additionally, on platforms configured to allow secondary 
      injection firing order is always used for the secondary set of injectors.

      fault_rev_lim Fault low rev limit speed: Lower rev limit during faults 
      requesting this feature. The rpm governor rev limit will be attempted by 
      the max speed governor using the throttle and the rpm governor + rpm fuel 
      delta will be implemented by cutting the fuel supply to the engine 
      fault_rev_limd Fault low rev limit speed delta 
      fault_rev_lim_latch This switch determines whether or not a fault 
      commanding a low rev limit will stay latched for the remainder of the 
      key-cycle or if it will only be in effect during an active fault condition 
      and while unlatch engine conditions are not yet fulfilled. 
      fault_SD_dis_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the input, this value 
      determines the active logic state(s). The Default values are:

      Aux DIG1 = Gnd
      Aux DIG2 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG3 = Gnd
      Aux DIG4 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG5 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG6 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG7 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG8 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG9 = Gnd
      Aux DIG10 = Gnd
      Aux DIG11 = Gnd
      Aux DIG12 = Gnd
      Aux DIG13 = Gnd
      Aux DIG14 = Gnd
      Aux DIG15 = Gnd
      Aux DIG16 = Gnd
      Aux DIG17 = Gnd
      Aux DIG18 = Gnd
      Aux DIG19 = Gnd
      Gov1 = Gnd
      Gov2 = Gnd 
      fault_SD_dis_ena Selects the input used for fault shutdown inhibit. When 
      this input is active, it prevents any fault from being able to shut down 
      the engine. However, the "Engine overspeed" fault is excluded and this 
      fault will still shut down the engine. 
      fault_store_EE This switch determines whether faults are retained in 
      battery supported memory or permanent memory. In battery supported memory, 
      faults will be cleared if the battery power is removed from the ECM. In 
      permanent memory, a technician must use a service tool to clear faults. 
      Per legislated requirements, if the "Fault system mode" is configured as 
      'Euro VI' or 'CARB' this setting is ignored and faults will be permanently 
      retained. 
      fault_store_EEa Actual fault retention memory that may be adjusted from 
      desired based on the active fault system mode. 
      FAUX1 Auxiliary flow determined by volts vs. flow table lookup 
      FAUX1_ena Auxiliary Flow Sesnor 1 (FAUX1) enable/channel select switch 
      FAUX1_Faux_cal Auxiliary Flow Sesnor 1 (FAUX1) calibration table select 
      switch 
      FAUX1_units Units of flow based on selected cal table 
      FAUX1_volts Voltage from sensor (filtered) 
      FAUX2 Auxiliary flow determined by volts vs. flow table lookup

      FauxB_Funits Units selection for Auxiliary Flow B Calibration table 
      FCtl_cal_grp Calibration Group: Assigned Group to Faults 
      FCtl_DTC This scalar display provides a hook for updating the displayed 
      DTC for the faults. Note that the UIR file will have a control for this 
      scalarDis, but it is hidden. Note that This *must* be low priority or 
      custom code will break. 
      FCtl_DTC_0x04 Fault table: Fault DTC (Format 0x04 - HEX2DEC) 
      FCtl_FMI Fault table: Fault FMI

      fc_blink_output This setting specifies the logical output channel to use 
      to blink flash codes. The actual physical output pin is determined based 
      on the "Warning/MIL Output Configuration" settings. 
      FDC_CLAL_ref EGR fuel diluent compensation parameter.

      in Flight Data Recorder (EDIS and calibration spreadsheet) 
      FDR_cust_tbl Configuration table - define customizable parameters to be

      FDR_storage Flight data recorder storage area 
      FIMP_BTU_act Use this for fuel impurity interpolation based on BTUs. Input 
      the BTU value for the fuel in its actual form. 
      FIMP_BTU_imp Use this for fuel impurity interpolation based on BTUs. Input 
      the BTU value for the fuel in its 100% impure form. 
      FIMP_BTU_pure Use this for fuel impurity interpolation based on BTUs. 
      Input the BTU value for the fuel in its pure form. 
      FIMP_ena This switch controls the fuel impurity (composition) compensation 
      system. This allows the phi target, nominal EPR/MJ pressure and phi, base 
      and offset spark timing, CWT spark retard values, fuel specific gravity 
      and stoich fuel/air ratio, and fuel/rpm based load-limiting to be 
      interpolated between the base fuel cal (usually LPG) and the 100% impure 
      fuel cal (usually NG).

      If the active fuel type is not LPG or NG, fuel impurity compensation is 
      automatically disabled regardless of this parameter's setting. 
      FIMP_extV_0pct Voltage level that represents a fuel impurity of 0% 
      FIMP_extV_100pct Voltage level that represents a fuel impurity of 100% 
      FIMP_extV_input_pin External voltage fuel impurity input pin - external 
      0-5 V input source for 0-100 percent fuel impurity. 
      FIMP_extV_tau Low-pass filter time constant in ms for the external voltage 
      impurity input 
      FIMP_fault_def Default fuel impurity to use when a FTT or FTP sensor fault 
      is active. When set to a negative value and a sensor fault is active, fuel 
      impurity will be calculated based on default values for fuel tank 
      temperature and pressure. 
      FIMP_init_mode This switch controls how the fuel impurity is initialized 
      at key-on. Either the value can always be initialized to the cold power-up 
      default, or the last value at key-off can remain intact (subject to 
      battery voltage not being removed from the ECM). 
      FIMP_learn_tau Once all conditions are satisfied for LPG FTP/FTT based 
      fuel impurity adaptation updates (engine start wait, MAP/RPM window wait), 
      the fuel impurity will be updated at a rate defined by this time constant. 

      FIMP_LL_ena This switch selects the method used to determine the 
      load-limiting factor with respect to the current fuel impurity percentage. 

      - 'Disabled' option, the load-limit factor will be 1. (Thus, no impact to 
      load-limits based on fuel impurity.) 
      - 'Linear start-to-finish' option, the calculated load-limit factor will 
      use linear interpolation between the start and finish values defined 
      below. 
      - 'Nonlinear derate table' option, the calculated load-limit factor will 
      use non-linear interpolation based on the 9-point fuel impurity table on 
      the Derate page. This option has the same effect as the 'start and finish' 
      values, but this table provides more calibration points for non-linear 
      operation.
      - 'Speed-based derate tables' option, the calculated load-limit factor 
      will use linear interpolation between 'Table 2/LPG' and 'Table 3/NG' of 
      the 'Speed-Based Load Limit' tables on the Derate page. 
      FIMP_LL_pct Lower Limit of FIMP_percent 
      FIMP_LL_stop These two parameters define how the fuel/RPM based 
      load-limiting tables will be interpolated when fuel impurity mode is 
      enabled. The base fuel (usually LPG) load-limit will be used up to the 
      'start' impurity value, and the impure fuel (usually NG) load-limit will 
      be used beyond the 'finish' value with linear interpolation between the 
      two. Therefore, finish >= start, and start=0%/finish=100% defines a 
      straight linear relationship. 
      FIMP_LL_strt These two parameters define how the fuel/RPM based 
      load-limiting tables will be interpolated when fuel impurity mode is 
      enabled. The base fuel (usually LPG) load-limit will be used up to the 
      'start' impurity value, and the impure fuel (usually NG) load-limit will 
      be used beyond the 'finish' value with linear interpolation between the 
      two. Therefore, finish >= start, and start=0%/finish=100% defines a 
      straight linear relationship. 
      FIMP_MAP_max MAP adaptive learn zone requirements (max value) for 
      FIMP_pct. This is one of 4 values that define a MAP min/max and RPM 
      min/max operational window within which the LPG FTP/FTT based fuel 
      impurity adaptation mode will attempt to learn the current fuel impurity 
      level. 
      FIMP_MAP_min MAP adaptive learn zone requirements (min value) for 
      FIMP_pct. This is one of 4 values that define a MAP min/max and RPM 
      min/max operational window within which the LPG FTP/FTT based fuel 
      impurity adaptation mode will attempt to learn the current fuel impurity 
      level. 
      FIMP_pct_high Fuel leak (regulator to mixer) diagnostic: This parameter 
      represents the rate of change of the battery voltage in volts/sec. In 
      order to detect a sudden voltage drop when the starter is engaged, set 
      this value to a sufficiently large negative value. 
      FIMP_pct_init This switch controls how the fuel impurity is initialized at 
      key-on. Either the value can always be initialized to the cold power-up 
      default, or the last value at key-off can remain intact (subject to 
      battery voltage not being removed from the ECM). 
      FIMP_pct_ss Value of FIMP_percent before Low Pass Filter 
      FIMP_percent Fuel Impurity. Zero percent FI indicates computations based 
      on current base fuel maps. 100 percent FI indicates computations based on 
      indicated alternate fuel maps. 
      FIMP_RPM_max Engine speed adaptive learn zone requirements (rpm max value) 
      for FIMP_pct. This is one of 4 values that define a MAP min/max and RPM 
      min/max operational window within which the LPG FTP/FTT based fuel 
      impurity adaptation mode will attempt to learn the current fuel impurity 
      level. 
      FIMP_RPM_min Engine speed adaptive learn zone requirements (rpm min value) 
      for FIMP_pct. This is one of 4 values that define a MAP min/max and RPM 
      min/max operational window within which the LPG FTP/FTT based fuel 
      impurity adaptation mode will attempt to learn the current fuel impurity 
      level. 
      FIMP_strt_wait Before LPG FTP/FTT based fuel impurity adaptation updates 
      are allowed, the engine must be running for at least this amount of time. 
      FIMP_SW_input_cfg Tri-state fuel impurity switch configuration 
      FIMP_SW_input_pin Tri-state fuel impurity switch input pin - This switch 
      determines what hardware pin on the ECM is used to select tri-state fuel 
      impurity. 
      FIMP_type This switch controls the method that is used to determine the 
      fuel impurity level.
      - 'Constant/Default' causes the initialization value to be used.
      - 'LPG FTP/FTT Adapt' uses LPG tank pressure/temperature to estimate the 
      impurity level using the associated table.
      - 'Tri-state switch input' uses an external tri-state toggle switch to 
      indicate an impurity level of 0%, 50% or 100%
      - 'External voltage input' uses an external analog 0-5v input signal to 
      indicate an impurity level of 0-100%
      - 'Fuel BTU input' is a calibration value indicating the actual BTU value 
      of the fuel. This value is used in conjunction with the BTU pure and BTU 
      impure calibration variables to calculate a fuel impurity percentage. 
      FIMP_wndw_wait Before LPG FTP/FTT based fuel impurity adaptation updates 
      are allowed, the engine must enter the 4-point MAP/RPM window defined 
      above and remain there for at least this amount of time. 
      FIP FIP sensor value after low-pass 
      FIP_def FIP default pressure value 
      FIP_ena FIP sensor input source 
      FIP_LL_ena If enabled, the 4G ECM will use the fuel inlet pressure to do a 
      table lookup to determine the maximum allowed load based on fuel inlet 
      pressure. 
      FIP_LoExp_mdot FIP lower than expected diagnostic - fuel flow lower limit 
      entry condition 
      FIP_Paux_cal Fuel inlet pressure auxiliary pressure calibration table 
      selection 
      FIP_raw Raw FIP sensor value prior to low-pass 
      FIP_tau Time constant for FIP sensor low-pass 
      FKNK_ena Enables or disables fuel based knock control. When enabled, the 
      target phi for the engine will be modified based on the calibration 
      parameters during a knocking (spark retarded by knock) condition. 
      FKNK_enrich_max This is the fuel modifier used at knock retard values 
      greater than or equal to the control completion retard value. This is 
      implemented as a % change in the phi target - and may be positive or 
      negative (+ enrichment, - enleanment). Fuel modifiers between the 
      initiation and completion retard values are interpolated between this 
      value and zero. 
      FKNK_enrich_mod Current knock fuel modifier 
      FKNK_enr_dec_tau When lower retard values command lower (absolute value) 
      fuel modifier values, this time constant is used to low-pass the fuel 
      modifier. 
      FKNK_enr_inc_tau When higher retard values command higher (absolute value) 
      fuel modifier values, this time constant is used to low-pass the fuel 
      modifier. 
      FKNK_ret_max The knock retard value at which fuel-based knock control will 
      reach its maximum. Knock retard values higher than this (less advanced) 
      will command the constant maximum fuel modifier. 
      FKNK_ret_start The minimum knock retard value at which fuel-based knock 
      control will begin. Knock retard values lower than this (more advanced) 
      will command a 0% fuel modifier. 
      flag1_HWARN Hard warning indicator 
      flag1_SWARN Soft warning indicator 
      flag2_IVS_AT_IDLE Idle Validation Switch (IVS) state (off-idle, at idle) 
      flag4_ACTIVE_FPP Active FPP source (FPP1, FPP2) 
      FLEVgd_chan Enable and select the output channel for the gauge driver 
      FLEVgd_DC Gaseous fuel level (FLEV) gauge driver duty-cycle 
      FLEVgd_per "Gauge driver pulse period": Value is only applicable for 
      output channels 'Aux PWM1' through 'Aux PWM4'. 'Aux PWM5' has a hardcoded 
      period of 0.5 ms. 
      FLEV_ena Enables/disables gaseous fuel level monitoring. This must be 
      enabled for gauge driver output and/or low-fuel level handling. 
      FLEV_FTP_empty Empty (0 percent) fuel tank pressure 
      FLEV_FTP_full Full (100 percent) fuel tank pressure 
      FLEV_FTstd Specify the standard fuel tank temperature used for the low 
      fuel level and gauge driver calibrations. 
      FLEV_FT_crct Enables fuel tank temperature (density) correction on fuel 
      tank pressure. The corrected FTP is used for both gauge driver output and 
      low fuel level handling. 
      FLEV_lo_active Fuel level low handling active indication if YES, otherwise 
      disabled 
      FLEV_lo_chan Select an output for a fuel level low indicator. Note that 
      this toggle switch only controls the external low fuel level indicator and 
      does not disable low fuel level handling. 
      FLEV_lo_faults If set to 'Enabled - Legacy' and gaseous fuel level is 
      actively low (FLEV_lo_active), then the following faults are inhibited 
      from updating:
      "Control underboost 1" fault
      "Control underboost 2" fault
      "Boost control slow to respond" fault
      "CL low gasoline bank 1" fault
      "CL high gasoline bank 1" fault
      "CL low gasoline bank 2" fault
      "CL high gasoline bank 2" fault
      "CL low LPG" fault
      "CL high LPG" fault
      "CL low NG" fault
      "CL high NG" fault
      "CL air/fuel ratio control at limit - too lean" fault
      "CL air/fuel ratio control at limit - too rich" fault
      "EPR / CFV regulation pressure lower than expected" fault
      "EPR secondary regulation pressure lower than expected" fault

      This parameter does not disable AL or CL. To disable AL, use Low Fuel 
      Monitoring in the DiagConfig worksheet.

      If set to 'Use Low Fuel Monitoring', then the Low Fuel Monitoring section 
      in the DiagConfig worksheet must be enabled and configured. Set "Low fuel 
      monitoring input" to 'Gaseous Fuel Level FLEV Monitoring (NG)'. Low Fuel 
      Monitoring is more configurable as it provides a variety of low-fuel input 
      sources and more fault options. 
      FLEV_lo_hyst Low fuel level hysteresis. Once low fuel level handling is 
      active, the (corrected) fuel pressure must satisfy FTP_crct > low trig + 
      low hysteresis before low fuel level handling goes inactive. 
      FLEV_lo_LLpct Load limit when low fuel level is active. Set this to 100% 
      to disable low fuel level load limiting.
