      FLEV_lo_trig Fuel level (%) when low fuel level handling should go active. 
      Set this to 0 to disable all low fuel level functionality. 
      FLEV_pct Fuel level percentage 
      FltStartMax This setting specifies the number of engine stopped-running 
      cycles before clearing a historic fault automatically. Entering a 0 here 
      causes all faults to be retained until manually cleared (automatic 
      clearing is disabled). Per legislated requirements, if the 'Fault system 
      mode' is configured as 'Euro VI' or 'CARB' this setting is ignored and a 
      value of 40 warm-up cycles will be used. 
      FltStartMaxa Number of cycles (engine or warmup) before auto-clearing 
      historic faults potentially adjusted based on active fault system mode 
      FltStartMaxPnd This setting specifies the number of engine stopped-running 
      cycles before clearing a pending fault automatically. Entering a 0 here 
      causes all faults to be retained until manually cleared (automatic 
      clearing is disabled). Per legislated requirements, if the 'Fault system 
      mode' is configured as 'Euro VI' or 'CARB' this setting is ignored and a 
      value of 0 is enforced, preventing automatic clearing. 
      FltStartMaxPnda Number of cycles (engine or warmup) before auto-clearing 
      pending faults potentially adjusted based on active fault system mode 
      fm_ac_cyc_type This setting specifies the type of cycle to be used for 
      automatic clearing of faults. When set to 'Engine cycle', each start/stop 
      cycle of the engine will be counted as a cycle. When set to 'Warm-up 
      cycle', each start/stop cycle of the engine that meets the "Warm-up Cycle 
      Configuration" requirements will be counted as a cycle.

      Per legislated requirements, if the "Fault system mode" is configured as 
      'Euro VI' or 'CARB', then this setting is ignored and warm-up cycles will 
      be used. 
      fm_ac_cyc_typea Cycle type for fault autoclearing potentially adjusted 
      based on fault system mode 
      fm_clr_mode Indicates the fault clearing mode. Possible values:

      "Normal": faults are cleared as directed by the calibrated fault operation 
      cycle type

      "Paused during remote stop": faults are not cleared or unlatched while the 
      engine is not running during a remote shutdown. This state is only used 
      when hybrid fault mode is enabled. 
      fm_cont_mil_na_cyc Operation cycles since the continuous MI was last 
      active 
      fm_cycles_wo_b1 Euro VI number of sequential operation cycles without a 
      confirmed and active B1 fault 
      fm_derate_clear This setting specifies whether or not active "Power 
      Derate" conditions may be cleared using a scan tool over the J1939 or ISO 
      15765 protocols. This controls clearing of both active "Power Derate 1" 
      and "Power Derate 2" faults as well as key-cycle latched "Power Derate 2" 
      states. 
      fm_discmil Effective Euro VI discriminatory MIL state 
      fm_dist_since_clr cumulative distance in km since DTCs were cleared. 
      fm_dist_while_MIL cumulative distance in km for the most recent MIL 
      activation. 
      fm_drive_cyc_tmr Elapsed time for the current drive cycle 
      fm_dtc_svr_ena Enables use of the optional per-fault "DTC Severity" 
      configuration within the UDS services. When disabled fault queries based 
      on the UDS severity and class information will exclude the "DTC severity 
      information" portion and only query against the "DTC Class" configuration. 

      fm_gd_cont_rt_idle Current idle time required for incrementing general 
      denominator 
      fm_gd_cum_rt_env Cumulative engine runtime in applicable environment 
      required for incrementing general denominator 
      fm_gd_cum_rt_oper Cumulative engine runtime in operation required for 
      incrementing general denominator 
      fm_gd_idle_req_env Indicates that elevation and ambient air temperature 
      requirements must be met to increment the general denominator continuous 
      idle time. 
      fm_gd_oper_AAT_max Specifies the upper ambient air temperature limit for 
      incrementing the IUPR general denominator cumulative operation time. If 
      AAT exceeds this limit, the cumulative operation time freezes on its 
      current accumulated value. 

      For compliance with HD OBD regulations, set this value to 94.7 deg F (308 
      deg K) for Euro VI applications and 100.1 deg F (311 deg K) for China VI 
      applications. This parameter is ignored for CARB 1971.1 applications. 
      fm_gd_oper_load_ena Indicates that load will be included when determining 
      engine operation for the cumulative operation time. 
      fm_gd_oper_req_env Indicates that elevation and ambient air temperature 
      requirements must be met to increment the general denominator cumulative 
      operation time. 
      fm_gd_oper_rpm_ena Indicates that RPM will be included when determining 
      engine operation for the cumulative operation time. 
      fm_gd_oper_rs_ena Indicates that roadspeed will be included when 
      determining engine operation for the cumulative operation time. 
      fm_gd_rt_oper_mode One of the requirements for incrementing the IUPR 
      general denominator is that the engine must operate for at least 3 
      seconds. The system supports determining engine operation based on road 
      speed (requires active road speed input) or RPM. The allowed methods of 
      determining engine operation depend on the desired OBD legislation.

      - For Euro VI either road speed or RPM may be used.
      - For CARB road speed should be used for gasoline engines and RPM should 
      be used for diesel engines. 
      fm_general_denom The IUPR general denominator 
      fm_hybrid_mode Enables fault behaviors for hybrid applications. When 
      enabled, the fault clearing mode will indicate “Pause during remote stop” 
      when a remote stop request is received, and will return to “Normal” when 
      the remote stop request is inactive and the engine is in a normal running 
      state.

      When the fault clearing mode is "Paused during remote stop":
      - Fault indicators are not cleared
      - Faults with “Pause During Remote Stop” checked cannot unlatch or clear
      - Inducement state is not cleared
      - CFV low fuel pressure derate pauses 
      fm_ign_cyc_counter count of ignition cycles in counts. Rolls over to 0. 
      fm_induce_actv_chan Selects the output channel to use when the inducement 
      system derate is active or is requested and waiting for activation. 
      fm_induce_derate Reports the current state of inducement system derate. 
      fm_induce_dn_EGR 36-hour faults cleared inducement reset timer. 
      fm_induce_dn_Mon 36-hour faults cleared inducement reset timer. 
      fm_induce_ena Enables the Euro VI and China VI fault inducement system 
      counters and derates. Inducement status is reported via J1979 PID 0xF494. 
      fm_induce_l1_ll Selects the Derate Load-Limit table to use when enforcing 
      the Level 1 / low-level torque reduction inducement. 
      fm_induce_l3_km Selects the road speed limit to use when enforcing the 
      Level 3 / severe "creep mode" inducement. If a load-limit is used for 
      severe enforcement instead of a road speed limit, this value should be set 
      to value beyond the expected road speed possible during the severe 
      enforcement load-limit. 
      fm_induce_l3_ll Selects the Derate Load-Limit table to use when enforcing 
      the Level 3 / severe torque reduction inducement. 
      fm_induce_l3_ll_flt Parameter selects the derate load-limit table to use 
      when enforcing the Level 3 / severe "creep mode" inducement while the 
      roadspeed is considered faulted. One or more of the following faults must 
      be considered faulted:
      "Roadspeed short to ground" fault
      "Roadspeed open/short to power" fault
      "Roadspeed loss" fault
      "Roadspeed sensor disconnected" fault
      "J1939 roadspeed error or message receipt lost" fault 
      fm_induce_l3_ll_pre Parameter determines if Level 1 / low-level torque 
      reduction is allowed while Level 3 / severe "creep mode" inducement is 
      active. When parameter is set to 'Enabled - Before RS Limit', the 
      "Inducement Level 1 low-level" load-limit table is enforced while the 
      roadspeed is below the "Inducement Level 3 severe" roadspeed limit. Once 
      roadspeed becomes greater than the inducement roadspeed limit, then 
      low-level torque reduction ceases. Note: the "Inducement Level 3 
      load-limit from roadspeed fault" is a higher priority load-limit if 
      enabled. When parameter is set to 'Enabled - Always', then the "Inducement 
      Level 1 low-level" load-limit table is always active while Level 3 / 
      severe "creep mode" inducement is active. 
      fm_induce_l3_tmr Severe inducement 8-hour continuous operation wait timer. 

      fm_induce_state Reports the current state of inducement system. 
      fm_induce_up_EGR 36 and 100-hour inducement up timer. 
      fm_induce_up_Mon 36 and 100-hour inducement up timer. 
      fm_mode This setting controls the overall fault system behavior so that it 
      conforms to On-Board Diagnostics (OBD) legislation. The following options 
      are available:

      - Custom – the fault system follows the legacy behavior and provides full 
      customization
      - State Standard V (SSV) – the fault system will conform to China State 
      Standard V legislation (HJ 437-2008)
      - Euro VI – the fault system will conform to Euro VI legislation (UN/ECE 
      Regulation No 49)
      - CARB 1971.1 - the fault system will conform to CARB 1971.1 legislation 
      fm_mon_act_cnt Percentage closeness to faulted 
      fm_mon_CDTC statusOfDTC byte confirmedDTC 
      fm_mon_confact Computed Confirmed Active DTC state 
      fm_mon_con_cnt Percentage closeness to diagnostic conclusion 
      fm_mon_cycles_cnt Engine or warmup cycles while in previously active state 

      fm_mon_ena Enables the fault monitor functionality 
      fm_mon_fctl_ndx Fault Control Index for the fault to monitor 
      fm_mon_mil_cnt MIL countdown 
      fm_mon_mil_type Fault level MIL state 
      fm_mon_PDTC statusOfDTC byte pendingDTC 
      fm_mon_pending Computed Pending DTC state 
      fm_mon_permanent Computed Permanent DTC state 
      fm_mon_potential Computed Potential DTC state 
      fm_mon_prevact Computed Previously Active DTC state 
      fm_mon_sec_prevact Elapsed engine hours since transitioning to previously 
      active state 
      fm_mon_TF statusOfDTC byte testFailed 
      fm_mon_TFSLC statusOfDTC byte testFailedSinceLastClear 
      fm_mon_TFTOC statusOfDTC byte testFailedThisOperationCycle 
      fm_mon_TNCSLC statusOfDTC byte testNotCompletedSinceLastClear 
      fm_mon_TNCTOC statusOfDTC byte testNotCompletedThisOperationCycle 
      fm_mon_WIR statusOfDTC byte warningIndicatorRequested 
      fm_NOx_dep_delay Parameter configures the delay in activating the NOx 
      control system derate when a NOx control dependency fault is faulted. A 
      dependency fault is identified by the "NOx Control Dependency" fault 
      switch being set. When a dependency fault has been faulted for this 
      parameter's amount of engine run time, then the NOx derate specified by 
      "NOX Control Derate source" is activated. This parameter is only 
      applicable when the "NOx Control Derate source" is not 'Disabled'.

      The default value of 36 hours complies with China 5/Euro 5 legislation. 
      Setting the value to 0 disables the fault dependency-based derate. 
      fm_NOx_dep_run_time Engine run time that a NOx control system dependency 
      fault has been faulted. 
      fm_NOx_derate_table Parameter selects the load-limiting table used for the 
      NOx control system derate. The derate is activated if any of the following 
      are true:
      - A fault with the "NOx Control Derate" fault switch enabled is considered 
      faulted.
      - A fault with the "NOX Control Dependency" fault switch enabled has been 
      faulted for "NOx Control Dependency derate delay" engine hours.

      The vehicle must be stationary (roadspeed less than 0.5 km/hr) before 
      derate can activate. The engine speed must be at idle (rpm <= min_gov_rpm 
      + 100) before derate can deactivate. 
      fm_nox_retention This setting specifies the number of engine runtime hours 
      that NOx Control System faults will be retained. Prior to this time these 
      faults will not be erasable via scan tools or the "Start cycle for 
      auto-clearing" functionality.

      Once the configured amount of time has elapsed since the last occurrence 
      of a fault it will become clearable via scan tools or by the auto-clearing 
      functionality.

      The default value of 9600 hours complies with China 5/Euro 5 legislation. 
      Setting the value to 0 disables allowing clearing of NOx Control System 
      faults after a time period, effectively preventing them from ever being 
      cleared via a scan tool. 
      fm_operation_cycle Current operation cycle type 
      fm_oper_cyc_counter The current operation cycle for the fault system. 
      Equivalent to engine cycles for Custom, SSV, and Euro VI fault system 
      modes. CARB has the additional 'drive cycle' requirement of transitioning 
      every 4 hours of continuous engine operation. 
      fm_op_reset_key_on During an operation cycle reset, the previous cycle 
      global and per-fault status is used to finalize the results of previous 
      operation cycle. Once finalized various state is reset in preparation for 
      the next cycle. Historically, this transition has been performed at engine 
      start so that it follows the “operating sequence” definition from Euro VI 
      and China VI legislation where an operating sequence is from engine start 
      to the next engine start. For faults with “Stopped check” enabled, this 
      can result in a non-intuitive behavior where the time after key on and 
      until engine start is considered part of the previous operation cycle.

      When "Every key-on" is selected, operating cycle finalization and reset 
      for stopped check faults will instead occur at key-on rather than at first 
      engine start. Finalization and reset will still occur at all subsequent 
      engine starts during the key cycle. This has the result that the cycle for 
      stopped check faults will begin at every key-on, rather than waiting until 
      the first engine start.

      When "First key-on after engine stopped" is selected, operating cycle 
      finalization and reset for stopped check faults will occur at the first 
      key-on following a key cycle with an engine start, and will occur at all 
      subsequent engine starts during the key cycle. Additionally, the stopped 
      check switch will be ignored after battery reconnection while the key is 
      off; all faults, including stopped check faults, will remain cleared after 
      battery reconnection until the first key-on.

      This setting is not applicable to the “Key cycle” “Operation cycle type”. 
      fm_pending_cycle Specifies whether a key cycle or operation cycle is 
      required in-between incrementing the pending fault occurrence counter for 
      any diagnostics configured with a "Pending Unlatch (minutes)" column value 
      of -1 on the Diagnostics worksheet.

      When set to 'Operation cycle', the "Operation cycle type" calibration 
      parameter determines the cycle type.

      If "Fault system mode" is set to 'Euro VI' or 'CARB 1971.1', the operation 
      cycle type is used for pending fault occurrence counter handling, 
      regardless of the value set for this parameter. 
      fm_pending_cycle_act Current pending fault latching/unlatching cycle type 
      fm_rt_cont_mil Euro VI continuous MI counter engine operation hours while 
      continuous MI active 
      fm_rt_cont_mil_hld Engine operation hours since holding the continuous MI 
      counter 
      fm_rt_cumcont_mil Euro VI cumulative engine hours while continuous MI is 
      active 
      fm_rt_since_clr cumulative engine runtime in seconds since DTCs were 
      cleared. 
      fm_rt_while_b1 Euro VI engine operation hours while at least one B1 fault 
      is confirmed and active 
      fm_rt_while_MIL cumulative engine runtime in seconds for most recent MIL 
      activation. 
      fm_rt_while_nox_MIL cumulative engine runtime in seconds for most recent 
      MIL activation due to a NOx control system fault. 
      fm_wuc_wo_MIL number of warm-up cycles without MIL. Used to count up to 40 
      consecutive warm-up cycles for clearing of fm_rt_while_MIL and 
      fm_dist_while_MIL. This is an internal tracking item and not an item 
      reported over ISO 15765. 
      fm_wus_ect_delta The amount the ECT must rise from the temperature at 
      engine start to consider a drive cycle "warmed up". This value will be 
      specified in the target legislature/compliance level. Typically the value 
      is 40 deg F (22 K/22 deg C). 
      fm_wus_ect_min The minimum temperature the ECT must meet to consider a 
      drive cycle as "warmed up". This value will be specified in the target 
      legislature/compliance level. Typically the value is 160 deg F (343 K/70 
      deg C) for gasoline and 140 deg F (333 K/60 deg C) for diesel. 
      fm_wus_ect_start engine coolant temperature at engine start in deg R 
      fm_wus_ect_target minimum engine coolant temperature that must be achieved 
      during operation to consider drive cycle "warmed up" 
      fm_wu_cont_mil_hld Warmup cycles since holding the continuous MI counter 
      fm_wu_since_clr number of warm-up cycles since fault memory was cleared in 
      cycles. 
      FOBD_flags Fault level OBD status flags 
      FOBD_iupr_ids Fault level In-Use Performance Ratio (IUPR) system status 
      FOBD_pflags Persistent fault level OBD status flags 
      FOBD_rsys_ids Fault level readiness status.

      FOP_detect_time Parameter is only applicable when "Fuel pressure high 
      during start" fault is enabled and "Active fuel device" is 'Carb - MJ / 
      EPR'. When fault's entry conditions are valid, preemptive actions are 
      taken before fault latches. If the fault's entry conditions are valid for 
      this parameter's length of time, then the fuel lockoff(s) are closed and 
      spark is inhibited. The inhibition will cease once fuel pressure has 
      dropped below the entry condition's threshold for this parameter's length 
      of time. Parameter cannot be greater than 100 ms. 
      FOP_inhibit_active Indicates if fuel over pressure (FOP) during start 
      feature is inhibiting the lockoff(s) from opening and inhibiting spark. 
      FOP_MJ_P_act_lmt EPR feedback pressure threshold for "Fuel pressure high 
      during start" fault. 
      forced_idle_rpm Forced idle min-governor engine speed 
      FORCEIDLE_active Logical indicating on going forced idle activity 
      FO_BO Specifies whether cylinders are referred to in firing order or block 
      order for injector and spark diagnostics. FO_BO = 0 (Firing Order), FO_BO 
      = 1 (Block order) 
      FPcal_P 1D Interpolation Table: Fuel Rail Pressure Sensor (Primary). Input 
      is sensor voltage, output is primary sensor fuel pressure (either psig or 
      psia) 
      FPcal_P_I2 1D Interpolation Table: Fuel Rail Pressure Sensor (Secondary). 
      Input is sensor voltage, output is secondary sensor fuel pressure (either 
      psig or psia) 
      FPcal_V 1D Interpolation Table: Fuel Rail Pressure Sensor. Sensor voltage 
      input values. 
      FPCcmd pump command fraction 
      FPCcmd_DC pump command PWM duty-cycle 
      FPCcmd_tau Time constant for liquid fuel pressure control command output 
      low-pass filter. 
      FPCcmd_V pump command voltage 
      FPCVmax Fuel pump max control voltage. This is the voltage at which no 
      further increase in voltage will cause an increase in pressure. 
      FPCVmin Fuel pump min control voltage. This is the voltage at which no 
      further reduction in voltage will cause a decrease in pressure. 
      FPCV_CLauth The output of the pressure control closed-loop law is a 
      +/-100% value which is translated to a command voltage by multiplying by 
      this number. In effect, this value scales all gains up or down relative to 
      a final output voltage. This value must have enough +/- authority to 
      properly override the feedforward voltage schedule. 
      FPC_dot Fuel rail pressure derivative 
      FPC_dot_tau Low-pass filter value for backward difference liquid fuel 
      pressure control derivative calculation. 
      FPC_dot_window Backward difference window size for liquid fuel pressure 
      control derivative calculation. 
      FPC_ena This switch enables/disabled closed-loop liquid fuel pressure/pump 
      control on the specified output. The fuel pressure 'actual / desired' 
      value sets the target pressure, and a feedback sensor must be present. 
      FPC_FP_source Selects the fuel rail pressure sensor that should drive PID 
      control of the fuel pump. If an inlet metering valve is enabled, this 
      parameter should be set to "Secondary". 
      FPC_Iacc fuel pump integrator accumulator command fraction 
      FPC_Kd Liquid fuel pressure control feedback loop derivative gain. This 
      loop's output value is a fuel pump command. 
      FPC_Ki Liquid fuel pressure control feedback loop integrator gain. This 
      loop's output value is a fuel pump command. 
      FPC_Kiv Liquid fuel pressure control feedback loop integrator-velocity 
      gain. This loop's output value is a fuel pump command. 
      FPC_Kp Liquid fuel pressure control feedback loop proportional gain. This 
      loop's output value is a fuel pump command. 
      FPC_SD_deltaP Whenever the fuel pressure control law commands an output 
      voltage <= to the minimum voltage specified above, and the observed fuel 
      pressure is > the target (desired) pressure plus this delta, the fuel pump 
      voltage control is forced to zero. 
      FPD_off_hi Obsoleted parameter 
      FPD_off_loDC The "Fuel pump motor loop open or shorted to ground" fault 
      will update when the fuel pressure control duty cycle is less than this 
      value. 
      FPD_off_loVf The "Fuel pump motor loop open or shorted to ground" fault is 
      active when the fuel pressure control duty cycle is below the duty cycle 
      threshold and the feedback voltage is below this value. 
      FPD_off_maxVbat Obsoleted parameter 
      FPD_on_hiDC The "Fuel pump motor shorted to power" fault will update when 
      the fuel pressure control duty cycle is greater than this value. 
      FPD_on_hiVf The "Fuel pump motor shorted to power" fault is active when 
      the fuel pressure control duty cycle is greater than the duty cycle 
      threshold and the feedback voltage is greater than this value. 
      FPD_on_lo Obsoleted parameter 
      FPD_on_minVbat Obsoleted parameter 
      FPin Fuel rail pressure 
      FPin_a Liquid fuel inlet pressure at primary injector(s) - reflects actual 
      operating conditions 
      FPin_a_I2 Liquid fuel inlet pressure at secondary injector(s) - reflects 
      actual operating conditions 
      FPin_a_I2_type Selects the secondary fuel pressure target type: 
      static/calibrated or dynamic and based on MAP + 1 bar. 
      FPin_a_I2_val Current secondary fuel pressure target value based on either 
      a static/calibrated value or dynamic and based on MAP + 1 bar. 
      FPin_a_type Selects the primary fuel pressure target type: 
      static/calibrated or dynamic and based on MAP + 1 bar. 
      FPin_a_val Current primary fuel pressure target value based on either a 
      static/calibrated value or dynamic and based on MAP + 1 bar. 
      FPin_I2 Secondary fuel rail pressure 
      FPin_s Standard inlet fuel pressure used for the fuel flow calibration of 
      the liquid fuel injectors. 
      FPin_s_I2 Standard inlet fuel pressure used for the fuel flow calibration 
      of the secondary fuel injectors. 
      FPlo_derate_dly_off This value specifies the amount of time the pressure 
      error must stay below the "Derate dis-engage pressure error maximum" 
      threshold to deactivate low fuel pressure derate after engagement. 
      FPlo_derate_dly_on This value specifies the amount of time the pressure 
      error must persist at or above the "Derate engage pressure error minimum" 
      threshold to activate low fuel pressure derate. 
      FPlo_derate_ena If enabled, a low fuel pressure derate load-limit is 
      automatically calculated and applied if the pressure error reaches the 
      threshold specified in the "Derate engage pressure error minimum" 
      parameter. Once the derate is active, it will dis-engage when the pressure 
      error falls below the "Derate dis-engage pressure error maximum" 
threshold.

      This feature is supported for gaseous fuel applications utilizing the CFV 
      or Secondary Pulse Injection for fuel admission. 
      FPlo_derate_hybridwt When hybrid fault mode is enabled, this setting 
      specifies the minimum run time before enabling the low fuel pressure 
      derate load-limit. 
      FPlo_derate_LLmin This value specifies the lowest load-limit percentage 
      enforced for low fuel pressure derate.

      FPlo_derate_loadlim Low fuel pressure derate enforced load-limit 
      percentage. 
      FPlo_derate_off_tau This value specifies the time constant used for the 
      low-pass filter that is applied to the calculated load-limit after low 
      fuel pressure derate dis-engages. 
      FPlo_derate_on_tau This value specifies the time constant used for the 
      low-pass filter that is applied to the calculated load-limit after low 
      fuel pressure derate engages. 
      FPlo_derate_Poff To deactivate low fuel pressure derate after engagement, 
      the pressure error must fall below this threshold. If "Derate dis-engage 
      delay" is non-zero, then the pressure error must persist below this 
      threshold for the specified number of seconds before the derate is 
      dis-engaged. 
      FPlo_derate_Pon This value specifies the minimum pressure error that will 
      activate low fuel pressure derate. If "Derate engage delay" is non-zero, 
      then the pressure error must persist at or above this threshold for the 
      specified number of seconds before the derate is engaged. 
      FPlo_derate_Ptau This value specifies the time constant used for the 
      low-pass filter that is applied to the pressure error prior to determining 
      if the error has reached the "Derate engage pressure error minimum" 
      threshold for low fuel pressure derate activation or fallen below the 
      "Derate dis-engage pressure error maximum" threshold for derate 
      deactivation. 
      FPlo_derate_Ptgt If the active fuel device is Secondary Pulse Injection 
      and the low fuel pressure is then based on Secondary fuel rail pressure 
      target, this is the final computed target fuel pressure for the low fuel 
      pressure determination and derate. The low fuel pressure target is 
      computed:

      Secondary_fuel_rail_P_target * multiplier 
      FPlo_derate_P_hi If this value is > 0, and the pressure error is >= this 
      value, then the "Derate active pressure error high load-limit" is 
      activated. The "Derate active pressure error high load-limit" is a severe 
      load-limit and can be lower than the "Derate load-limit minimum". 
      FPlo_derate_P_hi_LL If the pressure error is >= "Derate active pressure 
      error high", then this value is activated for the load-limit. This value 
      is intended to be a severe or idle load-limit and can be lower than the 
      "Derate load-limit minimum". 
      FPlo_derate_time Low fuel pressure - forced limited power excessive 
      duration diagnostic time threshold. 
      FPlo_derate_tmr Total amount of time low fuel pressure derate is active 
      during the current drive cycle. 
      FPlo_derate_use Low fuel pressure derate active indicator. 
      FPout_loc Discharge fuel pressure environment - primary (MAP or TIP) 
      FPout_loc_I2 Discharge fuel pressure environment - secondary (MAP or TIP) 
      FPout_s Standard fuel outlet pressure used for the fuel flow calibration 
      of the liquid fuel injectors. 
      FPout_s_I2 Standard fuel outlet pressure used for the fuel flow 
      calibration for the secondary fuel injectors. 
      FPP12pct_hi FPP1 higher than FPP2 diagnostic: FPP1 - FPP2 delta upper 
      limit (positive value) entry condition 
      FPP12pct_lo FPP1 lower than FPP2 diagnostic: FPP1 - FPP2 delta lower limit 
      (negative value) 
      FPP1_5V_source This switch selects which 5V excitation source the FPP1 pot 
      is powered from. This is important since the health and trustworthiness of 
      this pot is dependent on the health of its power source. The 'rescaled' 
      version of the secondary source should be used if the secondary 5V source 
      is a high-impedance output and proper 'ratiometric' voltages are to be 
      used. 
      FPP1_center FPP1 default midpoint 
      FPP1_def default FPP1 voltage 
      FPP1_full Voltage at full open - FPP1 
      FPP1_full_init Initial value (just after key-on) for FPP1_full voltage. 
      FPP1_full will be learned upward if a higher voltage is detected at any 
      time during the key-on cycle. See comments for 'FPP1 learn wait' below for 
      a further description of this learning procedure.

      Note: For a negative-slope FPP1, the learning will be downward for 
      FPP1_full.

      Note: For a marine throttle & gear handle configuration, this value 
      specifies the full-forward voltage level. Learning should be disabled in 
      this scenario by setting the FPP1 learn wait parameter to 32767 ms. Also 
      note that the average of this voltage and the 'FPP1 idle init' voltage 
      will determine the center neutral point expected voltage. This center 
      voltage is usually the critical tolerance, so 'FPP1 idle init' and 'FPP1 
      full init' precision should be sacrificed to properly specify an accurate 
      center voltage. 
      FPP1_idle Voltage at idle - FPP1 
      FPP1_idle_init Initial value (just after key-on) for FPP1_idle voltage. 
      FPP1_idle will be learned downward if a lower voltage is detected at any 
      time during the key-on cycle. See comments for 'FPP1 learn wait' below for 
      a further description of this learning procedure.

      Note: For a negative-slope FPP1, the learning will be upward for 
FPP1_idle.

      Note: For a marine throttle & gear handle configuration, this value 
      specifies the full-reverse voltage level. Learning should be disabled in 
      this scenario by setting the FPP1 learn wait parameter to 32767 ms. Also 
      note that the average of this voltage and the 'FPP1 full init' voltage 
      will determine the enter neutral point expected voltage. This center 
      voltage is usually the critical tolerance, so 'FPP1 idle init' and 'FPP1 
      full init' precision should be sacrificed to properly specify an accurate 
      center voltage. 
      FPP1_IVS_max FPP1 higher than IVS limit diagnostic: Entry condition - If 
      IVS is at-idle when FPP1 is greater than this value, the fault is 
      triggered. 
      FPP1_IVS_min FPP1 lower than IVS limit diagnostic: Entry condition - If 
      IVS is off-idle when FPP1 is lower than this value, the fault is 
      triggered. 
      FPP1_kickdown_on_V When enabled, in addition to exceeding the “FPP 
      kickdown engagement” % limit, the FFP1 voltage (FPP1_rawfilt) must also 
      exceed this limit to engage active-kickdown in the J1939 EEC2 message.

      Setting this value to 0 will disable use of this limit.

      Use of this setting requires FPP1 learn to be disabled by setting “FPP1 
      learn wait” (FPP1_learn_wait) to 32767. 
      FPP1_learn_tau Whenever a voltage lower than the current minimum idle 
      voltage or greater than the current full voltage is detected, a new idle 
      or full voltage will be 'learned' using this low-pass time constant, once 
      the "FPP1 learn wait" period has elapsed. 
      FPP1_learn_wait Whenever a voltage lower than the current minimum idle 
      voltage or greater than the current full voltage is detected, this fixed 
      amount of time must expire before any 'learning' of this lower idle or 
      higher full position voltage is allowed. 
      FPP1_max FPP1 high voltage diagnostic: FPP1 voltage upper limit threshold 
      FPP1_min FPP1 low voltage diagnostic: FPP1 voltage lower limit threshold 
      FPP1_pct FPP1 percent 
      FPP1_PWM_edge FPP1 PWM edge capture mode. 
      FPP1_PWM_ena Selects the pulse input for the TSC1 redundant foot pedal. 
      When enabled:
      1. The PWM frequency is scaled to a voltage using the FPP1 calibration. 
      The “FPP1 high voltage” or “FPP1 low voltage” faults indicate out-of-range 
      frequencies or loss of signal.
      2. EEC2 SPN 91 is scaled to a voltage using the FPP2 calibration. 
      Depending on the voltage configuration, the “FPP2 high voltage” or “FPP2 
      low voltage” fault indicates EEC2 reception loss.
      3. The resulting FPP1 and FPP2 voltages are rationalized as a dual-pot 
      foot pedal without IVS. The “FPP1 higher than FPP2” and “FPP1 lower than 
      FPP2” faults indicate when the PWM-indicated position is valid.
      4. While TSC1 reception is lost and the "J1939 TSC1 message receipt lost" 
      fault is latched, the resulting PWM foot pedal position is used.
      5. If EEC2 reception is also lost, and the “FPP1 higher/lower than FPP2” 
      faults are not latched, then the PWM foot pedal position will continue to 
      be used. However, because of the lack of redundancy, the Force Idle derate 
      will temporarily be active while the foot pedal position appears to be 
      stuck based on the “Stuck Foot Pedal Detection” calibration. 
      FPP1_PWM_Hz FPP1 PWM foot pedal frequency. 
      FPP1_PWM_Hz_full PWM frequency indicating the TSC1 redundant foot pedal 
      fully-depressed position. Valid range is 1.193 Hz to 20 MHz. 
      FPP1_PWM_Hz_idle PWM frequency indicating the TSC1 redundant foot pedal 
      idle position. Valid range is 1.193 Hz to 20 MHz. 
      FPP1_PWM_idle_rpm Minimum idle speed when conditions are valid to use the 
      TSC1 redundant foot pedal. 
      FPP1_raw FPP1 raw voltage 
      FPP1_rawfilt FPP1 raw (LPF) voltage 
      FPP1_switch_ena This option is only valid if the "Primary foot pedal mode" 
      is set to 'Throttle Control' or 'Speed Control'. If a valid signal (e.g. 
      +V) is detected on the hardware pin selected, the actual FPP mode will 
      toggle from 'Throttle Control' to 'Speed Control', or 'Speed Control' to 
      'Throttle Control'. 
      FPP1_trust Trust indicator for FPP1 input (-1 = no trust, 0/1=OK but 
      proportionally less than ideal, 2=100% trustworthy) 
      FPP2atidle_ena FPP2 lower than IVS limit diagnostic: This switch enables 
      the 'FPP @idle' diagnostic which is designed to diagnose IVS switchpoint 
      disagreements on foot pedals with IVS switch points very close to the 
      minimum pedal position (no pedal depression). 
      FPP2atidle_IVSdelta FPP2 lower than IVS limit diagnostic: FPP2 < FPP2 
      learned idle delta 
      FPP2atidle_IVSmargin FPP2 @idle margin to IVS off-idle. When the 'FPP2 
      @idle' diagnostic is turned on, this amount of delta-voltage from the 
      learned idle position must be observed without the IVS switching to an 
      off-idle condition during an increase in FPP2 position. 
      FPP2atidle_max FPP2 @idle normal max. When the 'FPP2 @idle' diagnostic is 
      turned on, this parameter informs the pedal monitoring system of the 
      normal maximum possible voltage of the FPP2 pot in an idle condition (no 
      pedal depression). 
      FPP2atidle_min When the 'FPP2 @idle' diagnostic is turned on by setting 
      the FPP2 @idle switch on the diagnostic page to 'Enabled', this parameter 
      informs the pedal monitoring system of the normal minimum possible voltage 
      of the FPP2 pot in an idle condition (no pedal depression).

      Note: For a negative-slope FPP2, this is the normal maximum possible 
      voltage of the FPP2 pot in an idle condition.

      Note: This is normally an absolute voltage value to be compared against 
      FPP2. The one exception is when the "Marine throttle & gear handle FPP 
      mode" option is enabled on the 'Marine' page. In this scenario, this value 
      has no meaning since the center position voltage is idle. Only the "FPP2 
      @idle normal max" has meaning. 
      FPP2atidle_mode FPP2atIdle state (diagnostics) 
      FPP2_5V_source This switch selects which 5V excitation source the FPP2 pot 
      is powered from. This is important since the health and trustworthiness of 
      this pot is dependent on the health of its power source. The 'rescaled' 
      version of the secondary source should be used if the secondary 5V source 
      is a high-impedance output and proper 'ratiometric' voltages are to be 
      used. 
      FPP2_center FPP2 default midpoint 
      FPP2_def default FPP2 voltage 
      FPP2_full Voltage at full open - FPP2 
      FPP2_full_init Initial value (just after key-on) for FPP2_full voltage. 
      FPP2_full will be learned upward if a higher voltage is detected at any 
      time during the key-on cycle. See comments for 'FPP2 learn wait' below for 
      a further description of this learning procedure.

      Note: For a negative-slope FPP2, the learning will be downward for 
      FPP2_full.

      Note: For a marine throttle & gear handle configuration, this value 
      specifies the full-forward voltage level. Learning should be disabled in 
      this scenario by setting the FPP2 learn wait parameter to 32767 ms. Also 
      note that the average of this voltage and the 'FPP2 idle init' voltage 
      will determine the center neutral point expected voltage. This center 
      voltage is usually the critical tolerance, so 'FPP2 idle init' and 'FPP2 
      full init' precision should be sacrificed to properly specify an accurate 
      center voltage. 
      FPP2_idle Voltage at idle - FPP2 
      FPP2_idle_init Initial value (just after key-on) for FPP2_idle voltage. 
      FPP2_idle will be learned downward if a lower voltage is detected at any 
      time during the key-on cycle. See comments for 'FPP2 learn wait' below for 
      a further description of this learning procedure.

      Note: For a negative-slope FPP2, the learning will be upward for 
FPP2_idle.

      Note: For a marine throttle & gear handle configuration, this value 
      specifies the full-reverse voltage level. Learning should be disabled in 
      this scenario by setting the FPP2 learn wait parameter to 32767 ms. Also 
      note that the average of this voltage and the 'FPP2 full init' voltage 
      will determine the center neutral point expected voltage. This center 
      voltage is usually the critical tolerance, so 'FPP2 idle init' and 'FPP2 
      full init' precision should be sacrificed to properly specify an accurate 
      center voltage. 
      FPP2_IVS_max FPP2 higher than IVS limit diagnostic: Entry condition - If 
      IVS is at-idle when FPP2 is greater than this value, the fault is 
      triggered. 
      FPP2_IVS_min FPP2 lower than IVS limit diagnostic: Entry condition - If 
      IVS is off-idle when FPP2 is lower than this value, the fault is 
      triggered. 
      FPP2_learn_tau Whenever a voltage lower than the current minimum idle 
      voltage or greater than the current full voltage is detected, a new idle 
      or full voltage will be 'learned' using this low-pass time constant, once 
      the "FPP2 learn wait" period has elapsed. 
      FPP2_learn_wait Whenever a voltage lower than the current minimum idle 
      voltage or greater than the current full voltage is detected, this fixed 
      amount of time must expire before any 'learning' of this lower idle or 
      higher full position voltage is allowed. 
      FPP2_max FPP2 high voltage diagnostic: FPP2 voltage upper limit threshold 
      FPP2_min FPP2 low voltage diagnostic: FPP2 voltage lower limit threshold 
      FPP2_mode This switch selects what the FPP2 input is used for when the 
      'second foot pedal' option is engaged:
      1) disabled
      2) to determine throttle position
      3) to determine engine speed setpoint

      NOTE: This mode selection does not apply UNLESS the 'second foot pedal' 
      option is enabled. 
      FPP2_pct FPP2 percent 
      FPP2_raw FPP2 raw voltage 
      FPP2_rawfilt FPP2 raw (LPF) voltage 
      FPP2_source Designates the hardware pin for the FPP2 input. 
      FPP2_switch_ena This option is only valid if the "Secondary foot pedal 
      mode" is set to 'Throttle Control' or 'Speed Control'. If a valid signal 
      (e.g. +V) is detected on the hardware pin selected, the actual FPP mode 
      will toggle from 'Throttle Control' to 'Speed Control', or 'Speed Control' 
      to 'Throttle control'. 
      FPP2_trust Trust indicator for FPP1 input (-1 = no trust, 0/1=OK but 
      proportionally less than ideal, 2=100% trustworthy) 
      FPPatidle_ena FPP lower than IVS limit diagnostic: This switch enables the 
      'FPP @idle' diagnostic which is designed to diagnose IVS switchpoint 
      disagreements on foot pedals with IVS switch points very close to the 
      minimum pedal position (no pedal depression). 
      FPPatidle_IVSdelta FPP lower than IVS limit diagnostic: FPP < FPP learned 
      idle delta 
      FPPatidle_IVSmargin FPP @idle margin to IVS off-idle. When the 'FPP @idle' 
      diagnostic is turned on, this amount of delta-voltage from the learned 
      idle position must be observed without the IVS switching to an off-idle 
      condition during an increase in FPP position. 
      FPPatidle_max When the 'FPP1 @idle' diagnostic is turned on by setting the 
      FPP1 @idle switch on the diagnostic page to 'Enabled', this parameter 
      informs the pedal monitoring system of the normal maximum possible voltage 
      of the FPP1 pot in an idle condition (no pedal depression).

      Note: For a negative-slope FPP1, this is the normal minimum possible 
      voltage of the FPP1 pot in an idle condition.

      Note: This is normally an absolute voltage value to be compared against 
      FPP1. The one exception is when the "Marine throttle & gear handle FPP 
      mode" option is enabled on the 'Marine' page. In this scenario, this is 
      interpreted as a delta-voltage from the center position voltage in either 
      direction (+ for forward and - for reverse assuming a positive-slope 
      FPP1). 
      FPPatidle_min When the 'FPP1 @idle' diagnostic is turned on by setting the 
      FPP1 @idle switch on the diagnostic page to 'Enabled', this parameter 
      informs the pedal monitoring system of the normal minimum possible voltage 
      of the FPP1 pot in an idle condition (no pedal depression).

      Note: For a negative-slope FPP1, this is the normal maximum possible 
      voltage of the FPP1 pot in an idle condition.

      Note: This is normally an absolute voltage value to be compared against 
      FPP1. The one exception is when the "Marine throttle & gear handle FPP 
      mode" option is enabled on the 'Marine' page. In this scenario, this value 
      has no meaning since the center position voltage is idle. Only the "FPP1 
      @idle normal max" value below has meaning. 
      FPPatidle_mode FPPatIdle state (diagnostics) 
      FPPdp_dcy Idle Foot Pedal dashpot decay 
      FPPdp_max Idle foot-pedal dashpot maximum 
      FPPdualpot_ena This enables use of a dual pot (redundant pot) foot pedal. 
      FPPdual_pedal This option enables 2 independent FPP inputs (as opposed to 
      a redundant FPP1/2 potentiometer setup).

      For the 'Enabled BRAKE=FPP2' option, selection between these two 
      independent inputs is accomplished through the BRAKE digital input:
      BRAKE invalid = FPP1
      BRAKE valid = FPP2

      For the 'Enabled BRAKE=FPP max' option, when the BRAKE digital input is 
      valid, the greater of FPP1 and FPP2 is used:
      BRAKE invalid = FPP1
      BRAKE valid = max(FPP1, FPP2)
      Note this option requires FPP1 mode and FPP2 mode be set equal in the 
      calibration or unexpected behavior may result (e.g. do not set FPP1 for 
      throttle control and FPP2 for speed control when using this mode).

      For the 'Enabled input=FPP2' option, selection between these two 
      independent inputs is accomplished through the 'Second foot pedal input'. 
      If the input is true, FPP2 is used. 
      FPPdual_pedal_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the input, this value 
      determines the active logic state(s). The Default values are:
      Aux DIG1 = Gnd
      Aux DIG2 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG3 = Gnd
      Aux DIG4 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG5 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG6 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG7 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG8 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG9 = Gnd
      Aux DIG10 = Gnd
      Aux DIG11 = Gnd
      Aux DIG12 = Gnd
      Aux DIG13 = Gnd
      Aux DIG14 = Gnd
      Aux DIG15 = Gnd
      Aux DIG16 = Gnd
      Aux DIG17 = Gnd
      Aux DIG18 = Gnd
      Aux DIG19 = Gnd
      Gov1 = Gnd
      Gov2 = Gnd 
      FPPdual_pedal_chan This input toggle can be used to switch between 
      independent FPP1 and FPP2. The 'Second foot pedal control' must be set to 
      'Enabled input=FPP2'. This input toggle is used primarily on vehicles that 
      have a second independent foot pedal for engine operation during 
      maintenance. 
      FPPgear_command marine gear handle final commanded gear (-1=reverse, 
      0=neutral, 1=forward) - note that this selection may be gear-lockout 
      overridden 
      FPPgear_gear_dz This is the % movement from the vertical neutral position 
      on the handle to the point in forward/backward motion that a shift to 
      forward/reverse should occur. For interpretation of the % unit, 
      100%=center neutral to full-forward angular movement. 
      FPPgear_handle This switch indicates to FPP and shift handling software 
      that a marine handle is being used for both throttle and transmission 
      control based on handle position. Neutral is assumed to be at the 50% 
      center point of the FPP range, > 50% movement indicates forward gear 
      selection, and < 50% movement indicates reverse gear selection. Actual 
      shift and throttle points are defined by the deadzones. 
      FPPgear_indicate marine gear handle initial indicated gear (-1=reverse, 
      0=neutral, 1=forward) 
      FPPgear_ntrlk_t This is the live uptimer that must exceed 
      FPPgearl_ntrlk_tout before a neutral interlock will be released. 
      FPPgear_ntrlk_tout For a marine gear handle at key-on and following any 
      FPP fault forcing a return to neutral, gear selection will be locked out 
      for this amount of time until the FPP is valid and the user has selected 
      neutral (typically 50-200ms). 
      FPPgear_throt_Fdz This is the % movement from the vertical neutral 
      position on the handle to the point in forward motion that the FPP command 
      will begin to rise above zero. For interpretation of the % unit, 
      100%=center neutral to full-forward angular movement. This deadzone should 
      typically be larger than the shift deadzone above so that the shift can be 
      accomplished prior to engine speed increases. 
      FPPgear_throt_Rdz This is the % movement from the vertical neutral 
      position on the handle to the point in rearward (reverse) motion that the 
      FPP command will begin to rise above zero. For interpretation of the % 
      unit, 100%=center neutral to full-reverse angular movement. This deadzone 
      should typically be larger than the shift deadzone above so that the shift 
      can be accomplished prior to engine speed increases. 
      FPPIVS_ena This enables use of an idle-validation switch (IVS) on the 
      primary foot pedal input. The two non-network enabled modes select the 
      configuration of the IVS switch in the idle (and off-idle) conditions. If 
      the 'second foot pedal' option is selected, the IVS is only analyzed for 
      the FPP1 input. In 'Enabled - Network' mode, the IVS input source is 
      ignored since the IVS off-idle/at-idle indication is received via CAN. 
      FPPSC_int_max_ena This switch enables/disables use of the 4-point 
      independent range FPP speed control calibration maximum integrator limit 
      feature. 
      FPPSC_int_min_ena This switch enables/disables use of the 4-point 
      independent range FPP speed control calibration minimum integrator limit 
      feature. 
      FPPSC_mode FPP Speed Control Mode Switch 
      FPPSC_nomload_ena This switch enables/disables use of the 4-point 
      independent range FPP speed control calibration nominal load adder 
      feature. 
      FPPSC_rpmH FPP Speed Control 2 Point Method, Upper rpm value 
      FPPSC_rpmL FPP Speed Control 2 Point Method Lower rpm value 
      FPPslewdown_ena This switch controls whether or not the table below is 
      used to slew-rate limit decreasing FPP commands.

      If enabled, the current (i.e. slew-rate limited FPP) is used along with 
      the TIP to index into the table below to extract a slew rate limit for the 
      FPP command. In general, this table can be used to minimize turbo surge by 
      limiting the decreasing FPP slew rate at high TIP and low current FPP 
      levels. 
      FPPslew_max_hi Throttle Slew Rate Limiting: High FPP maximum slew rate 
      FPPslew_max_lo Throttle Slew Rate Limiting: Low FPP maximum slew rate 
      FPPTPSnl2_FPP FPP -> Load/TPS Nonlinear Mapping: Option 2 non-linear FPP 
      point 
      FPPTPSnl2_TPS FPP -> Load/TPS Nonlinear Mapping: Option 2 non-linear TPS 
      point 
      FPPTPSnl3_FPP FPP -> Load/TPS Nonlinear Mapping: Option 3 non-linear FPP 
      point 
      FPPTPSnl3_TPS FPP -> Load/TPS Nonlinear Mapping: Option 3 non-linear TPS 
      point 
      FPPTPSnl_cur FPP -> Load/TPS Nonlinear Mapping: Currently active 
      non-linear option 
      FPPTPSnl_ena The 2D Table is available in column U. 
      FPPTPSnl_FPP FPP -> Load/TPS Nonlinear Mapping: Option 1 non-linear FPP 
      point 
      FPPTPSnl_TPS FPP -> Load/TPS Nonlinear Mapping: Option 1 non-linear TPS 
      point 
      FPP_allspeed_rpm Initial FPP engine speed command applicable when 
      configured for all-speed control mode. 
      FPP_atidle_start FPP idle validation on start (Not Required / Required) 
      FPP_calmode_ena FPP Manual Mode: FPP calibration/automatic FPP mode 
      0=disabled, 1-4 select between cal mode FPP commands 
      FPP_calmode_latch FPP Manual Mode: FPP calibration/automatic latch actual 
      FPP 0=disabled, 1-4 latch current FPP into cal mode FPP commands 
      FPP_calmode_pct1 FPP Manual Mode: FPP calibration/automatic latch % 
      command 1 
      FPP_calmode_pct2 FPP Manual Mode: FPP calibration/automatic latch % 
      command 2 
      FPP_calmode_pct3 FPP Manual Mode: FPP calibration/automatic latch % 
      command 3 
      FPP_calmode_pct4 FPP Manual Mode: FPP calibration/automatic latch % 
      command 4 
      FPP_cmd_final Normalized commanded foot pedal (position) input (FPP) 
      FPP_cmd_pct Initial normalized commanded FPP input (percentage) 
      FPP_cmd_predz Value of FPP_cmd_pct prior to Cubic Deadzone algorithm 
      FPP_cmd_pstslew FPP command value prior to FPP to TPS mapping (used by FPP 
      slew algorithm) 
      FPP_diffout_ena FPP differential PWM translation: Enables differential FPP 
      translation mode. NOTE: This mode requires special hardware support and is 
      not available on most ECMs 
      FPP_dz_pct Enter the FPP deadzone. If , the deadzone is ignored and the 
      raw FPP voltage input is filtered using the LP fast filter time constant 
      from the 'Miscellaneous' tab. If a non-zero value is entered, the filtered 
      FPP input is passed through an additional low-pass filter (specified by 
      the FPP deadzone tau below). When the difference between the heavily 
      filtered and normally filtered FPP values exceeds this deadzone, the FPP 
      command is equal to the normally filtered FPP value. When the difference 
      is below this deadzone, the difference is cubed and added to the heavily 
      filtered FPP value to form the final FPP command.The maximum allowed value 
      for deadzone is 49.99% 
      FPP_dz_tau FPP deadzone time constant used in LPF 
      FPP_EOL_throt force engine into FPP mode into throttle control if in a 
      speed control mode 
      FPP_full_valid If FPP >= FPP_full-FPP_WOT_dedbnd, the FPP is at a WOT 
      condition of 100%. If FPP < FPP_full-FPP_WOT_dedbnd, the FPP is at less 
      than 100%. Use this value to install a WOT dead-band at the end of the FPP 
      travel - such as for a transmission kick-down switch. 
      FPP_idle_valid If FPP <= FPP_idle+FPP_idle_delta, an idle condition 
      (minimum FPP) is validated. If FPP > FPP_idle+FPP_idle_delta the FPP is 
      considered off-idle. This is the default value for FPP_idle, and may be 
      overridden by certain vehicle/transmission configurations. 
      FPP_idlvld_cur Currently active FPP idle deadzone. 
      FPP_kickdown_active FPP exceeded the kickdown engage threshold percentage 
      and has NOT decreased below the disengage setpoint 
      FPP_kickdown_ena Switch to engage FPP kickdown monitoring 
      FPP_kickdown_off FPP percentages above the engagement limit will be 
      flagged as active-kickdown in the J1939 EEC2 message. The FPP must drop 
      below this limit for the kickdown indication to unlatch. 
      FPP_kickdown_on FPP percentages above this limit will be flagged as 
      active-kickdown in the J1939 EEC2 message. The FPP must drop below the 
      disengagement limit for the kickdown indication to unlatch. 
      FPP_kickdown_src Parameter sets the FPP source for kickdown engagement and 
      disengagement. When set to 'FPP Command', the source is the normalized FPP 
      command (FPP_cmd_pct). When set to 'FPP Position', then the source is the 
      normalized FPP position without modifications from TSC1 requests, cruise 
      control, and roadspeed limiting (FPP_unadjust_pct). 
      FPP_learn_sync_ena This enables synchronized learning of a dual pot 
      (redundant pot) foot pedal. When enabled, learning will occur only if both 
      FPP1 and FPP2 have expired learn wait timers and position voltages 
      below/above their respective idle/full voltages. 
      FPP_mode This switch selects what the FPP1 or FPP1/2 input is used for 
      within the software:
      1) ignored
      2) to determine throttle position
      3) to determine engine speed setpoint

      NOTE: This mode must be enabled (either throttle or speed control mode) 
      before any other foot pedal options apply. 
      FPP_pct Normalized value of FPP position (percentage). Value does include 
      modifications from active TSC1 requests, engaged cruise control, or 
      roadspeed limiting. 
      FPP_stuck_dz Dead zone for detecting a stuck PWM foot pedal. The force 
      idle derate will be active if the minimum and maximum measured foot pedal 
      positions remain less than this value for the calibrated maximum time. The 
      maximum time depends on three position regions defined by "Stuck FPP idle 
      threshold" and "Stuck FPP WOT threshold":
      - infinite for idle foot pedal positions (position < idle threshold)
      - "Stuck FPP WOT time limit" for fully-depressed pedal positions (position 
      >= WOT threshold)
      - "Stuck FPP off-idle time limit" for other off-idle pedal positions 
      FPP_stuck_idle Maximum foot pedal position where stuck pedal detection is 
      disabled. 
      FPP_stuck_offidle_tm Maximum time for an off-idle 
      FPP_stuck_tmr Time foot pedal position has remained within the dead zone. 
      FPP_stuck_wot Minimum foot pedal position for using the maximum time at a 
      fully-depressed pedal position. 
      FPP_stuck_wot_tm Maximum time that the foot pedal is permitted to remain 
      steady in a fully-depressed position. 
      FPP_switch_FPP FPP switch (transition) mode tracking FPP value 
      FPP_switch_FPP_inc FPP command slew rate to use during a speed to throttle 
      control transition if the throttle control command is greater than the 
      (filtered) governor TPS command. Entering '0' here interlocks the current 
      throttle command as the max throttle control command until the user 
      reduces the FPP position. 
      FPP_switch_FPP_tau Additional low-pass filter time constant for foot pedal 
      command. This filter is always actively filtering the governor TPS command 
      (speed control utilizes governor 3) unless a speed to throttle control 
      transition is active. 
      FPP_switch_rpm Entry Value: FPP switch (transition) mode tracking rpm 
      value 
      FPP_switch_rpm_inc Engine speed slew rate to use during a throttle to 
      speed control transition if the speed control command is greater than the 
      (filtered) engine speed. Entering '0' here interlocks the current engine 
      speed as the max speed control command until the user reduces the FPP 
      position. 
      FPP_switch_rpm_tau Additional low-pass filter time constant for engine 
      speed. This filter is always actively filtering the current engine speed 
      unless a throttle to speed control transition is active. 
      FPP_switch_slew_ena This feature allows a slew between foot pedal throttle 
      and speed control modes. It is primarily intended to be used with a 
      hardware pin selecting between user-generated throttle and speed control 
      (governor 3) modes. Note the engine speed/throttle command is always 
      allowed to decrease when a speed/throttle control mode switch occurs 
      (required for safety). 
      FPP_switch_state FPP Switch State tracking state variable for Throttle 
      Mode/Speed mode transition control 
      FPP_toggle_ena FPP Manual Mode: toggle between defined FPP cal modes 
      FPP_toggle_ms FPP Manual Mode: FPP toggle period 
      FPP_unadjust_pct Normalized value of FPP position (percentage) without 
      modifications from TSC1 requests, cruise control, and roadspeed limiting. 
      FPraw_LP Fuel Pressure LPF Time Constant, Primary 
      FPraw_LP_I2 Fuel Pressure LPF Time Constant, Secondary 
      FPrm_latch Fault-level latch period 
      FPrm_latchtype Fault-level latch units 
      FPrm_pending Fault level pending latched status 
      FPrm_severity Fault level severity classification. Euro VI emissions 
      faults are faults that have a class configured (e.g. Class A, B1, B2, or 
      C) 
      FPrm_switches Fault level tally of individual fault switch configurations 
      FPrm_switches_ext1 Fault level tally of individual fault switch 
      configurations (extended switch set) 
      FPrm_unlatch Fault level unlatch period 
      FPrm_unlatchtype Fault level unlatch units 
      FPUMP_FB_raw FPUMP output low/high-side voltage diagnostic input 
      FPUMP_hw_config FPUMP hardware configuration 
      fpump_key_wait This is the timeout value for a key-on engine-stopped 
      condition past which the fuel pump will be turned off. This value must be 
      <= to the key-on stopped wait general power timeout to be meaningful since 
      the power timeout will override the fuel supply disable timeout if it is 
      shorter. 
      FPUMP_off_hiVf Maximum valid high-side driver off-state voltage feedback 
      for the "Fuel pump relay coil short to power" diagnostic. 
      FPUMP_off_hi_volt Maximum valid high-side driver off-state voltage 
      feedback for the "Fuel pump relay coil open" diagnostic. 
      FPUMP_off_loVf Minimum valid low-side driver off-state voltage feedback 
      for the "Fuel pump relay coil open" diagnostic. 
      FPUMP_on_hiVf Maximum valid low-side driver on-state voltage feedback for 
      the "Fuel pump relay coil short to power" diagnostic. 
      FPUMP_on_loVf Minimum valid high-side driver on-state voltage feedback for 
      the "Fuel pump relay control ground short" diagnostic. 
      FPUMP_pin This switch selects what output pin will control the fuel pump 
      relay. The 'Standard' option means that the typical 'named' pin on the ECM 
      will control this function. The 'Disabled' option means that no output pin 
      will be manipulated in response to a request to control this device. 
      FPUMP_wakeup Time required for the gasoline fuel pump to pressurize the 
      fuel rail. 
      FP_abs_gage Fuel Pressure Gage/Absolute switch, Primary 
      FP_abs_gage_I2 Fuel Pressure Gage/Absolute switch, Secondary 
      FP_crct fuel pressure correction factor in fraction 
      FP_ena Fuel (Rail) Pressure Sensor source, Primary 
      FP_ena_I2 Fuel (Rail) Pressure Sensor source, Secondary 
      FP_fault_mode Primary fuel pressure high diagnostic: Enables/disables the 
      fuel pressure high/low faults for various fuel types. 
      FP_fault_mode_I2 Secondary fuel pressure high diagnostic: Enables/disables 
      the fuel pressure high/low faults for various fuel types. 
      FP_high Primary fuel pressure high diagnostic: Non-Common-Rail Primary 
      fuel pressure upper limit entry condition 
      FP_highlow_wait run time wait for primary fuel pressure high/low faults 
      FP_highlow_wait_I2 run time wait for secondary fuel pressure high/low 
      faults 
      FP_high_I2 Secondary fuel pressure high diagnostic: Secondary fuel 
      pressure upper limit entry condition 
      FP_I2_MAP_dP_high Secondary fuel pressure delta high diagnostic: Secondary 
      fuel pressure delta from MAP upper limit. 
      FP_I2_MAP_low Secondary fuel pressure high diagnostic entry condition: 
      Manifold pressure lower limit 
      FP_low Primary fuel pressure low diagnostic: Non-Common-Rail Primary fuel 
      pressure lower limit entry condition 
      FP_low_I2 Secondary fuel pressure low diagnostic: Secondary fuel pressure 
      upper limit entry condition 
      FP_MAP_dP_high Primary fuel pressure delta high diagnostic: Primary fuel 
      pressure delta from MAP upper limit. 
      FP_MAP_low Primary fuel pressure high diagnostic entry condition: Manifold 
      pressure lower limit 
      FP_maxv Primary FP high voltage diagnostic: Primary fuel pressure voltage 
      upper limit entry condition 
      FP_maxv_I2 Secondary FP high voltage diagnostic: Secondary fuel pressure 
      voltage upper limit entry condition 
      FP_minv Primary FP low voltage diagnostic: Primary fuel pressure voltage 
      lower limit entry condition 
      FP_minv_I2 Secondary FP low voltage diagnostic: Secondary fuel pressure 
      voltage lower limit entry condition 
      fric_cold_ena This selection determines if the Cold Friction Torque values 
      are used in conjunction with the Hot Friction Torque values to determine 
      the friction torque reported over J1939. If Disabled, the Hot Friction 
      Torque value is reported over J1939. When ECT or OILT is selected, an 
      interpolation between the Cold and Hot Friction Torque values is 
      calculated based on the Cold Friction and Hot Friction Trigger values. 
      fric_cold_T Cold Friction trigger value: At temperatures equal or below 
      this trigger value, the Cold Friction Torque value will be used. At temps 
      greater than this value and less than the Hot Friction trigger value, the 
      friction will be an interpolation between the CF Torque and HF Torque. 
      fric_hot_T Hot Friction trigger value: At temperatures equal or great than 
      this value, the Hot Friction Torque value will be used. At temps less than 
      this value and greater than the CF trigger value, the friction will be an 
      interpolation between the CF Torque and HF Torque. 
      FRO_ESD_ena If enabled, when using the CD Spark and Knock (SPOCK) 
      controller, if an Emergency Shutdown is requested, fuel run-out will 
      activate prior to the engine stopping to avoid a potential intake backfire 
      upon restart. If an active lockoff fault exists, fuel run-out is skipped 
      regardless of this option's setting and the engine will immediately 
      shutdown. 
      FRO_fuelclear_ms If non-zero, at the end of the fuel runout period, the 
      ECM will close the MJ/EPR fully in order to clear the fuel from the 
      manifold for the subsequent restart (in case of a lockoff failure or 
      extended fuel run-out times). For example, if the "Fuel run-out maximum 
      time" is set to 10000 ms and this parameter is set to 500ms, the engine 
      will operate in fuel run-out mode for the first 9500 seconds after the key 
      is switched off. The MJ/EPR will be closed during the final 500ms, and at 
      the end of the 10000ms period, the engine will be shut down. 
      FRO_gov_state_freeze If enabled, the governor switch state will be frozen 
      when fuel run-out begins. For example, if governor 3 is active and fuel 
      run-out begins, the engine will continue operating on governor 3 during 
      the fuel run-out period. If this option is disabled (default), the engine 
      will switch to the min governor during fuel run-out. 
      FRO_IGN_DIS_ena If enabled, when using the CD Spark and Knock (SPOCK) 
      controller, if an Ignition Disable is requested, fuel run-out will 
      activate prior to the engine stopping to avoid a potential intake backfire 
      upon restart. If an active If enabled, when using the CD Spark and Knock 
      (SPOCK) controller, if an Ignition Disable is requested, fuel run-out will 
      activate prior to the engine stopping to avoid a potential intake backfire 
      upon restart. If an active lockoff fault exists, fuel run-out is skipped 
      regardless of this option's setting and the engine will immediately 
      shutdown. 
      FRO_key_mode This switch determines engine behavior when the key switch is 
      transitioned back to ON following the initial transition to OFF while the 
      engine is running with fuel run-out mode enabled. Normally, the key being 
      transitioned back to on is ignored and the engine will remain in fuel 
      run-out mode until it runs out of fuel and stops or is halted due to a 
      timeout. If this switch is set to 'Continue Running', then the engine will 
      return to a normal running mode if it was still at or above run speed when 
      the key was switched back to ON. 
      FRO_shutdown_ena If enabled, when a fault requiring an engine shutdown 
      occurs, fuel run-out will activate prior to the engine stopping to avoid a 
      potential intake backfire upon restart. If an active lockoff fault exists, 
      fuel run-out is skipped regardless of this option's setting and the engine 
      will immediately shutdown. 
      FRO_sleep If enabled, and EPR is the active fuel system during fuel 
      run-out, the processor will honor the 'Key-off sleep wait' timer and will 
      enter sleep during fuel run-out.

      If disabled, or CFV / MFG is the active fuel system during fuel run-out, 
      the processor will not enter sleep until fuel run-out has completed. 
      FRP_raw Fuel rail pressure - raw volts 
      FRT Fuel temperature at the fuel rail or mixer. 
      FRT_crct Fuel temperature correction 
      FRT_est_ena Set this switch='FRT=FT' to use the normal FT analog input to 
      calculate the FRT.Set this switch='IAT-FT based estimate' to use an IAT-FT 
      based estimate for the FRT. 
      FRT_est_tau FRT_tau is the low-pass filter time constant for the estimated 
      FRT value. The FRT will reach 63% of the estimated steady-state value 
      within FRT_tau seconds. 
      FRT_est_xmax Calibration value for determining maximum proportion of FT 
      contribution 
      FRT_est_xmin "FT_%min": value for determining minimum proportion of FT 
      contribution. See "FRT Estimate" for a description of this value. 
      FSF2_ALL_MON_READY Indicates if all supported monitored readiness systems 
      are ready 
      FSF2_GD_FAULT Indicates that at least one of the faults on which 
      incrementing the GD is dependent is currently faulted 
      FSF2_GD_INC Indicates that the IUPR general denominator has been 
      incremented for the current cycle 
      FSF2_NOX_FAULT_MIL Indicates that at least one NOx control system fault is 
      active and requesting MIL illumination 
      FSF2_ON_DEMAND_MIL At least one fault requesting Euro VI on demand MIL 
      FSF2_SHORT_MIL At least one fault requesting Euro VI short MIL 
      FSFP_CLR_THIS_CYCLE Indicates if fault memory was cleared during the 
      current drive cycle. 
      FSFP_MIL_THIS_CYCLE Indicates if a MIL occurred during the current drive 
      cycle. 
      FSFP_WARMED_UP Indicates that the current drive cycle should be considered 
      "warmed-up" 
      FSF_FAULT_MIL At least one fault requesting Euro VI continuous MIL 
      FSF_MIL_STATE Faultgoverned MIL state 
      FSO_bstfault_init Boost control fault count down timer initial value 
      FSO_ECT_lockout Fuel shutoff cold ECT lockout 
      FSO_ena When parameter is set to 'Enabled - UEGO Cal Only', the UEGO drift 
      compensation feature settings on the 'Inputs' page will determine how 
      often FPP-based fuel shutoff will be engaged.

      When set to 'Enabled - FPP Only', fuel shutoff is allowed based on the FPP 
      position. The active governor must be either Min Gov or Max Gov and the 
      FPP is in the idle position.

      When set to 'Enabled - FPP or Gov3', fuel shutoff is allowed based on the 
      FPP position and Gov3 load. For FPP-based FSO, the active governor must be 
      either Min Gov or Max Gov and the FPP is in the idle position. For 
      Gov3-based FSO, the active governor must be Gov3 and the engine load 
      considered to be low.

      MAP-based fuel shutoff is always enabled. However, MAP-based FSO does not 
      open the throttle. 
      FSO_engbrk_exitwait Delay before exiting fuel shutoff after engine 
      braking. 
      FSO_fault_init FSO UEGO fault ignore time. See FSO_fault_mode for more 
      details 
      FSO_fault_mode If set to 'FSO Active', the FSO EGO/UEGO fault ignore time 
      will be used whenever MAP or FPP based fuel shutoff is active. If 'FSO 
      Active + CL Inactive' is selected, the FSO EGO/UEGO fault ignore time will 
      also be used if CL is inactive due to:
      1. manual forcing of CL inactive
      2. the CL waveform exceeding its authority limit
      3. the CL enable MAP forcing the system into open-loop mode 
      FSO_Gov3_dis_rpm_err When Gov3-based FSO is engaged, FSO will disengage if 
      the Gov3 speed error is less than this parameter. The speed error is 
      defined as the current engine speed minus the governor's target engine 
      speed. Parameter is only applicable if "FSO system" is set to 'Enabled - 
      FPP and Gov3'. 
      FSO_Gov3_ena_rpm_err The minimum allowed Gov3 speed error when engaging 
      Gov3-based FSO. The speed error is defined as the current engine speed 
      minus the governor's target engine speed. Parameter is only applicable if 
      "FSO system" is set to 'Enabled - FPP and Gov3'. 
      FSO_Gov3_load_delta When Gov3-based FSO is engaged, FSO will disengage if 
      the Gov3 desired load increases by this parameter's amount. The increase 
      in desired load is measured from the lowest desired load during the 
      Gov3-based FSO event. Parameter is only applicable if "FSO system" is set 
      to 'Enabled - FPP and Gov3'. 
      FSO_Gov3_load_max The maximum allowed engine load when engaging Gov3-based 
      FSO. Parameter is only applicable if "FSO system" is set to 'Enabled - FPP 
      and Gov3'. 
      FSO_Gov3_timer_init Fuel shutoff validation time for Gov3-based FSO. All 
      Gov3-based FSO engage criteria must be satisfied for this parameter's 
      amount of time before FSO will engage. If FPP-based FSO is already engaged 
      when governor switches to Gov3, then Gov3 validation time will be 
      temporarily overridden to allow FSO to remain engaged. However, Gov3-based 
      FSO criteria must still be met to keep FSO engaged. Parameter is only 
      applicable if "FSO system" is set to 'Enabled - FPP and Gov3'. 
      FSO_idle_off This value is added to the current idle speed target to 
      obtain a speed below which fuel-shutoff is absolutely disabled regardless 
      of any other parameters. 
      FSO_load_delay Parameter is used to calibrate the delay time between FSO 
      disengagement and the estimated engine load becoming greater than zero. 
      The total delay time is calculated as this parameter plus "FSO disengage 
      load transport delay" multiplied by the current transport delay. Parameter 
      is only applicable when "FSO disengage load reduction" is non-zero and 
      "FSO spark retard mode" is set to 'Table Based' on the Spark worksheet. 
      FSO_load_init If enabled, when FSO initially engages, the estimated engine 
      load is assumed to be zero. Upon FSO disengagement, estimated engine load 
      will remain zero until a delay time elapses, refer to "FSO disengage load 
      fixed delay" and "FSO disengage load transport delay". After the delay 
      elapses, this value determines the initial percent reduction in the 
      estimated engine load due to FSO. The reduction is slewed to 0% as the FSO 
      spark retard decays to 0. Set this value to 0 to disable all reductions to 
      estimated engine load during FSO. 
      FSO_load_reduct fuel shutoff reduction in load in pct 
      FSO_load_T_delay Parameter is used to calibrate the delay time between FSO 
      disengagement and the estimated engine load becoming greater than zero. 
      The total delay time is calculated as "FSO disengage load fixed delay" 
      plus this parameter multiplied by the current transport delay. Parameter 
      is only applicable when "FSO disengage load reduction" is non-zero and 
      "FSO spark retard mode" is set to 'Table Based' on the Spark worksheet. 
      FSO_MAP MAP-based FSO engage pressure. Note: MAP-based FSO does not open 
      the throttle. 
      FSO_MAP_hyst Adder above "MAP FSO engage" to exit FSO mode and return to 
      fueling the engine. 
      FSO_ovrspd_TPS_wait This delay timer functions just like the "FSO throttle 
      open delay" timer but is only applicable during an active engine overspeed 
      condition when "Retarder braking during engine overspeed" (Outputs page) 
      is enabled. 
      FSO_phi_delt_wt If non-zero and an active post-cat EGO sensor is 
      available, post-cat delta-phi processing is disabled when exiting fuel 
      shutoff for this period of time. If FSO phi catalyst enrichment is 
      enabled, then this delay timer will start when the enrichment ends. 
      Otherwise, this delay timer starts immediately upon fuel shutoff 
      disengagement. 
      FSO_retard Start/FSO retard 
      FSO_ret_decay Upon an FSO ON->OFF transition (fuel has been turned back 
      on), the value 'FSO spark retard' will be used to initialize a spark 
      retard modifier. It will be decayed back to 0 at the rate given by this 
      value. This is used to generate a smooth power transition as fuel hits the 
      cylinders following FSO. 
      FSO_ret_init Upon an FSO ON->OFF transition (fuel has been turned back 
      on), this spark retard value will be used. It will be decayed back to 0 at 
      the rate given by 'FSO retard decay'. This is used to generate a smooth 
      power transition as fuel hits the cylinders following FSO. 
      FSO_ret_mode Set this value to "Single Point" to use the 'FSO spark retard 
      max' parameter to set the spark retard modifier upon an FSO ON->OFF 
      transition (fuel has been turned back on). The spark retard modifier will 
      be decayed back to 0 at the rate specified by the 'FSO retard decay' 
      parameter.

      Set this value to "Table Based" to use the 'MAP-based Spark Retard' table 
      to determine the spark retard modifier upon an FSO ON->OFF transition. The 
      spark retard modifier is updated based on changing MAP load values and 
      applied for the duration of time specified by the 'FSO Spark Retard Hold' 
      table. Once the hold time expires, the spark retard modifier is decayed 
      back to 0 at a rate calculated from the 'Spark retard decay time' 
      parameter. 
      FSO_rpm_high FSO engage engine speed. Applicable to both FPP-based and 
      Gov3-based FSO. 
      FSO_rpm_low FSO disengage engine speed. Applicable to both FPP-based and 
      Gov3-based FSO. 
      FSO_rpm_mode When parameter set to 'fixed' mode (the default), then all of 
      the RPM-based FSO parameters are taken as absolute values.
      When set to 'idle relative' mode, then all of the RPM-based FSO parameters 
      have an offset added to them = (idle_target-idle_default).

      The FSO parameters affected are:
      "FSO engage speed"
      "FSO disengage speed"
      "FSO throttle open speed"

      An example would be:
      - a cold idle speed of 850 rpm
      - a default warm idle speed of 650 rpm
      - an FSO engage speed of 1400 rpm
      - the new computed FSO engage speed will be 1600 rpm
      - all other RPM-based FSO parameters will also be raised by 200 rpm 
      FSO_rpm_TPSoff Minimum engine speed for opening the throttle during fuel 
      shutoff. 
      FSO_runtime_wait Fuel shutoff will not be allowed prior to this amount of 
      run time on the engine. 
      FSO_timer_init Fuel shutoff validation time for FPP-based FSO. All 
      FPP-based FSO engage criteria must be satisfied for this parameter's 
      amount of time before FSO will engage.

      When "FSO system" is set to 'Enabled - FPP and Gov3', Gov3-based FSO is 
      already engaged, and the active governor switches from Gov3 to Min/Max 
      Gov, then this parameter will be temporarily overridden to allow FSO to 
      remain engaged. However, FPP-based FSO criteria must still be met to keep 
      FSO engaged. 
      FSO_TPSmin Minimum throttle position during fuel shutoff.

      When "FSO throttle open control mode" is set to 'Pre-open UEGO check', 
      this setting is used:
      1. After the "FSO throttle open UEGO limit" condition is met,
      2. After "FSO throttle open delay" lapses following the phi condition, and
      3. When permitted by "FSO TPS/engine brake coordination".

      When "FSO throttle open control mode" is set to 'Post-open UEGO check', 
      this setting is used after the "FSO throttle open delay" time lapses. 
      However, if the pre-catalyst phi does not drop below "FSO throttle open 
      UEGO limit" within a specified time, then the throttle will close. See 
      "FSO throttle open UEGO limit" and "FSO post TPS open UEGO check" 
      descriptions for further details. 
      FSO_TPSmin_braking Fuel shutoff throttle open position during engine 
      braking.
