      FSO_TPSmin_entry Minimum throttle position at entry to fuel shutoff. This 
      position is used after the validation time and before the "FSO throttle 
      open UEGO limit" condition is met. 
      FSO_TPS_coord_ena This option enables coordination of the throttle and the 
      engine brake during FSO. Option can only be enabled if "FSO throttle open 
      control mode" is set to 'Pre-open UEGO check'. If this option is enabled, 
      the following sequence of events will be performed AFTER the UEGO drift 
      sampling has been completed:
      1) Close the throttle
      2) Wait for MAP to drop to the specified "FSO coordination MAP target"
      3) Enable the engine brake
      4) Wait the "FSO coordination TPS reopen delay"
      5) Reopen the throttle 
      FSO_TPS_coord_MAP After initial throttle open period and UEGO drift 
      sample, close TPS and wait for MAP to drop to this target 
      FSO_TPS_coord_wait After MAP has dropped and engine brake has been 
      enabled, wait this amount of time before reopening throttle 
      FSO_TPS_ctrl_mode The 'Pre-open UEGO check' control mode will not open the 
      throttle until the pre-catalyst phi drops below "FSO throttle open UEGO 
      limit" (if non-zero) and the throttle open delay timer expires.

      The 'Post-open UEGO check' control mode will open the throttle after the 
      throttle open delay timer expires, regardless of phi. Phi is subsequently 
      checked after the throttle is open. See description of "FSO post TPS open 
      UEGO check" setting for more details. 
      FSO_TPS_diag_pct Percentage of successful post-open UEGO checks required 
      to reach a diagnostic conclusion for "Failed to reach FSO post throttle 
      open UEGO limit" fault. This setting only applies when "FSO throttle open 
      control mode" is set to 'Post-open UEGO check' and fault is enabled. 
      FSO_TPS_flt_chk_mode Parameter determines how the "Pre-catalyst O2 sensor 
      out of range" fault is checked before allowing the throttle to open during 
      FSO. Parameter is only applicable when a pre-catalyst UEGO sensor is 
      present and "FSO throttle open UEGO limit" is calibrated. When parameter 
      is set to 'Instantaneous (Legacy)', the instantaneous status of the 
      "Pre-catalyst O2 sensor out of range" fault is only checked. If fault's 
      instantaneous status is active, then the throttle is not allowed to open 
      during FSO. When parameter is set to 'Pending or Confirmed', then the 
      fault must be pending or confirmed and active to prevent the throttle from 
      opening during FSO. 
      FSO_TPS_open_tmr FSO TPS open count up timer 
      FSO_TPS_phi_check The maximum time that phi can be greater than "FSO 
      throttle open UEGO limit" with the throttle opened. If this timer expires 
      and phi has not dropped, then the throttle is closed immediately. This 
      setting only applies when "FSO throttle open control mode" is set to 
      'Post-open UEGO check'. Setting must be greater than 0ms, but no more than 
      1000ms. 
      FSO_TPS_spk_kill Kills spark during the throttle open portion of fuel 
      shutoff. 
      FSO_TPS_UEGO_lmt This option should only be enabled if a pre-catalyst UEGO 
      sensor is present.

      When "FSO throttle open control mode" is set to 'Pre-open UEGO check': If 
      this setting is non-zero, the pre-catalyst UEGO-based equivalence ratio 
      must be below this limit before the throttle open delay timer begins.

      When "FSO throttle open control mode" is set to 'Post-open UEGO check': 
      The pre-catalyst UEGO-based equivalence ratio must drop below this limit 
      before the "FSO post TPS open UEGO check" timer expires. Used to verify 
      that equivalence ratio drops while the throttle is open during fuel 
      shutoff. Setting must be greater than 0. 
      FSO_TPS_variable_ena Enables alternative throttle positions during fuel 
      shutoff. When enabled and engine braking is active, the throttle open 
      position is set to "FSO throttle open position during braking". When 
      disabled, or when engine braking is not active, the throttle open position 
      is set to "FSO throttle open position". 
      FSO_TPS_wait This is the delay time between fuel shutoff initiation and 
      the time at which the throttle will be commanded open during FSO throttle 
      open operating windows. This delay time gives the intake manifold time to 
      clear of any residual fuel before raising the MAP due to throttle opening. 

      FSO_TPS_wait_cur This is the delay time between FPP based fuel shutoff 
      initiation and the time at which the throttle will be commanded open 
      during FSO throttle open operating windows. This delay time gives the 
      intake manifold time to clear of any residual fuel before raising the MAP 
      due to throttle opening. The delay is interpolated from the "FSO Throttle 
      Open Delay" table based on road speed. 
      FSO_TPS_wait_mode Specifies whether the fuel shutoff throttle open delay 
      is a single point or interpolated from the "FSO Throttle Open Delay" table 
      based on road speed. 
      FSS_base_tbl Configuration table - define base parameters to be captured 
      in Fault Snapshot (EDIS and calibration spreadsheet) 
      FSS_cust_tbl Configuration table - define customizable parameters to be 
      captured in Fault Snapshot (EDIS only) 
      FSS_cust_tbl_def Configuration table - define customizable parameters to 
      be captured in Fault Snapshot (calibration spreadsheet only) 
      fss_fault_dtc The fault DTC (Flash Code) 
      fss_fault_ndx The internal fault index 
      fss_fault_rank The calculated ranking for the fault for prioritized fss 
      occupancy 
      FSS_storage Fault snapshot storage area 
      FST Fuel source temperature. 
      FST_def If the FST input voltage value is invalid or the FST sensor is 
      disabled, this is the value that will be used for FST. 
      FST_ena This switch determines the auxiliary input channel connected to a 
      FST (fuel source temperature) sensor. FST is typically used for engine 
      derate on CNG fueled engines using the aux temperature derate function. 
      FST is typically located at the exit of the high-pressure regulator on CNG 
      applications. 
      FST_Taux_cal Fuel source temperature (FST) calibration table selection 
      FST_vdr Fuel source temperature (FST) pullup resistor configuration 
      FT Fuel Temperature 
      FTgaseous_vdr Alt Fuel Temp (gaseous) calibration pullup resistor 
      resistance configuration 
      FTgasf_maxT Maximum valid fuel temperature for the "FT gaseous fuel high" 
      diagnostic. 
      FTgasf_maxv Maximum valid fuel temperature sensor voltage for the "FT 
      gaseous fuel high" diagnostic. 
      FTgasf_minECT Minimum ECT for evaluating the minimum fuel temperature for 
      the "FT gaseous fuel low" diagnostic. 
      FTgasf_minT Minimum valid fuel temperature for the "FT gaseous fuel low" 
      diagnostic. 
      FTgasf_minv Minimum valid fuel temperature sensor voltage for the "FT 
      gaseous fuel low" diagnostic. 
      FTgsln_maxT FT gasoline fuel high diagnostic: Fuel temp upper limit entry 
      condition 
      FTgsln_minT FT gasoline fuel low diagnostic: Fuel temp lower limit entry 
      condition 
      FTP Fuel tank pressure. 
      FTPcal_P 1D Interpolation Table: Fuel Tank Pressure Sensor. Input is 
      sensor voltage, output is fuel tank pressure (either psig or psia) 
      FTPcal_V 1D Interpolation Table: Fuel Tank Pressure Sensor. Sensor voltage 
      input values. 
      FTPM_expected_FTP Expected fuel tank pressure, interpolated from the fuel 
      impurity table using the learned fuel impurity and the current fuel tank 
      temperature. 
      FTPM_imp_actv Indicates when conditions are valid for learning fuel 
      impurity. 
      FTPM_imp_dec_tau Decreasing tau for learning fuel impurity after the 
      initial learn time has lapsed. 
      FTPM_imp_inc_tau Increasing tau for learning fuel impurity after the 
      initial learn time has lapsed. A value of 0 seconds disables increasing 
      the learned fuel impurity after the initial learning period. 
      FTPM_imp_inst Instantaneous fuel impurity, calculated when:
      1. fuel flow is greater than the minimum fuel flow for learning fuel 
      impurity, and run time is less than the maximum run time for applying this 
      condition;
      2. fuel flow is less than the maximum fuel flow for learning fuel 
      impurity; and
      3. FTT monitoring state is "Monitoring" 
      FTPM_imp_learn_tau Tau for learning fuel impurity before the initial learn 
      time has lapsed. 
      FTPM_imp_learn_tm Time to rapidly learn fuel impurity at the start of the 
      run cycle. 
      FTPM_imp_lp Learned fuel impurity, updated only when conditions are valid 
      for computing the instantaneous fuel impurity. 
      FTPM_imp_max_idle_tm Maximum run time for applying the minimum fuel flow 
      condition for learning fuel impurity. 
      FTPM_imp_md_f_max Maximum fuel flow for learning fuel impurity. At very 
      high fuel flow rates, the fuel tank pressure may drop. Setting this value 
      to 0 disables the upper fuel flow limit for learning fuel impurity. 
      FTPM_imp_md_f_min Minimum fuel flow for rationalizing FTT and learning 
      fuel impurity. This value is the maximum fuel flow where heat soak into 
      the fuel line from the regulator/engine bay can influence the fuel tank 
      temperature sensor.

      When fuel flow exceeds this value:
      - the tank heat increasing slew rate is used
      - when the fuel tank temperature monitoring state is "Above normal", the 
      state can return to the normal "Monitoring" state (when other conditions 
      are valid)
      - fuel impurity can learn (when other conditions are valid)
      - the minimum fuel tank pressure may increase.

      When fuel flow does not exceed this value:
      - the idle increasing fuel tank temperature slew rate is used 
      FTPM_imp_tmr Elapsed time learning fuel impurity from the start of the run 
      cycle. 
      FTPM_latch_tm Time to latch or unlatch the low fuel pressure state. The 
      low pressure state will latch up when:
      - the fuel impurity initial learn time has lapsed, and the fuel tank 
      pressure is below the minimum expected pressure, based on the current fuel 
      tank temperature and learned fuel impurity.

      The low pressure state and latch timer will latch up immediately when:
      - a lower pressure limit was specified, and the fuel tank pressure is 
      below the lower limit; or
      - the accumulated fuel tank temperature error exceeds the specified limit, 
      interpolated based on the learned fuel impurity.

      The low pressure indication is available over CAN in PGN 65410, SPN 64925. 
      When "Low fuel monitoring input" is set to 'FTPM (LPG) + Fuel level input 
      (Gasoline)' on the DiagConfig worksheet, then the low pressure indication 
      is also available over CAN in PGN 65435, SPN 65161, or PGN 65446, SPN 
      65270. 
      FTPM_latch_tmr Timer for latching or unlatching the low fuel pressure 
      state. 
      FTPM_low Indicates when fuel tank pressure is too low to maintain liquid 
      fuel flow. 
      FTPM_min_FTP Instantaneous minimum fuel tank pressure, calculated as 
      expected fuel tank pressure times the minimum fuel tank pressure 
      multiplier. 
      FTPM_min_FTP_inc_tau Tau for increasing the minimum fuel tank pressure. 
      The tau for decreasing the minimum fuel tank pressure is fixed at 0. 
      FTPM_min_FTP_lim Minimum fuel tank pressure for proper engine operation. 
      If set to 0, the lowest pressure is determined solely by the fuel impurity 
      table, and fuel tank pressure monitoring will be disabled during the 
      initial fuel impurity learning period or during a FTT sensor fault. 
      FTPM_min_FTP_lp Low-passed minimum fuel tank pressure. The low pressure 
      state will latch up when the fuel tank pressure exceeds the low-passed 
      minimum fuel tank pressure. 
      FTPM_min_FTP_mult Multiplier for calculating the minimum fuel tank 
      pressure. The expected fuel tank pressure is interpolated from the fuel 
      impurity table using the learned fuel impurity and the current fuel tank 
      temperature. The minimum fuel tank pressure is calculated as expected fuel 
      tank pressure times the minimum fuel tank pressure multiplier. 
      FTPM_mode When set to "Enabled":
      1. Fuel impurity is learned rapidly near the start of a run cycle, when 
      conditions are valid. The fuel impurity continues to learn slowly after 
      the initial learn period.
      2. A minimum fuel tank pressure is calculated based on the learned fuel 
      impurity and the current fuel tank temperature, when the fuel tank 
      temperature is stable. When the fuel tank temperature is unstable, the 
      minimum fuel tank pressure remains unchanged.
      3. When the fuel tank pressure is below the minimum pressure threshold for 
      the specified latch time, the low fuel pressure state becomes active.

      In the low fuel pressure state:
      1. Closed loop faults and adaptive updates will be disabled if configured 
      to do so. See "Low fuel monitoring input" on DiagConfig worksheet.
      2. Low fuel pressure faults are disabled.
      3. The low fuel pressure status is available in ECI SPN 65161, 65270, or 
      64925.
      4. The low fuel pressure state will become inactive if the fuel tank 
      pressure is above the minimum pressure threshold for the latch time. 
      FTP_abs_gage Fuel Tank Pressure Sensor - psia vs. psig units selector 
      FTP_def default Fuel Tank Pressure (FTP) value 
      FTP_ena This switch determines the source of the fuel tank pressure (FTP). 
      When configured as 'CAN sourced', the following PGN/SPNs are available:
      ECI PGN 65515, SPN 64873
      ECI PGN 65299, SPN 64868 
      FTT Fuel tank temperature. 
      FTT_ena This switch determines the auxiliary input channel connected to a 
      FTT (fuel tank temperature) sensor. 
      FTT_expected_max Maximum expected fuel tank temperature, accounting for 
      both heat soak and ambient tank heating. 
      FTT_expected_tank Maximum expected fuel tank temperature, accounting only 
      for ambient tank heating. 
      FTT_inc_slew_idle Maximum fuel tank temperature increase rate due to heat 
      soak at low liquid fuel flow rates. 
      FTT_inc_slew_tank Maximum fuel tank temperature increase rate due to 
      ambient heating of the fuel tank at higher liquid fuel flow rates. Fuel 
      impurity will not learn when the fuel tank temperature increases faster 
      than this rate. 
      FTT_max_tank Maximum fuel tank temperature for learning fuel impurity and 
      for fuel tank pressure monitoring. 
      FTT_min_vapor Minimum fuel tank temperature where vaporization is assumed 
      to occur. 
      FTT_state Fuel tank temperature rationalization state. 
      FTT_tolerance Current fuel tank temperature tolerance, which is added to 
      expected fuel tank temperatures to account for normal cyclic temperature 
      variations. 
      FTT_vapor_Ierr Current accumulated temperature rise above the minimum 
      vaporization temperature. 
      FTT_vapor_Ierr_lim Current limit for the accumulated temperature rise 
      above the minimum vaporization temperature. 
      FTT_vdr Fuel Tank Temperature (FTT) calibration pullup resistor 
      configuration 
      FT_bleedoff_delay Fuel transition bleedoff start delay 
      FT_bleedoff_dP_cmd Fuel transition bleedoff rate 
      FT_bleedoff_ena Enables the bleed-off function during LPG, NP, or both LPG 
      and NP fuel transition to gasoline. 
      FT_bleedoff_fuelType Fuel transition bleedoff fuel type 
      FT_bleedoff_Ptarget Fuel transition bleedoff target pressure 
      FT_bleedoff_state Enable/disable for LPG/NG fuel transition bleedoff 
      FT_def Default value of FT 
      FT_ena Fuel temperature sensor disable/enable switch for gasoline or 
      gaseous injection (gasoline mode). 
      FT_fault_mode Select between voltage and engineering setpoint mode. If the 
      voltage only mode is enabled, the default fuel temperature is used for 
      fuel temperature whenever a fault condition is active. In temperature-only 
      mode, the measured temperature is used for fuel temperature regardless of 
      the fault state. In voltage or temperature mode, the default fuel 
      temperature is used if the voltage out-of-range condition is at least 
      partially responsible for the fault setting. 
      FT_gaseous_ena Fuel temperature sensor disable/enable switch for gaseous 
      regulators/mixers. 
      FT_gsln_slew_att Gasoline slew in attenuation factor during fuel 
      transition 
      FT_input_cfg Defines the fuel types controlled by the select switch, as 
      well as the voltage strategy assigned to each fuel (configured as part of 
      Fuel Switching Control, FT_input_pin) 
      FT_input_pin This switch determines what hardware pin on the ECM is used 
      to switch fuels. 
      FT_MAPsw The manifold pressure must be below this parameter's value before 
      a manual switch to an alternate fuel will be carried out. Parameter is 
      only applicable when "Fuel switch mode" is set to 'Normal'. 
      FT_maxv FT gasoline high diagnostic: FT voltage upper limit entry 
      condition 
      FT_minv FT gasoline low diagnostic: FT voltage lower limit entry condition 

      FT_raw Fuel temperature signal raw volts 
      FT_RPMsw The engine speed must be below this parameter's value before a 
      manual switch to an alternate fuel will be carried out. Parameter is only 
      applicable when "Fuel switch mode" is set to 'Normal'. 
      FT_s Standard fuel temperature used for the fuel flow calibration 
      FT_sw_mode Determines the operation of the manual fuel selection toggle 
      switch. When value is set to 'Normal', then the active fuel can be changed 
      by the toggle switch regardless of the engine's operational state. When 
      value is set to 'Stopped Engine', then changes in the toggle switch 
      position are ignored unless the engine is stopped. The legacy modes were 
      never implemented and remain unimplemented. 
      FT_vdr Fuel temperature input pullup resistor configuration 
      fuelclr_auto_ena When set to "Enabled", the "Automatic Fuel Clear" table 
      is used to determine the maximum cranking time with fuel on. When the 
      maximum cranking time with fuel on is exceeded, the table is used to 
      determine the minimum cranking time with fuel off.

      During fuel clearing, for gasoline, the fuel command will be multiplied by 
      "Fuel clear function fuel multiplier"; for gaseous fuels, the fuel command 
      is zero.

      An operator switch and/or foot pedal input will switch automatic fuel 
      clearing into the fuel clearing state. After operator inputs are inactive, 
      fuel clearing will continue for the minimum time specified in the table. 
      fuelclr_auto_rstmode Specifies when to reset the automatic fuel clear 
      timer.

      When set to "After key-off sleep", the fuel on/off cranking time is not 
      reset immediately at key-off, and is reset "Key-off sleep wait" seconds 
      after the key is switched off. In other words, the operator is not allowed 
      to switch the key off to defeat the automatic clearing time.

      When set to "Every key-off", the fuel on/off cranking time is reset when 
      the key is switched off. 
      fuelclr_auto_state State of the automatic fuel clear function. 
      fuelclr_auto_tmr Time that the automatic fuel clear function is in the 
      "Wait for start" or "Clearing" states. 
      fuelclr_chan This switch enables fuel clear mode activation via an 
      auxiliary input when the engine is not running. If “Disabled”, FPP will be 
      used to initiate fuel clear mode. 
      fuelclr_chan_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the input, this value 
      determines the active logic state(s). The Default values are:

      Aux DIG1 = Gnd
      Aux DIG2 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG3 = Gnd
      Aux DIG4 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG5 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG6 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG7 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG8 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG9 = Gnd
      Aux DIG10 = Gnd
      Aux DIG11 = Gnd
      Aux DIG12 = Gnd
      Aux DIG13 = Gnd
      Aux DIG14 = Gnd
      Aux DIG15 = Gnd
      Aux DIG16 = Gnd
      Aux DIG17 = Gnd
      Aux DIG18 = Gnd
      Aux DIG19 = Gnd
      Gov1 = Gnd
      Gov2 = Gnd

      fuelclr_debounce If "Fuel clear function AUX DIG" is selected and the 
      digital input has been active for more than this time, the fueling command 
      will be multiplied by following multiplier (0.000 < multiplier <= 1.000). 
      fuelclr_FPP If "Fuel clear function Aux DIG" is Disabled and the FPP is 
      greater than this value during cranking, the fueling command will be 
      multiplied by following multiplier (0.000 < multiplier <= 1.000). 
      fuelclr_gaseous Enables fuel clear mode on DEPR gaseous fueled systems. 
      Note: this option has no effect on trim-valve based systems and should not 
      be used on MJ/EPR systems. 
      fuelclr_mult Fueling command will be multiplied by this value if FPP is 
      greater than the Fuel clear function minimum FPP value. 
      fuelclr_requested Indicates when fuel clearing is requested. 
      fuellev_in_ena This switch controls the source of a fuel level input 
      signal.

      When configured as 'Network Source', the following PGN/SPNs are available:
      ECI PGN 42310, SPN 64869
      ECI PGN 42311, SPN 64870 (ECM calculates level from volumes)
      ECI PGN 42312, SPN 64871
      ECI PGN 42313, SPN 64872 
      fuellev_low_latch Amount of time the fuel level must be <= to the Low Fuel 
      Level % to latch a low fuel level condition. The range of values are 0 
      (immediate) to 65 seconds. 
      fuellev_low_pct Defines a low fuel condition for gasoline fueled engines 
      where CL, AL, and low fuel pressure faults are disabled. The associated 
      latch and unlatch timers are used to prevent against false indications 
      during tank slosh. 
      fuellev_low_tmr Fuel level sender - low fuel level latch/unlatch in 
      percent 
      fuellev_low_unlatch Amount of time required for the measured fuel level to 
      be greater than the "Low fuel level" percent before the low fuel level 
      indication is cleared. The range of values are 0 (immediate) to 65 
      seconds. 
      fuellev_pct Fuel level in percent 
      fuellev_pct_def Default fuel level percentage (fuellev_pct). 
      fuellev_ratio_md This switch controls the type of fuel level sender. An 
      'Absolute voltage output' sender's signal is independent of the supply 
      voltage. A '5V ratiometric output' sender is powered by and ratiometric to 
      the ECM's external 5V excitation. A 'Vbat ratiometric output' sender is 
      powered by and ratiometric to the 12V/24V system supply voltage. 
      fuellev_volt Fuel level sender output voltage 
      fuellev_Vstd This value is the standard excitation voltage used for 
      ratiometric output sensors. This value has no meaning for an absolute 
      output sender type. 
      fuellev_V_0 This is the sender output voltage for a 0% fuel level 
      (relative to the standard excitation voltage for ratiometric senders) 
      fuellev_V_1 This is the sender output voltage for a 100% fuel level 
      (relative to the standard excitation voltage for ratiometric senders) 
      fuellev_V_inter 1D calibration table: Fuel level corresponding to 25%, 50% 
      and 75% fuel levels (0% and 100% levels contained on separate parameters) 
      fuelrunout_ena Engages a fuel run-out engine stopping mode when the key is 
      turned off on alternate fuels (LPG and NG). In this mode, sparks continue 
      to fire for up to the maximum time specified below or until the engine 
      actually stops with the alternate fuel control lockoff turned off. 
      fuelrunout_max Maximum time that sparks will continue to fire during an 
      alternate fuel engine stopping event with fuel run-out mode enabled. If 
      this parameter is set to 65535 ms, then the run-out time will be extended 
      indefinitely. 
      FuelSpk_SD_active Logical indicating that fuel/spark shutdown is active 
      FuelSpk_SD_input This software switch controls the criteria for an 
      external input pin command of a fuel/spark inhibit either while the engine 
      is cranking or running. Note that this input specification is explicit, 
      and may coincide with a particular state of a fuel-select input channel if 
      desired. 
      FuelSpk_SD_tdelay If this time is nonzero and the min/max momentary window 
      times are zero, this value specifies a non-momentary switch validation 
      delay time to engage fuel/spark inhibit. Note this time is in addition to 
      any latch time required to diagnose an active switch input. Note the timer 
      used to measure the switch delay has a 50ms resolution. 
      FuelSpk_SD_tmax If this time or the min time are nonzero, a momentary 
      switch depressed time must fall between the min/max times for the inhibit 
      to latch as engaged. Note this time is in addition to any latch time 
      required to diagnose an active switch input. Note the timer used to 
      measure button/switch presses has a 50ms resolution. 
      FuelSpk_SD_tmin If this time or the max time are nonzero, a momentary 
      switch depressed time must fall between the min/max times for the inhibit 
      to latch as engaged. Note this time is in addition to any latch time 
      required to diagnose an active switch input. Note the timer used to 
      measure button/switch presses has a 50ms resolution. 
      FuelSpk_SD_tmr ms timer used to measure the fuel/spark shutdown input 
      active time 
      FuelSpk_SD_vehspd Enter the maximum vehicle speed for the fuel/spark 
      inhibit input to activate. 
      fuel_ctl_mode Current active fuel closed-loop control mode 
      fuel_device_LP This switch indicates what type of fuel admission device is 
      used for LPG fueling:

      1) Carburetion = a gaseous carburetor with either a MegaJector, EPR, PWM 
      pressure trim, or pure open-loop inlet pressure control. The 'Carburetor 
      fuel trim device type' switch and the fuel-specific closed-loop enable 
      switch on the 'CL' page further specify these carbureted control options.

      2) Pulse injection - Pri = pulse type fuel injectors operating on the 
      primary injector drivers (i.e. lower driver numbers - example 1-4 or 1-8 
      if no secondary injection is enabled). The location of all pulse injectors 
      is always indicated by the 'Fuel injection type' switch below - i.e. 
      throttle-body, port, or direct.

      3) Pulse injection - Sec = pulse type fuel injectors operating on the 
      secondary injector drivers (i.e. higher driver numbers - example 5-8) for 
      bi-fuel injected applications. The location of all pulse injectors is 
      always indicated by the 'Fuel injection type' switch below - i.e. 
      throttle-body, port, or direct. This option is not currently supported in 
      EICS.

      4) Continuous injection = CFV (continuous flow valve). The fuel 
      introduction point is always at the throttle body for CFV, but the 
      'Discharge fuel pressure environment' switch above indicates whether the 
      fuel is injected upstream (TIP) or downstream (MAP) of the throttle. This 
      option is not currently supported in EICS.

      5) MFG Injection - Uses the Mass Flow Gas (MFG) device. The "MFG location" 
      setting specifies the location of the MFG device. 
      fuel_device_NG This switch indicates what type of fuel admission device is 
      used for NG fueling. See "LPG fuel admission device type" description for 
      further information. 
      fuel_FP_crct_ena Injector supply fuel pressure correction (Primary) - This 
      switch enables a gaseous fuel pulse-width correction based on a 
      square-root temperature ratio of the actual to standard fuel temperatures. 

      fuel_FP_crct_ena_I2 Injector supply fuel pressure correction (Secondary) - 
      This switch enables a gaseous fuel pulse-width correction based on a 
      square-root temperature ratio of the actual to standard fuel temperatures. 

      fuel_FT_crct_ena Injector supply fuel temperature correction (Primary) - 
      This switch enables a gaseous fuel pulse-width correction based on a 
      square-root temperature ratio of the actual to standard fuel temperatures. 

      fuel_FT_crct_ena_I2 Injector supply fuel temperature correction 
      (Secondary) - This switch enables a gaseous fuel pulse-width correction 
      based on a square-root temperature ratio of the actual to standard fuel 
      temperatures. 
      fuel_MAP_crct_ena Injector discharge fuel pressure correction (Primary) - 
      Setting this switch to 'on' performs a square-root based fuel flow 
      correction for non-MAP biased fuel injection regulators. 
      fuel_MAP_crct_ena_I2 Injector discharge fuel pressure correction 
      (Secondary) - Setting this switch to 'on' performs a square-root based 
      fuel flow correction for non-MAP biased fuel injection regulators. 
      fuel_mon_boost Low fuel monitoring reaction - when configured as 'Inhibit 
      updates' and fuel is low, the following faults are not updated:
      "Control underboost 1" fault
      "Control underboost 2" fault
      "Boost control slow to respond" fault 
      fuel_mon_CL_ctl_lmt Low fuel monitoring reaction - when configured as 
      'Inhibit updates' and fuel is low, the following faults are not updated:
      "CL air/fuel ratio control at limit - too lean" fault
      "CL air/fuel ratio control at limit - too rich" fault 
      fuel_mon_CL_lmt Low fuel monitoring reaction - when configured as 'Inhibit 
      updates' and fuel is low, the following faults are not updated:
      "CL low gasoline bank 1" fault
      "CL high gasoline bank 1" fault
      "CL low gasoline bank 2" fault
      "CL high gasoline bank 2" fault
      "CL low LPG" fault
      "CL high LPG" fault
      "CL low NG" fault
      "CL high NG" fault 
      fuel_mon_EPR_low Low fuel monitoring reaction - when configured as 
      'Inhibit updates' and fuel is low, the following faults are not updated:
      "EPR / CFV regulation pressure lower than expected" fault
      "EPR secondary regulation pressure lower than expected" fault 
      fuel_mon_precat_OOR Low fuel monitoring reaction - when configured as 
      'Inhibit updates' and fuel is low, the "Pre-catalyst O2 sensor out of 
      range" fault is not updated. 
      fuel_mon_pres_low Low fuel monitoring reaction - when configured as 
      'Inhibit updates', the following faults are not updated when pressure is 
      low:
      "Primary fuel pressure low" fault
      "Secondary fuel pressure low" fault 
      fuel_shutoff_chk Internal variable. Provides current fuel shutoff status 
      fuel_slct_volt fuel select input voltage in volts 
      fuel_supply Indicates current ON/OFF requested state of fuel supply source 
      (fuel pump or lockoff) 
      fuel_throt_mode Throttle fuel admission mode. Select between legacy and 
      corrected throttle fueling mode. Legacy mode lumps manifold filling fuel 
      flow in with throttle flow, but mostly neglects steady-state throttle fuel 
      flow. Corrected mode separates throttle fuel and air flow based on the 
      calibration configuration (carburetion, draw or blow-through, etc.) 
      fuel_total_gas gaseous fueled total (non-resetable) consumption in kg 
      fuel_trip_gas gaseous fuel trip consumption in kg 
      fuel_trip_liquid liquid fuel trip consumption in mL increments 
      fuel_type Fuel type (NG, LPG, Diesel, Gasoline) 
      fuel_type_indicate Turn light on for selected fuel type (gasoline, LPG, 
      NG) 
      fuel_type_keyoff Fuel type at last key off used for startup fuel 
      transition bleedoff 
      fuel_type_u16 fuel_type in unsigned16 format for use by diagnostic data 
      recording systems 
      gagedrv_chan The output (sender connection) channel for the gauge driver. 
      gagedrv_DC This is the PWM duty cycle either used directly in PWM duty 
      cycle mode, or the internal PWM duty cycle used to simulate resistance in 
      resistance simulation mode. 
      gagedrv_manual Gauge driver mode (automatic or manual) 
      gagedrv_per Value is only applicable for output channels 'Aux PWM1' 
      through 'Aux PWM4'. 'Aux PWM5' has a hardcoded period of 0.5 ms. 
      gammaf_act Current fuel specific heat ratio. 
      gamma_N Specific heat ratio for natural gas (gamma). 
      gamma_P Specific heat ratio for LPG (gamma). 
      gamma_throttle Current mixture specific heat ratio at the throttle. 
      gas2gsln_overlap Time that the gasoline fuel injectors will start 
      injecting before the manifold is clear of gaseous fuel mixture on a 
      gaseous fuel to gasoline transition. 
      gas2gsln_slew Gaseous (LPG/NG) to gasoline slew in time 
      GasCarb_trim_mode Carburetor Fuel Trim Device Type (PWM Valve or MJ/EPR). 
      This switch is used to differentiate between PWM and continuous flow trim 
      device (EPR/DEPR) types. 
      Gen_calcs Generator power configuration 
      Gen_crct_real_pwr Generator corrected real power 
      gen_den_idle_src Selects whether the idle status used to increment the 
      continuous idle runtime is determined internally from the foot pedal input 
      or through receipt of an EEC2 CAN message. This source only applies to the 
      idle status used in general denominator incrementing.

      When “Automatic” is selected, at-idle status is determined internally. 
      This option should be used when a foot pedal input is present.

      When “EEC2 FPP1 at Idle” is selected, at-idle status is received from the 
      Accelerator Pedal 1 Low Idle Switch SPN in an EEC2 CAN message. 
      Gen_derate Generator manual power derate 
      Gen_freq Generator frequency in Hz 
      Gen_freq_src Generator frequency source 
      Gen_parasitic_pwr Generator parasitic power 
      Gen_PF Generator Power Factor 
      Gen_phase_amps Generator RMS current per phase [amps] 
      Gen_phase_volts Generator RMS volts per phase [volts] 
      Gen_real_pwr Generator Real power [kW] 
      Gen_total_pwr Generator Total power [kW] 
      Ginj_cs_active YES/NO indication that peak/hold injection cold start mode 
      is currently active 
      Ginj_cs_ect The engine coolant temperature (ECT) must be below this 
      threshold for the cold start functionality to be active. 
      Ginj_cs_ect_I2 The engine coolant temperature (ECT) must be below this 
      threshold for the cold start functionality to be active. 
      Ginj_cs_max_post This setting specifies the total number of post-run speed 
      injections that should use the higher peak current and extended peak 
      current hold time. This setting provides a way to extend these values for 
      a brief period after the engine starts to ensure all injectors have fully 
      opened.

      Post run-speed injections will only use the cold start peak current and 
      peak hold time if the number of pre-run speed injections did not exceed 
      the configured "Cold start max pre-running injections". 
      Ginj_cs_max_post_I2 This setting specifies the total number of post-run 
      speed injections that should use the higher peak current and extended peak 
      current hold time. This setting provides a way to extend these values for 
      a brief period after the engine starts to ensure all injectors have fully 
      opened.

      Post run-speed injections will only use the cold start peak current and 
      peak hold time if the number of pre-run speed injections did not exceed 
      the configured "Cold start max pre-running injections". 
      Ginj_cs_max_pre This setting controls the peak and hold injection cold 
      start functionality. When enabled if the ECT is below the threshold 
      defined by "Cold start ECT threshold" during engine start then:

      - The higher peak current specified by the "Cold start peak current 
      target" will be used during injection
      - The longer peak current hold time specified by the "Cold start peak 
      current hold time" will be used during injection

      Setting this value to 0 disables the cold start functionality. When set to 
      a value > 0 then up to this number of pre-run speed total injections will 
      use the higher peak current and extended peak current hold time. 
      Ginj_cs_max_pre_I2 This setting controls the peak and hold injection cold 
      start functionality. When enabled if the ECT is below the threshold 
      defined by "Cold start ECT threshold" during engine start then:

      - The higher peak current specified by the "Cold start peak current 
      target" will be used during injection
      - The longer peak current hold time specified by the "Cold start peak 
      current hold time" will be used during injection

      Setting this value to 0 disables the cold start functionality. When set to 
      a value > 0 then up to this number of pre-run speed total injections will 
      use the higher peak current and extended peak current hold time. 
      Ginj_cs_ptime The higher peak current hold time to use when cold start 
      mode is active 
      Ginj_cs_ptime_I2 The higher peak current hold time to use when cold start 
      mode is active 
      Ginj_ctrl_type Obsoleted parameter 
      Ginj_ctrl_type_I2 Obsoleted parameter 
      Ginj_peaka_avg Average actual peak-hold time 
      Ginj_peakd_avg Average desired peak-hold time 
      Ginj_peak_offset This setting specifies the elapsed time for the injector 
      to turn off from the peak current target as specified by the "Peak current 
      target" setting.

      For instances of short total pulse width injections this setting it used 
      to determine if the hold time should be skipped and the injector should be 
      instead just be turned off from the peak target current. Specifically, if 
      the effective total pulse width time is less than or equal to the peak 
      current hold time plus a small minimal setup time then the hold time will 
      be skipped. 
      Ginj_peak_offset_I2 This setting specifies the elapsed time for the 
      injector to turn off from the peak current target as specified by the 
      "Peak current target" setting. For instances of short total pulse width 
      injections this setting it used to determine if the hold time should be 
      skipped and the injector should be instead just be turned off from the 
      peak target current. Specifically, if the effective total pulse width time 
      is less than or equal to the peak current hold time plus a small minimal 
      setup time then the hold time will be skipped. 
      Ginj_peak_time Obsoleted parameter 
      Ginj_peak_time_I2 Obsoleted parameter 
      GLOW_active Glow output activity flag 
      GLOW_channel Glow output channel 
      GLOW_DC_max Maximum duty cycle for glow PWM output 
      GLOW_DC_min Minimum duty cycle for glow PWM output

      GLOW_pre_max_ms Post-glow timer, scheduled based on temperature before

      GLOW_pre_ms Pre-glow timer 
      GLOW_pre_time_max Pre-glow maximum timer (for delayed start after glow 
      lamp extinguished) 
      GLOW_pre_Vbat_low Lower limit for battery voltage to allow glow control 
      GLOW_shutoff_temp Shut-off temperature threshold for post-glow 
      GLOW_starter_pause Time to pause the glow output to allow for large 
      starter motor current in-rush 
      GLOW_starter_pause_ms Glow starter in-rush current pause timer 
      GLOW_state Maximum duty cycle for glow PWM output 
      GLOW_temp Glow control feedback temperature 
      GLOW_temp_input Temperature signal to use for glow control feedback 
      GLOW_time_max Maximum permitted glow time for combined pre- and post-glow 
      GLOW_type Glow device output type 
      GLOW_Vbat_high Upper limit for battery voltage to allow glow control 
      GLOW_voltage Target effective voltage for glow PWM output

      Gov3_odz Gov3 output deadzone value 
      Gov3_odz_tau Gov3 output deadzone time constant 
      Gov3_odz_wall Gov3 output deadzone wall, bidirectional 
      Gov3_rmt_ff_ena This switch enables a remotely triggered Gov3 feedforward. 
      The only supported trigger signal is from SPN 64867 in ECI PGN 65473. The 
      feature utilizes a single-shot trigger. When the remote signal transitions 
      from inactive to active, a feedforward value is added to Gov3's integral 
      accumulator. The signal must become inactive before another trigger event 
      is allowed. The feedforward value is calculated by interpolating the "Gov3 
      Remote Feedforward" table with the governor's trajectory target. 
      Gov3_rmt_ff_rpm_min The minimum Gov3 target speed allowed while the remote 
      feedforward signal is active. Only applicable when "Gov3 remote 
      feedforward mode" is not set to 'Disabled'. 
      Gov3_rpm Gov3 Discrete Governor engine speed setpoint 
      Gov3_spk_dzo Gov3 Spark Governor overshoot deadzone 
      Gov3_spk_dzu Gov3 Spark Governor undershoot deadzone 
      Gov3_spk_Kpo Gov3 Spark Governor overshoot gain 
      Gov3_spk_Kpu Gov3 Spark Governor undershoot gain 
      Gov3_spk_mxadv Gov3 Spark Governor max advance 
      Gov3_spk_mxret Gov3 Spark Governor max retard 
      Gov3_TPSLP Discrete Gov3 TPS Low pass time constant 
      GovMax_rpm Loadlimit adjusted max governor 
      gov_app_mode If set to 'Stationary', discrete speed governing modes 
      requiring a vehicle-interlock for safety are bypassed.

      If set to 'Vehicle, neutral required', the vehicle-interlock safety 
      conditions (using the options below) are required at any roadspeed.

      If set to 'Vehicle, neutral required if stationary', vehicle-interlock 
      safety conditions (using the options below) are required only while the 
      vehicle is stopped. Additionally, the multi-function input will be used 
      for the PTO up to the roadspeed cruise minimum speed. 
      gov_auth_max Governor current maximum load authority 
      gov_eng_load_d Governor current desired engine load 
      gov_gain_aux_cfg When "Governor gain selection aux input" is not set to 
      'Disabled', this parameter determines which gains are active. When 
      configured as '+V = Aux Gains', the auxiliary input gain selections are 
      used when input is connected to +V. When configured as 'GND = Aux Gains', 
      the auxiliary input gain selections are used when input is grounded. 
      Otherwise, the default fuel-based gain selections are used. 
      gov_gain_aux_chan This parameter allows the governor gains to be switched 
      via an auxiliary digital input (Aux DIG). When not set to 'Disabled', the 
      input can switch the governor gains between the default fuel type gain 
      selections and the auxiliary input gain selections. 
      gov_gain_gsln Gasoline Fuel Based Gov Gain selection (Standard Gains or 
      Alternate Gains) 
      gov_gain_gsln_aux Gasoline fuel-based governor gain selection when 
      auxiliary input is used. 
      gov_gain_gsln_auxdis Gasoline fuel-based discrete governor gain selection 
      when auxiliary input is used. 
      gov_gain_gsln_dis Gasoline mode governor gains discrete 
      gov_gain_LPG LPG Fuel Based Gov Gain selection (Standard Gains or 
      Alternate Gains) 
      gov_gain_LPG_aux LPG fuel-based governor gain selection when auxiliary 
      input is used. 
      gov_gain_LPG_auxdis LPG fuel-based discrete governor gain selection when 
      auxiliary input is used. 
      gov_gain_LPG_dis LPG mode governor gains discrete 
      gov_gain_man governor gain source - 0=automatic table lookup, 1=manual 
      gov_gain_NG NG Fuel Based Gov Gain selection (Standard Gains or Alternate 
      Gains)

      is used. 
      gov_gain_NG_auxdis NG fuel-based discrete governor gain selection when 
      auxiliary input is used.

      gov_gain_slct Governor min/max gain schedule selection - 0=std1, 1=alt1, 
      2=std2, 3=alt2

      gov_MAPdt_d Desired MAPdt 
      gov_MAP_d Governor desired MAP 
      gov_max_abslimit The absolute maximum upper speed bound for all governor 
      systems. 
      gov_min_abslimit The absolute minimum lower speed bound for all governor 
      systems. 
      gov_mode Active governor type (None, Droop, and/or Isochronous) 
      gov_nomld_ECTadd Nominal droop governor load ECT based adder 
      gov_ntrlock_chan (For vehicle governing applications only)
      If IVS is selected, the IVS must be off-idle while the FPP is at idle to 
      allow engagement of discrete speed governing modes. If the foot brake 
      input is selected, the foot brake input must be valid before allowing 
      secondary discrete speed governing modes.

      If the 'Neut/Park/Secondary' option is selected, the secondary speed 
      control input and/or the transmission neutral/park safety inputs are used 
      for validation.

      NOTE: The Neut/Park switch must ALWAYS be satisfied if it is enabled, in 
      addition to any secondary setting specified by this parameter. The same is 
      true for the secondary speed switch. This allows for redundant validation 
      of the vehicle interlock. 
      gov_ntrlock_fail IVS/Brake/Trans-Park interlock failure diagnostic - 
      interlock failure persistent period entry condition 
      gov_rpmd_effective Effective rpm target for the current gov_type_engaged 
      mode. Set to the current engine speed (rpm) when gov_type is No Gov 
      Active/Selected 
      gov_rs_ena When the Max Governor is the controlling governor, these 
      multipliers will be used to adjust the governor gains based on the current 
      road speed. The Max Governor "TPS low-pass" time is also adjusted based on 
      the current road speed. 
      Gov_start_wait Value is only applicable when "Gov1/2/3 delay from start 
      mode" is set to 'Time-based'. 
      gov_strt_wait_mode This parameter determines the delay before Gov1, Gov2, 
      or Gov3 can become active after a start.

      When set to 'Time-based', the "Gov1/2/3 delay from start" value is used as 
      the delay.

      When set to 'Warm up complete', the warm-up phase must be completed (hold 
      time elapsed, engine coolant warmed up, and oil temperature warmed up). 
      The "Starting initial speed mode" must be set to 'ECT Table-Based + Warm 
      Up' to use the 'Warm up complete' mode. 
      gov_switchover_time Parameter configures the time allowed to switch the 
      active governor (gov_type). When set to '50 ms (Legacy)', a switch between 
      governors can take up to ~50 ms. When set to '5 ms', the governor will 
      switch in 5 ms. Governors include Min Gov, Max Gov, Gov1, Gov2, and Gov3. 
      Gov_sw_debounce Governor switch digital input debounce - Time to validate 
      the state of the Gov1/2 digital inputs. 
      gov_sw_state Current governor selected switch state (precursor to gov_type 
      being defined) 
      gov_TPSd_TM_calc governor computed TPS for the desired engine conditions 
      in fraction 
      gov_type Current selected governor (None, Gov1/2/3, Min Gov, and/or Max 
      Gov) 
      gov_type_engaged Engaged governor type. 
      GPS_Edot GPS east velocity 
      GPS_ENspeed GPS supplied East-North plane true ground speed 
      GPS_ENZdot_st GPS speed state (Offline, Valid, Error, Disconnected, 
      Unacquired) 
      GPS_ENZdot_tmr GPS speed info wait timer 
      GPS_Ndot GPS north velocity 
      gsln2gas_overlap Time that the gasoline fuel injectors will continue to 
      inject once gaseous fuel mixture has reached the intake ports on a 
      gasoline to gaseous fuel transition. 
      Gtap_1tap_rpm This the amount the tap up/down speed setpoint will change 
      immediately following 1 button press. 
      Gtap_ena This switch controls the tap up/down speed control system. 
      Gtap_engaged Logical indicating Tap Up/Tap Down system is attempting to 
      set engine speed 
      Gtap_max_rpm This is the upper bound for the speed tap up/down function. 
      Gtap_min_rpm This is the lower bound and initial value for the speed tap 
      up/down function. Additionally, when both up and down buttons are pressed, 
      the engine speed will change immediately to this value. 
      Gtap_ramp_delay When either tap up/down button is held down, this is the 
      wait time (following the governor switch debounce time and "set minimum" 
      debounce time) before the speed will begin continuous ramping. 
      Gtap_ramp_final When either tap up/down button is held down, this is the 
      amount of time (following the delay time) during which the speed ramp rate 
      will be increased from zero to the full ramp rate value. 
      Gtap_ramp_phase When either tap up/down button is held down, this is the 
      amount of time (following the delay time) during which the speed ramp rate 
      will be increased from zero to the full ramp rate value. 
      Gtap_rpm Tap Up/Tap Down target rpm setting 
      Gtap_rpmmin_adjust If engine speed is below this limit, tap up/down 
      setpoint adjustment is disabled. Set this value to '0' to allow tap 
      up/down setpoint adjustments under all conditions. 
      Gtap_setmin_wait Additional debounce time for the Gov1 and Gov2 inputs. A 
      nonzero time here allows the system time to validate a simultaneous Gov1 
      and Gov2 button press without regard to which button is pressed first. 
      However, if nonzero, the tap up/down system will wait the specified time 
      before accepting either input as ON. 
      HBA_ctl_cmd HBA output drive command 
      HBA_ctl_max HBridge A PWM DC max limit 
      HBA_ctl_min HBridge A PWM DC min limit 
      HBA_device_status HBA device status 
      HBA_fault_Ilim HBA drive current high diagnostic: HBA electrical model 
      current upper limit entry condition 
      HBA_FB_cmd_LP LPF timer constant used for HBridge A or B Smart Actuator 
      output 
      HBA_iFB_amps HBA current feedback (amps) 
      HBA_iFB_raw HBA current feedback (raw volts) 
      HBA_output_Hz The H-bridge output has a lower-limit of approximately 310 
      Hz in full-bridge mode, and 1 Hz in half-bridge mode. NOTE: Frequencies 
      above 4 KHz must be approved by EControls Engineering to avoid excessive 
      H-bridge driver heating. 
      HBA_output_invert HBridge A Switch that allows for output inversion. 

      Example: -100 percent DC inverted = +100 percent DC. For a smart coil, 
      inversion results in 0 percent DC => +100 percent DC. 
      HBA_output_type Select the type of drive output. Generally, this should 
      always be set to fullbridge mode. However, if a smart throttle (or 
      similar) actuator is present, smart halfbridge mode will output a 
      commanded position as a 0-100% dutycycle on the + leg of the Hbridge 
      output, without implementing a closed loop position control algorithm. The 
      throttle feedback is still available, and faults will still function 
      normally. The (dumb) halfbridge mode can be used to output a 0-100% full 
      closed loop output on the + leg of the Hbridge output. 
      HBA_pot1_closed_EE HBA PS1 idle/closed 
      HBA_pot1_open_EE HBA PS1 full/open 
      HBA_pot2_closed_EE HBA PS2 idle/closed 
      HBA_pot2_open_EE HBA PS2 full/open 
      HBA_spring_0 HBA - actuator spring load at 0% 
      HBA_spring_100 HBA - actuator spring load at 100% 
      HBA_toggle_cmd1 H-Bridge Manual Modes: HBA toggle command 1 
      HBA_toggle_cmd2 H-Bridge Manual Modes: HBA toggle command 2 
      HBA_toggle_ena H-Bridge Manual Modes: HBA toggle enable switch 
      HBA_toggle_ms H-Bridge Manual Modes: HBA toggle period 
      HBA_Vcomp_max HBA voltage compensation max - This is the maximum voltage 
      for the voltage compensation correction. Voltages >= this voltage will not 
      result in a further reduction in the HB control drive beyond min/max. Set 
      max=min to eliminate voltage compensation. 
      HBA_Vcomp_min HBA voltage compensation min/std - This is the 
      standard/minimum voltage for the voltage compensation correction. Voltages 
      <= this voltage will not result in a change in the HB control drive. 
      HBB_ctl_cmd HBB output drive command 
      HBB_ctl_max HBridge B PWM DC max limit 
      HBB_ctl_min HBridge B PWM DC min limit 
      HBB_device_status HBB device status 
      HBB_fault_Ilim HBB drive current high diagnostic: HBB electrical model 
      current upper limit entry condition 
      HBB_FB_cmd_LP HBB command - "smart" feedback time constant 
      HBB_iFB_amps HBB current feedback (amps) 
      HBB_iFB_raw HBB current feedback (raw volts) 
      HBB_output_Hz The H-bridge output has a lower-limit of approximately 310 
      Hz in full-bridge mode, and 1 Hz in half-bridge mode. NOTE: Frequencies 
      above 4 KHz must be approved by EControls Engineering to avoid excessive 
      H-bridge driver heating. 
      HBB_output_invert HBridge B Switch that allows for output inversion. 

      Example: -100 percent DC inverted = +100 percent DC. For a smart coil, 
      inversion results in 0 percent DC => +100 percent DC. 
      HBB_output_type Select the type of drive output. Generally, this should 
      always be set to fullbridge mode. However, if a smart throttle (or 
      similar) actuator is present, smart halfbridge mode will output a 
      commanded position as a 0-100% dutycycle on the + leg of the Hbridge 
      output, without implementing a closed loop position control algorithm. The 
      throttle feedback is still available, and faults will still function 
      normally. The (dumb) halfbridge mode can be used to output a 0-100% full 
      closed loop output on the + leg of the Hbridge output. 
      HBB_pot1_closed_EE HBB PS1 idle/closed 
      HBB_pot1_open_EE HBB PS1 full/open 
      HBB_pot2_closed_EE HBB PS2 idle/closed 
      HBB_pot2_open_EE HBB PS2 full/open 
      HBB_spring_0 HBB - actuator spring load at 0% 
      HBB_spring_100 HBB - actuator spring load at 100% 
      HBB_toggle_cmd1 H-Bridge Manual Modes: HBB toggle command 1 
      HBB_toggle_cmd2 H-Bridge Manual Modes: HBB toggle command 2 
      HBB_toggle_ena H-Bridge Manual Modes: HBB toggle enable switch 
      HBB_toggle_ms H-Bridge Manual Modes: HBB toggle period 
      HBB_Vcomp_max HBB voltage compensation max - This is the maximum voltage 
      for the voltage compensation correction. Voltages >= this voltage will not 
      result in a further reduction in the HB control drive beyond min/max. Set 
      max=min to eliminate voltage compensation. 
      HBB_Vcomp_min HBB voltage compensation min/std - This is the 
      standard/minimum voltage for the voltage compensation correction. Voltages 
      <= this voltage will not result in a change in the HB control drive. 
      Hbridge_power H-Bridge power source 
      HEX_CCP_oem_key CCP OEM level override for seed/key 
      HEX_CCP_svc_key CCP service center level override for seed/key 
      HEX_F201_ids List the CCP Addresses for the scalar values (or table 
      elements) 
      HEX_FSS_DID_tbl Enter the data identifiers (DIDs) to include in an ISO 
      14229-1 UDS Fault Snap Shot. Format each DID as four hexadecimal digits 
      (example: FD03). To include SAE J1979 PIDs (F4xx) in the Fault Snap Shot, 
      use the "FSS PIDs" table instead, as PIDs are not supported in this table. 
      Fault Snap Shots will include both PIDs from the "FSS PIDs" table and DIDs 
      from this table.

      The first occurrence of 0 in this table will signify the end of the DID 
      list. 
      HEX_FSS_PID_tbl Enter the J1979 PIDs to include in a 14229 UDS Fault Snap 
      Shot. Use this list to select a static set of PIDs to be included in each 
      Fault Snap Shot. If the first entry of this list is 0, the Snap Shot PIDs 
      will be dynamically selected based on operating conditions when the Snap 
      Shot is created. The PID values should be entered using hex digits 05 
      (ECT), 0C (RPM), 6B (EGRT), etc. from SAE J1979. 
      HEX_MILblk_def_code Flash Code Blink Configuration: Default first code 
      (always output) 
      HEX_UDS_oem_key UDS OEM level override for seed/key 
      HEX_UDS_svc_key UDS service center level override for seed/key 
      HG_gov_ena Max governor control (Disabled, Droop, or Isochronous) 
      HiDiagTemp_wait ECT too high to enable diagnostics diagnostic: minimum 
      run-time entry condition 
      HM_hours engine hour-meter in hours 
      HM_MIL_hours MIL on-time in hours 
      HM_MIL_seconds MIL on-time in seconds 
      HM_offset_write Hour meter/starts offset write 
      HM_RAMr_seconds Raw (non-offset) hour meter 
      HM_RAMr_starts Raw (non-offset) hour cumulative starts 
      HM_RAM_seconds engine hour-meter in seconds including offset 
      HM_RAM_starts total number of engine starts 
      HM_seconds_hst Software version history hour meters 
      HM_sec_offset Hour meter offset 
      HM_start_offset Cumulative starts offset 
      HSDL_at_ecipp_index Specifies the ECIPP index of the variable whose value 
      should initiate auto-triggering of high speed data logger data collection. 

      HSDL_at_mode Selects the desired high speed data logger auto-trigger mode. 
      If "Disables" auto-triggering is disables and data collection must be 
      initiated manually. If "Rising edge" is selected data collection will 
      automatically begin when the selected auto-trigger ECIPP variable value 
      rises above the selected auto-trigger target. If "Falling edge" is 
      selected data collection will automatically begin when the selected 
      auto-trigger ECIPP variable value falls past the selected auto-trigger 
      target. 
      HSDL_at_target_type This is an internal variable used to provide 
      auto-trigger ECIPP variable's data type to the target device to facilitate 
      auto-triggering value comparison. 
      HSDL_at_target_val Specifies the target value at which auto-triggering of 
      high speed data logger data collection will occur. 
      HSDL_buffer1 High Speed Data Logger buffer 1 
      HSDL_buffer2 High Speed Data Logger buffer 2 
      HSDL_buffer3 High Speed Data Logger buffer 3 
      HSDL_buffer4 High Speed Data Logger buffer 4 
      HSDL_buffer_size Number of HSDL samples to collect, latched when HSDL is 
      initialized or reset 
      HSDL_buffer_sizerqst Number of samples to collect using the High-Speed 
      Data Logger 
      HSDL_custom_max1 High Speed Data Logger custom parameter 1 max value 
      HSDL_custom_max2 High Speed Data Logger custom parameter 2 max value

      HstIBF_LT_total Total intake backfire events logged in lifetime 2D 
      histogram. When histogram is cleared, this variable is also cleared to 0.

      intake backfire histograms were cleared. 
      HstIBF_total Total intake backfire events logged in recent 2D histogram. 
      When histogram is cleared, this variable is also cleared to 0. 
      HstSL_expTbl Speed-load histogram data. 
      HstSL_expTbl_RPM Current RPM axis divisions for speed-load histogram

      default values 
      HWARNblk_off A hard warning may cause a continuous output activation or a 
      blinking/pulsing output. The on/off times specify this behavior. For a 
      continuously on output in an active state, simply set the offtime to zero 
      and the ontime to any value. 
      HWARNblk_on A hard warning may cause a continuous output activation or a 
      blinking/pulsing output. The on/off times specify this behavior. For a 
      continuous output in an active state, simply set the offtime to zero and 
      the ontime to any value. 
      HWARNblk_open_off Hard warning open-output transfer Blink/Pulse off-time 
      (ms) 
      HWARNblk_open_on Hard warning open-output transfer Blink/Pulse on-time 
      (ms) 
      HWARNchan_open This switch controls which output pin will be actuated when 
      a hard warning is triggered and the normal hard-warning output is detected 
      to be open. If the MIL, soft, and hard warning channels are set or 
      transferred to the same output, MIL functionality receives the highest 
      priority and soft warning functionality receives the lowest priority. 
      HWARNfcn Hard warning function status (Disconnected, Idle off, MIL, Hard 
      warning, Soft warning, Audible alert) 
      HWARNout_mirror Hard warning output pin 
      HWARN_bulbchk This is the time that the hard warning output will remain on 
      following an initial keyon/enginestopped event to allow the operator to 
      observe that the output (bulb) is functioning. 
      HWARN_bulbon Hard Warning Output Bulp-Check Config - Determines whether 
      the warning output will be continuously on or blinked/pulsed during the 
      key-on bulb check period. 
      HWARN_chan This switch controls which output pin will be actuated when a 
      hard warning is triggered. A selection of 'None' will not control an 
      output pin, but will continue to communicate a hard warning over the 
      various communications links. In particular, the J1939 'Stop' lamp 
      indication will be on during an active hard warning condition. If the soft 
      and hard warning channels are set to the same output, hard warning 
      functionality (blinking or continuous) takes precedence during an active 
      hard warning. 
      HWARN_lamp Output lamp associated with hardwarning faults. 
      HW_delta_raw Obsoleted parameter 
      HW_nominal_raw Obsoleted parameter 
      IACflw_active This indicates the current activity (control) state of the 
      idle follower function. 
      IACflw_cmd Current command IAC throttle follower position. 
      IACflw_cmd_0 Idle Air Control throttle follower schedule - commanded IAC% 
      point 0 
      IACflw_cmd_1 Idle Air Control throttle follower schedule - commanded IAC% 
      point 1 
      IACflw_dec This is the maximum rate at which the throttle-follower will 
      decrease the IAC commanded position. 
      IACflw_ena This switch controls the IAC throttle follower system. 
      IACflw_FPP_0 IAC throttle follower schedule in terms of FPP (TPS) position 
      versus commanded IAC position. 
      IACflw_FPP_1 Idle Air Control throttle follower schedule - FPP% point 1 
      IACflw_inc This is the maximum rate at which the throttle-follower will 
      increase the IAC commanded position. 
      IAC_act_sgnpct Idle Air Control actual position (%) 
      IAC_cmd_pct Idle Air Control commanded position (%) 
      IAC_faultstat Idle Air Control test status 
      IAC_full_req 1=request fullopen sequence, 2=pending, 3=complete, 0=reset 
      IAC_home_int_min During homing, the step rate will be nominally increased 
      by 50% to prevent bouncing off of the hard stop. In addition, the step 
      rate must be at least this long regardless of the value of the actual step 
      rate * 1.5. 
      IAC_home_req 1=request home sequence, 2=pending, 3=complete, 0=reset 
      IAC_Ilearn_drpm During active IAC control for min governing (and inactive 
      throttle-follower control), this delta-rpm tolerance will be used to 
      validate learning the current min governor integrator value for the IAC. 
      IAC_Ilearn_tau During validated active IAC control for min governing (and 
      inactive throttle-follower control), this low-pass time constant will be 
      used to average the current min governor integrator into the learn value. 
      IAC_min_gov_pct Current command IAC position from the PID min governor. 
      IAC_pwr_ena Idle Air Control driver power status 
      IAC_step_a Idle Air Control actual step position 
      IAC_step_d Idle Air Control desired step position 
      IAC_step_home This is the number of steps in the closed direction (a 
      positive number) that the IAC will traverse during the homing sequence. 
      IAC_step_int Idle Air Control desired stepping interval 
      IAC_step_max The maximum allowed step position for the IAC if the actual 
      home location is 0. This is the 100% commanded position. 
      IAC_step_min The minimum allowed step position for the IAC if the actual 
      home location is 0. This is the 0% commanded position. 
      IAC_step_park This is the parked location of the stepper prior to 
      power-down of the ECM/driver. 
      IAC_Vbat_min Below this battery voltage, all IAC stepping will be frozen 
      until the voltage returns to a higher level. 
      IAT Intake Air Temperature 
      IATdt Time derivative of intake air temperature. 
      IATdt_key_cyc_max Maximum time derivative of intake air temperature for 
      the current key cycle. 
      IATs Standard operating Intake Air Temperature 
      IAT_analog_cfg IAT configuration 
      IAT_def Default Intake Air Temperature value 
      IAT_ena Intake air temperature (IAT) sensor input channel selection. If 
      this input is set to 'Disabled', the default IAT value will be used as a 
      constant.

      When set to 'Aux PUD3', the ECM hardware must have a 22.1K pullup on Aux 
      PUD3. Likewise, the IAT's pullup configuration must be set to '22.1K ohms 
      (fixed)'. The pullup's value is not software-selectable or auto-detected. 
      IAT_HiExp IAT higher than expected 1 diagnostic: IAT upper limit threshold 

      IAT_HiExp2 IAT higher than expected 2 diagnostic: IAT upper limit 
      threshold 
      IAT_HiExp2_mdota_min Minimum air mass flow threshold for the "IAT higher 
      than expected 2" diagnostic. 
      IAT_HiExp2_rpm IAT higher than expected 2 diagnostic: RPM entry condition 
      IAT_HiExp_FSOdis When set to YES, disables IAT higher than expected 1 and 
      2 faults when fuel shut off is active. 
      IAT_HiExp_mdota_min Minimum air mass flow threshold for the "IAT higher 
      than expected 1" diagnostic. 
      IAT_HiExp_rpm IAT higher than expected 1 diagnostic: RPM entry condition 
      IAT_HiExp_wait IAT higher than expected 1/2 diagnostics: run-time wait 
      entry condition 
      IAT_maxv IAT high voltage diagnostic: IAT voltage upper limit threshold 
      IAT_minv IAT low voltage diagnostic: IAT voltage lower limit threshold 
      IAT_raw IAT signal raw volts 
      IAT_vdr Intake Air Temperature signal calibration pullup resistor 
      resistance 
      IAT_vdr_slct Intake Air Temperature (IAT) pullup resistor selection.

      When the IAT source is configured as 'Standard Input' or 'Aux PU3':
      If ECM hardware supports a software-selectable IAT pullup, then this 
      parameter configures the pullup's value. If the ECM does not support a 
      software-selectable IAT pullup, then the pullup's value is automatically 
      determined by the ECM and this parameter is ignored.

      When IAT source is configured as 'Aux PUD3':
      The ECM hardware must have a 22.1K pullup on Aux PUD3. Likewise, this 
      parameter must be set to '22.1K ohms (fixed)'. The pullup's value is not 
      software-selectable or auto-detected. 
      IBF_action_request Intake backfire action request. Ability to reset both 
      of the recent 1D and 2D intake backfire histograms. 
      IBF_fault_events Number of intake backfire events required to latch the 
      "Intake backfire detected" fault. 
      IBF_fault_hours Timeframe in operating hours used to monitor for intake 
      backfire events when updating the "Intake backfire detected" fault. 
      IBF_IATdt_lim Specifies the IAT derivative threshold for detecting an 
      intake backfire. Value should be higher than any other possible 
      temperature effects on the intake air temperature. This parameter is only 
      used if "Intake backfire detection mode" is set to "IATdt". 
      IBF_latch_tm Latch time for detecting an intake backfire. This parameter 
      is only used if "Intake backfire detection mode" is set to "IATdt" or 
      "MAP". 
      IBF_MAP_lim Specifies the MAP threshold for detecting an intake backfire. 
      Value should be higher than any possible barometric pressure or engine 
      rock-back effect at shutdown. This parameter is only used if "Intake 
      backfire detection mode" is set to "MAP". 
      IBF_mode Intake backfire detection mode. When set to "Disabled", intake 
      backfire detection and logging is disabled. When set to "IATdt", an intake 
      backfire is detected when IATdt exceeds "Intake backfire IATdt limit". 
      When set to "MAP", an intake backfire is detected when rMAP exceeds 
      "Intake backfire MAP limit". "IATdt" should be used for boosted engines; 
      "MAP" should be used for naturally aspirated engines. 
      IBF_unlatch_tm Unlatch time for detecting an intake backfire. This 
      parameter is only used if "Intake backfire detection mode" is set to 
      "IATdt" or "MAP". 
      ICam_coil_Id Cam1 coil desired current 
      ICam_coil_Imax Intake cam coil max current 
      ICam_coil_Imin Intake cam coil min current 
      ICam_coil_Inom Icam nominal current. Used when ECam_control_cal = Intake / 
      Cam1

      Intake / Cam1
