      J1939_mdot_f_ports J1939 engine fuel rate 
      J1939_MIL_ena This switch determines the MIL status in the J1939_lamps 
      portion of the DM messages. If disabled, all J1939 MIL indications will be 
      '0'. Standard practice is to leave this feature enabled. 
      J1939_MIL_mode This switch determines the MIL status in the J1939_lamps 
      DM1 message portion during a key-on/engine-stopped condition. Standard 
      practice is to indicate that the MIL is on continuously in this state. 
      Alternatively, the MIL can only be indicated as continuously on or 
      blinking off every 5 seconds in this state if there are stored fault codes 
      in the system. This switch has no impact on the hardware pin controlled 
      MIL output on the ECM. 
      J1939_MIL_state MIL state as reported over J1939 
      J1939_NG_Vdot_ratio Ratio of gaseous NG to LNG for the fuel volume (Liters 
      per hour) reported in the J1939 LFE PGN and ISO 15031 PIDs and 14229 DIDs. 
      See 'J1939 engine fuel rate mode' for more information.

      LNG applications should set this value to 600 or 610. 
      J1939_PGN_tout List of EControls cal 16-bit decimal PGNs to be monitored 
      for timeout by the custom J1939 PGN timeout faults. These values are not 
      necessarily the same as the actual J1939 PGNs seen on the CAN bus. See 4G 
      CAN documentation spreadsheet for details.

      A value of 65535 disables the corresponding fault. 
      J1939_PGN_tout_keytm This is the time after a key on condition is detected 
      that a failure to receive the specified PGN will cause the timeout faults 
      below to latch.

      If this value is set to 0, key state will be ignored and a minimum key on 
      time will not need before the faults are able to latch. 
      J1939_PGN_tout_runtm This is the time after an engine run condition is 
      detected that a failure to receive the specified PGN will cause the 
      timeout faults below to latch.

      If this value is set to 0, engine run state will be ignored and the faults 
      will be able to latch even if the engine is not running. 
      J1939_RC_SA_ena This selection determines the source address(es) for PGN 
      65249 (Retarder Configuration) messages:
      - Default: the RC PGN Source Address will be the ECU address
      - Engine Retarder (15): the RC PGN Source Address will be 15
      - Exhaust Retarder (41): the RC PGN Source Address will be 41
      - Both + torque curves: the RC PG will be sent from Source Address 15 when 
      ECI PGN 42350 is in the "Supported Tx PGN List", and sent from Source 
      Address 41 when ECI PGN 42349 is in the "Supported Tx PGN List". 
      Additionally, the torque curve SPN's will be set according to the engine 
      retarder and exhaust retarder tables for the current fuel type. (For all 
      other selections, the torque curve SPN's are reported as Not Available.) 
      J1939_rc_torque_ref This is the 'reference torque' used in the J1939 
      'Retarder Configuration' (RC) PG used as a scale basis for the torque 
      curve delivered in this packet. It MUST be greater than or equal to the 
      highest torque entered in the retarder torque range calibration below. In 
      general, it should always be at least 20% higher than the highest torque. 
      J1939_reload J1939 CAN1 refresh 
      J1939_reload2 J1939 CAN2 refresh 
      J1939_reload3 J1939 CAN3 refresh 
      J1939_retard_actv Indicates the status of the transmission retarder, as 
      reported by J1939 SPN 520, 900, or 1715 in the ERC1 message. 
      J1939_RSsetpt_loss J1939 ETC message loss while in-gear diagnostic: This 
      is the time after an engine run condition is detected that a failure to 
      receive an electronic (network) throttle position command message with the 
      transmission engaged in a forward or reverse gear will cause this fault to 
      begin setting validation. 
      J1939_Rx2Fail CAN2 Rx failure diagnostic: failure count threshold 
      J1939_Rx3Fail CAN3 Rx failure diagnostic: failure count threshold 
      J1939_RxFail CAN1 Rx failure diagnostic: failure count threshold 
      J1939_SOFT_mode This parameter should only be modified as directed by 
      EControls. 
      J1939_spark_KV CD spark KV in block order for transmission over J1939. 
      J1939_static_pwr If set to a non-zero value, specifies a fixed value to be 
      transmitted for the Engine Rated Power SPN in the EEC4 J1939 message. When 
      this setting is left at its default value of 0, the rated power will be 
      calculated normally by the ECM torque/power estimation system. 
      J1939_torque_pct_tbl This selection determines the value broadcast in SPN 
      92 'Engine Percent Load at Current Speed.' The default is governor tables, 
      which is determined from the MAP full-load/no-load table used for 
      governing. If the engine torque estimation table below is fully 
      calibrated, select 'J1939 Torque Tables, Indicated %'. The governor load 
      table provides a reasonable estimate (though it will have error near the 
      no-load/full-load endpoints) if the table below has not been calibrated. 
      For naturally aspirated engines, select 'J1939 Torque Tables, Indicated %, 
      Baro Corrected' to correct the torque estimate for altitude. The 'J1939 
      Torque Tables, Net %' and 'J1939 Torque Tables, Net %, Baro Corrected' 
      options exist only for backwards compatibility and should not be used. 
      J1939_TP_BAM This switch optionally enables TP.BAM (broadcast) for all 
      J1939 Transport Protocol (TP) messages. 

      If disabled, TP.BAM or TP.CM messages are selected per the SAE J1939-21 
      specification and the contents of the received PGN request. 
      J1939_TP_mod This switch selects which modifications to the
      CAN ID should be made when sending J1939 Transport Protocol (TP) messages.
      This includes TP.CM and TP.DT messages.The CAN priority for J1939 TP 
      messages can be set to 6 instead of the J1939-21 standard priority 7. 
      J1939_TSC1_loss This is the time after an engine run condition is detected 
      that a failure to receive a TSC1 message will cause this fault to begin 
      setting validation. 
      J1939_TSC1_loss_mode Specifies how to handle TSC1 messages after the 
      "J1939 TSC1 message receipt lost" fault has latched.

      If "Normal" is selected, then TSC1 message handling does not change after 
      the fault latches.

      If "Negative torque requests and negative torque limits" is selected, then 
      after the fault latches:
      - Speed requests: ignored
      - Torque requests: Only negative torque permitted
      - Speed limits: ignored
      - Torque limits: Only zero and negative torque permitted

      If "Negative torque requests and all torque/speed limits" is selected, 
      then after the fault latches:
      - Speed requests: ignored
      - Torque requests: Only negative torque permitted
      - Speed limits: permitted
      - Torque limits: permitted

      J1939_TSC1_mode Select the J1939 TSC1 prioritization scheme for handling 
      multiple valid TSC1 requests. The default option uses the most recent 
      message and ignores previous messages. The lowest-limit option is a 
      modified version of Figure SPN695_A in J1939-71 Instead of defaulting to 
      the oldest message, this option takes the minimum speed limit and minimum 
      torque limit and from all valid messages and implements them 
      simultaneously. The following approach is used:

      1. The highest priority (SPN 897) messages are accepted. If a lower 
      priority message is valid at the same time as a higher priority message, 
      it is discarded completely.
      2. If any message requests speed control and remote speed requests (above) 
      is set to 'Full Authority', speed control mode becomes active. The target 
      speed is the lowest speed from all valid speed control or speed limit 
      requests. A torque limit can be simultaneously applied using the lowest 
      torque control or torque limit request from all valid messages.
      3. If any message requests torque control and torque control requests 
      (above) is set to 'Full Authority', torque control becomes active. The 
      target torque value is the lowest torque from all valid torque control or 
      torque limit requests. A speed limit can be simultaneously applied using 
      the lowest speed limit from all valid speed limit messages.
      4. Simultaneous speed/limit requests using the lowest speed/torque limit 
      values. 
      J1939_TSC1_P1_ena Parameter configures the arbitration method and usage of 
      TSC1 messages with a P1 control purpose. P1 messages are identified by SPN 
      3350 set to a value of 0 and are intended for control of the accelerator 
      pedal. When parameter is set to 'Disabled', then received P1 TSC1 messages 
      are arbitrated with all other P32 messages and considered temporary 
      powertrain control.

      When set to 'Enabled - Verification Optional' or 'Enabled - Verification 
      Required', then P1 messages are excluded from normal arbitration. Instead, 
      P1 messages with a torque control request are converted to a foot-pedal 
      percentage and stored into FPP1_pct. If multiple messages are received, 
      then the lowest torque is selected. P1 messages with a control mode not 
      equal to torque control (value of 2) are discarded. Requested torque 
      values <= 0% will result in FPP1_pct = 0%. The following calibration is 
      required:
      - "Primary foot pedal mode" is set to 'Network Throttle'
      - "Secondary foot pedal mode" is set to 'Disabled'
      - "Dual pot pedal" is set to 'Disabled'.

      The term "verification" refers to verification of the TSC1 message in 
      accordance with SPN 4206 and SPN 4207. When parameter is set to 'Enabled - 
      Verification Required', then the message checksum and counter must be 
      received (not equal to 0xff). If the SPNs are not received or not valid, 
      then message is discarded. When parameter is set to 'Enabled - 
      Verification Optional', then SPN 4206 and 4207 are only checked if they 
      are received and their associated diagnostics are enabled.

      All FPP modifications/filtering are still available to use if desired, 
      such as: idle/full valid deadzones, dashpot filtering, slew-rate limiting, 
      non-linear mapping, FPP Unidirectional Filtering (FUF), cubic deadzone 
      limiting, etc. However, enabling the idle/full deadzones or non-linear 
      mapping will result in the engine controlling to a different steady-state 
      torque than what was requested by the P1 message.

      Only specific TSC1 messages support SPN 3350. See CAN documentation. 
      J1939_TSC1_P2_ena Parameter configures the arbitration method and usage of 
      TSC1 messages with a P2 control purpose. P2 messages are identified by SPN 
      3350 set to a value of 1 and are intended for cruise control. When 
      parameter is set to 'Disabled', then any received P2 TSC1 messages are 
      arbitrated with all other P32 messages and considered temporary powertrain 
      control.

      When set to 'Enabled - Verification Optional' or 'Enabled - Verification 
      Required', then P2 messages are excluded from normal arbitration. Instead, 
      P2 messages with a torque control request are converted to a engine load 
      percentage and stored into RMT_P2_load. If multiple P2 messages are 
      received, then the lowest torque is selected. P2 messages with a control 
      mode not equal to torque control (value of 2) are discarded. Requested 
      torque values <= 0% will result in 0% engine load. To use the P2 messages, 
      "Roadspeed cruise control device" must be set to 'External - P2 Torque 
      Control' on the Roadspeed worksheet. See "Roadspeed cruise control device" 
      for more details. When cruise control is enabled (RSC_enabled) and a valid 
      P2 torque control message is received, then cruise control will engage and 
      RMT_P2_load will be stored into the min FPP governor (RS_min_FPP).

      The term "verification" refers to verification of the TSC1 message in 
      accordance with SPN 4206 and SPN 4207. When parameter is set to 'Enabled - 
      Verification Required', then the message checksum and counter must be 
      received (not equal to 0xff). If the SPNs are not received or not valid, 
      then message is discarded. When parameter is set to 'Enabled - 
      Verification Optional', then SPN 4206 and 4207 are only checked if they 
      are received and their associated diagnostics are enabled.

      Only specific TSC1 messages support SPN 3350 (ECI SPN 3349). See CAN 
      documentation. 
      J1939_TSC1_pre_filt Parameter configures pre-arbitration filtering of TSC1 
      requests as defined by the J1939 standard. When set to 'Enabled - Filter 
      SPN 695', then any TSC1 with SPN 695 equal to 0 (override disabled) will 
      be excluded from arbitration. The SPN 695 pre-arbitration filter was added 
      to the J1939 standard in February 2017 to reduce undesired arbitration 
      interactions. "Override Disabled" commands are not a request for active 
      control and therefore they do not need to be arbitrated. However, if such 
      TSC1 commands are arbitrated and have an elevated priority, their 
      inclusion in the arbitration process can interfere with other TSC1 
      commands that are requesting active control. 
      J1939_TSC1_rx_tout If set to a non-zero value, this parameter overrides 
      the default timeout for all TSC1 messages. 
      J1939_Tx2Fail CAN2 Tx failure diagnostic: failure count threshold 
      J1939_Tx3Fail CAN3 Tx failure diagnostic: failure count threshold 
      J1939_TxFail CAN1 Tx failure diagnostic: failure count threshold 
      J1939_Vdot_f_ports Fuel rate volume reported in the J1939 LFE PGN, ISO 
      15031 PIDs, and ISO 14229 DIDs. The reported fuel rate is based on the 
      selected 'J1939 fuel rate mode'. 
      J1939_VI_fmt Selects the order of the strings reported in the J1939 
      Vehicle Identification (VI) PGN 65260. 
      KCYC_enable Knock cycle-sample updates toggle switch (Active or Halted) 
      Kd_AFB H-Bridge A PID Derivative gain 
      Kd_BFB H-Bridge B PID Derivative gain 
      Kd_clo_AFB H-Bridge A output device closing Kd additional gain 
      Kd_clo_BFB H-Bridge A output device closing Kd additional gain 
      Kd_clo_TFB Sets an offset to the derivative gain term for the closing 
      direction. 
      Kd_gov Governor Derivative Gain 
      Kd_gov_mult Kd governor gain multiplier 
      Kd_TFB Sets the derivative gain term for the feedback loop. 
      keysw_type If the key switch is set to 'Automatic', reprogramming and 
      flash page commits are allowed without requiring a key-on condition. 
      Setting the key switch to automatic also prevents the ECM from entering a 
      low-power sleep state while the PC display is connected.

      If the key switch is set to 'Manual', reprogramming and flash page commits 
      will not begin unless the key switch is on. 
      key_offrel_valid Time to wait after the relative key switch voltage is 
      below the trigger before validating a key-off condition. 
      key_off_clr_active Key-off clear active time (seconds) 
      key_off_clr_EGR EGR valve command during the key-off relay on clear 
      period. 
      key_off_clr_EGR_cnt Selects the number of close/open cycles performed 
      after key-off when the 'Key-off clear with relay on' is set to 'Clear and 
      zero'. 
      key_off_clr_EGR_DC Selects the EGR valve duty-cycle to use after key-off 
      when the 'Key-off clear with relay on' is set to 'Clear and zero'. Selects 
      the duty-cycle used during the zero-position determination. 
      key_off_clr_EGR_ena Enables a series of EGR valve opens and closes to 
      clear any deposits which formed during the drive cycle. After the series 
      of opens and closes, the valve will be supplied a fixed Duty Cycle to 
      determine an updated 0% valve open feedback voltage.

      NOTE: This should only be used when Key-off clear with relay on is enabled 
      and with H-Bridge controlled EGR valves. The Key-off clear hold time must 
      be sufficient to allow the selected number of Key-off clear EGR cycles and 
      zero voltage determination to complete. 
      key_off_clr_EGR_V Selects the EGR valve voltage target to use during the 
      close/open cycles performed after key-off when the 'Key-off clear with 
      relay on' is set to 'Clear and zero'. The artificially lowered close 
      voltage allows the valve to hard close to remove valve seat deposits. 
      key_off_clr_ena If enabled, the relay will turn on following an engine 
      stopped situation in order to allow residual water to drain from the EGR 
      valve (and potentially the throttle). During this period, pressure pegging 
      might also be active.

      'Clear and zero' will also include a series of EGR valve opens and closes 
      to clear any deposits which formed during the drive cycle. After the 
      series of opens and closes, the valve will be supplied a fixed Duty Cycle 
      to determine an updated 0% valve open feedback voltage. NOTE: 'Clear and 
      zero' should only be used with H-Bridge controlled EGR valves, and the 
      Key-off clear hold time must be sufficient to allow the selected number of 
      Key-off clear EGR cycles and zero voltage determination to complete. 
      key_off_clr_hold Duration of the clear procedure. 
      key_off_clr_TPS Throttle command during the key-off relay on clear period. 

      key_off_clr_wt Wait period following a confirmed engine-stopped situation 
      before the clear sequence begins. 
      key_off_sleep Key-off/on abs trigger. Absolute trigger voltage for 
      determining key-off or key-on state. 
      key_off_valid Time to wait after the key switch voltage is below the 
      absolute trigger before validating a key-off condition. 
      key_on_relay_force This option forces the RELAY output to ON when key-on. 
      The RELAY output normally enables distribution of high side power to 
      components needed while the engine is running. The starter and other 
      components that are needed before the engine is running are not normally 
      powered based on the RELAY output. Using this option to force RELAY ON is 
      a non-standard configuration and should only be used if the wiring harness 
      cannot be modified to a standard configuration. 
      key_on_wait Time to wait on gasoline after a key-on condition exists with 
      the engine stopped before turning off the fuel-pump, throttle, ... until 
      engine motion is detected. Alternate fuels have their own timeout. The 
      fuel pump may be alternatively disabled earlier than this value using the 
      fuel pump stopped wait value. 
      key_on_waitalt Time to wait on gaseous (alternate) fuels after a key-on 
      condition exists with the engine stopped before turning off the lockoff, 
      throttle, ... until engine motion is detected. Gasoline has its own 
      timeout. The lockoff may be alternatively disabled earlier than this value 
      using the lockoff stopped wait value. 
      key_trigrel_volts Key-off rel trigger - Relative trigger voltage between 
      the switched and continuous battery supplies for determining key-off or 
      key-on state. 
      key_trig_volts Key-off/on abs trigger - Absolute trigger voltage for 
      determining key-off or key-on state.

      KNK_control_status Knock control system status (Disabled, Inactive: sensor 
      invalid, Inactive: assignment invalid, Active) 
      KNK_CWT_0_V Knock CWT adjusted 0% voltage 
      KNK_CWT_100_V Knock CWT adjusted 100% voltage 
      KNK_CWT_mult In the calculation of the knock voltage thresholds, this 
      multiplier will be used with the CWT % to elevate the Light Knock voltage 
      level based on the CWT %.

      If this multiplier is > 0 and if CWT % is greater than 0, the following 
      adjustments to the Light Knock (0%) and Heavy Knock (100%) voltage levels 
      are made:

      0Vdelta = (CWTmultiplier * CWT%) * 0V
      0V = 0V + 0Vdelta
      100V = 100V + 0Vdelta 
      KNK_CWT_mult_legacy Legacy knock CWT multiplier only used with software 
      versions less than 305. Newer versions use KNK_CWT_mult.

      In the calculation of the knock voltage thresholds, this multiplier will 
      be used with the CWT % to elevate the Light Knock voltage level based on 
      the CWT %.

      If this multiplier is > 0 and if CWT % is greater than 0, the following 
      adjustments to the Light Knock (0%) and Heavy Knock (100%) voltage levels 
      are made:

      0Vdelta = (CWTmultiplier * CWT%) * 0V
      0V = 0V + 0Vdelta
      100V = 100V + 0Vdelta 
      KNK_cycle_CAD 1D array of knock cycle CAD - used as inputs for knock 
      sampling 
      KNK_ECT_ena Knock min ECT (temperature) requirement 
      KNK_enable Enables or disables knock control. To activate knock control, 
      set this parameter to 'Enabled - ECM only' for applications in which the 
      ECM is monitoring the knock sensors and performing knock control 
      processing. Otherwise, if an ECM is paired with a SPOCK device to perform 
      knock control, then select 'Enabled - ECM+SPOCK'. 
      KNK_FSO_0_V Knock FSO adjusted 0% knock threshold value. 
      KNK_FSO_100_V Knock FSO adjusted 100% knock value. 
      KNK_FSO_debounce Minimum time that must be spent in fuel shutoff before 
      knock control is disabled.

      Set to 0 to disable FSO knock disable.

      Once this debounce time has been reached, knock control is immediately 
      disabled and remains so until fuel shutoff is exited and the extra disable 
      time has elapsed. 
      KNK_FSO_disabled Indicates when knock control is disabled due to fuel 
      shutoff. 
      KNK_FSO_disabled_tm Additional time that knock control will remain 
      disabled after the engine has left fuel shutoff. This must be set to a 
      non-zero value in addition to the debounce time above in order to enable 
      the FSO knock disable feature. 
      KNK_FSO_min_mdot Minimum fuel flow at which knock FSO threshold will 
      continue to decrease to 0. If fuel flow is below this value, the knock FSO 
      threshold will remain at its current value. 
      KNK_FSO_win_peak_tau Knock FSO peak low pass filter time constant. 
      KNK_FSO_win_tm Knock FSO peak window time. 
      KNK_hw_mode Knock hardware mode (Not Available, Flat response (high gain), 
      Tuned response (low gain), Software selectable) 
      KNK_HW_scale The internal hardware gain of the incoming raw knock signal 
      for a fixed gain platform, or the low gain for a duel gain capable ECM 
      platform. Typically, the input amp has a gain of 0.332 feeding a +/ 1.65V 
      A/D input, so the HW gain is approximately 4.97 V/full scale RMS. 
      KNK_HW_scale2 The internal hardware gain of the incoming raw knock signal 
      when in the high gain setting on a dual gain capable ECM platform. 
      Typically, the input amp has a gain of 3.00 feeding a +/ 1.65V A/D input, 
      so the HW gain is 0.55 V/full scale RMS. 
      KNK_Ksel This switch selects the knock circuit analog input gain for 
      either a tuned response (low gain), or flat response (high gain) sensor 
      type. This option is only available on hardware ECM platforms that support 
      software analog dual-gain selection. 
      KNK_manual Knock mode (automatic or manual) selector 
      KNK_MAP_mode Specifies whether the knock control and adaptive octane 
      estimation enable MAP conditions and fault MAP conditions use MAP or MAP 
      load.

      threshold

      KNK_min_MAPlim Knock sensor open diagnostic: MAP lower limit entry 
      condition 
      KNK_min_mode If set to "Filtered/windowed", then the "Knock sensor open" 
      fault voltage threshold is compared to the filtered RMS volts during knock 
      foreground windows when knock control is engaged.

      If set to "Unfiltered/engine cycle", then the fault voltage threshold is 
      compared to the unfiltered RMS volts sampled every 1 ms over the last 
      engine cycle, regardless of knock control engagement conditions. 
      KNK_min_RPMlim Knock sensor open diagnostic: RPM lower limit entry 
      condition

      KNK_sig_pweight In the calculation of the knock feedback RMS voltage, this 
      is the weighting factor relative to the average of all selected cylinders 
      for the peak detected knock for any given engine cycle: feedback = peak * 
      x + average * (1-x) where x is this weighting factor.

      KOR_action_1 Key-On Reset allows the reset of the Closed Loop Adaptive 
      Learn table and/or the Adaptive Octane table.

      A specified number of key-cycle (ON-OFF-ON) and/or Foot Pedal Position 
      (FPP) snaps can be used in sequence to select the table to reset. The 
      sequence must be performed before the engine is cranked and the table 
      select sequence must be completed within 65 seconds of initial key-on.

      Hold key-off for 10 seconds to abort the sequence. 
      KOR_action_2 KeyOn Reset select table to reset 2nd action 
      KOR_conf_chan_1 An output channel can be selected to optionally flash a 
      confirmation upon successful table selection and reset. 
      KOR_conf_chan_2 KeyOn Reset confirmation output chan 2nd action 
      KOR_conf_cycles_1 KeyOn Reset num confirmation flashes 
      KOR_conf_cycles_2 KeyOn Reset num confirmation flashes 2nd action 
      KOR_conf_off_time KeyOn Reset confirmation flash off time 
      KOR_conf_on_time KeyOn Reset confirmation flash on time 
      KOR_FPP_cycles_1 KeyOn Reset num FPP cycles required 
      KOR_FPP_cycles_2 KeyOn Reset num FPP cycles required 2nd action 
      KOR_FPP_dpsd_pct KeyOn Reset FPP depressed threshold 
      KOR_FPP_rlsd_pct KeyOn Reset FPP released threshold 
      KOR_key_cycles_1 KeyOn Reset num key cycles required 
      KOR_key_cycles_2 KeyOn Reset num key cycles required 2nd action 
      KOR_seq_end_time KeyOn Reset keyon time after sequence prior to action 
      KOR_state KeyOn Reset state machine for tracking execution 
      KOR_state_max_time KeyOn Reset max time for state to be valid 
      KOR_state_min_time KeyOn Reset min time for state to be valid 
      Kp_AFB H-Bridge A PID Proportional gain 
      Kp_BFB H-Bridge B PID Proportional gain 
      Kp_clo_AFB H-Bridge A Output device closing Kp additional gain 
      Kp_clo_BFB H-Bridge B Output device closing Kp additional gain 
      Kp_clo_TFB Sets an offset to the proportional gain term for the closing 
      direction. 
      Kp_gov Governor Proportional Gain 
      Kp_gov_mult Kp (proportional) governor gain multiplier 
      Kp_TFB Sets the proportional gain term for the feedback loop. 
      KVHighest KV Highest value 
      KVHighest_max KV Highest maximum 
      KVHighest_tau KV Highest low-pass tau 
      KV_diag_tau KV Block Order & diagnostics low pass tau 
      KV_high Sets the increment to add to the nominal KV when checking the 
      Spark KV high diagnostic fault. 
      KV_low Sets the decrement to subtract from the nominal KV when checking 
      the Spark KV low diagnostic fault. 
      KV_MFskip Threshold for primary skip deltaKV test 
      KV_term Secondary Spark Termination Inductor 
      K_adapt Gasoline: Adaptive Learn Gain 
      K_CL This parameter is a proportional gain that is applied to the Phi 
      error (measured Phi/commanded Phi) to determine the rate of closed-loop 
      correction (for gasoline engines). 
      K_CL_acquire Gasoline: Closed Loop Acquire Gain 
      LdLimECT_method ECT-based load limiting method:
      0 = 'ECT 1D Table'
      1 = 'ECT & AAT 2D Table' 
      LG_gov_ena Min Governor Software Switch. Select Disabled, Droop, and/or 
      Isochronous governor mode 
      Linde_ff_loadval Linde feedforward load value 
      Linde_ff_torq_req Remote feedforward torque request 
      LLAdapt_dld_max This is the maximum (positive) % load-limit adaptation 
      delta allowed. It is >= 0. 
      LLAdapt_dld_min This is the minimum (negative) % load-limit adaptation 
      delta allowed. It is <= 0. 
      LLAdapt_dload This is the current loadlimit adaptation offset in % load 
      that is added to the base calibrated loadlimit to achieve a match with the 
      calculated engine load. 
      LLAdapt_ena Enables/Disables load-limit target adaptation to compensate 
      for variations in the throttle model, air pulsation throttle model flow 
      disturbances, ... 
      LLAdapt_frz_wait This is the number of ms that the system will delay 
      before engaging load-limit adaptation following authority engagement of 
      the load-limit TPS value. The last load-limit adaptation offset stays 
      intact whenever load-limit is not in authority. 
      LLAdapt_Ki This is the integrator gain for the load-limit delta 
      adaptation. An error of 5% in load will be adapted at a rate of 5%/sec if 
      this gain is set to 1.00. 
      LLAdapt_slew_lim This is the load-limit adaptation slew limit in % load 
      per second. It is a positive number which is used to limit the adaptation 
      movement symmetrically in both the positive and negative directions. 
      LLgear_axle_ratio Drive axle ratio used to calculate the gear ratio to 
      determine the current transmission gear. Parameter is only applicable when 
      "Gear-based load-limiting" is set to 'Enabled - Cal Based'. 
      LLgear_dir Transmission gear direction indicator input status:
      0 = Forward
      1 = Reverse
      2 = Error / Fault
      3 = Not Available
      4 = Park
      5 = Neutral 
      LLgear_dir_cfg When "Gear direction input" is configured as an Aux DIG 
      input, then this value determines the active logic state(s). An active 
      input state indicates reverse direction while an inactive state is forward 
      direction. When parameter is set to 'Default', the active state is defined 
      as follows:
      Aux DIG1 = Gnd
      Aux DIG2 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG3 = Gnd
      Aux DIG4 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG5 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG6 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG7 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG8 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG9 = Gnd
      Aux DIG10 = Gnd
      Aux DIG11 = Gnd
      Aux DIG12 = Gnd
      Aux DIG13 = Gnd
      Aux DIG14 = Gnd
      Aux DIG15 = Gnd
      Aux DIG16 = Gnd
      Aux DIG17 = Gnd
      Aux DIG18 = Gnd
      Aux DIG19 = Gnd
      Gov1 = Gnd
      Gov2 = Gnd 
      LLgear_dir_input Selects the input source for determining the 
      transmission's gear direction. An active input state indicates reverse 
      direction while an inactive state is forward direction. When parameter is 
      set to 'Disabled', the gear direction is defaulted to forward. When set to 
      'CAN sourced', the gear direction is received from SPN 1622 in ECI PGN 
      65132 or 65422. If SPN is not received or in error, then the direction is 
      defaulted to forward. Parameter is only applicable when "Gear-based 
      load-limiting" is set to 'Enabled - Cal Based'. 
      LLgear_ena When set to 'Enabled - Cal Based', the 4G ECM will determine 
      the current transmission gear by performing a lookup in the gear-based 
      load-limiting table using the calculated gear ratio. The gear ratio is 
      calculated from the tire circumference, drive axle ratio, engine speed, 
      and vehicle speed. Once the current gear is determined, the associated 
      "Load-Limit Source" selection specifies which Speed-Based Load Limit table 
      is used to look up the maximum allowed load based on engine speed. When 
      set to 'Enabled - CAN Based', the current transmission gear is obtained 
      through ETC2.

      In addition to enabling this parameter, set the "Load-limiting system" 
      parameter above to either standard or expanded mode in order to activate 
      gear-based load-limiting. 
      LLgear_loadlim Current gear-based load limit 
      LLgear_num Current gear number 
      LLgear_table1 Load-limit table selection for 1st gear 
      LLgear_table10 Load-limit table selection for 10th gear 
      LLgear_table11 Load-limit table selection for 11th gear 
      LLgear_table12 Load-limit table selection for 12th gear 
      LLgear_table13 Load-limit table selection for 13th gear 
      LLgear_table14 Load-limit table selection for 14th gear 
      LLgear_table15 Load-limit table selection for 15th gear 
      LLgear_table16 Load-limit table selection for 16th gear 
      LLgear_table2 Load-limit table selection for 2nd gear 
      LLgear_table3 Load-limit table selection for 3rd gear 
      LLgear_table4 Load-limit table selection for 4th gear 
      LLgear_table5 Load-limit table selection for 5th gear 
      LLgear_table6 Load-limit table selection for 6th gear 
      LLgear_table7 Load-limit table selection for 7th gear 
      LLgear_table8 Load-limit table selection for 8th gear 
      LLgear_table9 Load-limit table selection for 9th gear 
      LLgear_table_rev1 Load-limit table selection for 1st reverse gear 
      LLgear_table_rev2 Load-limit table selection for 2nd reverse gear 
      LLgear_tire Tire circumference used to calculate the gear ratio to 
      determine the current transmission gear. Parameter is only applicable when 
      "Gear-based load-limiting" is set to 'Enabled - Cal Based'. 
      LLTO_actv Indicates when the load-limit is actively being elevated by the 
      Load-Limit Temporary Override feature. 
      LLTO_hold_time The amount of time after VE CWT correction has fallen back 
      below the threshold during which the full value of the elevated load-limit 
      remains active. The hold period follows VE CWT dropping back below the 
      threshold and precedes the slewing down to the Speed-Based Load-Limit.

      A value of 0 seconds eliminates the hold time and causes the slewing down 
      to begin once VE CWT drops below the calibrated threshold. 
      LLTO_hold_tmr The amount of time remaining in the 'hold at elevated 
      load-limit' timer. 
      LLTO_multi_fuel_ena Select single load-limit override or fuel based 
      load-limit override 
      LLTO_pct The percent of the current Speed-Based Load-Limit which is added 
      to temporarily elevate the load-limit during a load dump transient. This 
      is only applied when "Load-limit override" is set to 'All Fuel Types' and 
      will not differentiate fuel types. The size of the load-limit elevation is 
      calculated once at the time the VE CWT correction % is exceeded (at the 
      onset of the transient).

      Example: if the Speed-Based Load-Limit is currently 80%, a 10% "Load-limit 
      override" will temporarily increase the Speed-Based Load-Limit to 88%.

      A value of 0% will disable the Load-Limit Temporary Override feature. 
      LLTO_pct_gsln Load-limit override percent for gasoline fuel type. 
      LLTO_pct_inc The current magnitude of the elevation of the load-limit. 
      LLTO_pct_LPG Load-limit override percent for LPG fuel type. 
      LLTO_pct_NG Load-limit override percent for NG fuel type. 
      LLTO_slew_rate The rate of change from the elevated load-limit to the 
      normal Speed-Based Load-Limit. 
      LLTO_state The current state of the Load-Limit Temporary Override feature. 

      LLTO_VE_CWT_crct_pct The threshold where the elevated load-limit is 
      triggered. 
      LoadLim_A_volts Target voltage for the 'Analog - A' selection for the 
      "Input config" parameter 
      LoadLim_B_volts Target voltage for the 'Analog - B' selection for the 
      "Input config" parameter 
      LoadLim_C_volts Target voltage for the 'Analog - C' selection for the 
      "Input config" parameter 
      LoadLim_dmd_pct Load limiting function maximum load fraction - does not 
      include TSC1 load limits 
      LoadLim_eco_table If 'performance mode' is enabled and 'economy' is 
      commanded, this load-limiting table will be enforced. 
      LoadLim_ECT_tau This value specifies the time constant used for the 
      low-pass filter that is applied to the ECT-based load-limit speed 
      adjustment multiplier. 
      LoadLim_EGR_pct % load-limit, typically less than 100% if EGR_minnom_frac 
      < 0.0 
      LoadLim_ena Load-limit processing will use the calibration in the "Speed 
      Based Load-Limiting - Standard" section when this value is set to 'Enabled 
      - standard'. Calibration in the "Speed Based Load-Limiting - Expanded" 
      section will be ignored.

      Set this value to 'Enabled - enhanced' to allow load-limit processing to 
      use the calibration in the expanded section and ignore the calibration in 
      the standard section. 

      For diagnostic fault induced derate processing, this value is not required 
      to be enabled in either standard or expanded mode for Tables 1-16 to be 
      used as power derate 1/2 DBW limit sources. 
      LoadLim_gvauthTPSena If enabled, load and TPS limits apply to the current 
      governor maximum load authority and maximum TPS command. 
      LoadLim_max_gov_actv Indicator for load limiting override of the Max 
      Governor 
      LoadLim_max_gov_ena If enabled, the engine's active max governor speed 
      will update based on the currently active load-limit table's "Max Governor 
      speed" selection from the table below. The ECM will restrict the max 
      governor engine speed to the maximum specified on the Governor page if the 
      load-limit "Max Governor speed" table contains values > than the Governor 
      page Max Governor, i.e. the values in the load-limit "Max Governor speed" 
      table should be < the Governor's Max Governor. 
      LoadLim_max_pct Load limiting function maximum load 
      LoadLim_max_TPS Load limiting function maximum allowed TPS position 
      LoadLim_max_TPS_src The source of the current maximum TPS limit 
      LoadLim_mode If fuel-based is selected, the current fuel type determines 
      which of the 3 load limiting tables below is active. If an analog input is 
      selected, the input voltage is compared to the 3 target voltages below. 
      The table with the target closest to the actual analog input voltage 
      becomes active. 
      LoadLim_perf_input This selection determines whether or not a 'performance 
      mode' input selection is enabled. If disabled, load-limiting functions 
      normally. If enabled, a 'power' command will override load-limiting and 
      set it to 100% or the value from Table 4-16. An 'economy' command will 
      enforce the load-limiting table indicated by the LoadLim_eco_table 
      selection below. 
      LoadLim_perf_stat currently active load-limiting 'performance mode' status 

      LoadLim_T10_chan This parameter allows an analog or digital input to be 
      specified when table matching by a combination of fuel type and active 
      logic state(s) or input voltage level is desired. 
      LoadLim_T10_chan_cfg This parameter specifies either the active logic 
      state(s) or voltage-based selection for the analog or digital input 
      channel. For active logic state(s) evaluation, select 'Analog GND/+V' for 
      analog inputs and 'Default' or one of the DIG options for digital inputs. 
      For voltage-based selection, choose one of the three options: 'Analog - 
      A', 'Analog-B' or 'Analog-C'. Voltage-based selection is available for all 
      of the analog and digital input channels. 
      LoadLim_T10_fuel This parameter determines whether a table is evaluated 
      for a match during load-limit processing. A value of 'Disabled' removes a 
      table from load-limit processing regardless of the values for input 
      channel and network selection.

      If 'Gasoline', 'LPG', or 'NG' is selected, the current fuel type 
      determines whether the table is a match candidate. A value of 'All Fuels' 
      should only be used if matching based on input channel or network 
      selection and the resulting active speed based load-limits are not fuel 
      specific. 
      LoadLim_T10_ntwk This parameter allows a CAN-based network selection mode 
      to be specified when table matching by a combination of fuel type and 
      selected mode is desired. To enable network selection mode, set this 
      parameter to one of the following values:
      - 'Table Number': match based on receipt of a table number command in an 
      engine load-limit select request.
      - 'Performance': match based on receipt of a performance command.
      - 'Economy': match based on receipt of an economy command.
      - 'Standard': match based on receipt of a standard command. 
      LoadLim_T11_chan This parameter allows an analog or digital input to be 
      specified when table matching by a combination of fuel type and active 
      logic state(s) or input voltage level is desired.

      specific. 
      LoadLim_T3_ntwk This parameter allows a CAN-based network selection mode 
      to be specified when table matching by a combination of fuel type and 
      selected mode is desired. To enable network selection mode, set this 
      parameter to one of the following values:
      - 'Table Number': match based on receipt of a table number command in an 
      engine load-limit select request.
      - 'Performance': match based on receipt of a performance command.
      - 'Economy': match based on receipt of an economy command.
      - 'Standard': match based on receipt of a standard command. 
      LoadLim_T3_volts Load Limiting Table 3 target voltage - typically 4.5 
      volts 
      LoadLim_T4_chan This parameter allows an analog or digital input to be 
      specified when table matching by a combination of fuel type and active 
      logic state(s) or input voltage level is desired. 
      LoadLim_T4_chan_cfg This parameter specifies either the active logic 
      state(s) or voltage-based selection for the analog or digital input 
      channel. For active logic state(s) evaluation, select 'Analog GND/+V' for 
      analog inputs and 'Default' or one of the DIG options for digital inputs. 
      For voltage-based selection, choose one of the three options: 'Analog - 
      A', 'Analog-B' or 'Analog-C'. Voltage-based selection is available for all 
      of the analog and digital input channels. 
      LoadLim_T4_fuel This parameter determines whether a table is evaluated for 
      a match during load-limit processing. A value of 'Disabled' removes a 
      table from load-limit processing regardless of the values for input 
      channel and network selection.

      If 'Gasoline', 'LPG', or 'NG' is selected, the current fuel type 
      determines whether the table is a match candidate. A value of 'All Fuels' 
      should only be used if matching based on input channel or network 
      selection and the resulting active speed based load-limits are not fuel 
      specific. 
      LoadLim_T4_ntwk This parameter allows a CAN-based network selection mode 
      to be specified when table matching by a combination of fuel type and 
      selected mode is desired. To enable network selection mode, set this 
      parameter to one of the following values:
      - 'Table Number': match based on receipt of a table number command in an 
      engine load-limit select request.
      - 'Performance': match based on receipt of a performance command.
      - 'Economy': match based on receipt of an economy command.
      - 'Standard': match based on receipt of a standard command. 
      LoadLim_T5_chan This parameter allows an analog or digital input to be
