      MEFI_FPP_anchor Malibu FPP anchor position 
      MEFI_RS_source_ena This switch allows interpretation of information in 
      byte 7 of the 'MEFI command packet' to select the roadspeed input source 
      (i.e. pulse-input / ZeroOff GPS / generic GPS). 
      MEFI_RS_source_req The currently requested roadspeed source from the 'MEFI 
      command packet'. This function is enabled by the switch above. 
      MEFI_sync_status If enabled, the cruise/sync status will be embedded in 
      the upper 2 bits of the MEFI command acknowledgment status byte. 
      MES_allspeed_cmd Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES sync (slave) 
      allspeed command 
      MES_allspeed_mstr Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES master allspeed 
      command 
      MES_allspeed_ntrlk Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES dis-engagement 
      allspeed interlock 
      MES_auth_neg This is the sync closed-loop speed modifier total negative 
      authority limit (must always be a negative number). It will be attenuated 
      toward zero across the phase-in speed. 
      MES_auth_pos This is the sync closed-loop speed modifier total positive 
      authority limit (must always be a positive number). It will be attenuated 
      toward zero across the phase-in speed. 
      MES_ena This controls what input source (if any) allows the multi-engine 
      speed sync function to be activated. On tri-state inputs (such as the Aux 
      DIG inputs), any state other than open will engage sync. 
      MES_FPPdelt_0 When the MES system is in 'Lever Match' or 'FPP-Match' mode, 
      this is the +/- tolerance between the master and slave levers that cause 
      0% engagement (complete disengagement) of engine speed sync. Between this 
      value and the 100% engagement value, there will be a linear attenuation of 
      the authority of the engine speed sync. This value should always be >= the 
      100% engagement value. 
      MES_FPPdelt_1 When the MES system is in 'Lever Match' or 'FPP-Match' mode, 
      this is the +/- tolerance between the master and slave levers that cause 
      100% engagement of engine speed sync. It is also a requirement that all 
      connected engines be in forward gear for this engagement to occur. 
      MES_FPP_cmd Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES sync (slave) FPP 
      command 
      MES_FPP_mode This switch controls the type of engine sync mode that the 
      engine will be in when 'FPP' or lever operation mode is selected (as 
      opposed to syn'd RPM user setpoint mode). 'Master Lever' mode is also 
      known as single-lever control, and this mode uses the slave FPP as the max 
      authority for the slave engine. 'Lever Match' mode only initiates sync 
      when the slave FPP matches the master FPP within the defined tolerances. 
      MES_FPP_mstr Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES master FPP command 
      MES_FPP_ntrlock Sync FPP command at the time of sync disengagement. 
      MES_gain_slct This switch controls which gain schedules will be used for 
      the engine-sync function. Only the following gains are used: Kp, Ki, Kd, 
      Kiv, Kp_dz, Ki_dz, Kd_dz. Note that the 'droop' and 'isochronous' 
      designations do not actually cause different governor behaviors. 
      MES_Iacc Currently speed sync integrator value 
      MES_Ilim_neg This is the sync integrator negative authority limit (must 
      always be a negative number). It will be attenuated toward zero across the 
      phase-in speed. 
      MES_Ilim_pos This is the sync integrator positive authority limit (must 
      always be a positive number). It will be attenuated toward zero across the 
      phase-in speed. 
      MES_Kd Currently computed (from selected gain schedule) speed sync 
      feedback loop derivative gain. 
      MES_Ki Currently computed (from selected gain schedule) speed sync 
      feedback loop integrator gain. 
      MES_Kiv Currently computed (from selected gain schedule) speed sync 
      feedback loop integrator velocity gain. 
      MES_Kp Currently computed (from selected gain schedule) speed sync 
      feedback loop proportional gain. 
      MES_light Follows the status light/output state for the multiengine sync 
      system. 
      MES_loadref_max The reference load must be limited to less than 100% to 
      allow a positive load correction near WOT. 
      MES_loadref_min The reference load must be limited to greater than 0% to 
      allow a negative load correction near closed throttle. 
      MES_load_PID Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES closed-loop slave 
      load adjustment 
      MES_load_ref Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES engine load reference 

      MES_MAP_d Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES final slave target MAP 
      MES_MAP_mstr Master engine lowpass filtered MAP used as a reference for 
      the slave engine. 
      MES_MAP_mstr_tau This is the low-pass filter time constant used on the 
      master engine current MAP to produce a reference MAP for the slave engine. 

      MES_MAP_ref Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES reference MAP 
      MES_phase Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES phase-in value 
      MES_PID_tau This is the low-pass filter time constant used on the 
      closed-loop output load command portion of the engine speed sync control. 
      The master TPS command is still fed through directly to the slave without 
      delay. 
      MES_rpmdelt_0 This is the delta rpm from the current idle target above 
      which speed sync will begin to engage. 
      MES_rpmdelt_1 This is the delta rpm from the initiation speed over which 
      speed sync will be fully engaged. This is a linear phase-in from 0% to 
      100% engagement. 
      MES_rpmdtdz_Kd Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES Kd deadzone 
      MES_rpmdz_Ki Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES Ki deadzone 
      MES_rpmdz_Kp Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES Kp deadzone 
      MES_rpm_mstr Master engine lowpass filtered rpm used as a target for the 
      slave engine. 
      MES_rpm_mstr_tau This is the low-pass filter time constant used on the 
      master engine current rpm to produce a target rpm for the slave engine. 
      MES_state Current state of the speed sync system. 
      MES_status Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES sync engagement (Master 
      or slave / Master only) 
      MES_status_lamp This switch optionally configures an output on the master 
      engine to indicate when all connected slaves are within the defined RPM 
      tolerance band to indicate sync achieved. 
      MES_status_mstr Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES sync communicated 
      status - This switch controls the J1939 communicated multi-engine symc 
      status. If set to "Master Only", slave engines will communicate 'Not 
      Available' for multi-engine sync status. 
      MES_status_rpmtol This is the +/- rpm speed difference between the 
      currently commanded master engine sync speed and any slave to validate the 
      sync achieved status indication. 
      MES_sw_source Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES switch source 
      (normal, master engine, network override) 
      MES_sync_cmd Currently received or transmitted sync command logical 
      indicator. 
      MES_TPSest_d Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES TM estimated target 
      TPS 
      MES_TPSest_ref Multi-engine speed synchronization: MES TM estimated 
      reference TPS 
      MES_usblk_offt When engine sync is commanded but the engines speeds do not 
      match by the specified indication tolerance, the sync indication 
      light/output will blink with the given on-time and off-time. The blink 
      total period is the sum of these two values, and the duty-cycle can be 
      modified using asymmetry. 
      MES_usblk_ont When engine sync is commanded but the engines speeds do not 
      match by the specified indication tolerance, the sync indication 
      light/output will blink with the given on-time and off-time. The blink 
      total period is the sum of these two values, and the duty-cycle can be 
      modified using asymmetry. 
      MES_WOTds_0 At this absolute FPP position on each slave engine, the WOT 
      de-sync feature will be completed (fully de-sync'd) if the software switch 
      above is enabled. Therefore, the phase-in value will linearly decrease 
      from 100% to 0% as the FPP position increases toward this completion value 
      from the initiation value. 
      MES_WOTds_1 At this absolute FPP position on each slave engine, the WOT 
      de-sync feature will initiate if the software switch above is enabled. 
      Therefore, the phase-in value will linearly decrease from 100% to 0% as 
      the FPP position increases toward the completion value. 
      MES_WOT_desync This switch allows a sync'd set of master/slave engines to 
      de-synchronize at wide-open-throttle (WOT) conditions in order to take 
      advantage of the maximum power of each engine individually. This de-sync 
      will begin at the smaller absolute FPP value below, and complete a full 
      phase-out of synchronization at the larger absolute FPP value below. 
      ME_DERATE1_active Multi-engine Derate1 
      ME_DERATE2_active Multi-engine Derate2 
      ME_derate_ena If this switch is 'Enabled' and multi-engine communications 
      are active over the CAN link with the proprietary engine-to-engine 
      transmit packet PGN '61184', then a derate on another engine will cause 
      all engines to derate temporarily (until unlatched by driver throttle 
      interaction as defined above for 'Derate release'). 
      ME_derate_resett This is the time that must expire once an engine has 
      de-rated itself and then unlatched the derate due to another engine derate 
      in a multi-engine configuration before re-arming derates from another 
      engine. Set this value to zero to immediately re-arm, and set this value 
      to > 60.0 seconds to permanently keep from re-arming. 
      ME_derate_state Multi-engine derate logic state 
      ME_LOWREVLIM_active Multi-engine Low rev limit 
      MFAI_cur_cal_mod The current MFA calibration model number and revision 
      level. 
      MFAI_cur_HW_mod The current MFA hardware model number and revision level. 
      MFAI_cur_SW_mod The current MFA software model number and revision level. 
      MFAI_flash_wr_force Used to force writing of the flash parameters into the 
      MFA. 
      MFAI_flash_wr_left The number of flash writes left available in the MFA 
      during this power-cycle. Starts at 10 and downcounts to 0. 
      MFA_cal_state MFA calibration/parameters communications state machine 
      value. 
      MFA_comm_tout MFA communications timeout 
      MFA_ctltype_act The actual MFA control type feedback from the MFA. 
      MFA_ctltype_cmd The commanded MFA control type. 
      MFA_DPPress MFA delta pressure 
      MFA_DPPress_final MFA final dP used for mass-flow calculations 
      MFA_DPPress_Pcrct MFA corrected version of the dP based on upstream 
      pressure – downstream pressure 
      MFA_dP_avg_window MFA dP averaging window in ms based on number of 
      cylinder events and rpm 
      MFA_dP_cyl_events MFA dP averaging window based on number of cylinder 
      events 
      MFA_DSPress MFA downstream pressure 
      MFA_DSPressdt "Switch used to enable transmission of specific high-speed 
      data from the device to the ECU. The transmission of the actual throttle 
      position and actual mass flow are always performed at high speed. 
      Additionally, transmission of pressure and temperature values always 
      transmitted but typically at a slower speed. 

      This setting enables the transmission of an additional CAN packet from the 
      device to the ECU at a high speed that contains the following data:

      - Fast-filtered downstream pressure
      - Slow-filtered downstream pressure
      - Downstream pressure dt
      - Fast-filtered upstream pressure

      The following options are provided:
      - Disabled – High speed data transmission is disabled

      - Enabled – High speed data transmission is enabled

      - Automatic – High speed data transmission is enabled if the data is used 
      as the source for a standard ECU input. (No ECU inputs currently make use 
      of MFG high speed data so this setting will result in high speed data 
      transmission from the MFG being disabled)."

      MFA_DSPress_fast Fast-filtered downstream pressure reported by the MFA. 
      MFA_DSPress_slow Change in downstream pressure over time reported by the 
      MFA. 
      MFA_enabled Enables or disables support for operating with an MFA device. 
      MFA_fault_range_1 Bit flag of active status for fault range 1 on the MFA 
      (faults indexes 0 through 15) 
      MFA_fault_range_2 Bit flag of active status for fault range 2 on the MFA 
      (faults indexes 16 through 31) 
      MFA_flow_min_MAP Minimum intake manifold pressure threshold fault 
      condition for the "MFA flow lower than expected" and "MFA flow higher than 
      expected" diagnostics. 
      MFA_flow_min_RPM Minimum engine speed threshold fault condition for the 
      "MFA flow lower than expected" and "MFA flow higher than expected" 
      diagnostics. 
      MFA_FTemp MFA fuel temperature 
      MFA_hi_flow_pct Flow error percentage threshold fault condition for the 
      "MFA flow higher than expected" diagnostic. 
      MFA_hsdata_active Indicates if high speed data packets are being received 
      from the MFA. 
      MFA_hsdata_tx_act Slow-filtered downstream pressure reported by the MFA. 
      MFA_hsdata_tx_ena Indicates the actual high speed data transmission 
      enablement state. 
      MFA_hsd_comm_tout Timeout value for MFA high speed data comm timeout 
      fault. 
      MFA_lo_flow_pct Flow error percentage threshold fault condition for the 
      "MFA flow lower than expected" diagnostic. 
      MFA_man_mode Controls the active MFA mode. Allows selection of either 
      automatic control or one of the manual modes. 
      MFA_mdot_act MFA reported mdot mixture flow. 
      MFA_mdot_act_pct MFA reported mdot mixture flow percentage of MFA Full 
      scale (MFA_mdot_FS). 
      MFA_mdot_cmd MFA commanded mdot mixture flow. 
      MFA_mdot_cmd_pct MFA commanded mdot mixture flow percentage of MFA Full 
      scale (MFA_mdot_FS). 
      MFA_mdot_FS This is the full-scale mass flow rate in g/sec used for a MFA 
      throttle. Mixture flows are transmitted as a % of this value in order to 
      properly scale the dynamic range of the valve. This should be set to a 
      value slightly higher than the maximum expected flow rate through the 
      device. 
      MFA_param_differ MFA internal parameter match status indicating if all 
      parameters match or if at least one does not match. 
      MFA_param_NA_cnt The MFA ParamOCAN index not available counter for either 
      timed-out or N/A index response ParamOCAN requests. 
      MFA_param_upload Used to force parameter upload from the MFA to the ECM. 
      MFA_status The overall status of the MFA. 
      MFA_TPS_act_pct MFA actual throttle position %. 
      MFA_TPS_cmd_max The maximum throttle position percent limit. This limit is 
      enforced when operating in position or flow mode. 

      This value is especially useful to limit to a reasonable TPS when using a 
      device that is oversized for an engine.

      This value is provided to and enforced by the MFA The default is 100 %. 
      MFA_TPS_cmd_min The minimum throttle position percent limit. This limit is 
      enforced when operating in position or flow mode. This position is not 
      enforced when the motor is commanded off. The return spring will return 
      the blade to 0 % in this case.

      This value is provided to and enforced by the MFA device. The default is 0 
      %. 
      MFA_TPS_cmd_pct MFA commanded throttle position %. 
      MFA_TPS_dP_min Minimum delta pressure enforced by the MFA used to 
      calculate a maximum TPS to prevent a zero delta pressure condition across 
      the throttle valve. 
      MFA_USPress MFA upstream pressure 
      MFA_VE_mdot_err MFA flow error percentage calculated based on the 
      difference between the MFA actual mass flow and the estimated 
      speed-density based mass flow. This flow error is compared to the 
      calibrated flow error percentage threshold for "MFA flow lower than 
      expected" and "MFA flow higher than expected" diagnostic processing. 
      MFGI_cur_cal_mod The current MFG calibration model number and revision 
      level. 
      MFGI_cur_HW_mod The current MFG hardware model number and revision level. 
      MFGI_cur_SW_mod The current MFG software model number and revision level. 
      MFGI_flash_wr_force Used to force writing of the flash parameters into the 
      MFG. 
      MFGI_flash_wr_left The number of flash writes left available in the MFG 
      during this power-cycle. Starts at 10 and downcounts to 0. 
      MFG_cal_state MFG calibration/parameters communications state machine 
      value. 
      MFG_comm_tout MFG communications timeout 
      MFG_ctltype_act The actual MFG control type feedback from the MFG. 
      MFG_ctltype_cmd The commanded MFG control type. 
      MFG_DPPress MFG delta pressure 
      MFG_DPPress_final MFG final dP used for mass-flow calculations 
      MFG_DPPress_Pcrct MFG corrected version of the dP based on upstream 
      pressure – downstream pressure 
      MFG_dP_avg_window MFG dP averaging window in ms based on number of 
      cylinder events and rpm 
      MFG_dP_cyl_events MFG dP averaging window based on number of cylinder 
      events 
      MFG_DSPress MFG downstream pressure 
      MFG_DSPressdt MAP source selection switch used to specify the source of 
      the MAP value(s). The following options are provided:

      - Standard Input – Specifies a MAP sensor connected directly to the MAP 
      input on the ECU. This is the default option.

      - MFA over CAN – Specifies the MAP value(s) will be obtained from an MFA 
      device over the CAN network. Use of this option requires an MFA to be 
      present and enabled on the system. The “MFA high speed data tx enabled” 
      (MFA_hsdata_tx_ena) setting on the “DBW” worksheet should be configured as 
      either “Enabled” or “Automatic” to allow high speed transmission of the 
      MAP value(s) from the MFA device. 
      MFG_DSPress_fast Fast-filtered downstream pressure reported by the MFA. 
      MFG_DSPress_slow Change in downstream pressure over time reported by the 
      MFG. 
      MFG_enabled Enables or disables support for operating with an MFG device. 
      MFG_fault_range_1 Bit flag of active status for fault range 1 on the MFG 
      (faults indexes 0 through 15) 
      MFG_fault_range_2 Bit flag of active status for fault range 2 on the MFG 
      (faults indexes 16 through 31) 
      MFG_flow_min_MAP Minimum intake manifold pressure threshold fault 
      condition for the "MFG flow lower than expected" and "MFG flow higher than 
      expected" diagnostics. 
      MFG_flow_min_RPM Minimum engine speed threshold fault condition for the 
      "MFG flow lower than expected" and "MFG flow higher than expected" 
      diagnostics. 
      MFG_FTemp MFG fuel temperature 
      MFG_fuel_calc Specifies the method used to calculate the fuel mass flow 
      command for the MFG.

      - “Speed-Density + dMAP/dt” – uses VE-based speed density computations 
      along with the “MFG location” setting and closed-loop correction to 
      determine the appropriate desired fuel.

      - "Throttle-Model Based" - used the throttle model to compute required 
      fuel flow.

      - “MFA mass flow” – uses the actual mixture mass flow calculated by the 
      MFA and closed-loop correction to determine the appropriate desired fuel. 
      This option requires an MFA to be present and enabled on the system. 
      MFG_hi_flow_pct Flow error percentage threshold fault condition for the 
      "MFG flow higher than expected" diagnostic. 
      MFG_hsdata_active Indicates if high speed data packets are being received 
      from the MFG. 
      MFG_hsdata_tx_act Slow-filtered downstream pressure reported by the MFG. 
      MFG_hsdata_tx_ena Switch used to enable transmission of specific 
      high-speed data from the device to the ECU. The transmission of the actual 
      throttle position and actual mass flow are always performed at high speed. 
      Additionally, transmission of pressure and temperature values always 
      transmitted but typically at a slower speed.

      This setting enables the transmission of an additional CAN packet from the 
      device to the ECU at a high speed that contains the following data:

      - Fast-filtered downstream pressure
      - Slow-filtered downstream pressure
      - Downstream pressure dt
      - Fast-filtered upstream pressure

      The following options are provided:
      - Disabled – High speed data transmission is disabled

      - Enabled – High speed data transmission is enabled

      - Automatic – High speed data transmission is enabled if the data is used 
      as the source for a standard ECU input. (No ECU inputs currently make use 
      of MFG high speed data so this setting will result in high speed data 
      transmission from the MFG being disabled). 
      MFG_hsd_comm_tout Timeout value for MFG high speed data comm timeout 
      fault. 
      MFG_loc Specifies the location of the MFG in the intake track.

      - “Air filter” – the MFG is operating in a draw-through environment and is 
      located between the air filter and the throttle in a naturally aspirated 
      system or between the air filter and the compressor in a boosted system.

      - “Pre-throttle” – the MFG is operating in a boosted environment and is 
      located between the compressor and the throttle. 
      MFG_lo_flow_pct Flow error percentage threshold fault condition for the 
      "MFG flow lower than expected" diagnostic. 
      MFG_man_mode Controls the active MFG mode. Allows selection of either 
      automatic control or one of the manual modes. 
      MFG_mdot_act MFG reported mdot fuel flow. 
      MFG_mdot_act_pct MFG reported mdot fuel flow percentage of MFG Full scale 
      (MFG_mdot_FS). 
      MFG_mdot_choke After-start fuel enrichment contribution to the MFG fuel 
      flow command. 
      MFG_mdot_cmd MFG commanded mdot fuel flow. 
      MFG_mdot_cmd_pct MFG commanded mdot fuel flow percentage of MFG Full scale 
      (MFG_mdot_FS). 
      MFG_mdot_cmd_tau Low-pass applied to the mass flow fuel command 
      transmitted to the MFG. Set this value to 0 to disable the low-pass. 
      MFG_mdot_FS This is the full-scale fuel mass flow rate in g/sec used for a 
      MFG based fueling. Fuel flow commands are transmitted as a % of this value 
      in order to properly scale the dynamic range of the valve. A typical value 
      of 32.0 g/sec will satisfy all installations up to approximately 600 bhp. 
      MFG_mdot_mult MFG mass flow fuel command multiplier that may be used to 
      adjust the final fuel command provided to the device. By default, the 
      multiplier is set to 1.000 (no adjustment). 
      MFG_MFA_mdot_cmd MFA-based fueling command used if the MFG fueling mode is 
      configured for MFA-based. 
      MFG_param_differ MFG internal parameter match status indicating if all 
      parameters match or if at least one does not match. 
      MFG_param_NA_cnt The MFG ParamOCAN index not available counter for either 
      timed-out or N/A index response ParamOCAN requests. 
      MFG_param_upload Used to force parameter upload from the MFG to the ECM. 
      MFG_RLV_cyc_elapsed Number of warm engine cycles since the last execution 
      of the CFV/MFG redundant lockoff verification fuel run-out test. 
      MFG_RLV_ena If enabled, MFG applications will verify the operation of the 
      secondary lockoff device when the number of warm engine cycles specified 
      for the 'MFG RLV test failed' diagnostic have occurred since the previous 
      execution of the test.

      The test starts when the key is turned off or a remote engine stop command 
      is received. Fuel run-out is engaged and only the secondary lockoff device 
      is closed. The test is successful if the engine stops before the fuel 
      run-out engine run time threshold calibrated for the 'MFG RLV test failed' 
      diagnostic is exceeded. The test fails if that diagnostic becomes 
      active-latched.

      For all other engine cycles in which the secondary lockoff verification 
      test is not active, only the primary lockoff is closed for engine stop 
      requests.

      In addition to setting this parameter to "Enabled", the following 
      calibration is required to enable the MFG redundant lockoff verification 
      mode: 
      - active fuel device: MFG
      - fuel type: NG and/or LPG
      - 'MFG RLV test failed' diagnostic: enabled
      - secondary gaseous lockoff enable pin: set to a valid output pin

      If tri-fuel mode is enabled, MFG applications will also verify the 
      operation of the tri-fuel secondary lockoff device if installed on the 
      second gaseous fuel line using the same fuel-run out procedure and 'MFG 
      RLV test failed' diagnostic as described above. Tri-fuel secondary lockoff 
      verification will occur every other drive cycle if the second gaseous fuel 
      is the active fuel type when the key if turned off or a remote engine stop 
      command is received. 

      MFG_RLV_eng_cyc Number of warm engine cycles between executions of the 
      CFV/MFG redundant lockoff verification fuel run-out test. 

      If tri-fuel mode is enabled, this threshold only affects which drive cycle 
      the CFV/MFG redundant lockoff test is executed on the secondary lockoff 
      solenoid for the first gaseous fuel designated by the "Tri-Fuel mode 
      LOCKOFF output" parameter on the Miscellaneous worksheet. When the second 
      gaseous fuel is the active fuel type, the CFV/MFG redundant lockoff test 
      is executed for the tri-fuel secondary lockoff solenoid every other drive 
      cycle. 
      MFG_RLV_FROmax At key-off when the CFV/MFG RLV fuel run-out test is 
      active, fuel run-out is engaged and the secondary lockoff is closed. If 
      the engine does not stop prior to exceeding this time threshold, the 'CFV 
      RLV test failed' (CFV applications) or 'MFG RLV test failed' (MFG 
      applications) fault will set. 
      MFG_RLV_FROWARNforce This switch controls the soft or hard warning output 
      if there is a historic fault stored for this lockoff diagnostic. If this 
      switch is set to other than 'Disabled', then that particular warning 
      output channel will be forced to an ON state continuously until the 
      historic fault is cleared by either a technician or the startcycle 
      autoclearing mechanism. 
      MFG_RLV_FRO_RS_ena Enables the "Fuel run-out longer than expected" fault 
      road speed condition for the “CFV RLV test failed” and “MFG RLV test 
      failed” faults. 
      MFG_RLV_HM_elapsed Number of engine hours since the last execution of the 
      CFV/MFG redundant lockoff verification fuel run-out test. 
      MFG_RLV_run_force Number of engine hours between executions of the CFV/MFG 
      redundant lockoff verification fuel run-out test. 
      MFG_RLV_state CFV/MFG redundant lockoff verification (RLV) fuel run-out 
      test state. When a test is active, this field will display which of the 
      four lockoff devices is undergoing verification. 
      MFG_SD_mdot_cmd Speed density-based fueling command used if the MFG 
      fueling mode is configured for speed density. 
      MFG_status The overall status of the MFG. 
      MFG_TPS_act_pct MFG actual throttle position %. 
      MFG_TPS_cmd_max The maximum throttle position percent limit. This limit is 
      enforced when operating in position or flow mode. 

      This value is especially useful to limit to a reasonable TPS when using a 
      device that is oversized for an engine.

      This value is provided to and enforced by the MFG. The default is 100 %. 
      MFG_TPS_cmd_min The minimum throttle position percent limit. This limit is 
      enforced when operating in position or flow mode. This position is not 
      enforced when the motor is commanded off. The return spring will return 
      the blade to 0 % in this case.

      This value is provided to and enforced by the MFG device. The default is 0 
      %. 
      MFG_TPS_cmd_pct MFG commanded throttle position %. 
      MFG_USPress MFG upstream pressure 
      MFG_VE_mdot_err MFG flow error percentage calculated based on the 
      difference between the MFG actual mass flow and the commanded 
      speed-density based mass flow. This flow error is compared to the 
      calibrated flow error percentage threshold for "MFG flow lower than 
      expected" and "MFG flow higher than expected" diagnostic processing. 
      mfi_ena Multi-function input 
      mfi_func_allowed Current function 
      mfi_idle_ena When enabled the multi-function input control will support 
      idle trim when the vehicle is stopped and the brake is depressed. 
      mfi_pto_ena When enabled the multi-function input control will support 
      power take-off enabling/disabling and increment/decrement. If the 
      "Governor application mode" is set to 'Vehicle, neutral required if 
      stationary', then the PTO function is enabled whenever conditions are not 
      valid for selecting the roadspeed cruise or idle trim function. If the 
      "Governor application mode" is set to 'Vehicle, neutral required', then 
      the PTO function is enabled when the vehicle is stopped, the transmission 
      is in neutral, and the brake is not depressed. 
      mfi_rsc_ena When enabled the multi-function input control will support 
      roadspeed cruise control enabling/disabling and increment/decrement when 
      the vehicle is moving. If the "Governor application mode" is set to 
      "Vehicle, neutral required if stationary", then the minimum roadspeed for 
      enabling cruise control function is the roadspeed cruise minimum speed; 
      otherwise, the minimum roadspeed is 0.5 kph. 
      MHGL_active logical indicating that the gear lockout button has been 
      pressed and EES.MHGL_latched is ready to latch gear lockout 
      MHGL_chan For marine throttle & gear handles, this selection allows for 
      the connection of a momentary push button to implement transmission gear 
      lockout (or neutral lock) functionality.
      If the button is depressed when the handle is in the neutral (vertical) 
      position, the handle can then be moved forward/backward without causing a 
      shift to forward/reverse.
      The button can be released once the handle is moved into the normal gear 
      engagement region and the gear lockout will remain latched. 
      MHGL_chan_cfg This setting determines the active state of the button used 
      for the gear lockout function described above. 
      MHGL_lamp This output channel allows a light/lamp to be illuminated once 
      the gear lockout function described above is latched. Illumination of this 
      lamp indicates that the momentary gear lockout button can be released as 
      long as the handle remains in a normal gear engagement region. 
      MHGL_latched logical YES/NO indicating that the marine handle gear lockout 
      (MHGL) button request has been validated and latched 
      MHGL_unlatch_tout Once the gear lockout function described above is 
      latched in a normal gear engagement region, this is the unlatch wait time 
      imposed after the handle is returned to neutral. 
      MILblk_btw_codes Fault shutdown inhibit input - Selects the input used for 
      fault shutdown inhibit. When this input is active, it prevents any fault 
      from being able to shut down the engine. 
      MILblk_btw_digits Flash Code Blink Configuration: Time between digits in a 
      code 
      MILblk_btw_repeat Flash Code Blink Configuration: Extra time between code 
      repeats 
      MILblk_code_rpt Flash Code Blink Configuration: Number of times to repeat 
      a code 
      MILblk_code_strt_max Maximum number of cycles to blink a flash code for a 
      historic fault. If set to 0, a flash code will blink until the fault 
      clears. 
      MILblk_derate Flash Code Blink Configuration: Power derate MIL blink 
      enable switch 
      MILblk_digit_off Flash Code Blink Configuration: Blink off-time 
      MILblk_digit_on Flash Code Blink Configuration: Blink on-time 
      MILblk_input_moment Flash Code Blink Configuration: Blink sequence input 
      switch type (toggle switch vs. momentary switch) 
      MILblk_off An active fault may cause a continuous MIL output activation or 
      a blinking/pulsing MIL output. The on/off times specify this behavior. For 
      a continuously on output in an active state, simply set the offtime to 
      zero and the ontime to any value. 
      MILblk_on An active fault may cause a continuous MIL output activation or 
      a blinking/pulsing MIL output. The on/off times specify this behavior. For 
      a continuously on output in an active state, simply set the offtime to 
      zero and the ontime to any value. 
      MILblk_open_ini MIL open-output transfer: Blink/Pulse Initial time - This 
      is the initial blink/pulse on-time that will be used for the first pulse 
      following an open-output transfer to another channel. 
      MILblk_open_off MIL open-output transfer: Blink/Pulse Off-Time 
      configuration (ms) 
      MILblk_open_on MIL open-output transfer: Blink/Pulse On-Time configuration 
      (ms) 
      MILblk_series_wait Flash Code Blink Configuration: Extra time before 
      starting codes over 
      MILblk_start_wait Flash Code Blink Configuration: Delay before start of 
      code blinking 
      MILblk_trigger_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the input, this value 
      determines the active logic state(s). The Default values are:
      Aux DIG1 = Gnd
      Aux DIG2 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG3 = Gnd
      Aux DIG4 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG5 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG6 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG7 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG8 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG9 = Gnd
      Aux DIG10 = Gnd
      Aux DIG11 = Gnd
      Aux DIG12 = Gnd
      Aux DIG13 = Gnd
      Aux DIG14 = Gnd
      Aux DIG15 = Gnd
      Aux DIG16 = Gnd
      Aux DIG17 = Gnd
      Aux DIG18 = Gnd
      Aux DIG19 = Gnd
      Gov1 = Gnd
      Gov2 = Gnd 
      MILblk_trigger_ena Select the ECM input that will trigger a blink 
      sequence. The 'Default' option looks for a grounded RS-232 Rx line on ECMs 
      that support RS-232. For ECMs without RS-232 support (the majority of 4G 
      variants DO NOT support RS-232), the 'Default' option disables flash code 
      blinking. Flash code blinking will only occur when the selected input is 
      grounded during an engine-stopped key-on situation. 
      MILchan_open This switch controls which output pin will be actuated when 
      the MIL s triggered and the normal MIL output is detected to be open. If 
      the MIL, soft, and hard warning channels are set or transferred to the 
      same output, MIL functionality receives the highest priority and soft 
      warning functionality receives the lowest priority. 
      MILout_mirror MIL output pin 
      MILpdfb_off Power Derate Mode MIL Fast-blink Configuration: Fast-blink 
      off-time 
      MILpdfb_on Power Derate Mode MIL Fast-blink Configuration: Fast-blink 
      on-time 
      MILst_off Key-on, Engine-off Stored Fault Blink Configuration: Blink 
      off-time 
      MILst_on Key-on, Engine-off Stored Fault Blink Configuration: Blink 
      on-time 
      MIL_DM1_output Sets DM1 lamps bit configuration. "Legacy" sends ON or OFF 
      only. "Euro VI Discriminatory MIL" sends MIL status based on Euro VI 
      dsicriminatory MIL states which allows blinking of the MIL. 
      MIL_LS_raw MIL output low-side voltage diagnostic input 
      MIL_off_loVf MIL open diagnostic: Low-side feedback lower limit threshold 
      MIL_on_hiVf MIL control short to power diagnostic: Low-side feedback upper 
      limit threshold 
      MIL_output_chan This switch controls which output pin will be actuated 
      when the MIL is triggered. The MIL output channel needs to be distinct 
      from the soft and hard warning output channels, as there is no priority 
      scheme in place to handle conflicts between these channel assignments when 
      a MIL output open condition is not present. 
      MIL_persist_min Minimum ON-time for the following indicators:
      - MIL (FSF_MIL_STATE, MIL_persist_tmr)
      - Soft warning (flag1_SWARN)
      - Hard warning (flag1_HWARN)
      - Derate 1 (DERATE1_active)
      - Derate 2 (DERATE2_active)
      - NOx derate (DERATE_NOx_active)
      - Low rev limit (LOWREVLIM_active)
      Once condition clears, the indicator will continue to persist for this 
      amount of time. Minimum value is 0.050 seconds. 
      MIL_persist_tmr MIL persistence timer 
      MIL_start_cnt MIL persistence engine start counter 
      MIL_start_cnt_min This value determines MIL illumination behavior after an 
      active fault has gone inactive. If it is set to zero, then the MIL will 
      extinguish as soon as the fault goes inactive (subject to the minimum 
      active on-time above).

      If it is set to a value > 0 then the MIL will be continuously illuminated 
      in this many subsequent engine start cycles even if the fault does not 
      reactivate. For example, a value of 1 will only cause the MIL to stay on 
      during the current engine run cycle in which the fault went active. A 
      value of 4 will cause the MIL to stay on during the current run cycle and 
      3 subsequent engine start cycles.

      If the "Fault system mode" is configured as 'Euro VI' or 'CARB 1971.1' 
      this setting is ignored. The MIL behavior will instead be determined by 
      the applicable legislation requirements.

      For 'Custom' and 'State Standard V (SSV)' fault system modes, this setting 
      is also ignored if "Fault action persist MIL" is enabled. Instead, the 
      fault action persist configuration will determine MIL illumination 
      behavior for all faults with the "Action Persist" fault switch selected. 
      For all other faults, a zero value for this parameter is enforced. 
      MIL_start_cnt_mina Actual/effective MIL_start_cnt_min value. May be 
      adjusted from desired base on active fault system mode. 
      MIL_status MIL state as used by configurable output feature 
      mindgv_I_max Min Droop Governor: Integrator Max 
      mindgv_I_min Min Droop Governor: Integrator Min 
      mingv_auth_max Min Governor: Max authority value 
      mingv_auth_min Min Governor: Min authority value 
      mingv_gain_slct Min Gov Gain selection (Fuel Based, Standard Gains, or 
      Alternate Gains) 
      mingv_nomload Droop governor nominal load 
      mingv_odz Min Governor output deadzone value

      mingv_spk_Kpu Min Spark Governor undershoot gain

      mingv_spk_mxret Min Spark Governor max retard

      (value)

      minigv_I_min Min Isochronous Governor: Integrator Min 
      MinMAP_ena Switch: Engine running Minimum MAP Control (Enable/Disable) 
      MinMAP_frz_wait This parameter defines a countdown timer that initiates 
      once the engine enters engine running mode – once countdown decays to 
      zero, calculation of real time Min MAP target values begins. 
      MinMAP_maxTPS This parameter value defines a maximum TPS modification 
      percentage authority to maintain minimum MAP. 
      MinMAP_psd minimum MAP control pseudo MAP target (psia ) 
      MinMAP_slew This parameter limits the rate at which the throttle opens 
      [psi/sec] while trying to achieve the Target Min MAP. 
      MinMAP_spdgov Enables minimum MAP control while in a discrete speed 
      governor mode (governors 1-3). 
      MinMAP_target Engine running Minimum MAP Control: MAP lower (minimum) 
      limit 
      min_allspeed_rpm Lower rpm value for FPP Speed Control when "FPP speed 
      control mode rpm range" is set to "Min-Max Governor rpm range". When the 
      Idle Pull Away Speed is disabled, this value is always equal to the min 
      governor speed. When the Idle Pull Away speed is enabled, this value is 
      not influenced by the idle pull away speed, and reflects the value that 
      would have been used as the min governor speed if the Idle Pull Away Speed 
      was disabled. 
      min_gov_rpm Min Gov current desired engine speed 
      min_gov_rpm_dummy min_gov_rpm_dummy 
      Min_KV Min KV

      MJ_azero_status MJ autozero status (applicable only to the DEPR product). 
      MJ_azero_wt This value determines how long a delay will be imposed after 
      key-on before a delta-P sensor autozero sequence is initiated. Note this 
      feature is only available on DEPR products and should be used with caution 
      in fixed-venturi applications only. A value of zero disables this feature. 

      MJ_A_act Legacy EPR duty-cycle feedback 
      MJ_A_cmd EPR Area command (units of percent) 
      MJ_cal_state Cal/Param communication state machine value 
      MJ_choke_pct Additional after-start fuel enrichment (%) for MJ/EPR fuel 
      trim devices. 
      MJ_comm_tout Timeout for receipt of at least one message from the 
      MegaJector. 
      MJ_crk_holdN If this value and the slew value below are both set to zero, 
      only the nominal/initial cranking pressure setpoint will be used during 
      cranking. Otherwise, the initial pressure will be used through this number 
      of cranking cycles and will begin to slew toward the final pressure 
      setpoint value after this hold period. 
      MJ_crk_holdP If this value and the slew value below are both set to zero, 
      only the nominal/initial cranking pressure setpoint will be used during 
      cranking. Otherwise, the initial pressure will be used through this number 
      of cranking cycles and will begin to slew toward the final pressure 
      setpoint value after this hold period. 
      MJ_crk_run_slewN Limits the maximum nominal pressure command slew during 
      the crank-to-run transition. Set this value to 0 to disable this feature. 
      MJ_crk_run_slewP Limits the maximum nominal pressure command slew during 
      the crank-to-run transition. Set this value to 0 to disable this feature. 
      MJ_crk_slewN If this value and the hold value above are both set to zero, 
      only the nominal/initial cranking pressure setpoint will be used during 
      cranking. Otherwise, the initial pressure will be used through the hold 
      cranking cycles and will then slew toward the final pressure setpoint 
      value over this number of cycles. 
      MJ_crk_slewP If this value and the hold value above are both set to zero, 
      only the nominal/initial cranking pressure setpoint will be used during 
      cranking. Otherwise, the initial pressure will be used through the hold 
      cranking cycles and will then slew toward the final pressure setpoint 
      value over this number of cycles. 
      MJ_ctltype_act Megajector control type feedback 
      MJ_ctltype_cmd EPR Control mode (offline, pressure, area, pulsed, and 
      pressure plus area feed forward) 
      MJ_ctl_strat Selects the Megajector control strategy type:
      Internal PID Only = no ECM feedforward information
      Feedforward Area = ECM provides feedforward information 
      MJ_ctl_support Megajector control-type support 
      MJ_ftran_Pdef If the switch above is set to 'Fixed command value', this is 
      the EPR target pressure used during a fuel type transition. 
      MJ_intF_bits Megajector internal fault bit pattern 
      MJ_man_mode Megajector / EPR / DEPR Manual Mode 
      MJ_man_mode_map Engine MAP must be below this limit to activate the 
      Megajector / EPR / DEPR Manual Mode. 
      MJ_man_mode_rpm Engine speed must be below this RPM limit to activate the 
      Megajector / EPR / DEPR Manual Mode. 
      MJ_nom_crkN Nominal/Initial pressure setpoint to use during cranking on 
      MegaJector/EPR systems. This pressure will be the only pressure used 
      during cranking if BOTH the hold and slew cranking cycle values are set to 
      zero below. Otherwise, this pressure will be used up through the hold 
      cycle value, and then will linearly slew toward the final value defined 
      below. 
      MJ_nom_crkP Nominal/Initial pressure setpoint to use during cranking on 
      MegaJector/EPR systems. This pressure will be the only pressure used 
      during cranking if BOTH the hold and slew cranking cycle values are set to 
      zero below. Otherwise, this pressure will be used up through the hold 
      cycle value, and then will linearly slew toward the final value defined 
      below. 
      MJ_nom_crkslwdN Final/Slewed pressure setpoint to use during cranking on 
      MegaJector/EPR systems. This pressure will be ignored and unused during 
      cranking if BOTH the hold and slew cranking cycle values are set to zero 
      above. Otherwise, this pressure will be the final pressure used during 
      cranking following the hold period and completion of the linear slew 
      period toward this value from the initial pressure setpoint. 
      MJ_nom_crkslwdP Final/Slewed pressure setpoint to use during cranking on 
      MegaJector/EPR systems. This pressure will be ignored and unused during 
      cranking if BOTH the hold and slew cranking cycle values are set to zero 
      above. Otherwise, this pressure will be the final pressure used during 
      cranking following the hold period and completion of the linear slew 
      period toward this value from the initial pressure setpoint. 
      MJ_offline_damp Parameter controls the EPR's mechanical damping when 
      offline and the engine is running. EPR is considered offline when it is 
      not the active fuel device. When parameter set to 'Enabled' and the EPR is 
      offline, the EPR will be commanded to a 0% duty cycle when the engine is 
      running. 
      MJ_param_comm Automatically download engine calibration version of the 
      Megajector control parameters into the Megajector on power-up and burn 
      them into the Megajector flash. 
      MJ_param_differ EPR cal parameter status 
      MJ_param_support Megajector parameter communication support level - 
      -1=None, 0=Unknown (not yet determined), 1=MJ, 2=EPR 
      MJ_param_upload upload parameters from MJ/EPR to ECM when requested by the 
      user 
      MJ_Pe_HiExp EPR / CFV regulation pressure higher than expected diagnostic: 
      EPR (actual-commanded) pressure lower limit threshold - Difference between 
      the commanded and actual EPR gaseous fuel delivery pressure on the 
      positive (high) side that will trigger a fault. 
      MJ_Pe_LoExp EPR / CFV regulation pressure lower than expected diagnostic: 
      Difference between the commanded and actual EPR gaseous fuel delivery 
      pressure on the negative (low) side that will trigger a fault. NOTE: Must 
      be a negative number.

      MJ_VVC_Ao_m For diaphragm-type carbs, the outer perimeter of the diaphragm 
      is held in a fixed position. Therefore, an 'effective' area should be used 
      for diaphragm force and displacement computations. 
      MJ_VVC_CdA_dia CdA for the vacuum transfer passages on the diaphragm. 
      MJ_VVC_Cd_a VV Carb Model: Carb inlet air flow Cd 
      MJ_VVC_damp VV Carb Model: Carb diaphragm damping 
      MJ_VVC_Di The area of the diaphragm exposed to the carburetor 
      mixer/throat. 
      MJ_VVC_Do The area of the diaphragm exposed to the incoming air flow when 
      the valve is shut (donut-shaped). 
      MJ_VVC_ena Enables/disables calculation of the VVC carb transient model. 
      MJ_VVC_iterreq Variable Venturi Mixer Pressure Corrections: VVC number of 
      iterations 
      MJ_VVC_ks VV Carb Model: Carb spring constant 
      MJ_VVC_MAP_add The steady-state TIP compensation term is used on boosted 
      engines where the instantaneous TIP may differ from the TIP when the fuel 
      table was calibrated (even after the transients have dissipated and the 
      transient correction term is inactive). A steady-state TIP correction term 
      is continuously applied using the filtered MAP + MAP delta-P as the 
      nominal TIP target. Entering a '0' for the TIP comp multiplier disables 
      this compensation. 
      MJ_VVC_MAP_tau The steady-state TIP compensation term is used on boosted 
      engines where the instantaneous TIP may differ from the TIP when the fuel 
      table was calibrated (even after the transients have dissipated and the 
      transient correction term is inactive). A steady-state TIP correction term 
      is continuously applied using the filtered MAP + MAP delta-P as the 
      nominal TIP target. Entering a '0' for the TIP comp multiplier disables 
      this compensation. 
      MJ_VVC_mdot_a Variable Venturi Mixer Pressure Corrections: VVC inlet air 
      flow 
      MJ_VVC_mdot_dia Variable Venturi Mixer Pressure Corrections: VVC diaphragm 
      flow 
      MJ_VVC_mdot_ports Variable Venturi Mixer Pressure Corrections: VVC port 
      flow 
      MJ_VVC_mdot_tau VV Carb Model: Carb throttle flow tau 
      MJ_VVC_mdot_thtl Variable Venturi Mixer Pressure Corrections: VVC throttle 
      flow 
      MJ_VVC_mount VV Carb Model: Carburetor Mounting 
      MJ_VVC_m_dia The total mass of the diaphragm assembly, including the fuel 
      valve. 
      MJ_VVC_num_carbs This value will typically be 1 and must be less than or 
      equal to 2. For multiple carburetor installations (200D, 2 carbs, ...) 
      enter the total number of carburetors and enter physical parameters for 1 
      diaphragm only. 
      MJ_VVC_Pcrct Variable Venturi Transient fuel pressure correction 
      multiplier 
      MJ_VVC_Pcrct_gt1 Enter the amount of transient compensation to apply on 
      tip-in. A value of 0.0 disables the compensation, while 1.0 applies full 
      compensation. When used with a Megajector or Cobra EPR, this usually leans 
      the mixture during tip-in. 
      MJ_VVC_Pcrct_lt1 Enter the amount of transient compensation to apply on 
      tip-out. A value of 0.0 disables the compensation, while 1.0 applies full 
      compensation. When used with a Megajector or Cobra EPR, this usually 
      richens the mixture during tip-out. 
      MJ_VVC_Pcrct_ss Variable Venturi Steady State fuel pressure correction 
      multiplier 
      MJ_VVC_Pcrct_TIP Enter the amount of steady-state TIP compensation to 
      apply. A value of 0.0 disables the compensation, while 1.0 applies full 
      compensation based on the difference between the current TIP and the 
      nominal TIP from the 'CL' calibration section. 
      MJ_VVC_Pdia Variable Venturi Mixer Pressure Corrections: VVC diaphragm 
      pressure 
      MJ_VVC_Pth Variable Venturi Mixer Pressure Corrections: VVC throat 
      pressure

      MJ_VVC_stict_delta VV Carb Model: Carb diaphragm sticktion delta

      MMF_delivery_press Micro Motion fuel flow rate voltage output 
      MMF_filter_dpress Micro Motion fuel filter differential pressure 
      MMF_flow_rate Micro Motion fuel flow rate 
      MMF_flow_rate_raw Micro Motion fuel delivery pressure 
      MMSD_ena This switch controls the engine spin-down minimum and maximum MAP 
      control function. This function will manage a DBW throttle to maintain an 
      approximate MAP following a key-off/engine-running condition as the engine 
      comes to a stop (spin-down).

      Minimum MAP can be used to limit MAP to a minimum value, such as baro, to 
      release vacuum through the engine and exhaust.

      Maximum MAP can be used to set a MAP maximum value, such as MAP near idle, 
      for smoother spin-down. 'Max MAP – filtered idle' will initialize the MAP 
      target to the single point target and will low-pass filter the target 
      while the engine is running, the FPP indicates idle, and engine speed is 
      within 200 RPM of the ECT-based idle.

      NOTE: this control will only remain active until the 'Underspeed' rpm 
      threshold is reached. To keep this control active longer on spin-down, 
      lower the 'Underspeed' parameter. 
      MMSD_maxMAP If 'Max MAP - filtered idle' is selected, this is the current 
      value for the filtered idle MAP target. 
      MMSD_maxTPS This value will be the maximum TPS used during active engine 
      spin-down MAP control. 
      MMSD_MinMAP This value will be the minimum or maximum (single point) MAP 
      target used during engine spin-down. For 'Max MAP – filtered idle', this 
      value will be the initial value which is then low-pass filtered during 
      idle conditions when the engine is running.

      NOTE: this is only an approximate value since no closed-loop MAP control 
      using the actual MAP is used. The MAP target is used to select TPS, and 
      the learned min/max TPS values will be reset to their defaults during 
      spin-down. 
      MMSD_minTPS This value will be the minimum TPS used during active engine 
      spin-down MAP control. 
      MMSD_TPS_pct If MMSD_active is active (MAP spin down control), this is the 
      target TPS setting 
      MODFRC_diesel_CRI Obsoleted parameter

      MSP2_appdn_kph This is the vehicle speed window below the max vehicle 
      speed setpoint where blinking/pulsing the control indication light/output 
      can take place AFTER speed control initial engagement. Set this value to 
      zero to disable this function. The output indication will simply go from 
      full-on to full-off once the speed control releases if this function is 
      disabled. This parameter only applies if the system is in primary vehicle 
      speed mode. 
      MSP2_appdn_rpm This is the rpm window below the max engine speed setpoint 
      where blinking/pulsing the control indication light/output can take place 
      AFTER speed control initial engagement. Set this value to zero to disable 
      this function. The output indication will simply go from full-on to 
      full-off once the speed control releases if this function is disabled. 
      This parameter only applies if the system is in primary engine speed mode. 

      MSP2_appup_kph This is the vehicle speed window below the max speed 
      setpoint where blinking/pulsing the control indication light/output can 
      take place PRIOR to speed control initial engagement. Set this value to 
      zero to disable this function. The output indication will simply go from 
      full-off to full-on once the speed control takes over if this function is 
      disabled. This parameter only applies if the system is in primary vehicle 
      speed mode. 
      MSP2_appup_rpm This is the rpm window below the max engine speed setpoint 
      where blinking/pulsing the control indication light/output can take place 
      PRIOR to speed control initial engagement. Set this value to zero to 
      disable this function. The output indication will simply go from full-off 
      to full-on once the speed control takes over if this function is disabled. 
      This parameter only applies if the system is in primary engine speed mode. 

      MSP2_app_lock_kph This is the vehicle speed +/- tolerance that indicates a 
      'locked' or solid user setpoint indication. This parameter only applies if 
      the system is in secondary vehicle speed mode. 
      MSP2_blkdn_offt In the fall-off indication rpm window, the control 
      indication light/output will blink with the given on-time and off-time. 
      The blink total period is the sum of these two values, and the duty-cycle 
      can be modified using asymmetry. This parameter only applies if the system 
      is in primary engine/vehicle speed mode. 
      MSP2_blkdn_ont In the fall-off indication rpm window, the control 
      indication light/output will blink with the given on-time and off-time. 
      The blink total period is the sum of these two values, and the duty-cycle 
      can be modified using asymmetry. This parameter only applies if the system 
      is in primary engine/vehicle speed mode. 
      MSP2_blkup_offt In the approach indication rpm window, the control 
      indication light/output will blink with the given on-time and off-time. 
      The blink total period is the sum of these two values, and the duty-cycle 
      can be modified using asymmetry. This parameter only applies if the system 
      is in primary engine/vehicle speed mode. 
      MSP2_blkup_ont In the approach indication rpm window, the control 
      indication light/output will blink with the given on-time and off-time. 
      The blink total period is the sum of these two values, and the duty-cycle 
      can be modified using asymmetry. This parameter only applies if the system 
      is in primary engine/vehicle speed mode. 
      MSP2_set_source This switch determines how and where the max engine speed 
      setpoint is determined. The 'governor switches' setting means that the 
      speed is set similar to a cruise control function momentary button 
      increase/decrease functionality, and the other 'proportional' inputs 
      indicate a voltage source determination of the setpoint. 
      MSP_1tap_rpm This is the amount the user max speed RPM setpoint will 
      change immediately following 1 increase button press. 
      MSP_1tap_RS This is the amount the user max speed roadspeed setpoint will 
      change immediately following 1 increase button press. 
      MSP_app_lock_kph This is the vehicle speed +/- tolerance that indicates a 
      'locked' or solid user setpoint indication. This parameter only applies if 
      the system is in primary vehicle speed mode. 
      MSP_blkdn_offt In the fall-off indication rpm window, the control 
      indication light/output will blink with the given on-time and off-time. 
      The blink total period is the sum of these two values, and the duty-cycle 
      can be modified using asymmetry. This parameter only applies if the system 
      is in primary engine/vehicle speed mode. 
      MSP_blkdn_ont In the fall-off indication rpm window, the control 
      indication light/output will blink with the given on-time and off-time. 
      The blink total period is the sum of these two values, and the duty-cycle 
      can be modified using asymmetry. This parameter only applies if the system 
      is in primary engine/vehicle speed mode. 
      MSP_blkup_offt In the approach indication rpm window, the control 
      indication light/output will blink with the given on-time and off-time. 
      The blink total period is the sum of these two values, and the duty-cycle 
      can be modified using asymmetry. This parameter only applies if the system 
      is in primary engine/vehicle speed mode. 
      MSP_blkup_ont In the approach indication rpm window, the control 
      indication light/output will blink with the given on-time and off-time. 
      The blink total period is the sum of these two values, and the duty-cycle 
      can be modified using asymmetry. This parameter only applies if the system 
      is in primary engine/vehicle speed mode. 
      MSP_incdec_HW_input This selection determines the source for the 
      increment/decrement speed momentary switch function of the user setpoint 
      max speed system. 
      MSP_incdec_sw Increment/Decrement software switch 
      MSP_max_rpm This is the upper bound and initial value for the max user 
      setpoint RPM control function. 
      MSP_max_RS This is the upper bound and initial value for the max user 
      setpoint roadspeed control function. 
      MSP_min_rpm This is the lower bound for the max user setpoint RPM control 
      function. 
      MSP_min_RS This is the lower bound for the max user setpoint roadspeed 
      control function. 
      MSP_mode_sw Current Software Switch State (OFF/Engine Speed/Ground Speed 
      modes) as an INPUT 
      MSP_prisec Current active primary/secondary/network MaxSetPt system 
      enabled 
      MSP_prop_rpm0 These parameters determine the linear transfer function 
      between input voltage and max engine speed setpoint. 
      MSP_prop_rpm1 These parameters determine the linear transfer function 
      between input voltage and max engine speed setpoint. 
      MSP_prop_tau Low-pass filter time constant to be applied to the incoming 
      proportional voltage source. 
      MSP_prop_V Current lowpass filtered proportion speed setpoint voltage 
      value for the max engine speed limit system when in proportional setpoint 
      mode. 
      MSP_prop_V0 These parameters determine the linear transfer function 
      between input voltage and max engine speed setpoint. 
      MSP_prop_V1 These parameters determine the linear transfer function 
      between input voltage and max engine speed setpoint. 
      MSP_prop_V_mstr User Setpoint Max Speed System: Proportional setpoint 
      enabled switch 
      MSP_rampRS_final When either increase or decrease button is held down, 
      this is the final full roadspeed increase ramp-rate that will be achieved 
      following the initial delay and the phase-in time. 
      MSP_ramp_delay This switch controls the user max speed setpoint control 
      system. The AUX PUx selections allow Off=OPEN, RPM or Roadspeed 
      control=GROUND options. The AUX DIGx selections allow Off=OPEN, RPM 
      control=GROUND, Roadspeed control=+V options. The PU2 options with DIG2 
      qualification use the state of DIG2 at key-on and ignore it thereafter.
      Engagement via PU2 is ignored on a Slave engine if the multi-engine sync 
      enable is set to 'PU2 on Slave'. 
      MSP_ramp_final When either increase or decrease button is held down, this 
      is the final full RPM increase ramp-rate that will be achieved following 
      the initial delay and the phase-in time. 
      MSP_ramp_phase When either increase or decrease button is held down, this 
      is the amount of time (following the delay time) during which the speed 
      ramp rate will be increased from zero to the full ramp rate value. 
      MSP_setclr_HW_input This selection determines the source for the set/clear 
      function of the user setpoint max speed system. 
      MSP_setclr_sw Set/Clear software switch 
      MSP_set_source This switch determines how and where the max engine speed 
      setpoint is determined. The 'governor switches' setting means that the 
      speed is set similar to a cruise control function momentary button 
      increase/decrease functionality, and the other 'proportional' inputs 
      indicate a voltage source determination of the setpoint. 
      MSP_status Max speed set point engagement 
      MSspk_fire Spark firing test status:
      1) Test Not Started
      2) Test Running
      3) Test Finished
      4) Condition 1 Not Met
      5) Condition 2 Not Met
      6) Condition 3 Not Met
      7) Condition 4 Not Met
      8) Cannot Start Test 
      MSspk_kill Spark kill test status:
      1) Test Not Started
      2) Test Running
      3) Test Finished
      4) Condition 1 Not Met
      5) Condition 2 Not Met
      6) Condition 3 Not Met
      7) Condition 4 Not Met
      8) Cannot Start Test 
      m_a_perL Mass of air per liter displacement inducted 
      m_a_port Mass of air per intake event at a single port 
      m_a_port_cmd Requested mass of air per intake event (does not include EGR) 
      at a single port 
      m_d_cmd_TD_tau Decreases in diluent commands are accepted immediately 
      without filtering or slewing. With low-pressure EGR applications, 
      reductions in diluent commands are filtered using this time constant in 
      order to more accurately represent the actual diluent flow and help reduce 
      fueling errors. This value is ignored in high-pressure EGR applications, 
      since CFV fueling is based on EGR feedback. Set this to 0 to disable this 
      filter. Typically, a value of 50-100ms yields good results. 
      m_d_pct_act EGR measured diluent 
      m_d_pct_act_dry EGR diluent actual (dry) 
      m_d_pct_cmd Diluent achievable/commanded flow component in percent by 
      mass-fraction of total flow (air+diluent) 
      m_d_pct_cmdmdl EGR diluent modeled - command 
      m_d_pct_cmd_dly EGR transport-delayed command 
      m_d_pct_cmd_dz Diluent command deadzone 
      m_d_pct_cmd_OFF If the EGR command is non-zero (i.e. the EGR command has 
      previously exceeded the 'on' limit above), the EGR command will be set to 
      0 when the EGR command percent drops below this limit. Set to 0 to disable 
      hysteresis based on the command percent. 
      m_d_pct_cmd_ON If the EGR command is 0, the EGR command percent must 
      exceed this limit before non-zero EGR commands are installed. Set to 0 to 
      disable hysteresis based on the command percent. 
      m_d_pct_cmd_tau Diluent command low-pass 
      m_d_pct_dP EGR measured diluent - dP 
      m_d_pct_FL Full load diluent command 
      m_d_pct_LL Off/Min limited diluent command 
      m_d_pct_MAF EGR measured diluent - MAF 
      m_d_pct_min Min diluent command 
      m_d_pct_nom Nominal diluent command 
      m_d_pct_octmin Octane-compensated min diluent request 
      m_d_pct_octnom Octane-compensated nom diluent request 
      m_d_pct_oct_ofst Actual additional percent EGR added to standard/alternate 
      commanded percent EGR for octane adaptation. 
      m_d_pct_reqmin Minimum diluent command request 
      m_d_pct_reqnom Nominal diluent command request 
      m_d_pct_req_lp Requested diluent flow component in percent by 
      mass-fraction of total flow (air+diluent) 
      m_d_pct_spk EGR diluent @ TDC for retard 
      m_d_pct_UEGO EGR measured diluent - UEGO 
      m_d_port Mass of diluent per intake event at a single port 
      m_f_choke Additional after-start fuel (mg/intake), derived from "Primary 
      Choke Fuel Adder (%)" table 
      m_f_choke2 Additional after-start fuel (mg/intake), derived from 
      "Secondary Choke Fuel Adder (%)" table. 
      m_f_port Mass of fuel per intake event at a single port 
      m_f_start Additional start fuel (mg/intake) 
      m_f_ww1 Mass fuel - wall-wet 
      NACK2_cnt NACK (not acknowledged) activity - CAN2 
      NACK2_last_PGN Requested PGN is not recognized 
      NACK2_last_RA Last NACK return address - CAN2 
      NACK2_last_SA Last NACK source address - CAN2 
      NACK3_cnt NACK (not acknowledged) activity - CAN3 
      NACK3_last_PGN Requested PGN is not recognized 
      NACK3_last_RA Last NACK return address - CAN3 
      NACK3_last_SA Last NACK source address - CAN3 
      NACK_cnt NACK (not acknowledged) activity - CAN1 
      NACK_last_PGN Requested PGN is not recognized 
      NACK_last_RA Last NACK return address - CAN1 
      NACK_last_SA Last NACK source address - CAN1 
      Ncyl Total engine cylinders. 
      NG_LPG_ovlp Time that both Lockoff valves will both be ON while 
      transitioning from NG to LPG. 
      NMHG_FPPidle_chk This switch enables an application specific Nacco (NMHG) 
      transmission type check based on a received CAN/J1939 message from the 
      Nacco VSM. If the transmission type is detected as a type 1 or type 14, 
      then the 'FPP idle valid' value is overridden and set to 3%. In addition, 
      the FPP->TPS non-linear mapping mode may be set to 'Network Select' and 
      these same transmissions will cause 'Option 2' to become active (instead 
      of 1). The CAN/J1939 parameters for this message are PGN Rx=65298, SPN 
      Rx=65367. 
      NMHG_perfmode_cmd Three bit performance mode command 
      NMHG_trans_type Integer indicating the Nacco (NMHG) transmission type.

      NOx_hi_ECT Minimum ECT required to initiate and maintain NOx Exceedance 
      fault validation. 
      NOx_hi_ppm NOx Exceedance fault threshold. 
      NOx_hi_tau Low-pass time constant used to generate the NOx Exceedance 
      fault measurement. 
      NOx_ppm_filt Measured and filtered NOx Exceedance value. 
      NTEphi_ALlo_active logical indicating that NTEphi_ALlo_slew should be used 
      as the global AL_lo limit 
      NTEphi_ALlo_lim NTE zone table extracted (instantaneous) lower AL limit 
      NTEphi_ALlo_slew slew rate limited version of NTEphi_ALlo_lim 
      NTEphi_AL_ramp_rate AL lower-limit transition slew rate when 
      engaging/disengaging NTE zone phi lower limiting. 
      NTEphi_CLlo_active logical indicating that NTEphi_CLlo_slew should be used 
      as the global CL_lo limit 
      NTEphi_CLlo_lim NTE zone table extracted (instantaneous) lower CL limit 
      NTEphi_CLlo_slew slew rate limited version of NTEphi_CLlo_lim 
      NTEphi_CL_ramp_rate CL lower-limit transition slew rate when 
      engaging/disengaging NTE zone phi lower limiting. 
      NTEphi_ena Enable/disable the NTE zone phi transition system. This system 
      establishes a RPM/MAP line through the standard phi calibration. At lower 
      MAP than this line, the standard phi calibration is used. At MAP 
      conditions higher than this line plus the MAP hysteresis value, the lower 
      limit phi target is enforced. Normal hysteresis is used between these 
      modes, and phi slewing is used between these modes to ensure smooth engine 
      operation. 
      NTEphi_lim NTE phi transition instant lower phi limit extracted from table 
      lookup 
      NTEphi_lim_active logical indicating NTE phi transition system actively 
      attempting to lower-limit the current phi 
      NTEphi_lim_slew NTE phi transition slew limited lower phi limit 
      NTEphi_MAP NTE zone table extracted MAP limit in psia 
      NTEphi_MAPdt_slewoff Any active phi transition slewing is immediately 
      terminated if the MAPdt exceeds this value. 
      NTEphi_MAP_hyst MAP hysteresis value to be used when engaging/disengaging 
      NTE zone phi lower limiting. Two MAP thresholds are established:
      MAP_lower = MAP table value
      MAP_upper = MAP_lower + MAP_hysteresis
      Below MAP_lower, no phi limiting is imposed, Above MAP_upper, phi lower 
      limiting is active. 
      NTEphi_MAP_LP NTE phi transition filtered MAP in psia 
      NTEphi_MAP_LP_tau Additional MAP low-pass time constant for use with the 
      NTE zone phi transition system. More filtering is typically required with 
      speed control systems to prevent the system from continuously engaging and 
      disengaging. 
      NTEphi_slew_rate Phi transition slew rate when engaging/disengaging NTE 
      zone phi lower limiting. Any MAP transitions exceeding the MAPdt threshold 
      below will immediately terminate this slewing.

      OBSOLETE_9266 Low-passed version of the total mass flow rate to the entire 
      engine at the ports used by the Envirotech ambient air temperature invalid

      OBSOLETE_931 Obsoleted parameter
