      RBC_ABS_disable Disables the driveline and exhaust brake while one or more 
      of the following J1939 messages are being received:

      1) TSC1 from ABS to ECM (ECI PGN 11) with SPN 695 Override Control Mode 
      set to 3 (Speed/Torque Limit Control)

      2) EBC1 SPN 563 set to 1 (ABS active) 
      RBC_allowed Retarder braking allowed indicator 
      RBC_CAN_ena When set to "Enabled", retarder braking is enabled if any of 
      the following J1939 messages are received:

      - EBC1 (SA 0x17, ECI PGN 42365 or SA 0x21, ECI PGN 42325) with SPN 973 
      'Engine Retarder Selection' set to 1-100%
      - Any of the following TSC1 CAN identifiers with SPN 695 'Engine Override 
      Control Mode' set to 2 (Torque control) and SPN 518 'Engine Requested 
      Torque/Torque Limit' set to a negative torque value:
      - 0x0C000003 (ECI PGN 42327)
      - 0x0C000F03 (ECI PGN 42347)
      - 0x0C000F0B (ECI PGN 42491)
      - 0x0C000F10 (ECI PGN 42352)
      - 0x0C000F21 (ECI PGN 42344)
      - 0x0C000F27 (ECI PGN 339)
      - 0x0C000F2A (ECI PGN 42364)
      - 0x0C002910 (ECI PGN 42326)
      - 0x0C002927 (ECI PGN 42340) 
      RBC_enabled This input is monitored to determine if 
      transmission/engine/exhaust braking is allowed. 
      RBC_enabled_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the "Retarder braking 
      enabled input", this value determines the active logic state(s). Default 
      values are defined when Aux DIG1 through Aux DIG12 are selected for the 
      control activation:
      Aux DIG1 = Select
      Aux DIG2 = Select
      Aux DIG3 = Select
      Aux DIG4 = Select
      Aux DIG5 = Select
      Aux DIG6 = Select
      Aux DIG7 = Select
      Aux DIG8 = Select
      Aux DIG9 = Select
      Aux DIG10 = Select
      Aux DIG11 = Select
      Aux DIG12 = Select 
      RBC_min_ECT_ena Used to disable the Driveline and/or Exhaust brake 
      activation when ECT is less than the corresponding minimum set below. 
      RBC_min_ECT_override Sets the engine run time when the Driveline and 
      Exhaust brake minimum ECT temperature thresholds are no longer required to 
      enable braking. A value of 0 disables the engine run time override, i.e. 
      the minimum ECT is always enforced.
      NOTE: the minimum ECT temperature thresholds and run time override both 
      require 'Retarder disabled by minimum ECT' to be set to YES. 
      RBC_mode_support Retarder torque mode (SPN 900) update method:
      'Brake is engaged (legacy)' - Retarder torque mode is supported when 
      driveline brake is actually engaged.
      'Brake switch is enabled' - Retarder torque mode is supported when 
      driveline brake is enabled.
      This parameter influences the value of SPN 900 in the following ERC1 
      messages:
      0x18F00000 (ECI PGN 61440)
      0x18F0000F (ECI PGN 42489 and 61568) 
      RBC_outofgear Disables brake activation if the driveline is not engaged 
      (e.g. clutch is depressed or transmission is in neutral). Note this only 
      applies to the engine compression and exhaust brake; the transmission 
      retarder is always allowed to engage. 
      RBC_ovrspd_ena If enabled, retarder braking is automatically engaged if an 
      engine overspeed condition is detected in order to reduce engine speed. 
      For the 'Engage at spark rev limit' option, an overspeed condition exists 
      if engine speed exceeds the RPM threshold specified for the "Spark rev 
      limit" diagnostic. An overspeed condition exists for the 'Engage at fixed 
      speed limit' if engine speed exceeds the "Overspeed braking fixed speed 
      limit" parameter value. 

      The type of retarder brake to engage is configured in the "Overspeed 
      braking engagement" parameter. 
      RBC_ovrspd_engage Specifies the type of retarder braking to engage when an 
      engine overspeed condition is detected and "Retarder braking during engine 
      overspeed" is enabled. The selected retarder braking type must be enabled 
      for engagement using the "Driveline brake mode" and/or "Exhaust brake 
      operating mode" parameters. 
      RBC_ovrspd_rpm_lmt Specifies the engine speed threshold to engage retarder 
      braking when an engine overspeed condition is detected. This limit is 
      enforced when "Retarder braking during engine overspeed" is set to 'Engage 
      at fixed speed limit'. 
      RBC_ovrspd_RS_min Specifies the minimum roadspeed required to engage 
      retarder braking when an engine overspeed condition is detected. 
      RBC_TSC1_arb_mode When parameter is set to 'Normal', the TSC1 arbitration 
      process is not modified. This parameter only applies when "J1939 TSC1 
      message prioritization" is set to 'Lowest speed/torque'.

      When set to 'Remove from arbitration', TSC1 requests sent to the retarder 
      are removed from normal TSC1 arbitration. The following ECI PGNs are 
      removed from normal TSC1 arbitration:
      - 0x0C000F03 (ECI PGN 42347)
      - 0x0C000F0B (ECI PGN 42491)
      - 0x0C000F10 (ECI PGN 42352)
      - 0x0C000F21 (ECI PGN 42344)
      - 0x0C000F24 (ECI PGN 42355)
      - 0x0C000F27 (ECI PGN 339)
      - 0x0C000F2A (ECI PGN 42364)
      - 0x0C00290B (ECI PGN 42490)
      - 0x0C002910 (ECI PGN 42326)
      - 0x0C002924 (ECI PGN 42356)
      - 0x0C002927 (ECI PGN 42340 or 42361)

      When set to 'Full authority override', active full authority TSC1 requests 
      will override any active retarder braking TSC1 requests having the same 
      priority (SPN 897).

      A retarder braking TSC1 request is defined as either:
      - A torque control request (SPN 695 set to 2) with a torque value less 
      than 0% (SPN 518).
      - A torque limit request (SPN 695 set to 3) with a torque limit value 
      equal to 0% (SPN 518).

      A full authority TSC1 request is defined as either:
      - A torque control request (SPN 695 set to 2) with a torque value greater 
      than 0% (SPN 518).
      - A speed control request (SPN 695 set to 1) with any speed value (SPN 
      898). 
      RBC_TSC1_disengage Parameter determines how TSC1 retarder braking 
      disengage requests are processed. A retarder braking disengage request is 
      defined as a torque limit request (SPN 695 set to 3) with a torque limit 
      value equal to 0% (SPN 518).

      When set to 'Arbitrate All', then all retarder braking disengage requests 
      are processed by the normal TSC1 arbitration process. Note: retarder 
      braking is not guaranteed to disengage when using this option. For 
      example, when "Retarder braking enabled input" is configured as an Aux DIG 
      input, an active input will override a TSC1 disengage request. This option 
      is not applicable when "Retarder braking TSC1 arbitration mode" is set to 
      'Remove from arbitration'.

      When set to 'Remove 42491 (Legacy)', then all retarder braking disengage 
      requests, except for ECI PGN 42491, are processed by the normal TSC1 
      arbitration process. Note: retarder braking is not guaranteed to disengage 
      when using this option. For example, when "Retarder braking enabled input" 
      is configured as an Aux DIG input, an active input will override a TSC1 
      disengage request. This option is not applicable when "Retarder braking 
      TSC1 arbitration mode" is set to 'Remove from arbitration'.

      When set to 'Disable Retarder Braking', then retarder braking disengage 
      requests are not processed through the normal TSC1 arbitration process. 
      The requests will disable retarder braking and override all other inputs. 
      Overridden inputs include: Aux DIG inputs, SPN 973 in EBC1, and TSC1 
      messages requesting retarder engagement). The only exception is when 
      engine overspeed is detected. This option only supports the following ECI 
      PGNs:
      - 0x0C000F03 (ECI PGN 42347)
      - 0x0C000F0B (ECI PGN 42491)
      - 0x0C000F10 (ECI PGN 42352)
      - 0x0C000F21 (ECI PGN 42344)
      - 0x0C000F24 (ECI PGN 42355)
      - 0x0C000F27 (ECI PGN 339)
      - 0x0C000F2A (ECI PGN 42364)
      - 0x0C00290B (ECI PGN 42490)
      - 0x0C002910 (ECI PGN 42326)
      - 0x0C002924 (ECI PGN 42356)
      - 0x0C002927 (ECI PGN 42340 or 42361)

      RELAY_keyoff_chk Relay key-off fault checking enable (for all relay

      feedback lower limit threshold 
      RELAY_powered_coil If the ignition coils are relay powered, all spark 
      faults will be ignored while the "Relay on low voltage" fault is active. 
      RELAY_powered_inj If the injectors are relay powered, all injector faults 
      will be ignored while the "Relay on low voltage" fault is active. 
      reprog_security Hardware model number and revision level are always 
      enforced. This dropdown optionally adds software model number and/or 
      revision level enforcement.

      Disabled - Software model number and revision level checks are disabled.

      Match SW Model # - Software model number of the incoming Mot file has to 
      match with the target's Software model number.

      Match SW Model # and Rev- Software model number of the incoming Mot file 
      has to match with the target and revision level has to be >= target. 
      reset_learn_action User selectable manual learn modes: none, learn TPS 
      idle/full, learn EGR zero, learn pressure offsets, learn all 
      reset_learn_active TPS idle/full, EGR zero, and pressure offset learning 
      active timer 
      reset_learn_reprog Enables TPS idle/full, EGR zero, and pressure sensor 
      offset learning after a flash reprogramming event when "Key-off clear with 
      relay on" is enabled. Learning will execute in a key-on, engine-off state 
      based on the calibration for the key-off clear and pressure offset pegging 
      parameters.

      During post-reprogramming learning, each of the following operations will 
      optionally execute if its associated calibration parameter is enabled:

      - Idle and full TPS voltage learning: "Key-off learn TPS idle/full"
      - EGR 0% valve open feedback voltage learning: "Key-off clear EGR and 
zero"
      - Pressure sensor offset pegging: "Pressure offset pegging"
      - EGRdP sensor offset learning: "EGRdP offset learn" 

      The "Key-off clear hold" parameter must be configured with sufficient time 
      to allow all of the enabled learn operations to complete.

      Deposit-clearing TPS and EGR sweep operations are not supported during 
      post-reprogramming learning. 

      reset_learn_state Current TPS idle/full, EGR zero, and pressure offset 
      learning state 
      resync_wait Crank tooth down-counter that disables all spark and injection 
      events while greater than zero. 
      ReverseRotation This switch is supported by some crank-cam modules (CCMs) 
      for right-hand (reverse) engine rotation indication. The firing order of 
      the engine must still be reversed in the calibration for some features to 
      operate properly. 
      rev_lim_fuel Fuel shutoff rev limit. 
      rev_lim_fuel_drpm "Fuel rev limit proportional span": If this value is 
      greater than zero, then fuel injectors will be shut off one by one over 
      this proportional rpm band. If this value is set to zero, then all 
      injectors are killed simultaneously. 
      rev_lim_spk Spark shutoff rev limit. 
      rev_lim_spk_drpm "Spark rev limit proportional span": If this value is 
      greater than zero, then spark coils will be shut off one by one over this 
      proportional rpm band. If set to zero, then all spark coils will be killed 
      simultaneously. 
      RFdur_CAD CAD required to have enough time to fire refire spark 
      rFPin non-defaulted version of fuel rail pressure (FPin) - primary 
      rFPin_I2 non-defaulted version of fuel rail pressure (FPin) - secondary 
      rFT non-defaulted version of fuel regulator temperature 
      RF_spk_ena Refire spark enable 
      RF_spk_MAP Refire spark MAP threshold. MAP must be below this value for 
      refire spark. 
      rho_diesel diesel fuel specific gravity in mg/mm^3 
      rIAT Nondefault version of IAT 
      rMAP Non-default version of MAP 
      RMT_AAT The AAT value received over the CAN network from a remote source 
      in the J1939 AMB PGN. 
      RMT_aux_SD_state Remote engine aux shutdown state (Inactive, Requesting 
      Stop, Stop Wait, Requesting Start) 
      RMT_BP The BP value received over the CAN network from a remote source. 
      RMT_clear_SD Remote shutdown clear (None, Request Clear) 
      RMT_cool_stop Remote cool down before shutdown request status. 
      RMT_ctl_COOL_STOP Remote cool down before shutdown request indicator. 
      RMT_ctl_FAULT Remote control fault indicator 
      RMT_ctl_flag1 remote control authority flag 1 
      RMT_ctl_FPPRAW Remote control FPP active indicator 
      RMT_ctl_FUEL Remote control fuel indicator 
      RMT_ctl_P1_TRQ Indicator that a TSC1 P1 torque control request is active. 
      RMT_ctl_P2_TRQ Indicator that a TSC1 P2 torque control request is active. 
      RMT_ctl_SD Remote control shutdown indicator 
      RMT_ctl_SPEED Remote control / Active TSC1 speed indicator 
      RMT_ctl_SPEED_LMT Remote control / Active TSC1 speed limit indicator 
      RMT_ctl_START Remote starter control indicator 
      RMT_ctl_STOP Remote engine stop request indicator 
      RMT_ctl_THROT Remote throttle request indicator 
      RMT_ctl_TRQ Remote control / Active TSC1 torque indicator 
      RMT_ctl_TRQ_LMT Remote control / Active TSC1 torque limit indicator 
      RMT_ff_torq_mode This software switch controls whether or not any network 
      feedforward torque requests will be supported using PGN 65351/SPN 65144.

      By setting this switch to other than 'Disabled', the value in SPN 65144 
      will be interpreted as a feedforward term in the Gov3 commanded load % 
      computation.

      If this switch is set to 'Enabled - Gov Load %', the value transmitted is 
      interpreted in units of governor load as defined by the no-load/full-load 
      governor calibration.

      If this switch is set to 'Enabled - Ref Torque %', the value transmitted 
      is interpreted as an absolute torque when multiplied by the J1939 Engine 
      Configuration (EC) reference torque. This value is resolved back to 
      governor load % units using the torque estimation calibration. 
      RMT_FPP1_raw Remote FPP1 raw voltage 
      RMT_FPP2_raw Remote FPP2 raw voltage 
      RMT_fuel_select Remote fuel select request (0 = gasoline, 1 = gaseous, 2 = 
      LPG only, 3 = NG only) 
      RMT_gov_att_ena This software switch controls whether or not any network 
      governor gain attenuators will be utilized. This feature is currently used 
      by Linde Forklift to attenuate the Kd gain using their proprietary 
      LINDE_GOV packet. 
      RMT_IVS_atidle Remote IVS at idle indication (0=off idle, 1= on idle) 
      RMT_Kd_att Remote Kd attenuator 
      RMT_load Remote torque percentage request after conversion to percent load 

      RMT_loadlim_tbl Displays the current J1939 engine speed based load-limit 
      table command 
      RMT_load_lmt Remote torque percent limit request after conversion to 
      percent engine load (see RMT_torq_lmt) 
      RMT_P1_load ECI engine load corresponding to the received TSC1 P1 torque 
      control request (RMT_P1_torq). 
      RMT_P1_torq Received torque control request percentage from a TSC1 message 
      with a P1 control purpose. 
      RMT_P2_load ECI engine load corresponding to the received TSC1 P2 torque 
      control request (RMT_P2_torq). 
      RMT_P2_torq Received torque control request percentage from a TSC1 message 
      with a P2 control purpose. 
      RMT_RH The RH value received over the CAN network from the remote source. 
      RMT_RS_mode Roadspeed network target mode Sumitomo 
      RMT_RS_pulses_per_km Roadspeed network pulse calibration received from 
      Sumitomo 
      RMT_RS_speed_1 Roadspeed network speed target 1 Sumitomo 
      RMT_RS_speed_2 Roadspeed network speed target 2 Sumitomo 
      RMT_RS_speed_byte Roadspeed network max speed byte. 
      RMT_SH The SH value received over the CAN network from a remote source. 
      RMT_speed Remote Speed Request 
      RMT_speed_gov_trans Parameter controls Gov3's target speed when 
      transitioning between governors due to a full-authority TSC1 speed request 
      becoming inactive. Full-authority TSC1 speed requests utilize Gov3. When a 
      speed request is no longer active, the active governor will change from 
      Gov3 to the Min or Max governor. However, a governor switch can take up to 
      50ms to complete. In 'Legacy' mode, Gov3 will target Gov3_rpm during the 
      governor transition. In 'Persist Speed Request' mode, Gov3 will target the 
      most recently received RMT_speed value before the request became inactive. 
      The speed request is persisted during the governor switch. 
      RMT_speed_lmt Remote speed limit request 
      RMT_speed_lmt_SA Remote speed limit source address 
      RMT_speed_SA Remote speed source address 
      RMT_start Remote starter control status 
      RMT_start_ena This switch enables remote starting via a communication link 
      command. The output is implemented on the 'starter lockout' control pin 
      but with inverse logic to the starter lockout. 
      RMT_start_rpm The output is implemented on the 'starter lockout' control 
      pin but with inverse logic to the starter lockout. 
      RMT_start_tmr Remote starter limit timer 
      RMT_start_tout The engine speed at which the ECM disengages the starter 
      motor during a remote start command 
      RMT_start_tstcomp Remote start test compression 
      RMT_stop The maximum time the ECM will allow a remote start request to 
      crank the engine before disengaging the starter motor 
      RMT_stop_occurred Remote engine stop log (Inactive, Caused Engine Stop) 
      RMT_throt Remote throttle request 
      RMT_torq Remote engine stop request (w/o shutdown fault logic) 
      RMT_torq_lmt Remote torque limit 
      RMT_torq_lmt_SA Remote torque limit source address 
      RMT_torq_SA Remote torque source address 
      RMT_tsc_fpp_ena Enables the operation of both TSC1 Full-Authoritative 
      speed requests and FPP Speed Control for rpm governance.

      In this mode, the foot pedal commands a speed based on position. However, 
      the commanded foot pedal speed value will be overridden by the value 
      received in a TSC1 Full-Authoritative speed request message (refer to TSC1 
      SPNs: 695 and 898).

      When Disabled, TSC1 Full-Authoritative speed requests are ignored, and the 
      FFP Speed Control has full control of the commanded speed value. 
      ROC_attempts_cnt Running-on-cam (ROC) activation attempts counter. 
      ROC_cam_est_rpm_min Parameter is the minimum required camshaft-estimated 
      engine speed when attempting to activate ROC. If camshaft-estimated engine 
      speed (rpm_cam_est) is less than this parameter, then ROC will not be 
      allowed to activate. Parameter can be used to prevent false-positive ROC 
      activations during engine spin-down. Set parameter slightly lower than the 
      cold-ambient cranking speed. To disable parameter, set to 0 rpm. 
      ROC_crank_rpm_min Parameter is the minimum required crankshaft-based 
      engine speed when attempting to activate ROC while cranking the engine. 
      This parameter is only applicable when the crankshaft sensor initially 
      detects teeth, but begins missing teeth while engine is cranking. When run 
      mode is 'Cranking', ROC can only activate if the last known 
      crankshaft-based engine speed is above this parameter. This parameter can 
      be used to prevent false-positive ROC activations after starter disengages 
      and engine is spinning down. Set parameter slightly lower than the 
      cold-ambient cranking speed. To disable parameter, set to 0 rpm. Note: 
      parameter does not prevent ROC activation when no crank teeth are detected 
      while cranking the engine. 
      ROC_ena Parameter enables running-on-cam (ROC) signal if crank signal is 
      lost. Feature only supports the following calibration configuration:
      "Engine type" is set to 'Spark-ignited non-DI'
      "Spark system type" is set to 'Coil Per Cylinder'
      "Fuel type select configuration" is set to 'NG Only' 
      "NG fuel admission device type" is set to 'Continuous Injection'
      "crank-cam module" is set to 'Generic 60-2 crank, 6+1 cam'
      "crank skip teeth" is set to 0
      "crank edge capture" is set to 'Falling Edges'
      "cam1 edge capture" is set to 'Falling Edges'
      "Tachometer output override" is set to 'Disable Override'

      When parameter is set to 'Enabled' and the above calibration criteria are 
      true, the ECM will use the cam signal to run the engine if the crank is 
      considered lost. The crank signal is considered lost if less than half of 
      the expected crank pulses are received between normal cam pulses. The 
      switch to cam can occur during engine cranking or running. After the 
      switch, the engine speed and spark/injection timing will be based on the 
      cam signal.

      Once the switch to the cam signal occurs, the "Crank loss" fault will 
      latch if enabled, knock faults are disabled, and misfire detection is 
      disabled. To switch back to running on the crank signal, the engine must 
      stop and key turned off. 
      ROC_run_rpm_min Parameter is the minimum crankshaft-based engine speed 
      required when attempting to activate ROC after engine has already started. 
      When run mode is 'Running' or 'Underspeed', ROC can only activate if the 
      last known crankshaft-based engine speed is above this parameter. 
      Parameter can be used to prevent false-positive ROC activations during 
      engine spin-down. Set parameter lower than the engine idle speed. To 
      disable parameter, set to 0 rpm. 
      ROC_stat Running-on-cam (ROC) status:
      0 = 'Disabled' - ROC_ena is disabled
      1 = 'Cal Unsupported' - enabled but calibration not supported
      2 = 'Inactive' - enabled but not active
      3 = 'Active' - enabled and active 
      ROC_stop_time_min Parameter is the minimum engine-stopped time before 
      allowing ROC activation while run mode is 'Stopped'. This parameter can 
      indirectly be used to prevent false-positive ROC activations during engine 
      spin-down. At very slow engine speeds, crank teeth may not be detectable 
      while cam teeth are detectable. The run mode will change to 'Stopped' when 
      crank teeth have not been received for 150ms. If a cam tooth is received 
      subsequently, this parameter can be used to prevent ROC from activating. 
      Set parameter to 1-2 seconds. To disable, set parameter to 0 seconds. 
      rpm Engine speed 
      rpmdt LPF version of drpm/dt (time rate of change or engine speed) 
      rpmdtdz_Kd Governor rpm Derivative deadzone 
      rpmdtd_gov Final target drpm/dt for governor 
      rpmdt_n RPMdt filter window 
      rpmdt_slow This is the slow filtered rpmdt value. This is typically used 
      during idle return min governor control and some nonstandard governor 
      conditions. 
      rpmdt_sLP This is the second-order filter time-constant use to generate 
      the slow-filtered rpmdt value. This is typically used during idle-return 
      min-governor control and some non-standard governor conditions. 
      rpmdt_xLP RPM dt filter low-pass 
      rpmdz_Ki Governor rpm Integral deadzone 
      rpmdz_Kp Governor rpm Proportional deadzone 
      rpmd_gain rpm target used for gain lookup and selection 
      rpmd_gov RPM trajectory target 
      rpmd_gov_lo_lmt Unable to achieve low target speed diagnostic: (rpm - 
      governor desired speed) delta threshold 
      rpmd_gov_lo_max Unable to achieve low target speed diagnostic: governor 
      desired speed upper limit threshold 
      rpmd_gov_lo_min Unable to achieve low target speed diagnostic: governor 
      desired speed lower limit threshold 
      rpm_cam_est Cam-estimated engine speed. Only calculated when 
      running-on-cam (ROC) is supported. 
      rpm_filt Actual RPM 
      rpm_filt_n Width of window average for slow filtered rpm. 
      RPM_high_air RPM at high airflow point (mdot_air_max); used for 
      calculating the MAT estimate 
      rpm_hi_expected RPM higher than expected diagnostic - RPM upper limit 
      threshold 
      rpm_instant Instantaneous engine speed, valid after crank synchronization. 

      RPM_stat_ena Enables the monitoring of the engine speed (rpm) to record 
      the max speed and the engine hour meter of the last speed >= the trigger 
      speed. 
      RPM_stat_hi_acc Accumulated time while meeting/exceeding the 
      RPM_stats_hi_trig threshold. 
      RPM_stat_hi_HM The hour meter at which the engine speed met or exceeded 
      the RPM_stat_hi_trig value. 
      RPM_stat_hi_trig If the engine speed meets or exceeds this trigger limit 
      the engine speed hour meter will be updated. The engine speed hour meter 
      update may only trigger once per engine cycle. 
      RPM_stat_max The maximum engine speed seens since last reset. 
      RPM_stat_reset_key Specifies the unique key (1-65535) required to clear 
      the engine speed statistics. 
      RPM_stat_reset_usr Engine speed statistics may be reset be setting this 
      variable to the RPM_stat_reset_key value. 
      RS2ovsc_deng This is the delta roadspeed below the target at which the 
      overshoot control will initiate. 
      RS2ovsc_denghyst This is the delta roadspeed below the target and the 
      engage delta at which the overshoot control will be rearmed after being 
      disarmed. 
      RS2ovsc_dIlim This is limit of authority of the integrator ramp rate 
      during roadspeed overshoot control. It is expressed as a positive number 
      even though the actual ramp rate on the integrator will be negative. 
      RS2ovsc_ena This switch enables/disables the roadspeed overshoot control 
      feature. This system introduces a potentially extremely high Kiv gain just 
      as the roadspeed approaches the target, and then removes this gain as soon 
      as the roadspeed derivative becomes <= 0. 
      RS2ovsc_Kiv This is the main gain used by the roadspeed overshoot control 
      system described above. It is only in effect when the system is armed, the 
      roadspeed is >= targetdeltaengage, and roadspeed derivative > 0. 
      RS2ovsc_Kiv_phout This is the time phaseout over which any additional Kiv 
      gain used for overshoot control will be ramped to zero. 
      RS2ovsc_table This switch selects either single-point or table-based 
      overshoot control gains/parameters. The table-based parameters are indexed 
      as a function of desired roadspeed. 
      RS2_dot_dzlim This cubic deadzone limit is applied to the final lowpass 
      acceleration estimation before use in the control loop error terms. 
      RS2_dot_ovsc_tau This is the time constant used to lowpass RS_dot todetect 
      a deceleration transition after overshoot control has approached the 
      target setspeed. 
      RS2_dot_tau Lowpass filter time constant for the 
      RS2_dot_window Time value over which to estimate the acceleration 
      RS2_gainset Control parameter set selection - set 2 
      RS2_Kd Road speed limiting PID loop derivative gain. This is the only Kd 
      gain used if the Kd_accel gain is set to < 900.0 (such as 999.0). If, 
      however, Kd_accel is set to a number > 900.0 (such as a normal positive 
      value), then this Kd gain becomes the Kd_decel gain and is only used when 
      the acceleration error is positive (deceleration). 
      RS2_Kd_accel Road speed limiting PID loop acceleration derivative gain. 
      Setting this gain to avalue > 900.0 (such as a normal positive number) 
      causes this gain to be used as the Kd when the acceleration error is 
      negative (acceleration). Setting this value to < 900.0 (such as 999.0) 
      causes this gain to be ignored and the standard Kd / Kd_decel gain is used 
      regardless of the sign of the acceleration error. 
      RS2_Ki Road speed limiting PID loop integrator gain. 
      RS2_Kiv Road speed limiting PID loop integral derivative 
      RS2_Kivapp_add During conditions in which the roadspeed is not in proper 
      tolerance, an additional Kiv 'adder' can be used to increase the effective 
      Kiv gain to prevent over/under shoot. This value is the +/ deadband from 
      the target roadspeed where the adder will be used at its full value (100% 
      Kiv adder). This is the Kiv adder that will be added to the base Kiv value 
      depending on the roadspeed error from the final target. The two values 
      below define how this adder is phased in as the roadspeed error increases 
      away from the setpoint. 
      RS2_Kivapp_RS0 During conditions in which the roadspeed is not in proper 
      tolerance, an additional Kiv 'adder' can be used to increase the effective 
      Kiv gain to prevent over/under shoot. This value is the +/ deadband from 
      the target roadspeed where the adder will be completely eliminated (adder 
      = 0). At roadspeed errors larger than this value, the adder will be 
      linearly increased from zero toward the full adder value at the 'full' 
      approach value. 
      RS2_Kivapp_RS100 During conditions in which the roadspeed is not in proper 
      tolerance, an additional Kiv 'adder' can be used to increase the effective 
      Kiv gain to prevent over/under shoot. This value is the +/ deadband from 
      the target roadspeed where the adder will be used at its full value (100% 
      Kiv adder). At roadspeed errors smaller than this value, the adder will be 
      linearly decreased toward zero as the 'zero' value is approached. 
      RS2_Kp Road speed limiting PID loop proportional gain. 
      RS2_Kp_dz This is the cubic deadzone that will be applied to the 
      proportional (Kp) error term for roadspeed control. 
      RS2_Kp_dz_tout This is a timeout value that will be used each time the 
      roadspeed error term exceeds the proportional (Kp) deadzone value. During 
      the timeout period, the deadzone value will be temporarily set to zero. 
      RS2_source This switch determines the source for the ground speed 
      measurement information. 
      RS2_speed_tau Lowpass filter time constant for the road speed 
      RS2_TPS_tau Lowpass filter time constant for the road speed 
      RS3ovsc_deng This is the delta roadspeed below the target at which the 
      overshoot control will initiate. 
      RS3ovsc_denghyst This is the delta roadspeed below the target and the 
      engage delta at which the overshoot control will be rearmed after being 
      disarmed. 
      RS3ovsc_dIlim This is limit of authority of the integrator ramp rate

      even though the actual ramp rate on the integrator will be negative.

      as the roadspeed approaches the target, and then removes this gain as soon

      system described above. It is only in effect when the system is armed, the 
      roadspeed is >= target deltaengage, and roadspeed derivative > 0. 
      RS3ovsc_Kiv_phout This is the time phaseout over which any additional Kiv

      RS3ovsc_table This switch selects either singlepoint or tablebased 
      overshoot control gains/parameters. The tablebased parameters are indexed 
      as a function of desired roadspeed. 
      RS3_dot_dzlim This cubic deadzone limit is applied to the final lowpass

      RS3_dot_ovsc_tau This is the time constant used to lowpass RS_dot to 
      detect a deceleration transition after overshoot control has approached 
      the target setspeed. 
      RS3_dot_tau Lowpass filter time constant for the 
      RS3_dot_window Time value over which to estimate the acceleration 
      RS3_gainset Control parameter set 3 selection 
      RS3_Kd Road speed limiting PID loop derivative gain. This is the only Kd 
      gain used if the Kd_accel gain is set to < 900.0 (such as 999.0). If, 
      however, Kd_accel is set to a number > 900.0 (such as a normal positive 
      value), then this Kd gain becomes the Kd_decel gain and is only used when 
      the acceleration error is positive (deceleration). 
      RS3_Kd_accel Road speed limiting PID loop acceleration derivative gain. 
      Setting this gain to a value > 900.0 (such as a normal positive number) 
      causes this gain to be used as the Kd when the acceleration error is 
      negative (acceleration). Setting this value to < 900.0 (such as 999.0) 
      causes this gain to be ignored and the standard Kd / Kd_decel gain is used 
      regardless of the sign of the acceleration error. 
      RS3_Ki Road speed limiting PID loop integrator gain. 
      RS3_Kiv Road speed limiting PID loop integral derivative 
      RS3_Kivapp_add During conditions in which the roadspeed is not in proper 
      tolerance, an additional Kiv 'adder' can be used to increase the effective 
      Kiv gain to prevent over/under shoot. This value is the +/ deadband from 
      the target roadspeed where the adder will be used at its full value (100% 
      Kiv adder). This is the Kiv adder that will be added to the base Kiv value 
      depending on the roadspeed error from the final target. The two values 
      below define how this adder is phased in as the roadspeed error increases 
      away from the setpoint. 
      RS3_Kivapp_RS0 During conditions in which the roadspeed is not in proper 
      tolerance, an additional Kiv 'adder' can be used to increase the effective 
      Kiv gain to prevent over/under shoot. This value is the +/ deadband from 
      the target roadspeed where the adder will be completely eliminated (adder 
      = 0). At roadspeed errors larger than this value, the adder will be 
      linearly increased from zero toward the full adder value at the 'full' 
      approach value. 
      RS3_Kivapp_RS100 During conditions in which the roadspeed is not in proper 
      tolerance, an additional Kiv 'adder' can be used to increase the effective 
      Kiv gain to prevent over/under shoot. This value is the +/ deadband from 
      the target roadspeed where the adder will be used at its full value (100% 
      Kiv adder). At roadspeed errors smaller than this value, the adder will be 
      linearly decreased toward zero as the 'zero' value is approached. 
      RS3_Kp Road speed limiting PID loop proportional gain. 
      RS3_Kp_dz This is the cubic deadzone that will be applied to the 
      proportional (Kp) error term for roadspeed control. 
      RS3_Kp_dz_tout This is a timeout value that will be used each time the 
      roadspeed error term exceeds theproportional (Kp) deadzone value. During 
      the timeout period, the deadzone value will be temporarily set to zero. 
      RS3_source This switch determines the source for the ground speed 
      measurement information. 
      RS3_speed_tau Lowpass filter time constant for the road speed 
      RS3_TPS_tau Lowpass filter time constant for the road speed 
      RS485_bad_fmt RS-485 Invalid Packet Format diagnostic: number of invalid 
      formats minimum packet threshold 
      RS485_Rx_inact RS-485 Rx inactive diagnostic: "power alive" minimum 
      duration threshold 
      RS485_Rx_noise RS-485 Rx noise diagnostic: minimum number of noisy packets 
      threshold 
      RS485_SD_rq RS-485 shutdown request diagnostic: minimum number of shutdown 
      requests threshold 
      RSC_CAN_set_sw This parameter determines how receipt of the "Cruise 
      Control Set Switch" (SPN 599) in the J1939 Cruise Control/Vehicle Speed 1 
      (CCVS1) PGN is processed. If set to "Engage only", receipt of SPN 599 with 
      a value of 0x01 (Cruise control activator in position "set") will engage 
      cruise control if currently disengaged. Any subsequent active set switch 
      signals are ignored once cruise control is engaged. 

      If this parameter is set to "Engage + disengage", receipt of SPN 599 value 
      0x01 will also engage cruise control if currently disengaged. However, 
      subsequent active set switch signals will disengage cruise control.

      For the "Disengage only" option, receipt of SPN value 0x01 will only 
      disengage cruise control if currently engaged. 

      This parameter only applies when the 'Roadspeed cruise set/inc input' and 
      'Roadspeed cruise set/dec input' parameters are set to "CAN sourced".

      RSC_CCVS_status Roadspeed cruise status:
      • Disabled
      • Holding
      • Accelerating
      • Decelerating
      • Resuming
      • Setting
      • User Override 
      RSC_control_device Parameter selects the device which controls the cruise 
      control engagement/disengagement, roadspeed setpoint, and min FPP cruise 
      control governor. When set to 'ECM', then the engagement and computation 
      of the cruise control governor is internal to the ECM.

      When set to 'External - P2 Torque Control', then an external device 
      computes the cruise control governor and sends a TSC1 torque control 
      request with a P2 control purpose. The "J1939 TSC1 P2 control purpose" 
      calibration parameter must be enabled on the Comms worksheet. See "J1939 
      TSC1 P2 control purpose" for details. When cruise control is enabled 
      (RSC_enabled) and a valid P2 torque control message is received, then 
      cruise control will engage and RMT_P2_load will be stored into the min FPP 
      governor (RS_min_FPP). Cruise control will disengage if RSC_enabled is 
      false or the TSC1 P2 message times out or is no longer requesting torque 
      control. The max roadspeed governor (RS_max_FPP) is still computed and 
      controlled by the ECM while cruise control is engaged.

      Cruise control entry conditions and overrides are the responsibility of 
      the external device which is providing the P2 TSC1 message. The ECM's only 
      entry condition is RSC_enabled which contains the following conditions 
      when external device is controlling cruise:
      - Roadspeed must be greater than "Roadspeed cruise min speed disengage". 
      Set to 0 km/hr to disable criteria.
      - "Roadspeed cruise enable" input is active. Set to 'Always enabled' to 
      always allow cruise control.

      The following ECM calibration parameters will not be applicable when an 
      external device is controlling cruise control: RSC_disable_by_RBC, 
      RSC_disable_2inputs, RSC_min_kph, RSC_max_kph, RSC_disable_rpm, 
      RSC_resume_ramp, RSC_setinc_tap, RSC_setinc_wait, RSC_setinc_ramp, 
      RSC_setdec_tap, RSC_setdec_wait, RSC_setdec_ramp, RSC_ramp_time_max, 
      RSC_error_pct, RSC_error_wait, RSC_CAN_set_sw, and AMT_neut_coast_mode.

      The following ECM measurements will not be available when an external 
      device is controlling cruise control: RS_FPPmin_Iacc, RS_speed_d, 
      RSC_speed_accum, RSC_speed_slew, RSC_CCVS_status, and AMT_RSC_suspend.

      The ECM's cruise control switch inputs for 
      disable/resume/increment/decrement can still be configured and broadcasted 
      to the external device using ECI PGN 42278. 
      RSC_disable_2inputs If enabled, roadspeed cruise is disabled if two or 
      more resume, set, accelerate (set/+) or decelerate (set/-) active input 
      signals are received simultaneously. 
      RSC_disable_by_RBC Disables cruise when retarder braking is allowed by 
      conditions in "Retarder Braking Control", or after receiving a J1939 ERC1 
      message with any of the following conditions:
      - SPN 520, "Actual Retarder - Percent Torque" is negative, or
      - SPN 1715, "Drivers Demand Retarder - Percent Torque" is negative; or
      - SPN 900, "Retarder Torque Mode", is not set to 0, "No request". 
      RSC_disable_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the input, this value 
      determines the active logic state(s). The Default values are:
      Aux DIG1 = Gnd
      Aux DIG2 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG3 = Gnd
      Aux DIG4 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG5 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG6 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG7 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG8 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG9 = Gnd
      Aux DIG10 = Gnd
      Aux DIG11 = Gnd
      Aux DIG12 = Gnd
      Aux DIG13 = Gnd
      Aux DIG14 = Gnd
      Aux DIG15 = Gnd
      Aux DIG16 = Gnd
      Aux DIG17 = Gnd
      Aux DIG18 = Gnd
      Aux DIG19 = Gnd
      Gov1 = Gnd
      Gov2 = Gnd 
      RSC_disable_chan Can optionally be paired with a momentary Cruise Enable 
      switch. If a Cruise Disable switch is configured, the momentary Cruise 
      Enable will no longer toggle between ON and OFF states. The Cruise Enable 
      will only toggle ON. The Cruise Disable is by default a momentary switch. 
      RSC_disable_kph Enter the absolute minimum vehicle speed allowed while 
      cruise is active. If the vehicle speed drops below this limit at any time, 
      cruise will be automatically disengaged. This limit should generally be 
      set considerably below the minimum speed setpoint above. Set this value to 
      0.0 to disable this feature. 
      RSC_disable_rpm If the engine speed fails below this limit, cruise will 
      disengage if active. If not active, the engine speed must reach or exceed 
      this limit before cruise will engage.

      Set this value to 0 to disable this feature. 
      RSC_disable_sw_stat Roadspeed cruise disable switch input status 
      (0=Inactive, 1=Active, 2=Error/Fault, 3=Not Configured). 
      RSC_enabled Latched version of cruise enabled state, used for momentary 
      button presses 
      RSC_enable_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the input, this value 
      determines the active logic state(s). The Default values are:
      Aux DIG1 = Gnd
      Aux DIG2 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG3 = Gnd
      Aux DIG4 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG5 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG6 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG7 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG8 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG9 = Gnd
      Aux DIG10 = Gnd
      Aux DIG11 = Gnd
      Aux DIG12 = Gnd
      Aux DIG13 = Gnd
      Aux DIG14 = Gnd
      Aux DIG15 = Gnd
      Aux DIG16 = Gnd
      Aux DIG17 = Gnd
      Aux DIG18 = Gnd
      Aux DIG19 = Gnd
      Gov1 = Gnd
      Gov2 = Gnd 
      RSC_enable_chan If set to "CAN sourced", receipt of "Cruise Control Enable 
      Switch" (SPN 596) in the J1939 Cruise Control/Vehicle Speed 1 (CCVS1) PGN 
      will enable or disable full-authority roadspeed cruise control.

      Set this value to "Always enabled" to enable roadspeed cruise if no enable 
      switch input is available or desired. Any actual enable switch input is 
      ignored in this mode. Set/inc, set/dec, and resume inputs are still 
      required to engage cruise control. If the disable switch is configured in 
      this mode, cruise will disengage when the switch is ON. 
      RSC_enable_moment Roadspeed cruise enable switch type (toggle or momentary 
      switch) 
      RSC_enable_sw_stat Roadspeed cruise enable switch input status 
      (0=Inactive, 1=Active, 2=Error/Fault, 3=Not Configured). 
      RSC_engaged Logical indicating roadspeed cruise is engaged 
      RSC_engaged_light Determines the output channel for the roadspeed cruise 
      engaged light 
      RSC_error_pct If active cruise control fails to bring the vehicle's 
      roadspeed within this error margin above or below the cruise setpoint 
      within the duration specified in the "Roadspeed cruise persistent error 
      disengage time" parameter, cruise control will be disengaged. This feature 
      is not enforced when accelerator override above the cruise setpoint is 
      applied or the set/+ or set/- buttons are in use.

      Set this value to 0% to disable this feature. 
      RSC_error_wait If active cruise control fails to bring the vehicle's 
      roadspeed within the "Roadspeed cruise persistent error threshold" margin 
      above or below the cruise setpoint within the duration specified by this 
      parameter, cruise control will be disengaged. This feature is not enforced 
      when accelerator override above the cruise setpoint is applied or the 
      set/+ or set/- buttons are in use. 
      RSC_gainset_reengage Parameter provides hysteresis for reengaging 'Cruise 
      Engaged' roadspeed control parameters when cruise control is engaged. When 
      the 'Cruise Engaged' roadspeed control parameters are actively being used, 
      the roadspeed must be below the instantaneous maximum roadspeed limit. If 
      the roadspeed exceeds the maximum roadspeed limit, then the roadspeed 
      control parameters will switch to another set (to 'Default' if no others 
      are enabled). The 'Cruise Engaged' roadspeed control parameters are 
      reengaged after the roadspeed drops below the maximum roadspeed limit 
      minus this parameter's value. Parameter is only applicable when one of the 
      "Control parameter set selection" values is configured as 'Cruise 
      Engaged'. 
      RSC_max_kph Roadspeed cruise max speed setpoint 
      RSC_min_kph Roadspeed cruise min speed setpoint 
      RSC_ramp_time_max While cruise is active, if a set/+ or set/- active input 
      signal is continuously received for this amount of time, cruise will 
      disengage. 

      This function is not available when 'Roadspeed cruise enable' is set to 
      "Always enabled". 
      RSC_resume_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the input, this value 
      determines the active logic state(s). The Default values are:
      Aux DIG1 = Gnd
      Aux DIG2 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG3 = Gnd
      Aux DIG4 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG5 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG6 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG7 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG8 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG9 = Gnd
      Aux DIG10 = Gnd
      Aux DIG11 = Gnd
      Aux DIG12 = Gnd
      Aux DIG13 = Gnd
      Aux DIG14 = Gnd
      Aux DIG15 = Gnd
      Aux DIG16 = Gnd
      Aux DIG17 = Gnd
      Aux DIG18 = Gnd
      Aux DIG19 = Gnd
      Gov1 = Gnd
      Gov2 = Gnd 
      RSC_resume_chan A momentary press of the resume input will install the 
      previous cruise control setpoint if cruise control is enabled. If the 
      set/+ input below is configured for a different input than this switch, 
      this switch serves no other purpose. Otherwise, it is also used as an 
      increment (without functioning as a 'set' input) input.

      If this value is set to 'CAN sourced', then the J1939 Cruise 
      Control/Vehicle Speed 1 (CCVS1) PGN will provide set, resume, increment, 
      and decrement input signals. Any values other than 'CAN sourced' for the 
      "Roadspeed cruise set/inc input" and "Roadspeed cruise set/dec input" 
      parameters are ignored when this value is set to 'CAN sourced'. 
      RSC_resume_ramp When 'resume' is pressed after temporarily exiting cruise 
      control, the speed setpoint is slewed to the previous target speed at this 
      rate. 
      RSC_resume_sw_stat Roadspeed cruise resume switch input status 
      (0=Inactive, 1=Active, 2=Error/Fault, 3=Not Configured). 
      RSC_retard_braking Determines if retarders (transmission, engine 
      compression, exhaust butterfly valve) are allowed to engage while 
      roadspeed cruise control is active. 
      RSC_setdec_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the input, this value 
      determines the active logic state(s). The Default values are:
      Aux DIG1 = Gnd
      Aux DIG2 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG3 = Gnd
      Aux DIG4 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG5 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG6 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG7 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG8 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG9 = Gnd
      Aux DIG10 = Gnd
      Aux DIG11 = Gnd
      Aux DIG12 = Gnd
      Aux DIG13 = Gnd
      Aux DIG14 = Gnd
      Aux DIG15 = Gnd
      Aux DIG16 = Gnd
      Aux DIG17 = Gnd
      Aux DIG18 = Gnd
      Aux DIG19 = Gnd
      Gov1 = Gnd
      Gov2 = Gnd 
      RSC_setdec_chan Configure the vehicle speed set/- input.For 4-switch 
      cruise control setups (on/off, resume, set/+, set/-):
      --------------------------------------
      Select an input different than the resume input above. This input will 
      latch the current vehicle speed when pressed for time < ramp down wait, 
      and will decrease the target speed if pressed longer.

      For 3-switch cruise control setups with shared resume/dec (on/off, 
      resume/-, set/+):
      --------------------------------------------------
      Set the set/- and resume inputs to the same pin. The pin will then 
      function as a resume switch when pressed for time < ramp down wait (i.e. 
      it will not latch the current vehicle speed when pressed momentarily; only 
      the set/+ switch can be used to latch the current vehicle speed). When 
      pressed for time > ramp down wait, this input pin will function as the 
      set/-switch and will decrease the target vehicle speed.

      For "CAN sourced" input: 
      ------------------------------
      If this value is set to "CAN sourced", then the J1939 Cruise 
      Control/Vehicle Speed 1 (CCVS1) PGN will provide set, resume, increment 
      and decrement inputs. Any values other than "CAN sourced" for the 
      'Roadspeed cruise resume input' and 'Roadspeed cruise set/inc input' 
      parameters are ignored when this value is set to "CAN sourced". 
      RSC_setdec_ramp Configures the roadspeed cruise SET/Decrement ramp rate 
      RSC_setdec_sw_stat Roadspeed cruise set/decrement switch input status 
      (0=Inactive, 1=Active, 2=Error/Fault, 3=Not Configured). 
      RSC_setdec_tap Configures the roadspeed cruise SET/Decrement tap step 
      RSC_setdec_wait Configures the roadspeed cruise SET/Decrement ramp wait 
      time 
      RSC_setinc_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the input, this value 
      determines the active logic state(s). The Default values are:
      Aux DIG1 = Gnd
      Aux DIG2 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG3 = Gnd
      Aux DIG4 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG5 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG6 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG7 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG8 = +V/Gnd
      Aux DIG9 = Gnd
      Aux DIG10 = Gnd
      Aux DIG11 = Gnd
      Aux DIG12 = Gnd
      Aux DIG13 = Gnd
      Aux DIG14 = Gnd
      Aux DIG15 = Gnd
      Aux DIG16 = Gnd
      Aux DIG17 = Gnd
      Aux DIG18 = Gnd
      Aux DIG19 = Gnd
      Gov1 = Gnd
      Gov2 = Gnd 
      RSC_setinc_chan Configure the vehicle speed set/+ input.For 4-switch 
      cruise control setups (on/off, resume, set/+, set/-):
      --------------------------------------
      Select an input different than the resume input above. This input will 
      latch the current vehicle speed when pressed for time < ramp up wait, and 
      will increase the target speed if pressed longer.

      For 3-switch cruise control setups with shared resume/inc (on/off, 
      resume/+, set/-):
      --------------------------------------------------
      Set the set/+ and resume inputs to the same pin. The pin will then 
      function as a resume switch when pressed for time < ramp up wait (i.e. it 
      will not latch the current vehicle speed when pressed momentarily; only 
      the set/- switch can be used to latch the current vehicle speed). When 
      pressed for time > ramp up wait, this input pin will function as the set/+ 
      switch and will increase the target vehicle speed.

      For "CAN sourced" input: 
      ------------------------------
      If this value is set to "CAN sourced", then the J1939 Cruise 
      Control/Vehicle Speed 1 (CCVS1) PGN will provide set, resume, increment 
      and decrement inputs. Any values other than "CAN sourced" for the 
      'Roadspeed cruise resume input' and 'Roadspeed cruise set/dec input' 
      parameters are ignored when this value is set to "CAN sourced". 
      RSC_setinc_ramp Configures the roadspeed cruise SET/Increment ramp rate 
      RSC_setinc_sw_stat Roadspeed cruise set/increment switch input status 
      (0=Inactive, 1=Active, 2=Error/Fault, 3=Not Configured). 
      RSC_setinc_tap Configures the roadspeed cruise SET/Increment tap step 
      RSC_setinc_wait Configures the roadspeed cruise SET/Increment ramp wait 
      time 
      RSC_speed_accum Cruise control final target 
      RSC_speed_slew instantaneous roadspeed setpoint for cruise-control resume 
      slewing in km/hr 
      RSdrop_kph_arm Instantaneous Dropout Fault condition 
      RSdrop_kph_trig Roadspeed loss diagnostic (alternate instantaneous dropout 
      detection method): subsequent (slower) roadspeed, measured over a 
      calibrated duration 
      RSdrop_rpm_arm Instantaneous Dropout Fault condition 
      RSdrop_status Roadspeed dropout detection 
      RSdrop_tout_arm Instantaneous Dropout Fault condition 
      RSdrop_tout_disarm Instantaneous Dropout Fault condition 
      RSdrop_tout_trig Instantaneous Dropout Fault condition 
      RSovsc_armed This is an indicator which reports the armed/disarmed status 
      of the roadspeed overshoot control system. It is armed whenever roadspeed 
      control is out of authority and the roadspeed droops. It is disarmed once 
      the roadspeed derivative <= 0 and the roadspeed is near the target. 
      RSovsc_deng This is the delta roadspeed below the target at which the 
      overshoot control will initiate. 
      RSovsc_denghyst This is the delta roadspeed below the target and the 
      engage delta at which the overshoot control will be rearmed after being 
      disarmed. 
      RSovsc_dIlim This is limit of authority of the integrator ramp rate during 
      roadspeed overshoot control. It is expressed as a positive number even 
      though the actual ramp rate on the integrator will be negative. 
      RSovsc_dIlim_a Roadspeed overshoot control rate limit 
      RSovsc_ena This switch enables/disables the roadspeed overshoot control 
      feature. This system introduces a potentially extremely high Kiv gain just 
      as the roadspeed approaches the target, and then removes this gain as soon 
      as the roadspeed derivative becomes <= 0. 
      RSovsc_Kiv This is the main gain used by the roadspeed overshoot control 
      system described above. It is only in effect when the system is armed, the 
      roadspeed is >= targetdeltaengage, and roadspeed derivative > 0. 
      RSovsc_Kiv_a Roadspeed overshoot control Kiv 
      RSovsc_Kiv_phout This is the time phaseout over which any additional Kiv 
      gain used for overshoot control will be ramped to zero. 
      RSovsc_table This switch selects either singlepoint or tablebased 
      overshoot control gains/parameters. The tablebased parameters are indexed 
      as a function of desired roadspeed. 
      RSP_selected currently selected roadspeed parameter set (0,1,2 = Set1,2,3) 

      RS_ana_raw roadspeed mag pickup bias voltage feedback 
      RS_CAN_source Specifies which received J1939 PGN is used for ground speed 
      measurement information when the active roadspeed signal source is set to 
      "J1939 Comm". The default option uses the most recent message and ignores 
      previous messages. 

      The "J1939 TCO1" option takes the roadspeed signal from the received 
      "Tachograph Vehicle Speed" (SPN 1624) contained in the Tachograph 1 PGN. 

      The CCVS option sources the roadspeed signal from the received "Wheel 
      Based Vehicle Speed" (SPN 84) in the Cruise-Control / Vehicle Speed PGN. 
      RS_capture roadspeed edge capture 
      rs_digital_config Roadspeed configuration 
      RS_dir Roadspeed direction 
      RS_disc_ana Roadspeed sensor disconnected measured voltage w/ MAG_BIAS 
      RS_disc_calc Roadspeed sensor disconnected calculated offset + MAG_BIAS 
      RS_disc_ena Roadspeed disconnected diags test enable/disable 
      RS_disc_rpm Roadspeed disconnected engine rpm threshold 
      RS_disc_thr Roadspeed sensor disconnected offset 
      RS_disc_tmr The number of seconds between attempts to run the roadspeed 
      sensor disconnected diagnostic test.

      If the key position is ON and the engine is running, this period value 
      will be used. If the key position is ON, but the engine is NOT running, 
      the period value defaults to 1 second.

      NOTE: With key-ON and engine-OFF the test runs at a faster rate because 
      there is no fear of missing legitimate roadspeed pulses.

      This fault only applies to mag pick-up roadspeed sensors. 
      RS_disc_Vbat Roadspeed disconnected diags runs if over this voltage 
      RS_dot Current measured derivative of road speed 
      RS_dot_dz Current measured derivative of road speed with deadzone applied. 

      RS_dot_dzlim This cubic deadzone limit is applied to the final lowpass 
      acceleration estimation before use in the control loop error terms. 
      RS_dot_ovsc_tau This is the time constant used to lowpass RS_dot to detect 
      a deceleration transition after overshoot control has approached the 
      target setspeed. 
      RS_dot_tau Lowpass filter time constant for the 
      RS_dot_window Time value over which to estimate the acceleration 
      RS_dt This is the current instantaneous time between 
      RS_ena Use this switch to enable/disable the roadspeed governing function. 
      If this switch is set to 'Enable - Limit Max + Cruise', all the 'Enable - 
      Limit Max' options still apply. However, the options available in the 
      cruise control section below will simultaneously be used to generate a 
      minimum throttle position. 
      RS_FPPmax_Iacc Current roadspeed control integrator value 
      RS_FPPmin_Iacc Current roadspeed control integrator value 
      RS_freq_raw Unfiltered roadspeed pulse input frequency 
      RS_gainset Control parameter set selection 
      RS_GPS_UA_tout Selects the amount of time the GPS control parameter set 
      remains a valid source during a GPS UNACQUIRED state. 
      RS_hist_avg_t The length of time over which the roadspeed will be sampled 
      from pulse versus time data. This should be >= 20ms and <= 150ms. 
      RS_hist_tout Timeout value during lack of receiving pulses to label as 
      zero speed. This value should be >= 50ms and <= 190ms, and should also be 
      > the speed averaging window time. Typical value is 150ms - no real reason 
      to change. 
      RS_hiV Roadspeed diagnostic internal 05V high voltage 
      RS_HW_cfg Roadspeed input hardware interface configuration. 
      RS_HW_switch This selection determines the hardware input (if any) that is 
      used to enable roadspeed limiting. Set this switch to disabled if using 
      roadspeed cruise control mode. 
      rs_Hz_capture logical YES/NO indicating whether the roadspeed input can be 
      used for PWM input capture 
      RS_Iacc Current roadspeed control integrator value 
      RS_Iacc_init Roadspeed Control Parameters initial Integrator for cases 
      where J1939 sourced RS will never be received 
      RS_input_redirect This switch allows hardware edge events coming into the 
      roadspeed input pin to redirect to other software handling routines (such 
      as Cam1 or Cam2). For example, if a hardware platform does not have a 
      physical (i.e. hardware) Cam2 input channel but does have an available 
      Roadspeed input channel, this switch can be set to Cam2 to make the 
      platform behave as if the Roadspeed input pin is connected to the Cam2 
      input pin. 
      RS_Kd Road speed limiting PID loop derivative gain. This is the only Kd 
      gain used if the Kd_accel gain is set to < 900.0 (such as 999.0). If, 
      however, Kd_accel is set to a number > 900.0 (such as a normal positive 
      value), then this Kd gain becomes the Kd_decel gain and is only used when 
      the acceleration error is positive (deceleration). 
      RS_Kd_accel Road speed limiting PID loop acceleration derivative gain. 
      Setting this gain to avalue > 900.0 (such as a normal positive number) 
      causes this gain to be used as the Kd when the acceleration error is 
      negative (acceleration). Setting this value to < 900.0 (such as 999.0) 
      causes this gain to be ignored and the standard Kd / Kd_decel gain is used 
      regardless of the sign of the acceleration error. 
      RS_Ki Road speed limiting PID loop integrator gain. 
      RS_Kiv Road speed limiting PID loop integral derivative 
      RS_Kivapp_add During conditions in which the roadspeed is not in proper 
      tolerance, an additional Kiv 'adder' can be used to increase the effective 
      Kiv gain to prevent over/under shoot. This value is the +/ deadband from 
      the target roadspeed where the adder will be used at its full value (100% 
      Kiv adder). This is the Kiv adder that will be added to the base Kiv value 
      depending on the roadspeed error from the final target. The two values 
      below define how this adder is phased in as the roadspeed error increases 
      away from the setpoint. 
      RS_Kivapp_RS0 During conditions in which the roadspeed is not in proper 
      tolerance, an additional Kiv 'adder' can be used to increase the effective 
      Kiv gain to prevent over/under shoot. This value is the +/ deadband from 
      the target roadspeed where the adder will be completely eliminated (adder 
      = 0). At roadspeed errors larger than this value, the adder will be 
      linearly increased from zero toward the full adder value at the 'full' 
      approach value. 
      RS_Kivapp_RS100 During conditions in which the roadspeed is not in proper 
      tolerance, an additional Kiv 'adder' can be used to increase the effective 
      Kiv gain to prevent over/under shoot. This value is the +/ deadband from 
      the target roadspeed where the adder will be used at its full value (100% 
      Kiv adder). At roadspeed errors smaller than this value, the adder will be 
      linearly decreased toward zero as the 'zero' value is approached. 
      RS_Kp Road speed limiting PID loop proportional gain. 
      RS_kph_crct_ena If enabled, the actual roadspeed signal is derived by 
      looking up the measured roadspeed signal. This transformation table can be 
      used to correct the measured roadspeed from non-linear roadspeed pulse 
      sensors, such as paddle-wheels. A (0,0) entry is assumed prior to the 
      start of this table for interpolations below the first entry in the table. 
      For interpolations beyond the last entry in the table, a fixed speed 
      offset is assumed. For example, if the last entry is 40kph measured = 
      42kph actual, then 55kph measured will translate to 55+2=57kph actual. 
      RS_Kp_dz This is the cubic deadzone that will be applied to the 
      proportional (Kp) error term for roadspeed control. 
      RS_Kp_dz_tout This is a timeout value that will be used each time the 
      roadspeed error term exceeds the proportional (Kp) deadzone value. During 
      the timeout period, the deadzone value will be temporarily set to zero. 
      RS_loss Roadspeed input loss fault condition 
      RS_loss_MAP Roadspeed input loss fault condition 
      RS_loss_PTO_stat "Roadspeed loss" fault condition - PTO status. When 
      parameter is set to "Inactive", the roadspeed loss diagnostic test will 
      only run when all PTO status are inactive. PTO status include both 
      proportional and discrete control modes. When parameter is set to 
      "Ignored", PTO status are not used as a fault condition.

      Note: this setting does not apply to instantaneous dropout detection, only 
      the engine load portion of the diagnostic test. 
      RS_loss_RPM Roadspeed input loss fault condition 
      RS_loss_slowPWM Roadspeed loss diagnostic: slow PWM input validation 
      requirement 
      RS_loV Roadspeed diagnostic internal 05V low voltage 
      rs_mag_dec_tau roadspeed input mag decreasing tau 
      rs_mag_inc_tau roadspeed input mag increasing tau 
      rs_mag_maxpct Limits the PWM trigger level output to this percentage of 
      the adaptive trigger level measurement. Generally, 80% provides reasonably 
      robust performance. 
      rs_mag_trig_min Amplitude, multiply by 2 for peak-to-peak voltage trigger. 

      RS_max_allspeed_ena When FPP control is configured for all-speed mode and 
      the roadspeed function is configured to limit max throttle the default 
      mode of operation is to limit road speed by adjusting the maximum throttle 
      command. When this setting is enabled roadspeed will be limited by instead 
      adjusting the maximum RPM and allowing the governor to implement the 
      limit. 
      RS_max_allspeed_rpm Roadspeed limited maximum RPM when operating in 
      all-speed mode and limiting max TPS (e.g. when Roadspeed rPM-based 
      all-speed limit function is enabled (RS_max_allspeed_ena)) 
      RS_max_allspeed_use This boolean value indicates when the roadspeed max 
      all-speed rpm is actively limiting RPM. 
      RS_max_FPP Roadspeed max FPP command 
      RS_max_load Currently computed engine load limit due to 
      RS_max_load_inc_slew Maximum increasing slew rate of the road speed load 
      limit when the road speed input is lost and the foot pedal is off-idle. 
      RS_max_TPS Currently computed TPS limit due to 
      RS_min_FPP Roadspeed min FPP command 
      rs_min_pw Enter the minimum pulse width. Pulses smaller than this will be 
      rejected and treated as noise. This value should be < 6.4us. Set this 
      parameter to zero to disable the noise cancellation feature. 
      RS_odom_total Vehicle total odometer distance 
      RS_OOA_state Roadspeed out of authority indicator (-1 = requesting less 
      power, +1 = requesting more power, 0 = in authority) 
      RS_pattern For typical evenly spaced pulse pattern sources, use the 
      'Uniform Non-Directional' setting. For coded wheel patterns to determine 
      direction of rotation, pick the appropriate pattern. Directional patterns 
      are typically used in conjunction with marine transmission output shaft 
      diagnostics to detect proper gear engagement. 
      RS_ppkm_Ulim This is an upper limit on the roadspeed pulse calibration 
      enforced if a Network Setpoint roadspeed pulse calibration is being used. 
      RS_prop_RS0 Proportional setpoint, speed low table value (These parameters 
      determine the linear transfer function between input voltage and roadspeed 
      limit setpoint.) 
      RS_prop_RS1 Proportional setpoint, speed high table value (These 
      parameters determine the linear transfer function between input voltage 
      and roadspeed limit setpoint.) 
      RS_prop_tau Proportional setpoint input low pass time constant (Lowpass 
      filter time constant to be applied to the incoming proportional voltage 
      source.) 
      RS_prop_V (Current lowpass filtered proportional roadspeed setpoint 
      voltage value for the roadspeed limit when in proportional setpoint mode.) 

      RS_prop_V0 Proportional setpoint, voltage low table value (These 
      parameters determine the linear transfer function between input voltage 
      and roadspeed limit setpoint.) 
      RS_prop_V1 Proportional setpoint, voltage high table value (These 
      parameters determine the linear transfer function between input voltage 
      and roadspeed limit setpoint.) 
      RS_pulses_per_km The calibration of the pulse input in number of pulses 
      per kilometer traveled. 
      RS_pulse_cnt Roadspeed rolling pulse accumulator. 
      RS_pulse_space This is the forced minimum dead-time between roadspeed 
      pulses. When a pulse is received, any pulses coming in during this time 
      duration afterward will be ignored. This acts as a false-pulse filter. The 
      user must be careful not to make this value too large since it can mask 
      actual high roadspeeds. In general, it should be no longer than 1/3 to 1/4 
      the minimum pulse spacing (maximum speed) that the vehicle can physically 
      experience. 
      rs_rise_trigger Roadspeed rising trigger level 
      RS_rpmtol_Ifrz If the roadspeed governor is in RPM control mode, this is 
      the +/- (positive) RPM error that will signal temporary freezing of the 
      roadspeed integrator until the inner RPM control loop is back in control. 
      This freezing only affects directional movement of the integrator that 
      would produce additional RPM error. 
      RS_rpm_nom Nominal speed at which roadspeed limiting occurs. 
      RS_setsrc This parameter determines the target roadspeed value when 
      "Roadspeed function" is set to one of the standard 'Enabled' modes.

      When set to 'Network Setpoint', the roadspeed setpoint is received from 
      the Sumitomo J1939 message.

      When set to 'Gov Switch State', the roadspeed setpoint is determined based 
      on the value of "Governor switch state":
      'None' - setpoint is 256 km/hr
      'Gov1' - setpoint is "Roadspeed setpoint lower-limit"
      'Gov2' - setpoint is "Roadspeed setpoint upper-limit"
      'Gov3' - setpoint is "Roadspeed setpoint default"
      Note: if "Max speed user setpoint - Primary" is not 'Disabled', then 
      "Governor switch state" is forced to 'None'. If a full-authority remote 
      TSC1 speed request is received, then "Governor switch state" is forced to 
      'Gov3'. Refer to the "Governor Select Input Configuration" section on the 
      Inputs worksheet to configure.

      When set to 'Gov1', the roadspeed setpoint is determined using Gov1 as an 
      auxiliary input. Parameter "Gov1 switch input function" must be set to 
      'Auxiliary Input' on the Inputs worksheet. When input is inactive, then 
      roadspeed setpoint is "Roadspeed setpoint default". When active, setpoint 
      is "Roadspeed setpoint lower-limit".

      When set to 'Gov2', behavior and configuration is the similar to 'Gov1'. 
      See 'Gov1' description above for details. 
      RS_setsrc_cfg Parameter determines the active logic state(s) for Gov1/Gov2 
      inputs when "Roadspeed setpoint source" is set to 'Gov1' or 'Gov2'. The 
      default value is equivalent to 'GND'. 
      RS_setsrc_ntwk When "Roadspeed setpoint source" is set to "Network 
      Setpoint", this selects which PGN sets the roadspeed limit.

      When "PGN 65473" is selected and the network roadspeed limit reception is 
      lost, the roadspeed limit is set to "'Roadspeed setpoint default" for the 
      remainder of the key cycle. When other options are selected and the 
      network roadspeed limit reception is lost, the roadspeed limit is set to 
      "'Roadspeed setpoint lower-limit".

      When "PGN 65450" is selected, the "J1939 PGN 65450 roadspeed setpoint 
      command receipt lost" diagnostic should be enabled. When other options are 
      selected, a "J1939 PGN timeout" diagnostic should be configured for the 
      selected PGN.

      When "PGN 62720" is selected, a PGN receipt timeout of 200ms will be 
      enforced. On Rx timeout, the "Roadspeed setpoint default" will be set for 
      the roadspeed limit. 
      RS_setsrc_stat Roadspeed setpoint source status 
      RS_setsrc_valid This switch allows an additional input other than the 
      proportional roadspeed setpoint voltage input itself to determine if the 
      proportional setpoint is used. For Toyota Forklifts, this is the slow PWM 
      input being present and valid. If the validation signal is enabled but not 
      present or invalid, then the proportional roadspeed setpoint input is 
      ignored and the system defaults to the fixed value setpoint. 
      RS_source SET1 Roadspeed control: Switch configures source for the ground 
      speed measurement. Flowchart normalized as RSP_source 
      RS_speed Current measured road speed according to the 
      RS_speed_CAN Current (measured) roadspeed, filtered for CAN transmission 
      RS_speed_CAN_tau Additional low-pass filter time constant for the road 
      speed measurement communicated via CAN messages. 
      RS_speed_d Desired roadspeed setpoint 
      RS_speed_Llim This is a lower roadspeed setpoint limit enforced if a 
      Network Setpoint roadspeed target is being used. It can also be the 
      roadspeed target if "Roadspeed setpoint source" is configured as 'Gov 
      Switch State', 'Gov1', or 'Gov2'. See "Roadspeed setpoint source" for more 
      details. 
      RS_speed_max Roadspeed control max speed limit if the setpoint source is 
      set to:
      - 'Fixed Value'
      - 'Aux * Proportional' and the input has an active fault condition
      - 'Gov Switch State' and "Gov switch state" has a value of 'Gov3'
      - 'Gov1' and Gov1 input is not active
      - 'Gov2' and Gov2 input is not active
      - 'Network Setpoint', "Roadspeed setpoint source network" is set to 'PGN 
      65473', and network roadspeed limit reception is lost 
      RS_speed_meas_acc current measured roadspeed in km/hr (32-bit low-pass 
      accumulated) 
      RS_speed_tau Lowpass filter time constant for the road speed 
      RS_speed_Ulim This is an upper roadspeed setpoint limit enforced if a 
      Network Setpoint roadspeed target is being used. It can also be the 
      roadspeed target if "Roadspeed setpoint source" is configured as 'Gov 
      Switch State'. See "Roadspeed setpoint source" for more details. 
      rs_TIF14_config Roadspeed T1F14 available 
      RS_TPS_bstld_crct When boost control mode is enabled, this parameter 
      determines whether the calculated boost load is limited by the roadspeed 
      maximum TPS governor when active.

      This parameter only applies to the 'Enabled - Limit Max Throttle' and 
      'Enabled - Limit Max + Cruise' roadspeed functions. 
      RS_TPS_FPPlim_ena This parameter determines whether the foot pedal 
      position is limited by the roadspeed maximum TPS governor when active.

      This parameter only applies to the 'Enabled - Limit Max Throttle' and 
      'Enabled - Limit Max + Cruise' roadspeed functions. 
      RS_TPS_lmt_ena Parameter determines whether the throttle position is 
      limited by the roadspeed maximum TPS governor. When set to 'Enabled', the 
      roadspeed maximum TPS governor will always limit the throttle position. 
      When set to 'Enabled - TSC1 Inactive', the throttle position will only be 
      limited when no full-authority TSC1 request is active.

      This parameter is only applicable when "DBW / IAC configuration" is set to 
      'DBW' on the DBW worksheet and when "Roadspeed function" is set to 
      'Enabled - Limit Max Throttle' or 'Enabled - Limit Max + Cruise' on the 
      Roadspeed worksheet. 
      RS_TPS_tau Lowpass filter time constant for the road speed 
      RTC_sec_epoch Real time clock, as seconds since 1/1/1970. 
      rTIP non-defaulted version of TIP w/o pressure offset pegging applied 
      rTOP Real time measurement of TOP. This value remains even if the TOP 
      measurement was found to be invalid (and thus set to MAP) 
      run_latch_wait Required run-time before the auto-crank feature latches the 
      engine in the "run" state. 
      run_mode Current engine state (stopped, cranking, running) 
      run_mode_latch Current latched run mode of the engine for use in starter 
      lockout logic 
      Run_rpm RPM at which the engine is considered RUNNING after transitioning 
      through the 'Crank Speed' and 'Under Speed'. Once the engine is running, 
      the RPM must drop below 'Under Speed' before being considered not running. 

      run_tmr engine run-time in ms 
      run_tmr_sec engine run-time in seconds 
      r_comp Engine compression ratio 
      SCC1_calc_min Hydraulic Forward Solenoid Control: falling current 
      calculation threshold 
      SCC1_cmd_max Hydraulic Forward Solenoid Control: Maximum Command Threshold 

      SCC1_cmd_min Hydraulic Forward Solenoid Control: Minimum Command Threshold 

      SCC1_Iavg_a Hydraulic Forward Solenoid Control: Actual average current 
      SCC1_Iavg_d_mA Hydraulic Forward Solenoid Control: Commanded average

      SCC1_Imax Hydraulic Forward Solenoid Control: Maximum commanded current 
      threshold 
      SCC1_Imin Hydraulic Forward Solenoid Control: Minimum commanded current 
      threshold

      SCC1_L Hydraulic Forward Solenoid Control: Solenoid inductance 
      SCC1_pwm_duty_cycle Hydraulic Forward Solenoid Control: PWM duty cycle 
      SCC1_R Hydraulic Forward Solenoid Control: Solenoid resistance 
      SCC1_Vd Hydraulic Forward Solenoid Control: Re-circulation diode voltage
