      Tinj_CAD_PW_I2 2D interpolation table secondary pulsewidth (X-axis) input 
      values 
      Tinj_CAD_rpm 2D interpolation table rpm (y-axis) input values 
      Tinj_CAD_rpm_I2 2D interpolation table secondary rpm (y-axis) input values 

      TIP Throttle Inlet Pressure 
      TIPAdaptMAP 2D Interpolation Table: MAP Based Slave Throttle Adaptive 
      Learn Table. MAP (psia) input axis values 
      TIPAdaptRPM 2D Interpolation Table: MAP Based Slave Throttle Adaptive 
      Learn Table. RPM input axis values 
      TIPAdaptTbl 2D Interpolation Table: MAP Based Slave Throttle Adaptive 
      Learn Table. Given MAP (psia) and RPM inputs, updates TIP Correction % 
      points 
      TIPAdapt_cmd_final Final TPS % (load_cmd_pct) 
      TIPAdapt_cmd_mstr Master TPS requested 
      TIPAdapt_cmd_slv Slave TPS final 
      TIPAdapt_correction TPS % adaptive correction 
      TIPAdapt_deadzone The difference between MAP raw and MAP filtered must be 
      more than the deadzone before the adaptive table will be updated. 
      TIPAdapt_dMAP_max MAP delta max is the maximum difference between the raw 
      MAP value and the low passed MAP value allowable to update the adaptive 
      correction table. If the difference is greater than this value, then the 
      engine is not considered stable enough to allow changes to the adaptive 
      algorithm, i.e., the MAP is going through a transient change. 
      TIPAdapt_ECT_min The minimum ECT value is used as a stability criterion. 
      Both the Master ECM and Slave ECM must report an ECT above this minimum 
      before the adaptive table will be updated. This helps ensure both sides of 
      the engine have entered a stable state. 
      TIPAdapt_ECT_mstr Master ECT 
      TIPAdapt_ECT_slv Slave ECT 
      TIPAdapt_ena Multi-ECM MAP based slave throttle control updates a MAPxRPM 
      adaptive table with the error correction to be applied to the calculated 
      Master ECM TIP value used by the Slave ECM to calculate the related TPS % 
      used to match the Master MAP value.

      The correction is based on the difference between the Master ECM MAP and 
      the Slave ECM MAP:

      error = Master MAP - Slave MAP
      correction = TIP Adapt Gain x error x delta T (loop time)

      Adaptive learning does not take place during transient states. If the 
      filtered MAP value deviates from the raw MAP value by more than a 
      configurable difference, then learning is temporarily disabled until the 
      difference is within tolerance for at least the stabilization time.

      Adaptive learning will not take place if the error (Master/Slave MAP 
      difference) is less than the dead zone limit.

      ECT must be reached and/or exceeded before adaptive learning will be 
      updated.

      MAP and RPM must be within limits before adaptive learning will be 
      updated. 
      TIPAdapt_gain Obsoleted parameter 
      TIPAdapt_gain_pct Adaptive gain 
      TIPAdapt_MAPerror TIP adapt MAP error 
      TIPAdapt_MAP_LPmstr Master filtered MAP value 
      TIPAdapt_MAP_LPslv Slave filtered MAP value 
      TIPAdapt_MAP_mstr Master raw MAP value 
      TIPAdapt_MAP_slv Slave raw MAP value 
      TIPAdapt_MAP_tau This is the MAP low pass time constant. 
      TIPAdapt_max This is the cap on the maximum correction allowed in the 
      adaptive table. 
      TIPAdapt_maxMAP Multi-ECM MAP Based Slave Throttle Adaptive Correction: 
      maximum MAP 
      TIPAdapt_maxRPM Multi-ECM MAP Based Slave Throttle Adaptive Correction: 
      maximum RPM 
      TIPAdapt_min This is the cap on the minimum correction allowed in the 
      adaptive table. 
      TIPAdapt_minMAP Multi-ECM MAP Based Slave Throttle Adaptive Correction: 
      minimum MAP 
      TIPAdapt_minRPM Multi-ECM MAP Based Slave Throttle Adaptive Correction: 
      minimum RPM 
      TIPAdapt_tblcorrect Multi-ECM MAP Based Slave Throttle Adaptive 
      Correction: table delta correction 
      TIPAdapt_TIPcorrect TIP correction 
      TIPAdapt_TIP_mstr TIP Adapt master TIP (calculated) 
      TIPAdapt_TIP_slv TIP Adapt slave TIP 
      TIPAdapt_updating Indicates when adaptive table is actively updating 
      TIPAdapt_wait The TIP transient wait time is the amount of time to wait 
      after the difference between raw MAP and filtered MAP comes back into an 
      acceptable range following a transient event. Once this timer has expired, 
      the adaptive table will be allowed to be updated. 
      TIpark_DBW_Ilim 1D Interpolation Table: Actuator Current Park Limit (Park 
      current limit when '1-D Table-Based' mode is selected.). Given Position 
      Sensor % input, returns DBW actuator current park limit (amps) 
      TIpark_HBA_Ilim 1D Interpolation Table: Actuator Current Park Limit (Park 
      current limit when '1-D Table-Based' mode is selected.). Given Position 
      Sensor % input, returns HBA actuator current park limit (amps) 
      TIpark_HBB_Ilim 1D Interpolation Table: Actuator Current Park Limit (Park 
      current limit when '1-D Table-Based' mode is selected.). Given Position 
      Sensor % input, returns HBB actuator current park limit (amps) 
      TIpark_tps 1D Interpolation Table: Actuator Current Park Limit (Park 
      current limit when '1-D Table-Based' mode is selected.). Position Sensor % 
      input axis values 
      TIPc TIP/TOP sensor calibration: scaling 
      TIPcal_P 1D Interpolation Table. Converts sensor voltages to pressure 
      (sensor calibration table). This table (x,y) is also converted internally 
      to a linear equation with computed parameters, TIPc and TIPo. 
      TIPcal_V 1D interpolation table TIP sensor voltage input values 
      TIPo TIP/TOP sensor calibration: offset 
      TIPraw_LP LPF time constant applied to raw sensor input voltage 
      TIPrsc2D_tbl_mode Specifies which of the 2D tables are used for boost 
      altitude compensation.

      When set to 'Standard Tables (legacy)', the following 2D tables are 
      referenced by "Boost altitude compensation":
      Standard TIP Target Derate / Load-Limit Table
      Standard dPhi/dTIP Mult / EGR MinNom Table
      Standard Spark Timing Offset / MAP Load Table

      When set to 'Expanded Tables', the following 2D tables are referenced by 
      "Boost altitude compensation":
      Expanded TIP Target Derate / Load-Limit Table
      Expanded dPhi/dTIP Mult / EGR MinNom Table
      Expanded Spark Timing Offset / MAP Load Table 
      TIP_act This fault detects if the TIP sensor is pneumatically attached to 
      the intake system. It sets if MAP is rising without a corresponding change 
      in TIP. 
      TIP_actMAP TIP/TOP active diagnostic: MAP entry condition 
      TIP_C_int TIP Scaling Delta P Scaling Parameter (used in Intake Flow rate 
      estimator model) 
      TIP_defaulted Indicator that TIP is set to default value due to a TIP 
      fault. 
      TIP_def_select Specifies the default value for throttle inlet pressure 
      when the TIP sensor is faulted. For the 'TIP estimate' option, select the 
      desired estimate type using the "TIP pressure estimate" parameter. 
      TIP_dot TIP derivative (dTIP/dt) 
      TIP_dot_dz Deadzone limited TIP_dot_acc (TIP derivative) 
      TIP_dot_dzlim Cubic rolloff dead-zone limit value for dTIP/dt. 
      TIP_dot_tau Low-pass filter value for backward difference TIP derivative 
      calculation. 
      TIP_dot_window Backward difference window size for TIP derivative 
      calculation. 
      TIP_ena Assumed to be TOP for supercharged applications, and TIP 
      otherwise. 
      TIP_est Estimated throttle inlet pressure in psia. 
      TIP_est_ena This switch selects the type of throttle inlet pressure (TIP) 
      estimate to use when a TIP sensor is not available. Generally, this option 
      is only used on turbocharged engines that do not have a throttle. When set 
      to 'Throttle model - legacy', TIP is underestimated when throttle flow is 
      sonic. For example, when engine is idling with low load, the estimated TIP 
      may be below barometric pressure. Use option 'Throttle model - corrected' 
      to properly estimate TIP when flow is sonic. 
      TIP_est_tau Time constant for estimated throttle inlet pressure's 
      (TIP_est) low-pass filter. 
      TIP_flts_def_mode Parameter determines which TIP faults can cause TIP 
      sensor value to be overridden with the default value. When set to 
      'Standard Faults', the following fault are checked:
      "TIP/TOP low voltage" fault
      "TIP/TOP high voltage" fault
      "TIP/TOP active" fault
      At least one fault must be active-latched to override the TIP sensor value 
      with the default value.

      When set to 'Standard + TIP Pegging Offset Fault', the "TIP pegging offset 
      out-of-range" fault is also checked. This fault must be potential or 
      confirmed and active to override the TIP sensor value with the default 
      value. 
      TIP_flt_fuel_mode Parameter determines the fuel calculation whenever a TIP 
      sensor fault is active-latched and causing the default TIP value to be 
      used. When set to 'Speed-Density + dMAP/dt', the active fuel calculation 
      is automatically switched to 'Speed-Density + dMAP/dt' when the TIP 
      default value is being used due to an active-latched TIP sensor fault. The 
      applicable TIP sensor faults are determined by the "TIP faults that set 
      TIP to default" parameter. The overridden fuel calculation modes are the 
      "Throttle-body injection fuel mode" and "CFV fuel calculation mode".
      This parameter is only applicable when:
      "TIP/TOP source" is not 'Estimated' on the Inputs worksheet
      "Boost control type" is 'Turbocharged' on the Boost worksheet 
      TIP_gauge_def Default TIP gauge pressure used in Intake Flow rate model 
      TIP_global_filt This switch selects what type of general global filter 
      scheme is used for the TIP signal in most modes of operation. The 
      'Default' setting uses standard low-pass filtering. The 'Cylinder 
      Windowed' mode uses a sliding engine synchronous window averaging 
      technique. Refer to "MAP/TIP Cylinder Window Calculation" section for 
      configuration. Note that 'Throttle-Model Base Throttle-Body Fueling' 
      always uses cylinder windowing regardless of this switch setting. 
      TIP_maxMAP TIP/TOP high voltage diagnostic: MAP upper limit entry 
      condition 
      TIP_maxv TIP/TOP high voltage diagnostic: TIP/TOP voltage upper limit 
      threshold 
      TIP_minv TIP/TOP low voltage diagnostic: TIP/TOP voltage lower limit 
      threshold 
      TIP_raw TIP raw volts 
      TIP_slow Slow time constant version of TIP (LPF time constant of LP_slow) 
      TIP_windowed High speed cylinder event windowed TIP value 
      TIP_windowed_def Specifies the default value for the cylinder-event 
      windowed throttle inlet pressure (TIP_windowed) when the TIP sensor is 
      faulted or not available. When set to 'Enabled', the method specified by 
      "TIP default" is applied to both TIP and TIP_windowed. 
      TJ1939EC_LL J1939 Engine Configuration (EC1) governor-based load-limit 
      values for points 1-5 in percent of engine load. 
      TJ1939EC_rpm J1939 Engine Configuration (EC1) speed values for points 1-7 
      in rpm. 
      TJ1939EC_rpmd Table configures J1939 EC1 engine speed values for points 3, 
      4, and 5 (SPN 529-531). Engine speed values must be in ascending order. 
      Table is only applicable when "J1939 EC1 speed points 3-5 source" is set 
      to 'Table-Based' on the 'Comms' worksheet.

      The specified speed values in the table will always be limited by points 1 
      and 2 which are calculated based on the idle governor and max governor 
      configuration.

      Engine speed and torque values may be derated. See "J1939 EC1 variable 
      rate reporting" on the 'Comms' worksheet for configuring dynamic points. 
      TJ1939EC_trq J1939 Engine Configuration (EC1) torque values for points 1-5 
      in percent of engine reference torque. 
      TJ1939_Rx2_PGNs This group of PGNs is the list of messages that the ECM is 
      expecting to see on the network. If supported and configured by the ECM, 
      these PGNs will permit the ECM to receive data from other network devices 
      to use for control or feedback purposes. The entire arbitration 
      identification of a message must be as the ECM expects in order for the 
      ECM to receive it. 
      TJ1939_Rx2_SPNs This list is used to uniquely identify which supported 
      variable (i.e. SPN) should be received. If the PGN value for a supported 
      message is in the Required Rx PGN List but the SPN of interest is not in 
      the Rx SPN Update Access list, then the variable will not be retrieved by 
      the ECM. 
      TJ1939_Rx3_PGNs This group of PGNs is the list of messages that the ECM is 
      expecting to see on the network. If supported and configured by the ECM, 
      these PGNs will permit the ECM to receive data from other network devices 
      to use for control or feedback purposes. The entire arbitration 
      identification of a message must be as the ECM expects in order for the 
      ECM to receive it. 
      TJ1939_Rx3_SPNs This list is used to uniquely identify which supported 
      variable (i.e. SPN) should be received. If the PGN value for a supported 
      message is in the Required Rx PGN List but the SPN of interest is not in 
      the Rx SPN Update Access list, then the variable will not be retrieved by 
      the ECM. 
      TJ1939_Rx_PGNs This group of PGNs is the list of messages that the ECM is 
      expecting to see on the network. If supported and configured by the ECM, 
      these PGNs will permit the ECM to receive data from other network devices 
      to use for control or feedback purposes. The entire arbitration 
      identification of a message must be as the ECM expects in order for the 
      ECM to receive it. 
      TJ1939_Rx_SPNs This list is used to uniquely identify which supported 
      variable (i.e. SPN) should be received. If the PGN value for a supported 
      message is in the Required Rx PGN List but the SPN of interest is not in 
      the Rx SPN Update Access list, then the variable will not be retrieved by 
      the ECM. 
      TJ1939_Tx2_PGNs This group of PGNs is the list of messages that are always 
      broadcast on the CAN network at the appropriate time interval 
      TJ1939_Tx3_PGNs This group of PGNs is the list of messages that are always 
      broadcast on the CAN network at the appropriate time interval 
      TJ1939_TxOK2_PGNs This group of PGNs is the list of messages that are 
      transmitted ONLY when a PGN request is received by the ECM per J1939-21 
      5.4.2. 
      TJ1939_TxOK3_PGNs This group of PGNs is the list of messages that are 
      transmitted ONLY when a PGN request is received by the ECM per J1939-21 
      5.4.2. 
      TJ1939_TxOK_PGNs This group of PGNs is the list of messages that are 
      transmitted ONLY when a PGN request is received by the ECM per J1939-21 
      5.4.2. 
      TJ1939_Tx_PGNs List of messages that are transmitted (i.e. broadcast) by 
      the ECM at regular time intervals on a continual basis.

      Output is a low pass filter time constant which determines the rate at 
      which the elevated knock FSO threshold returns to 0 after exiting fuel 
      shutoff.

      updated from this table as fuel flow changes.

      TMtf_PRov_max See the comments for 'Lower PR override' above. 
      TMtf_PRov_min The pressure-ratio (PR) is defined as MAP/TIP.
      As PR approaches 1.0, the compressible flow solution through the throttle 
      becomes poorly conditioned. This is because at PR near 1.0, MAP and TIP 
      are very close to the same value and small errors in the measurement of 
      either one produce very large air flow estimate changes.
      The 'Lower PR override' and 'Upper PR override' values provide a way to 
      discontinue utilization of the flow estimate from the throttle-model 
      algorithm as PR approaches 1.0.
      Instead, speed density and dMAP/dt manifold filling are used during these 
      conditions.When PR <= 'Lower PR override' then the rest of the system is 
      free to use the throttle-model based port flow and transient flow estimate 
      as required.When PR >= 'Upper PR override' then the reset of the system is 
      only allowed to use speed-density for port flow and dMAP/dt for transient 
      flow.When PR is between these two values, linear interpolation is used for 
      a smooth transition. 
      TMtf_PR_wgt throttle-model throttle-flow pressure-ratio weight between 
      dMAP/dt and throttle-model manifold filling fueling 
      TMtf_TPScmd_tau_dec This the decreasing TPS command low-pass time constant 
      used to produce the lead-compensated TPS signal described more completely 
      in the comments for the increasing time constant above. 
      TMtf_TPScmd_tau_inc This is the first-order low-pass time constant applied 
      to increasing TPS position commands in order to produce a lead-compensated 
      estimate of the actual TPS. A shorter time constant provides more lead, 
      and longer time constant provides less lead - and can eventually produce 
      lag relative to the actual position.

      The lead-compensated TPS is used as the TPS signal for all throttle flow 
      calculations in this sub-system. This lead compensation can be used to 
      offset any response delays in the fuel metering device (i.e. CFV). 
      TMtf_trans_dzabspct throttle-model transient indication after deadzone 
      application in absolute % 
      TMtf_trans_max See the comments for 'Lower transient for 100% N-rho' 
      above. 
      TMtf_trans_min This air flow estimation technique uses three components 
      for computing the total air flow:

      1) Standard speed-density (N-rho) port (steady-state) flow. 
      2) Throttle-Model (TM) based port (steady-state) flow.
      3) Throttle-Model based throttle transient-only (maniflod filling only) 
      flow.

      Define the 'transient fraction' as the ratio of the transient flow to the 
      port flow:

      x = (3) / (1) 

      If x <= the 'Lower transient for 100% N-rho' then total flow = (1) + (3).
      If x >= the 'Upper transient for 100% TM' then total flow = (2) + (3).
      If x is between these two values, then linear interpolation is used for a 
      smooth transition. 
      TMtf_trans_sldn Whenever the throttle-model based steady-state (i.e. port) 
      flow estimate is used during a transient condition (see comment for 'Lower 
      transient for 100% N-rho'), this parameter determines how quickly N-rho 
      based port-flow is reinstituted once the transient is over. This decay 
      rate is another technique used to insure that any lead-compensation gained 
      from the use of this model during a transient lasts longer than the 
      response lag of the fuel metering device (i.e. CFV). In general, this is 
      on the order of about 2%/ms or about 50ms for a 100% transient. 
      TMtf_trans_wgt throttle-model throttle-flow transient weight between 
      speed-density and throttle-model port engine fueling 
      TMTPSad_pct throttle-model adaptive A*Cd correction 
      TM_SG_crct_ena Includes specific gravity corrections in all throttle model 
      calculations.

      TOperTempWUT_ECT 1D Interpolation Table: Operating Temperature Threshold 
      Warm-up Time. ECT (deg F) input axis values (NOTE: This table determines 
      the run-time threshold fault condition for the 'Failed to reach operating 
      temperature' fault on the Diagnostics page. When both the RPM and MAP 
      exceed the limits calibrated for the fault, the current ECT will be 
      latched as the starting temperature.) 
      TOperTempWUT_wait 1D Interpolation Table: Operating Temperature Threshold 
      Warm-up Time. This table determines the run-time threshold fault condition 
      for the 'Failed to reach operating temperature' fault on the Diagnostics 
      page. When both the RPM and MAP exceed the limits calibrated for the 
      fault, the current ECT will be latched as the starting temperature. Given 
      ECT (deg F) input, returns warm-up time (seconds). 
      TORM_active Logical indicating TORM system is in control of throttle 
      command 
      TORM_drpm_dFPP_max During active throttle override, this is the maximum 
      allowed FPP to RPM transfer function gain allowed. The system will try to 
      reach the max governor rpm unless lower limited by this value. 
      TORM_ena This switch controls the throttle override mode (TORM) system 
      engagement. 
      TORM_FPPdelt_ini This value determines the FPP tolerance required to 
      establish an initial steady-state FPP position prior to arming of TORM. 
      TORM_FPPdelt_mon This is the FPP movement tolerance that will trigger 
      entry into TORM rpm boost once the system has been armed through 
      initialization. 
      TORM_FPP_cmd_ss FPP steady-state tracking low-pass variable for TORM in 
      FPP fraction 
      TORM_FPP_rampback This ramp rate determines how quickly a throttle 
      override command is dissipated once initiated. 
      TORM_FPP_tau1 This time constant is used to generate a steady-state 
      reference FPP position in order to establish detection of a steady-state 
      FPP condition during the initialization and monitoring phases of the TORM 
      arming sequence. 
      TORM_mode Throttle override mode: Disabled, Enabled, Not Allowed 
      TORM_monvalid_t Prior to TORM arming, the FPP must be stable within the 
      FPP initialization tolerance for this amount of time to satisfy arming 
      conditions and move to the monitoring state. 
      TORM_rpm_delt TORM requested delta rpm 
      TORM_rpm_tol This value determines the engine rpm control tolerance 
      required to establish an initial steady-state control condition prior to 
      arming of TORM. 
      TORM_RS_phase Current level of control authority being granted to the 
      roadspeed control system (if active) by the TORM system during RPM 
      excursions. 
      TORM_RS_phaset This is the time span over which any active roadspeed 
      control will be phased back into authority for a bumpless transition from 
      override mode back to roadspeed control. 
      TORM_RS_tol This value determines the roadspeed control tolerance required 
      to establish an initial steady-state control condition prior to arming of 
      TORM. This value is only applicable if the MaxSetPt system is in a 
      roadspeed control mode. 
      TORM_state Throttle override state:
      • Offline
      • Wait for SS
      • Monitoring
      • Active 
      torque_driver Estimated driver demand torque as a percentage of the engine 
      reference torque. Calculation is dependent on configuration of "J1939 
      driver demand torque broadcast" and "J1939 torque / engine load 
      conversion" on the Estimators worksheet. 
      torque_Nm_gross Estimated actual/indicated gross torque at current 
      operating conditions. 
      torque_Nm_max Estimated max actual/indicated gross torque at current 
      operating conditions. 
      torque_Nm_ref This is the 'reference torque' used in the J1939 'Engine 
      Configuration' (EC) PG used as a scale basis for the torque curve 
      delivered in this packet. It MUST be greater than or equal to the highest 
      torque entered in the engine torque range calibration below. In general, 
      it should always be at least 20% higher than the highest torque. 
      torque_parasitic Computed Parasitic Losses Torque 
      torque_pct Estimated actual net torque percent (does not include engine 
      reference torque). 
      torque_pct_eng_dmd Estimated engine demand gross torque as a percentage of 
      the engine reference torque - includes friction, derate, and load limits. 
      Calculation is dependent on configuration of "J1939 torque / engine load 
      conversion" on the Estimators worksheet. 
      torque_pct_fric Estimated friction torque percent. If "J1939 engine torque 
      broadcast" is set to 'Torque Percent', then value is a percentage of the 
      engine reference torque. If "J1939 parasitic torque broadcast" is set to 
      'SPN 514 and 2978 (Legacy)', then value includes parasitic torque. 
      torque_pct_gross Estimated actual indicated/gross torque percent. If 
      "J1939 engine torque broadcast" is set to 'Torque Percent', then value is 
      a percentage of the engine reference torque. 
      torque_pct_max Estimated max indicated/gross torque as a percentage of the 
      engine reference torque. 
      torque_pct_max_avail Maximum available engine torque as a percentage of 
      the engine reference torque. Calculation is dependent on configuration of 
      "J1939 max available torque broadcast" and "J1939 torque / engine load 
      conversion" on the Estimators worksheet. 
      torque_select This selection determines the value broadcast in SPN 513 
      "Actual Engine - Percent Torque." The default is engine load, which is 
      determined from the MAP full-load/no-load table used for governing. If the 
      engine torque estimation table below is fully calibrated, select torque 
      percent. The governor load table provides an estimate (though it will have 
      error near the no-load/full-load endpoints) if the table below has not 
      been calibrated. However, the max brake torque at each engine speed will 
      be used to compute the torque in N-m and must be close to the reference 
      torque for reasonable J1939 broadcast results. 
      torque_tbl_fric Estimated friction torque. If "J1939 parasitic torque 
      broadcast" is set to 'SPN 514 and 2978 (Legacy)', then value includes 
      parasitic torque. 
      torq_avail_mode This selection determines the value broadcasted in EEC2 
      SPN 3357 - "Actual Maximum Available Engine - Percent Torque." The default 
      value is 'Engine Load' which is a legacy mode that ignores the reference 
      torque in SPN 544. If the engine torque estimation tables are fully 
      calibrated, select a torque percent option.

      When configured as 'Torque Percent - Maximum', the broadcasted value is 
      the maximum available torque as a percentage of the reference torque and 
      includes active TSC1 torque limits.
      When configured as 'Torque Percent - Maximum, No TSC1', the broadcasted 
      value is the maximum available torque as a percentage of the reference 
      torque and does not include active TSC1 torque limits.

      The next two configurations are currently only applicable to turbocharged 
      engines with "Boost control mode" set to 'delta-P':
      When configured as 'Torque Percent - Immediate', the broadcasted value is 
      the immediately available torque as a percentage of the reference torque 
      and includes active TSC1 torque limits.
      When configured as 'Torque Percent - Immediate, No TSC1', the broadcasted 
      value is the immediately available torque as a percentage of the reference 
      torque and excludes active TSC1 torque limits.

      When configured as one of the 'Torque Percent' options, the broadcasted 
      value is impacted by "J1939 torque / engine load conversion" on the 
      Estimators worksheet. 
      torq_driver_dmd_mode Parameter determines the value broadcasted in EEC1 
      SPN 512 - "Driver's Demand Engine - Percent Torque." The default value is 
      'Torque Percent - Legacy' which is a legacy mode that improperly 
      calculates the engine demand.

      When parameter is set to 'Torque Percent - Corrected, Limited', the 
      calculation is corrected but is limited to the friction torque. The 
      minimum broadcasted value is the friction torque.

      When parameter is set to 'Torque Percent - Corrected, Unlimited', the 
      calculation is corrected and is not limited to the friction torque. A 0% 
      FPP position correlates to 0% driver's demand.

      When parameter is set to 'Torque Percent - FPP Only', then only the user's 
      FPP position is reported. The maximum roadspeed governor and cruise 
      control are removed. Also, the calculation is corrected and is not limited 
      to the friction torque. A 0% FPP position correlates to 0% driver's 
demand.

      The driver's demand torque broadcast is also impacted by "J1939 torque / 
      engine load conversion" on the Estimators worksheet. 
      torq_load_convert Parameter configures the conversion between engine load 
      and net torque percentages for the following calculations:
      - EC1 torque curve points when dynamic points are enabled
      - EEC1 SPN 512 - Driver's Demand Engine Torque
      - EEC1 SPN 2432 - Engine Demand Torque
      - EEC2 SPN 3357 - Actual Maximum Available Engine Torque
      - TSC1 remote torque limit requests

      Engine load values are based on the Governor No-Load/Full-Load table. Net 
      torque percentages are based on the Engine Torque Estimation tables. When 
      parameter is set to 'Disabled (Legacy)', engine load values are not 
      converted to a corresponding net torque percentage. They are assumed to be 
      equivalent.

      When set to 'Enabled', engine load values are converted to a corresponding 
      net torque percentage using both the Governor No-Load/Full-Load table and 
      the Engine Torque Estimation tables. The tables must be calibrated. 
      torq_parasitic_mode Parameter configures the broadcasted engine parasitic 
      losses torque.

      When set to 'SPN 514 and 2978 (Legacy)', the estimated parasitic torque is 
      reported in two locations. It is added to the nominal frictional torque 
      (SPN 514) as well as reported in the estimated engine parasitic losses 
      torque (SPN 2978).

      When set to 'SPN 2978 Only', the estimated parasitic losses torque is only 
      reported in SPN 2978.

      The estimated parasitic losses are comprised of the variable speed fan 
      power consumption and air conditioning compressor torque. Refer to "Fan 
      Power Consumption" table on the Outputs page and "Parasitic Losses Torque" 
      table on the Estimators page for their respective calibrations. 
      TOSB_ena This switch enables the open-stop braking function to eliminate 
      high-velocity impacts in the open position. 
      TOSB_Kd This value is multiplied by the difference between the actual 
      dPS/dt and the limit values defined by the min/max PS PSdt parameters and 
      the current PS (from max to max-delta). For example, if the current dPS/dt 
      = +200 %/s, the actuator is about to impact the open-stop, and the min PS 
      PSdt parameter is +100 %/s, then for a Kd value of 1.0 %/%*sec, the 
      contribution to the braking force will be -100%. 
      TOSB_max_TPSdt dPS/dt value at the min PS (full-open minus open-stop PS 
      delta) position below which no braking action will occur. This must be a 
      value strictly > 0 and should be more positive than the min PS PSdt value. 

      TOSB_min_TPSdt dPS/dt value at the max PS (full-open) position below which 
      no braking action will occur. This must be a value strictly > 0. 
      TOSB_TPSdelta Delta voltage from the current min PS value to initiate 
      open-stop braking. PS values below this delta will not cause any braking 
      action under any condition. 
      TOT Turbocharger turbine (outlet) temperature 
      totalcal_CS_16 final 16-bit total-calibration checksum 
      totalcal_CS_32 final 32-bit total-calibration checksum 
      totalcal_CS_hst Software version history total calibration checksums 
      TOT_ena Turbocharger outlet turbine temperature sensor input channel 
      TOT_mdl Turbine outlet modeled temperature 
      TOT_Taux_cal TOT auxiliary temperature calibration table select 
      TOT_vdr TOT calibration: Pullup resistor configuration 
      TPhiC_ECT_ECT 1D interpolation table ECT (gasoline engines) input values 
      TPhiC_ECT_ECTN 1D interpolation table ECT (NG engines) input values 
      TPhiC_ECT_ECTP 1D interpolation table ECT (LPG engines) input values 
      TPhiC_ECT_frac 1D Interpolation Table: ECT Based Cold/Transition/Normal 
      Temperature Phi Contribution Table for Gasoline 
      TPhiC_ECT_fracN 1D Interpolation Table: ECT Based Cold/Transition/Normal 
      Temperature Phi Contribution Table for NG 
      TPhiC_ECT_fracP 1D Interpolation Table: ECT Based Cold/Transition/Normal 
      Temperature Phi Contribution Table for Propane 
      TPhi_base_MAP 2D interpolation table MAP (X-axis) input values 
      TPhi_base_MAPNG 2D interpolation table MAP (NG engines) (X-axis) input 
      values 
      TPhi_base_MAPP 2D interpolation table MAP (LP engines) (X-axis) input 
      values 
      TPhi_base_Phi 2D Interpolation Table: Gasoline Phi Base (Phi) 
      TPhi_base_PhiNG 2D Interpolation Table: NG Phi Base (Phi) 
      TPhi_base_PhiP 2D Interpolation Table: LPG Phi Base (Phi) 
      TPhi_base_rpm 2D interpolation table rpm (y-axis) input values 
      TPhi_base_rpmNG 2D interpolation table rpm (NG engines) (y-axis) input 
      values 
      TPhi_base_rpmP 2D interpolation table rpm (LPG engines) (y-axis) input 
      values 
      TPhi_cold_Phi 2D Interpolation Table: Gasoline Desired Cold Equivalence 
      Table (input parameters are rpm and MAPrsc_PHI 
      TPhi_cold_PhiN 2D Interpolation Table: Natural Gas Desired Cold 
      Equivalence Table (input parameters are rpm and MAPrsc_PHI 
      TPhi_cold_PhiP 2D Interpolation Table: Propane Gas Desired Cold 
      Equivalence Table (input parameters are rpm and MAPrsc_PHI 
      TPhi_FSO_CBT CBT column for the "Post-FSO Phi Catalyst Enrichment" table, 
      used only during cold start operation. When CBT is less than the first 
      row, enrichment is disabled. When CBT exceeds the last row, cold start 
      operation is disabled, and normal single-point enrichment operation 
      begins. 
      TPhi_FSO_offset Phi offset column for the "Post-FSO Phi Catalyst 
      Enrichment" table. The last row is equal to "FSO phi catalyst enrichment". 

      TPhi_FSO_offset_cal First three rows of the phi offset column for the 
      "Post-FSO Phi Catalyst Enrichment" table. 
      TPhi_tran_Phi 2D Interpolation Table: Gasoline Desired Transition 
      Equivalence Table (input parameters are rpm and MAPrsc_PHI 
      TPhi_tran_PhiN 2D Interpolation Table: Desired NG Transition Equivalence 
      Ratio. Given MAP load (psia) and RPM inputs, returns Transition Phi for NG 

      TPhi_tran_PhiP 2D Interpolation Table: Desired NG Transition Equivalence 
      Ratio. Given MAP load (psia) and RPM inputs, returns Transition Phi for 
      LPG 
      Tpostphi_ret_ld_MAP MAP load column of the "Spark Retard Minimum Load" 
      table for the "Post-Cat Phi Based Spark Retard" feature. 
      Tpostphi_ret_ld_rpm Engine speed column of the "Spark Retard Minimum Load" 
      table for the "Post-Cat Phi Based Spark Retard" feature. 
      TPS12ctl_choice This switch determines which PS (1 or 2) is the feedback 
      controlling PS during a PS1-PS2 mismatch active fault. This option is only 
      valid for dual-pot sensors with the backup control on PS2 enabled. 
      TPS12pct_hi TPS1 higher than TPS2 diagnostic: TPS1% - TPS2% delta upper 
      limit threshold 
      TPS12pct_lo TPS1 lower than TPS2 diagnostic: TPS1% - TPS2% delta lower 
      limit (negative value) threshold 
      TPS1_def DBW default PS1 
      TPS1_full DBW PS1 full 
      TPS1_full_def DBW default PS1 full 
      TPS1_full_init DBW PS1 full init 
      TPS1_idle DBW PS1 idle 
      TPS1_idle_def DBW default PS1 idle 
      TPS1_idle_init DBW PS1 idle init 
      TPS1_learn_tau DBW PS1 learn tau 
      TPS1_learn_wait DBW PS1 learn wait 
      TPS1_max TPS1 high voltage diagnostic: TPS1 upper limit threshold 
      TPS1_min TPS1 low voltage diagnostic: TPS1 lower limit threshold 
      TPS1_pct DBW TPS1 percent 
      TPS1_raw Throttle position sensor 1 feedback 
      TPS1_rawfilt DBW PS1 raw voltage 
      TPS1_source Please contact EControls for assistance in making a proper 
      position sensor feedback connection. For best performance, this input 
      should be high-speed sampled. Not all of these inputs are appropriate on 
      all platforms. 
      TPS2ctl_allow If a dual-pot sensor is being utilized, this option may be 
      selected to allow use of the PS2 signal during a PS1 voltage out-of-range 
      fault condition. 
      TPS2_angle_at_full DBW PS2 angle at full: Used for throttles that have a 
      PS2 feedback that reaches full voltage before 100% opening 
      TPS2_def DBW default PS2 
      TPS2_full DBW PS2 full 
      TPS2_full_init DBW PS2 full init 
      TPS2_idle DBW PS2 idle 
      TPS2_idle_init DBW PS2 idle init 
      TPS2_learn_tau DBW PS2 learn tau 
      TPS2_learn_wait DBW PS2 learn wait 
      TPS2_max TPS2 high voltage diagnostic: TPS2 upper limit threshold 
      TPS2_min TPS2 low voltage diagnostic: TPS2 lower limit threshold 
      TPS2_pct DBW TPS2 percent 
      TPS2_raw Throttle position sensor 2 feedback 
      TPS2_rawfilt DBW PS2 raw voltage 
      TPS2_source Please contact EControls for assistance in making a proper 
      position sensor feedback connection. For best performance, this input 
      should be high-speed sampled. Not all of these inputs are appropriate on 
      all platforms. 
      TPSad_adapt_assist Throttle Model Adaptive: TM adaptive cal assist mode: 
      • Inactive
      • Adapt Freeze Updates
      • Adapt Freeze + Zero Crct
      • Adapt Clear Tables 
      TPSad_adapt_dz If the absolute value of the area error is less than this 
      value, no further adaptive updates are performed on that adaptive area 
      cell(s). 
      TPSad_adapt_lim This is the authority limit enforced for each cell in the 
      area adaptive table. It is a positive number applied symmetrically for + 
      or - limits. 
      TPSad_CdA_adapt_Amin The max adaptive correction for any particular entry 
      in the area adaptive table is given by 

      max(min limit, learn +/- limit * nominal area)

      Examples:
      if adaptive learn +/- limit = 50%
      and adaptive learn min limit = 0.200 in^2

      For a nominal 0.1 in^2 entry, a 0.2 in^2 correction is allowed
      For a nominal 1.0 in^2 entry, a 0.5 in^2 correction is allowed

      The CdA adaptive limits (determined by this parameter and the +/- limit 
      multiplier) are shown in the nominal valve CdA plot. 
      TPSad_CdA_adapt_lim The max adaptive correction for any particular entry 
      in the area adaptive table is given by 

      max(min limit, learn +/- limit * nominal area)

      Examples:
      if adaptive learn +/- limit = 50%
      and adaptive learn min limit = 0.200 in^2

      For a nominal 0.1 in^2 entry, a 0.2 in^2 correction is allowed
      For a nominal 1.0 in^2 entry, a 0.5 in^2 correction is allowed

      The CdA adaptive limits (determined by this parameter and the +/- min area 
      limit) are shown in the nominal valve CdA plot. 
      TPSad_CdA_in2 Throttle Model Adaptive: TM adaptive CdA correction 
      TPSad_CdA_Kadapt This gain drives the speed of the adaptive area 
      correction updates. It is in units of % area change per area error % per 
      second. 
      TPSad_global_use Enabling this option allows the dual-mode throttle-model 
      adaptive corrections to be used in other parts of the system (e.g. for the 
      boost TPS control calculations). 
      TPSad_Kadapt This gain drives the speed of the adaptive area correction 
      updates. It is in units of % adaptive area change per area error % per 
      second. 
      TPSad_learn_wait If adaptive updates are disallowed for any reason (such 
      as those conditions defined by the parameters above), this wait time is 
      imposed after the condition is removed before adaptive updates resume. 
      TPSad_MAP_min When the absolute value of MAP is less than this value, no 
      adaptive updates are performed. 
      TPSad_mode Enable switch for single mode (legacy) or dual mode adaptive 
      function 
      TPSad_PRadapt_ratio ratio of PR adaptive vs. CdA adaptive: -1=OFF, 0.0=CdA 
      adaptive active, 1.0=PR adaptive active 
      TPSad_PRadapt_sw Specify the valve pressure ratio where the adaptive 
      updates should start transitioning from an area-based to a pressure 
      ratio-based approach. When the pressure ratio is between the start-end 
      limits, both CdA and PR adaptive are engaged, however, the gains are 
      limited to provide smooth transitions between the 2 adaptive modes. 
      TPSad_PRadapt_swend Specify the valve pressure ratio where the adaptive 
      updates should complete the transition from an area-based to a pressure 
      ratio-based approach. In general, this parameter should be the same as the 
      highlighted cells on the adaptive x-axes. When the pressure ratio is 
      between the start-end limits, both CdA and PR adaptive are engaged, 
      however, the gains are limited to provide smooth transitions between the 2 
      adaptive modes. 
      TPSad_PR_adapt_crct Throttle Model Adaptive: TM adaptive PR correction 
      TPSad_PR_adapt_lim The max adaptive correction for any particular entry in 
      the PR adaptive table is given by max(min limit, learn +/ limit * nominal 
      area)' 
      TPSad_PR_Kadapt The max adaptive correction for any particular entry in 
      the PR adaptive table is given by max(min limit, learn +/ limit * nominal 
      area)' 
      TPSad_PR_max When MAP/TIP pressure ratios are greater than this value, no 
      adaptive updates are performed. 
      TPSad_status Throttle model adaptive status 
      TPSad_store_EE This switch determines whether the single and dual mode 
      throttle-model adaptive learn tables are retained in battery supported 
      memory or permanent memory. In battery supported memory, the adaptive 
      tables will be cleared if the battery power is removed from the ECM. In 
      permanent memory, a key-on reset sequence must be performed to clear the 
      tables. 
      TPSad_strt_wait Wait time following engine start before any adaptive 
      updates are performed. 
      TPSad_TPS_min Adaptive area updates should be disabled at low valve 
      positions since the 0%, 0 in^2 table entry will not be updated. For 
      example, if the valve flow characterization table has the following 
      entries:

      0.00% 0.000 in^2
      2.56% 0.019 in^2

      then adaptive updates should be shut down when the valve position goes 
      sufficiently below 2.56% in order to keep the adaptive entry term used to 
      adjust the 0.019 in^2 entry from updating when that cell has little of the 
      interpolated focus. 
      TPSad_trans_lim If the ratio of transient flow (i.e. manifold filling only 
      flow) to steady-state flow (i.e. port flow) at the throttle exceeds this 
      value, no adaptive updates are performed. 
      TPScmd_dmdot Throttle flow derivative 
      TPScmd_dmdot_Dz Throttle flow derivative deadzone 
      TPScmd_dmdot_LP Throttle flow derivative low-pass filter time constant 
      TPScmd_dmdot_n Must be in 5ms increments, and < 100 ms. 
      TPSdP_config If absolute TIP and TOP sensors are present and should be 
      differenced to obtain the throttle delta-P, select the 'Absolute (TOP)' 
      option. 
      TPSdP_cyl_events Enter the number of cylinder events to use for TPSdP 
      measurement windowing. Lower values result in faster sensor response, 
      higher values minimize the engine-related pulsations. Set this value to 
      0.0 to disable cylinder event based windowing. Otherwise, this value must 
      be >= 1 if cylinder and the max window is limited to 200ms.

      NOTE: This option requires hardware support and will is not supported on 
      all input channels. 
      TPSdP_ena TPSdP sensor enable switch 
      TPSdP_float throttle cylinder-event windowed delta-P in psi 
      TPSdP_inst_float throttle instantaneous delta-P in psi 
      TPSdP_offset_dPmax This is the maximum TPS delta-P reading for no-flow 
      offset sampling. If the actual TPS delta-P reading is above this limit, 
      the sample is rejected. 
      TPSdP_offset_dPmin This is the minimum TPS delta-P reading for no-flow 
      offset sampling. If the actual TPS delta-P reading is below this limit, 
      the sample is rejected. 
      TPSdP_offset_float TPSdP instantaneous 
      TPSdP_offset_keywt TPSdP sensor offset sampling will be initialized by 
      default at key-on. This is the delay (e.g. for power-up of 5V output) 
      required before sampling should begin. 
      TPSdP_offset_strtwt Set this to a non-zero value to inhibit starting and 
      allow for a pre-start pressure offset pegging. Unlike some of the other 
      pressure pegging routines, the TPSdP offset sampling ONLY occurs during 
      the start inhibit period to ensure valid sampling. 
      TPSdP_offset_tau This is the low-pass filter time constant used to sample 
      the TPS delta-P offset value. 
      TPSdP_Paux_cal TPSdP sensor calibration table select 
      TPSdP_tau This is the low-pass time constant applied to the TPS delta-P 
      low-pass/cubic deadzone filter. It is applied after the offset is added to 
      the raw delta-P sensor reading. 
      TPSdualpot_ena This enables use of a dual pot (redundant pot) position 
      feedback system. 
      TPSerr_maxVbat Obsoleted parameter 
      TPSerr_minVbat Unable to reach lower TPS diagnostic: minimum battery 
      voltage 
      TPSerr_neg Unable to reach lower TPS diagnostic: target TPS - actual TPS 
      lower limit (negative value) threshold 
      TPSerr_pos Unable to reach higher TPS diagnostic: target TPS - actual TPS 
      upper limit 
      TPSerr_run_mode Unable to reach lower TPS diagnostic: Run mode - this 
      parameter should be set to stopped or cranking for systems where an 
      unable-to-reach position error will prevent the engine from reaching an 
      underspeed/running status. 
      TPSerr_wait Unable to reach lower TPS diagnostic: Wait period entry 
      condition 
      TPSlim_current Max throttle position calibration: Current max TPS limit 
      TPSlim_ena_gsln Max Throttle Position Calibration: Gasoline TPS Limiting 
      flag 
      TPSlim_ena_LP Max Throttle Position Calibration: LPG TPS Limiting flag 
      TPSlim_ena_NG Max Throttle Position Calibration: NG TPS Limiting flag 
      TPSraw_LP High-speed anti-aliasing low-pass time constant for the raw PS 
      feedback voltage. 
      TPS_cmd_AD DBW TPS command (volts) 
      TPS_cmd_pct DBW TPS command (percent) 
      TPS_ctl_auth Throttle position control authority - max position 
      calibration 
      TPS_EE_store If enabled, the idle/full offsets will be stored in EEPROM 
      and restored on power-on. Note a slight offset is applied to the learn 
      value prior to storing a successful learn in EEPROM to prevent the EEPROM 
      value from being the absolute min/max value ever seen during a learn 
      sequence (see "PS learn EEPROM offset"). 
      TPS_GovN_pct Normalized commanded throttle position as calculated by 
      Gov1/2/3 
      TPS_KcompPin Throttle Kcomp*Pin - filtered 
      TPS_KcompPin_raw Throttle Kcomp*Pin - raw 
      TPS_KOC_sweep_close Sets the command applied to close the throttle during 
      the key-off clear TPS sweep cycles. 
      TPS_KOC_sweep_cnt Selects the number of throttle close/open cycles 
      performed after key-off when the "Key-off clear TPS sweep" parameter is 
      set to 'Enabled'. 
      TPS_KOC_sweep_ena Enables a series of throttle close and open cycles to 
      clear any deposits which formed during the drive cycle. This operation 
      will not execute if "Key-off clear with relay on" is disabled or the ECT 
      has not reached the nominal minimal temperature threshold when key-off 
      occurs. At key-off, sweeping will begin after the time specified by the 
      "Key-off clear wait" parameter has elapsed. 

      Upon completion of the sweep operation, full and idle TPS voltage learning 
      will execute if enabled by the "Key-off learn TPS idle/full" parameter. 
      The "Key-off clear hold" parameter must be configured with sufficient time 
      to allow both the throttle sweep and learning operations to complete.

      TPS_KOC_sweep_hold Sets the amount of time the throttle is held closed or 
      open during the key-off clear TPS sweep cycles. 
      TPS_KOC_sweep_open Sets the command applied to open the throttle during 
      the key-off clear TPS sweep cycles. 
      TPS_learn_cmd_init Initial throttle position commanded to quickly get the 
      throttle close to the full and idle position while not allowing the 
      throttle to hard impact at the stops. The slew rate will be used when 
      moving the final distance from the initial position to the full and idle 
      limited position. 
      TPS_learn_cmd_slew Rate the command percentage increases/decreases to 
      reach full/idle position. If a rate of 0 %/sec is given, this will bypass 
      the slew causing the throttle to open/close as quickly as possible, which 
      may reduce the life of the throttle. 
      TPS_learn_EE_ofst DBW PS learn EEPROM offset 
      TPS_learn_ena Enables the sweeping of the throttle on key-off to learn the 
      full and idle TPS voltages. Learning will not execute if "Key-off clear 
      with relay on" is disabled or if the ECT has not reached the nominal 
      minimal temperature when key-off occurs. On key-off, throttle learning 
      will begin after completion of the key-off clear TPS sweep operation, if 
      enabled. Otherwise, throttle learning will commence after the time 
      specified by "Key-off clear wait" has elapsed.

      When throttle learning is complete, the learned full and idle TPS voltages 
      are committed to EEPROM and restored on power-on. 
      TPS_learn_full_lim DBW PS1 learn full limit 
      TPS_learn_full_ofst DBW PS learn full offset 
      TPS_learn_full_seek DBW PS learn full seek 
      TPS_learn_idle_lim DBW PS1 learn idle limit 
      TPS_learn_idle_ofst DBW PS learn idle offset 
      TPS_learn_idle_seek DBW PS learn idle seek 
      TPS_max_gov_pct Normalized commanded throttle position as calculated by 
      Max Gov 
      TPS_MinMAP_pct Minimum TPS setting that corresponds to the MAP minimum 
      target, MinMAP_target 
      TPS_min_gov_pct Normalized commanded throttle position as calculated by 
      Min Gov 
      TPS_pct DBW TPS position 
      TPS_step_max Used for 3phase motor control only used when PS1 is set to a 
      feedback option based on 'steps'. 
      TPS_TM_calc Throttle model computed TPS at current engine conditions 
      TPS_TM_full_MAP Throttle model estimate of the minimum throttle position 
      for the full-load MAP 
      TPW_VC_PCF 1D Interpolation Table: Primary Injector Voltage-Based 
      Calibration. Given Injector supply voltage, returns Pressure Correction 
      Factor (PCF) in ms per psi for the given supply voltage (vBat) based on a 
      nominal delta pressure between the calibrated fuel inlet pressure and fuel 
      outlet pressure. NOTE: This table is used when "Pressure Correction Mode" 
      = "Voltage-based". 
      TPW_VC_PCF_I2 1D Interpolation Table: Secondary Injector Voltage-Based 
      Calibration. Given Injector supply voltage, returns Pressure Correction 
      Factor (PCF) in ms per psi for the given supply voltage (vBat) based on a 
      nominal delta pressure between the calibrated fuel inlet pressure and fuel 
      outlet pressure. NOTE: This table is used when "Pressure Correction Mode" 
      = "Voltage-based". 
      TPW_VC_peak 1D Interpolation Table: Primary Injector Voltage-Based 
      Calibration. Given Injector supply voltage, returns Injector peak current 
      hold time in ms for the given supply voltage. NOTE: This table is used 
      when "Current control type" = "Peak & Hold". 
      TPW_VC_peak_I2 1D Interpolation Table: Secondary Injector Voltage-Based 
      Calibration. Given Injector supply voltage, returns Injector peak current 
      hold time in ms for the given supply voltage. NOTE: This table is used 
      when "Current control type" = "Peak & Hold". 
      TPW_VC_time 1D Interpolation Table: Primary Injector Voltage-Based 
      Calibration. Given Injector supply voltage, returns Injector on-time 
      offset in ms for the given supply voltage. 
      TPW_VC_time_I2 1D Interpolation Table: Secondary Injector Voltage-Based 
      Calibration. Given Injector supply voltage, returns Injector on-time 
      offset in ms for the given supply voltage. 
      TPW_VC_volts 1D Interpolation Table: Primary Injector Voltage-Based 
      Calibration. Injector supply voltage input axis values 
      TPW_VC_volts_I2 1D Interpolation Table: Secondary Injector Voltage-Based 
      Calibration. Injector supply voltage input axis values

      TransNeut_ena Transmission in-neutral status (valid / invalid) 
      TransNeut_ETC2_mode Parameter configures when ETC2 is checked for 
      park/neutral indication. When set to 'Use neutral safety switch config', 
      then park/neutral indication is determined by the "Trans/Park neutral 
      safety switch" parameter. ETC2 will only be checked if "Trans/Park neutral 
      safety switch" is configured as 'J1939 ETC2'. When this parameter is set 
      to 'Sometimes (Legacy)', several subsystems check ETC2 regardless of the 
      "Trans/Park neutral safety switch" configuration. These subsystems check 
      ETC2 to override cruise control, reset the roadspeed loss diagnostic, 
      provide interlock for diagnostic tests, and disengage braking. To always 
      check ETC2 for park/neutral indication, set this parameter to 'Use neutral 
      safety switch config' and set "Trans/Park neutral safety switch" to 'J1939 
      ETC2'. 
      TransNeut_sw If enabled, the transmission neutral safety switch must be 
      validated before a discrete speed governor can be engaged when operating 
      in 'Vehicle' application mode. 
      TransNeut_sw_cfg If an Aux DIG is selected for the switch input, this 
      value determines the active logic state(s). Default values are defined 
      when Aux DIG1 through Aux DIG3 are selected for the switch input:

      Aux DIG1 = Select
      Aux DIG2 = Select
      Aux DIG3 = Select

      If Aux PUD4 through Aux PUD15 is selected for the switch input, this value 
      determines the active logic state.

      NOTE: The Open state is not supported for Aux PUD inputs, nor are Defaults 
      defined, so only the GND and +V states are valid for Aux PUD4 through Aux 
      PUD15. 
      TRANS_gear_a Transmission actual/current gear engaged 
      TRANS_gear_auto Transmission shift mode 
      TRANS_gear_a_int Transmission actual/current gear engaged:
      0 = neutral
      126 = park
      1 to 125 = forward gears
      -1 to -125 = reverse gears
      -127 = error
      -126 = not available
      -128 = not received 
      TRANS_gear_d Transmission desired gear 
      TRANS_gear_d_int Transmission desired gear:
      0 = neutral
      126 = park
      1 to 125 = forward gears
      -1 to -125 = reverse gears
      -127 = error
      -126 = not available
      -128 = not received 
      trans_idle_trqpctlmt Torque limit to be applied if J1939 communication 
      with the transmission is lost and the foot pedal is at the idle position. 
      trans_offidle_trqlmt Torque limit to be applied if J1939 communication 
      with the transmission is lost and the foot pedal is not at the idle 
      position. 
      TRANS_ratio0 Transmission reverse gear ratio = engine speed / output shaft 
      speed. This parameter is currently unused. 
      TRANS_ratio1 Transmission 1st forward gear ratio = engine speed / output 
      shaft speed. This parameter is used to determine the safety of downshifts 
      and rpm matching. 
      TRANS_ratio2 Transmission 2nd forward gear ratio = engine speed / output 
      shaft speed. This parameter is used to determine the safety of downshifts 
      and rpm matching. This parameter is only meaningful for >= 2-speed 
      transmissions.

      TRAT_TAUX_n1 This is the ordinal number of the Auxiliary Temperature to

      TRIM_BM TRIM (fast) DC equivalent change from nominal Phi 
      TRIM_DC Alternate-fuel trim duty cycle 
      TRIM_dis_hold Alternate-fuel trim disable hold time 
      TRIM_EGO_ajlean Service lean mixture indicator 
      TRIM_EGO_ajrich Service rich mixture indicator 
      TRIM_EGO_ajstoc Service stoich mixture indicator 
      TRIM_EGO_avg TRIM carburetor manual adjustment EGO slow average 
      TRIM_ftran_DCdef If the switch above is set to 'Fixed command value', this 
      is the PWM TRIM duty-cycle used during a fuel type transition. 
      TRIM_fueltran_mode This switch controls how an EPR or PWM TRIM valve for 
      gaseous fuel control behaves during a fuel type transition. For the 'Fixed 
      command value' option, the specified values below will be used. For the 
      'Nominal lookup value' option, the nominal pressure or duty-cycle will be 
      used without modification. 
      TRIM_lim_bhvG switch to determine trim valve authority limit behavior 
      TRIM_lim_bhvN This switch controls how the CL system behaves when the trim 
      valve reaches its authority limits. The first option allows CL_BM to 
      continue ramping, the second option halts ramping at the authority limit 
      and therefore prevents CL_BM limit fault setting, and the last option 
      halts ramping but also behaves as if the CL_BM has reached its limits in 
      this condition so that a fault can still set. 
      TRIM_lim_bhvP This switch controls how the CL system behaves when the trim 
      valve reaches its authority limits. The first option allows CL_BM to 
      continue ramping, the second option halts ramping at the authority limit 
      and therefore prevents CL_BM limit fault setting, and the last option 
      halts ramping but also behaves as if the CL_BM has reached its limits in 
      this condition so that a fault can still set. 
      trim_load_src This switch selects either MAP or air mass inducted per 
      liter displacment as the load indication on the x-axis for the LP/NG 
      nominal fuel pressure, trim %, and associated nominal phi calibration 
      tables. The primary difference is that the air-mass load indication 
      includes volumetric efficiency (VE) changes as a function of MAT, ECT, 
      CWT, and EBP. 
      trim_LP_max Trim valve maximum duty-cycle - LP 
      trim_LP_min Trim valve minimum duty-cycle - LP 
      trim_MAP_Vdc Nominal Phi/Nominal fuel pressure LU MAP value with volume 
      flow correction. Used only when trim_load_src = MAP 
      TRIM_max_BM TRIM (fast) maximum BM allowed at the current mdot_air 
      (positive value) 
      TRIM_min_BM TRIM (fast) minimum BM allowed at the current mdot_air 
      (negative value) 
      TRIM_mode Alternative-fuel trim mode - Auto / Manual 
      trim_m_a_Vdc Nominal Phi/Nominal fuel pressure LU MAP value with volume 
      flow correction. Used when trim_load_src = Air Mass/L - Displacement 
      trim_NG_max Trim valve maximum duty-cycle - NG 
      trim_NG_min Trim valve minimum duty-cycle - NG 
      trim_nom_crkN PWM trim valve cranking nominal duty cycle (NG) 
      trim_nom_crkP PWM trim valve cranking nominal duty cycle (LPG) 
      TRIM_nom_DC PWM trim nominal duty cycle 
      TRIM_nom_phi (NG or LPG as applicable)Nominal Phi at Nominal Carburetor 
      Conditions (based on rpm and load conditions) 
      trim_ntran_forceN Negative Transient forced valve setpoint (NG) 
      trim_ntran_forceP Negative Transient forced valve setpoint (LPG) 
      TRIM_out_chan This switch controls which output is used for the TRIM PWM 
      valve control function. 
      TRIM_period_def PWM trim period 
      TRIM_sens PWM TRIM dphi/duty-cycle sensitivity 
      trim_SG_FA_x Specific gravity time F/A ratio fuel correction multiplier. 
      trim_TIPVd_load Current engine load estimate (used to compute 
      trim_TIPVd_TIPss) 
      trim_TIPVd_mult Carburetor volume flow correction multiplier 
      trim_TIPVd_TIPss Current estimated SS TIP into the carburetor 
      trim_TIP_Vdot_comp This switch enables/disables volume flow compensation 
      of the nominal fuel pressure lookup for steady-state TIP versus the 
      current instantaneous TIP into the gaseous carburetor. This is primarily 
      used on blow-through boosted engines where the transient TIP value is 
      significantly different than the steady-state TIP due to the use of an 
      electronic wastegate and a significant gradient vs. load (x-axis) in the 
      nominal fuel pressure table. 
      TRIM_trans_dis Trim transient compensation 
      trim_tran_forceN Positive Transient forced valve setpoint (NG) 
      trim_tran_forceP Positive Transient forced valve setpoint (LPG) 
      TRIM_trig_chg Trim disable air transient trigger 
      tri_fuel_ena Setting this switch to 'Enabled' will enable the use of one 
      or two tri-fuel lockoff solenoids for a second gaseous fuel. In this 
      configuration the fuel pump output will control the gasoline fuel pump, 
      the primary and secondary (if present) lockoff solenoids will control one 
      of the gaseous fuels, and the tri-fuel primary and secondary (if present) 
      lockoff solenoids will control the second gaseous fuel. 
      tri_fuel_lockoff When "Tri-Fuel mode" is enabled, this switch determines 
      which gaseous fuel is controlled by the primary and secondary (if present) 
      lockoff solenoids. The tri-fuel primary and secondary (if present) lockoff 
      solenoids will then control the other gaseous fuel type. 
      Trpmdt_rpm 1D interpolation table rpm input values 
      Trpmdt_rpmdtn 1D Interpolation Table: drpm/dt calculation rpm 
      interpolation window. More points yield a quieter and more accurate time 
      derivative BUT introduces more time lag. 
      Trpmdt_rpmdtx 1D Interpolation Table: Post drpm/dt interpolation LPF 
      constant 
      TRS2ovsc_dIlim 1D Interpolation Table: Overshoot Control Gains - Set 2. 
      Input is roadspeed (kph), output is Rate Limit (% / sec). This is limit of 
      authority of the Integrator ramp rate during roadspeed overshoot control. 
      TRS2ovsc_Kiv 1D Interpolation Table: Overshoot Control Gains - Set 2. 
      Input is roadspeed (kph), output is Integral Velocity Gain (% / kph). This 
      is the main gain used by the roadspeed overshoot control system. 
      TRS2ovsc_RS 1D Interpolation Table: Overshoot Control Gains - Set 2. 
      Roadspeed input values 
      TRS3ovsc_dIlim 1D Interpolation Table: Overshoot Control Gains - Set 3. 
      Input is roadspeed (kph), output is Rate Limit (% / sec). This is limit of 
      authority of the Integrator ramp rate during roadspeed overshoot control. 
      TRS3ovsc_Kiv 1D Interpolation Table: Overshoot Control Gains - Set 3. 
      Input is roadspeed (kph), output is Integral Velocity Gain (% / kph). This 
      is the main gain used by the roadspeed overshoot control system. 
      TRS3ovsc_RS 1D Interpolation Table: Overshoot Control Gains - Set 3. 
      Roadspeed input values 
      TRSovsc_dIlim 1D Interpolation Table: Overshoot Control Gains - Set 1. 
      Input is roadspeed (kph), output is Rate Limit (% / sec). This is limit of 
      authority of the Integrator ramp rate during roadspeed overshoot control. 
      It is expressed as a positive number even though the actual ramp rate on 
      the integrator will be negative. 
      TRSovsc_Kiv 1D Interpolation Table: Overshoot Control Gains - Set 1. Input 
      is roadspeed (kph), output is Integral Velocity Gain (% / kph). This is 
      the main gain used by the roadspeed overshoot control system. It is only 
      in effect when the system is armed, the roadspeed is >= target - 
      delta-engage, and roadspeed derivative > 0. 
      TRSovsc_RS 1D Interpolation Table: Overshoot Control Gains - Set 1. 
      Roadspeed input values 
      TRS_kph_act 1D Interpolation Table: Roadspeed pulse nonlinear correction 
      table (input measured RS, output corrected RS) 
      TRS_kph_meas 1D interpolation table measured roadspeed input values 
      TRS_setsrc_lim Road speed network setpoint speeds, for use with PGN 65473. 

      TSC1_SA active TSC1 source address 
      TSC_ff_loadval Current TSC1 feedforward governor load 
      TSC_ff_torque This switch controls the interpretation of the torque field 
      in a speed command (target) mode J1939 TSC1 message. Typically (per J1939) 
      this parameter is ignored and only the speed command field is used in this 
      mode.

      However, by setting this switch to other than 'Disabled', this value will 
      be interpreted as a feedforward term in the Gov3 commanded load % 
      computation.

      If this switch is set to 'Enabled - Gov Load %', the value transmitted is 
      interpreted in units of governor load as defined by the no-load/full-load 
      governor calibration.

      If this switch is set to 'Enabled - Ref Torque %', the value transmitted 
      is interpreted as an absolute torque when multiplied by the J1939 Engine 
      Configuration (EC) reference torque.

      This value is resolved back to governor load % units using the torque 
      estimation calibration. 
      TSC_gov_acc_setpnt Reinitializes the Gov3 integrator value when a J1939 
      TSC1 remote speed request message arrives. This initial integrator value 
      can help smooth the transition to the requested speed.A value of '0' 
      disables this feature. 
      TSC_idlelim_mode This switch controls whether or not a J1939 TSC1 speed 
      command below the current idle schedule will be accepted or limited back 
      to idle speed. If this switch is to '>= Abs Min Speed', then any speed 
      below idle will only be restricted to >= the absolute min governor speed. 
      If this switch is set to '>= Abs Min + Idle Delta', then any speed below 
      idle will only be restricted to >= the absolute min governor speed + the 
      difference between base (fully warm) idle and the current idle schedule 
      speed. 
      TSC_limit_only This switch controls the behavior of full-authority 
      speed-command modes of the TSC1 (torque/speed control) J1939 network 
      messages when a speed-up command greater than the current engine operating 
      condition is received. This switch forces these commands to behave like 
      the speed/torque limit mode of the TSC1 message. 
      TSC_limit_trq Enabled TSC1 torque control mode. The foot pedal must be set 
      to 'Network Throttle' for torque control mode to become active. 
      TSC_maxlim_mode This parameter controls whether or not a J1939 TSC1 speed 
      request above the max governor speed will be accepted or limited back to 
      the max governor speed.

      When set to '<= High Idle Speed', TSC1 speed requests will be allowed in 
      the droop region with full load permitted. Warning: There is a possibility 
      that the engine will be commanded to operate in a region outside of the 
      torque curve. To help mitigate potential engine damage, the Full Load Map 
      should be calibrated to provide suitable protection. In this mode, the Max 
      Governor's control mode must be set to 'Droop'.

      All TSC1 speed requests are restricted by the "Governor speed range 
      absolute max" parameter, regardless of this parameter's value. 
      TSC_RPM_0_ignore This software switch controls how J1939 TSC1 speed 
      setpoint requests with RPM = 0 are handled. By default, TSC1 speed 
      requests with RPM = 0 will be processed and the final speed target may be 
      overridden by the governors.

      If this switch is enabled, TSC1 speed requests with RPM = 0 are ignored. 
      GCP ignored TSC1 speed requests with RPM = 0, so enable this switch for 
      GCP compatibility. 
      TSH_phiC_SH 1D interpolation table specific humidity input values 
      TSH_phiC_x 1D Interpolation Table: Input is Specific Humidity (g/kg), 
      output is Phi Offset (%@0.65 phi).

      Tspkf_duration This is the maximum continuous amount of time that the 
      spark firing test will continue to pulse the selected spark coil. Set this 
      parameter to zero for a single spark pulse. Setting this value to greater 
      than 60.0 seconds (i.e. 61.0 seconds) effectively disables this timeout. 
      Tspkf_ena Use this switch to lock-out the use of the spark firing test if 
      desired.
